{"title_page": "Government of China", "text_new": "{{About|the government of the People's Republic of China|the government of the Republic of China (Taiwan)|Government of the Republic of China|governments in Chinese history|Government of China (disambiguation)}}\n{{For|the current [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|Central People's Government]] of China|Li Keqiang Government}}\n\n{{pp-semi-indef}}\n\n{{Infobox communist government\n| government_name  = {{nowrap|Government of the<br />[[China|People's Republic of China]]}}<br />{{small|\u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u653f\u5e9c}}<br />''{{small|Zh\u014dnghu\u00e1 R\u00e9nm\u00edn G\u00f2ngh\u00e9gu\u00f3 Zh\u00e8ngf\u01d4}}''\n| image            = People's Republic of China National Emblem.svg\n| caption          = [[Emblem of the People's Republic of China]]\n| date             = 1 October 1949\n| url              = [http://english.gov.cn/ English.gov.cn]\n| legislature      = [[National People's Congress]]\n| party            = [[Communist Party of China]]\n| leader_title     = [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|General Secretary]]\n| leader_name      = [[Xi Jinping]]<ref>{{cite web |url = https://multimedia.scmp.com/widgets/china/govt-explainer/index.html |title = How the Chinese government works |publisher = South China Morning Post |quote = Xi Jinping is the most powerful figure in China's political system, and his influence mainly comes from his position as the general secretary of the Chinese Communist Party.}}</ref>\n| executive        = [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council]]<br />([[Li Keqiang Government]])\n| president_title  = [[President of the People's Republic of China|President]]\n| president_name   = [[Xi Jinping]]\n| premier_title    = [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Premier]]\n| premier_name     = [[Li Keqiang]]\n| speaker_title    = [[Chairman of the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress|Congress Chairman]]\n| speaker_name     = [[Li Zhanshu]]\n| military         = [[People's Liberation Army]]<br />[[People's Armed Police]]<br />[[Militia (China)|Militia ]]\n| commander_title  = [[Chairman of the Central Military Commission|Military Chairman]]\n| commander_name   = [[Xi Jinping]]\n}}\n\n{{Infobox Chinese\n| title = Government of the People's Republic of China\n| t = \u4e2d\u83ef\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u570b\u653f\u5e9c\n| s = \u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u653f\u5e9c\n| p = Zh\u014dnghu\u00e1 R\u00e9nm\u00edn G\u00f2ngh\u00e9gu\u00f3 Zh\u00e8ngf\u01d4\n}}\n\n{{Politics of China}}\n\nThe '''central government of the People's Republic of China''' is divided among several state organs:\n\n# [[National People's Congress]] (NPC): the ultimate power of the state that makes the constitution and basic laws, and supervise and elects all following organs;\n# [[Standing Committee of the National People's Congress]] (NPCSC): the permanent legislative organ which makes most laws, interprets the constitution and laws, conducts [[constitutional review]], and supervise all following organs;\n# [[President of the People's Republic of China|President]], act as a ceremonial [[head of state]] in compliance with decisions made by the NPCSC, but exercises an independent power to nominate the Premier of the State Council; and the [[Vice President of the People's Republic of China|Vice-President]], who has no power itself, but assist the President.\n# [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council]] (synonymous with \"Central People's Government\"): the executive branch, whose [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Premier]] is the [[head of government]];\n# [[Central Military Commission (China)|Central Military Commission]] (CMC): the military branch, whose [[Chairman of the Central Military Commission|Chairman]] is the [[commander-in-chief]] of the national armed forces including the [[People's Liberation Army]] (PLA), the [[People's Armed Police]] (PAP), and the [[Militia (China)|Militia]];\n# [[National Supervisory Commission]] (NSC): the supervisory branch;\n# [[Supreme People's Court]] (SPC): the judicial branch;\n# [[Supreme People's Procuratorate]] (SPP): the prosecutorial branch.\n\nThe legal power of the [[Communist Party of China|Communist Party]] is guaranteed by [[Constitution of China|the PRC Constitution]] and its position as the supreme political authority in the PRC is realised through its comprehensive control of the state, military, and media.<ref>Ralph H. Folsom, John H. Minan, Lee Ann Otto, ''Law and Politics in the People's Republic of China'', [[West (publisher)|West Publishing]] (St. Paul, 1992), pp.&nbsp;76\u201377.</ref> According to a prominent government spokesman:<blockquote>We will never simply copy the system of Western countries or introduce a system of multiple parties holding office in rotation; although China\u2019s state organs have different responsibilities, they all adhere to the line, principles and policies of the party.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/7932091.stm \"China 'will not have democracy'] China will never adopt Western-style democracy with a multi-party system, its top legislator has said.\" BBC 9 March 2009, accessed October 9, 2010.</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe primary organs of state power are the [[National People's Congress]], the [[President of the People's Republic of China|President]], and the [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council]]. Members of the State Council include the [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Premier]], a variable number of [[Vice Premier of the People's Republic of China|Vice Premiers]], five [[State councillor (China)|State Councilors]] (protocol equal of vice premiers but with narrower portfolios), the [[Secretary-General of the State Council|Secretary-General]], and now 26 [[Ministries of the People's Republic of China|ministers and other cabinet-level department heads]].  During the 1980s there was an attempt made to separate party and state functions, with the party deciding general policy and the state carrying it out. The attempt was abandoned in the 1990s with the result that the political leadership within the state are also the leaders of the party. This dual structure thereby creates a single centralized focus of power.\n\nAt the same time there has been a move to separate party and state offices at levels other than the central government. It is not unheard of for a sub-national executive to also be party secretary.  This frequently causes conflict between the chief executive and the party secretary, and this conflict is widely seen as intentional to prevent either from becoming too powerful.  Some special cases are the [[special administrative regions of China|Special Administrative Regions]] of [[Hong Kong]] and [[Macau]], where according to constitution and respective basic law, most national laws do not apply and the [[autonomous regions of China|autonomous regions]] where, following Soviet practice, the chief executive is typically a member of the local ethnic group while the party general secretary is non-local and usually [[Han Chinese]].\n\nUnder the [[Constitution of China]], the NPC is the highest organ of state power in China. It meets annually for about two weeks to review and approve major new policy directions, laws, the budget, and major personnel changes. Most national legislation in the PRC is adopted by the [[Standing Committee of the National People's Congress]]. Most initiatives are presented to the NPCSC for consideration by the State Council after previous endorsement by the Communist Party's Politburo Standing Committee. Although the NPC generally approves State Council policy and personnel recommendations, the NPC and its standing committee has increasingly asserted its role as the national legislature and has been able to force revisions in some laws. For example, the State Council and the Party have been unable to secure passage of a fuel tax to finance the construction of [[Expressways of China|expressways]].<ref>[http://www.rsc.org/chemistryworld/Issues/2009/January/ChinaBitesTheBulletOnFuelTax.asp China bites the bullet on fuel tax]. Rsc.org (2009-01-01). Retrieved on 2013-07-21.</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/spl/hi/in_depth/china_politics/government/html/7.stm Bbc News]. BBC News. Retrieved on 2013-07-21.</ref>\n\n== Political leadership ==\n{{Main|Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of China}}\n\n[[File:Danghui.svg|thumb|upright|Emblem of the [[Communist Party of China]] ]]\n\nThe Politburo Standing Committee consists of the government's top leadership. Historically it has five to nine members, and currently has seven members. Its officially mandated purpose is to conduct policy discussions and make decisions on major issues when the Politburo, a larger decision-making body, is not in session. According to the party's [[Constitution of the Communist Party of China|Constitution]], the [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|General Secretary of the Central Committee]] must also be a member of the Politburo Standing Committee.<ref>[http://www.china.org.cn/english/features/49109.htm#4 Chapter III Central Organizations of the Party - Article 22]</ref>\n\nThe membership of the PSC is strictly ranked in [[Orders of precedence in the People's Republic of China|protocol sequence]]. Historically, the general secretary (or party chairman) has been ranked first; the rankings of other leaders have varied over time. Since the 1990s, the general secretary, premier, chairman of the [[National People's Congress]], the chairman of the [[Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference]], the secretary of the [[Central Commission for Discipline Inspection]], the party's top anti-graft body, and the first-ranked secretary of the [[Secretariat of the Communist Party of China|secretariat]] have consistently also been members of the Politburo Standing Committee.<ref name=\"CF111312\">{{cite news |title = China's Next Leaders: A Guide to What's at Stake |url = http://www.chinafile.com/china%E2%80%99s-next-leaders-guide-what%E2%80%99s-stake |access-date = 18 November 2012 |newspaper = China File |date = 13 November 2012 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130210034750/http://www.chinafile.com/china%E2%80%99s-next-leaders-guide-what%E2%80%99s-stake |archive-date = 2013-02-10 |url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\n== Paramount leader ==\n[[File:Xi Jinping March 2017.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Paramount leader]] and [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|General Secretary]] [[Xi Jinping]] ]]\n{{Main article|Paramount leader}}\n\nPower is concentrated in the [[Paramount leader]], currently [[Xi Jinping]], who heads the four most important political and state offices: He is [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|General Secretary]] of the [[Communist Party of China|Communist Party]], general secretary of the [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of China|Central Committee]], [[Chairman of the Central Military Commission]], and [[President of the People's Republic of China|President]] of the PRC.<ref>{{cite web |url =https://multimedia.scmp.com/widgets/china/cpc-primer/ |title = A simple guide to the Chinese government|publisher=[[South China Morning Post]] |quote = [[Xi Jinping]] is the most powerful figure in the Chinese political system. He is the [[President of the People's Republic of China|President of China]], but his real influence comes from his position as the [[General Secretary of the Chinese Communist Party]].}}</ref> Recently, experts have observed growing limitations to the Paramount leader's ''de facto'' control over the government.<ref>{{cite news | first = Andrew | last = Higgins | title = Hu's visit spotlights China's two faces | date = 2011-01-16 | publisher = [[The Washington Post Company]] | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/01/15/AR2011011504013.html | newspaper = [[The Washington Post]] | access-date = 2011-01-17 }}</ref>\n\n== Constitution ==\n{{Main|Constitution of the People's Republic of China}}\n\nThe Constitution was first created on September 20, 1954. Before that an interim constitution-like document created by the [[Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference]] was in force. The second promulgation in 1975 shortened the Constitution to just about 30 articles, and contained Communist slogans and revolutionary language throughout. The role of courts was slashed, and the Presidency was gone. The 3rd promulgation in 1978 expanded the number of articles, but was still under  the influence of the just-gone-by Cultural Revolution.\n\nThe current constitution is the PRC's fourth promulgation. On December 4, 1982, it was promulgated and has served as a stable constitution for 30 years. The roles of the presidency and the courts were normalized, and under the constitution, all citizens were equal. Amendments in 1988, 1993, 1999, 2004, and 2018 recognized private property, safeguarded human rights, and further promoted the non-public sector of the economy.\n\n==National People's Congress==\n{{Main|National People's Congress}}\n[[image:The 1st Session of the 12th National People's Congress open 20130305.jpg|thumb|right|270px|The 12th [[National People's Congress]] held in 2013]]\n\nThe [[National People's Congress]] (usually abbreviated NPC) is the national legislature of the People's Republic of China. With 2,924 members in 2017, it is the largest parliamentary body in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ipu.org/parline-e/mod-general.asp|title=IPU PARLINE Database: General Information|last=International Parliamentary Union|date=|website=|accessdate=2017-08-06}}</ref> Under China's current Constitution, the NPC is structured as a [[unicameral]] legislature, with the power to legislate, the power to oversee the operations of the government, and the power to elect the major officials of state. The NPC and the National Committee of the [[Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference|People's Political Consultative Conference]] (CPPCC), a consultative body whose members represent various social groups, are the main deliberative bodies of China, and are often referred to as the [[Lianghui]] (Two Assemblies).<ref>{{cite web |title = State Structure of the People's Republic of China |url = http://www.npc.gov.cn/englishnpc/stateStructure/node_3826.htm |website = \u4e2d\u56fd\u4eba\u5927\u7f51 |publisher=The National People's Congress of the People's Republic of China |access-date = 2016-09-29 }}</ref>\n\nThe NPC is elected for a term of five years. It holds annual sessions every spring, usually lasting from 10 to 14 days, in the [[Great Hall of the People]] on the west side of [[Tiananmen Square]] in Beijing. The NPC's sessions are usually timed to occur with the meetings of the CPPCC, and these annual meetings provide an opportunity for the officers of state to review past policies and present future plans to the nation. The fourth session of the 12th NPC was held from March 5 to March 16, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |title = The National People's Congress of the People's Republic of China |access-date = 2016-11-08 |url = http://www.npc.gov.cn/englishnpc/news/Events/node_2762_3.htm |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170202001035/http://www.npc.gov.cn/englishnpc/news/Events/node_2762_3.htm |archive-date = 2017-02-02 |url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\n== President ==\n{{Main|President of the People's Republic of China}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left; float:right; margin-right:9px; margin-left:2px;\"\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[File:Mao Zedong portrait.jpg|100px]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[File:LiuShaoqi Colour.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Mao Zedong]]<br /><small>[[List of Presidents of the People's Republic of China|First]] [[Chairman of the Communist Party of China|Chairman]]</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Liu Shaoqi]]<br /><small>[[List of Presidents of the People's Republic of China|2nd]] [[President of the People's Republic of China|Chairman]]</small>\n|}\nThe [[President of the People's Republic of China]] is the [[head of state]]. Under the PRC's [[Constitution of the People's Republic of China|constitution]], the presidency is a largely [[Figurehead|ceremonial office]] with limited powers.<ref name=\"auto\">[http://www.kkhsou.in/main/polscience/structure_function.html Krishna Kanta Handique State Open University], EXECUTIVE: THE PRESIDENT OF THE CHINESE REPUBLIC.</ref> However, since 1993, as a matter of convention, the presidency has been held simultaneously by the [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China]], the top [[Paramount leader|leader]] in the [[One-party state|one-party system]].<ref>{{cite news |title = Does Chinese leader Xi Jinping plan to hang on to power for more than 10 years? |url = http://www.scmp.com/news/china/policies-politics/article/2111123/does-chinese-leader-xi-jinping-plan-hang-power-more-10 |date=6 October 2017 |quote = If Xi relinquished the presidency in 2023 but remained party chief and chairman of the Central Military commission (CMC), his successor as president would be nothing more than a symbolic figure... \u201cOnce the president is neither the party\u2019s general secretary nor the CMC chairman, he or she will be hollowed out, just like a body without a soul.\u201d}}</ref> The office is officially regarded as [[Government of the People's Republic of China|an institution of the state]] rather than an administrative post; theoretically, the president serves at the pleasure of the [[National People's Congress]], the legislature, and is not legally vested to take executive action on its own prerogative.{{NoteTag|It is listed as such in the current Constitution; it is thus equivalent to organs such as the State Council, rather than to offices such as that of the premier.}} The current president is [[Xi Jinping]], who took office in March 2013.\n\nThe office was first established in the [[Constitution of the People's Republic of China]] in 1954 and successively held by [[Mao Zedong]] and [[Liu Shaoqi]]. Liu fell into political disgrace during the [[Cultural Revolution]], after which the office became vacant. The office was abolished under the Constitution of 1975, then reinstated in the Constitution of 1982, but with reduced powers. The official English-language [[translation]] of the title was \"[[Chairman]]\"; after 1982, this translation was changed to \"[[President (government title)|President]]\", although the Chinese title remains unchanged.{{NoteTag|In [[Chinese language|Chinese]] the President of the PRC is termed ''zh\u01d4x\u00ed'' (\u4e3b\u5e2d) while the Presidents of other countries are termed ''z\u01d2ngt\u01d2ng'' (\u603b\u7edf). Furthermore ''zh\u01d4x\u00ed'' continues to have the meaning of \"chairman\" in a generic context.}} In March 2018, presidential term limits were abolished.<ref>{{cite web|author=Steven Lee Myers |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/11/world/asia/china-xi-constitution-term-limits.html |title=China's Legislature Blesses Xi's Indefinite Rule. It Was 2,958 to 2. |website=The New York Times |date=March 11, 2018 |accessdate=2019-11-10}}</ref>\n\n== State Council ==\n{{Main article|State Council of the People's Republic of China}}\n{{Further|Premier of the People's Republic of China|Ministries of the People's Republic of China}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left; float:right; margin-right:9px; margin-left:2px;\"\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[File:Zhou Enlai in 1959.jpg|120px]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[File:Li Keqiang (cropped).jpg|100px]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Zhou Enlai]]<br /><small>[[List of Premiers of the People's Republic of China|First]] [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Premier]]</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Li Keqiang]]<br /><small>[[List of Premiers of the People's Republic of China|Current]] [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Premier]]</small>\n|}\n\nThe State Council is the chief authority of the People's Republic of China. It is appointed by the National People's Congress and is chaired by the [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Premier]] and includes the heads of each governmental department and agency. There are about 50 members in the council. In the politics of the People's Republic of China, the [[Central People's Government]] forms one of three interlocking branches of power, the others being the Communist Party of China and the People's Liberation Army. The State Council directly oversees the various subordinate People's Governments in the provinces, and in practice maintains an interlocking membership with the top levels of the Communist Party of China.\n\nCurrently the [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Premier of the State Council]] is [[Li Keqiang]] and the [[Vice Premier of the People's Republic of China|Vice Premiers]] are [[Han Zheng]], [[Sun Chunlan]], [[Hu Chunhua]] and [[Liu He (politician)|Liu He]]. Together with the five [[State Councilor]]s, they form the [[Li Keqiang Government|inner cabinet]] that regularly convenes for the [http://english.gov.cn/statecouncil/meetings/ State Council Executive Meeting].<ref>{{cite book |title = China's political system |last=Heilmann |first=Sebastian |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |year=2017 |isbn = 978-1-4422-7736-6 |pages=76\u201380 }}</ref>\n\n== Central Military Commission ==\n{{Main|Central Military Commission (China)}}\n\n[[File:ChinaDOD.jpg|thumb|The CMC is housed in the [[Ministry of National Defense of the People's Republic of China|Ministry of National Defense]] compound (\"August 1st Building\")]]\n\nThe Central Military Commission exercises the command and control of the [[People's Liberation Army]] and is supervised by the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress. The state CMC is nominally considered the supreme military policy-making body and its chairman, elected by the National People's Congress, is the commander-in-chief of the armed forces. In reality, command and control of the PLA, however, still resides with the Central Military Commission of the Chinese Communist Party Central Committee.\n\nCurrently the chairman of the Central Military Commission is [[Xi Jinping]].\n\n== National Supervisory Commission ==\n{{Main|National Supervisory Commission}}\n\nThe [[National Supervisory Commission]] of the People's Republic of China is the highest supervisory ([[List of anti-corruption agencies|anti-corruption]]) agency of the [[People's Republic of China]]. It supervises all public officials who exercise public power, at the same administrative ranking as the [[Supreme People's Court]] and [[Supreme People's Procuratorate]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chinalawtranslate.com/\u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u76d1\u5bdf\u6cd5\uff08\u8349\u6848\uff09/?lang=en |location=China |title=People's Republic of China Supervision Law (draft) |website=China Law Translate |publisher= |date=6 November 2017 |access-date=27 January 2018 }}</ref> Its operations are merged with the [[Central Commission for Discipline Inspection]] of the [[Communist Party of China]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.ccdi.gov.cn/special/zmsjd/zm19da_zm19da/201802/t20180202_163176.html |trans-title = Why should the National Supervisory Commission merges its operations with the Central Commission for Discipline Inspection of CPC? |script-title = zh:\u4e3a\u4ec0\u4e48\u4e2d\u592e\u7eaa\u59d4\u4e0e\u56fd\u5bb6\u76d1\u5bdf\u59d4\u5458\u4f1a\u8981\u5408\u7f72\u529e\u516c\uff1f |language = zh-CN |website = Website of CCDI&NSC |date = 2 Feb 2018 |access-date = 2 April 2018 }}</ref> It replaces the former [[Ministry of Supervision]].\n \nCurrently the director of National Supervisory Commission is [[Yang Xiaodu]].\n\n== Supreme People's Court and Supreme People's Procuratorate ==\n{{Main article|Supreme People's Court|Supreme People's Procuratorate}}\n\n[[File:Supreme People's Court of P.R.China's badge.svg|thumb|100px|Emblem of the [[Supreme People's Court|People's Court]]s]]\n[[File:Supreme People's Procuratorate of P.R.China's badge .svg|thumb|100px|Emblem of the [[People's Procuratorate]] ]]\n\nThe Supreme People's Court is of the People's Republic of China. Hong Kong and Macau, as special administrative regions, have separate judicial systems based on British common law traditions and Portuguese civil-law traditions respectively, and are out of the jurisdiction of the Supreme People's Court. The judges of the Supreme People's Court are appointed by the National People's Congress.\n\n{{As of|2018}}, the President of Supreme People's Court and the Procurator-General of Supreme People's Procuratorate are [[Zhou Qiang]] and [[Zhang Jun (politician)|Zhang Jun]] separately.\n\n== Provincial and local government ==\n{{Main|Administrative divisions of the People's Republic of China}}\nThe governors of China's [[Provinces of China|provinces]] and [[Autonomous regions of China|autonomous regions]] and mayors of its [[Direct-controlled municipalities of China|centrally controlled municipalities]] are appointed by the central government in Beijing after receiving the nominal consent of the [[National People's Congress]] (NPC). The [[Hong Kong]] and [[Macau]] special administrative regions (SARS) have some local autonomy since they have separate governments, legal systems, and basic constitutional laws, but they come under Beijing's control in matters of [[foreign policy]] and [[national security]], and their chief executives are handpicked by the central government. Below the provincial level in 2004 there were 50 rural prefectures, 283 prefecture-level cities, 374 county-level cities, 852 county-level districts under the jurisdiction of nearby cities, and 1,636 counties. There also were 662 cities (including those incorporated into the four centrally controlled municipalities), 808 urban districts, and 43,258 township-level regions. \n\nCounties are divided into townships and villages. While most have appointed officials running them, some lower-level jurisdictions have direct popular elections. The organs of self-governing ethnic autonomous areas (regions, prefectures, and counties)\u2014people's congresses and people's governments\u2014exercise the same powers as their provincial-level counterparts but are guided additionally by the Law on Regional Ethnic Autonomy and require NPC Standing Committee approval for regulations they enact \"in the exercise of autonomy\" and \"in light of the political, economic, and cultural characteristics of the ethnic group or ethnic groups in the areas.\"{{cn|date=January 2019}}\n\nWhile operating under strict control and supervision by the central government, China's local governments manage relatively high share of fiscal revenues and expenditures.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kadochnikov|first=Denis V.|date=2019-12-29|title=Fiscal decentralization and regional budgets' changing roles: a comparative case study of Russia and China|journal=Area Development and Policy|language=en|volume=|pages=1\u201319|doi=10.1080/23792949.2019.1705171|issn=2379-2949}}</ref>\n\n== Civil service ==\n{{Main|Civil service of the People's Republic of China}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Central People's Government of the People's Republic of China (1949\u201354)]]\n* [[Government of the Republic of China|Five Yuans of the Republic of China]]\n* [[History of political parties in China]]\n* [[Political systems of Imperial China]]\n* [[Politics of China|Politics of the People's Republic of China]]\n** [[Elections in China]]\n** [[Orders of precedence in China]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{NoteFoot}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Country study |country = China |abbr = cn |section = Government and Politics }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://english.gov.cn/ Official website of the Chinese Central Government] {{in lang|en}}  \n* [http://www.e-gov.org.cn/ China e-Government Network]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081224110923/http://www.chinainnovations.org/ China Government Innovation Network]\n* [http://www.ccgp.gov.cn/ China Government Procurement Information Network]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090504140432/http://govinfo.nlc.gov.cn/ Chinese Government Public Information Online Service Platform]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090830033427/http://www.prcgovernment.org/ Guide to Chinese Government Agencies]\n* [http://english.people.com.cn/data/organs/home.html Links to information regarding branches and departments of the PRC]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080518042419/http://www.uschina.org/public/china/govstructure/ US-China Business Council's PRC Central Government Structure Report]\n\n{{-}}\n\n{{PRC State Organs}}\n{{Separation of powers}}\n{{People's Republic of China politics}}\n{{China topics |state = autocollapse }}\n{{Asia topic |Government of |title = Governments of Asia }}\n{{Portal bar|Politics|China}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Government Of The People's Republic Of China}}\n\n[[Category:Government of China| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the government of the People's Republic of China|the government of the Republic of China (Taiwan)|Government of the Republic of China|governments in Chinese history|Government of China (disambiguation)}}\n{{For|the current [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|Central People's Government]] of China|Li Keqiang Government}}\n\n{{pp-semi-indef}}\n\n{{Infobox communist government\n| government_name  = {{nowrap|Government of the<br />[[China|People's Republic of China]]}}<br />{{small|\u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u653f\u5e9c}}<br />''{{small|Zh\u014dnghu\u00e1 R\u00e9nm\u00edn G\u00f2ngh\u00e9gu\u00f3 Zh\u00e8ngf\u01d4}}''\n| image            = People's Republic of China National Emblem.svg\n| caption          = [[Emblem of the People's Republic of China]]\n| date             = 1 October 1949\n| url              = [http://english.gov.cn/ English.gov.cn]\n| legislature      = [[National People's Congress]]\n| party            = [[Communist Party of China]]\n| leader_title     = [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|General Secretary]]\n| leader_name      = [[Xi Jinping]]<ref>{{cite web |url = https://multimedia.scmp.com/widgets/china/govt-explainer/index.html |title = How the Chinese government works |publisher = South China Morning Post |quote = Xi Jinping is the most powerful figure in China's political system, and his influence mainly comes from his position as the general secretary of the Chinese Communist Party.}}</ref>\n| executive        = [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council]]<br />([[Li Keqiang Government]])\n| president_title  = [[President of the People's Republic of China|President]]\n| president_name   = [[Xi Jinping]]\n| premier_title    = [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Premier]]\n| premier_name     = [[Li Keqiang]]\n| speaker_title    = [[Chairman of the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress|Congress Chairman]]\n| speaker_name     = [[Li Zhanshu]]\n| military         = [[People's Liberation Army]]<br />[[People's Armed Police]]<br />[[Militia (China)|Militia ]]\n| commander_title  = [[Chairman of the Central Military Commission|Military Chairman]]\n| commander_name   = [[Xi Jinping]]\n}}\n\n{{Infobox Chinese\n| title = Government of the People's Republic of China\n| t = \u4e2d\u83ef\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u570b\u653f\u5e9c\n| s = \u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u653f\u5e9c\n| p = Zh\u014dnghu\u00e1 R\u00e9nm\u00edn G\u00f2ngh\u00e9gu\u00f3 Zh\u00e8ngf\u01d4\n}}\n\n{{Politics of China}}\n\nThe '''central government of the People's Republic of China''' is divided among several state organs:\n\n# [[National People's Congress]] (NPC): the ultimate power of the state that makes the constitution and basic laws, and supervise and elects all following organs;\n# [[Standing Committee of the National People's Congress]] (NPCSC): the permanent legislative organ which makes most laws, interprets the constitution and laws, conducts [[constitutional review]], and supervise all following organs;\n# [[President of the People's Republic of China|President]], act as a ceremonial [[head of state]] in compliance with decisions made by the NPCSC, but exercises an independent power to nominate the Premier of the State Council; and the [[Vice President of the People's Republic of China|Vice-President]], who has no power itself, but assist the President.\n# [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council]] (synonymous with \"Central People's Government\"): the executive branch, whose [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Premier]] is the [[head of government]];\n# [[Central Military Commission (China)|Central Military Commission]] (CMC): the military branch, whose [[Chairman of the Central Military Commission|Chairman]] is the [[commander-in-chief]] of the national armed forces including the [[People's Liberation Army]] (PLA), the [[People's Armed Police]] (PAP), and the [[Militia (China)|Militia]];\n# [[National Supervisory Commission]] (NSC): the supervisory branch;\n# [[Supreme People's Court]] (SPC): the judicial branch;\n# [[Supreme People's Procuratorate]] (SPP): the prosecutorial branch.\n\nThe legal power of the [[Communist Party of China|Communist Party]] is guaranteed by [[Constitution of China|the PRC Constitution]] and its position as the supreme political authority in the PRC is realised through its comprehensive control of the state, military, and media.<ref>Ralph H. Folsom, John H. Minan, Lee Ann Otto, ''Law and Politics in the People's Republic of China'', [[West (publisher)|West Publishing]] (St. Paul, 1992), pp.&nbsp;76\u201377.</ref> According to a prominent government spokesman:<blockquote>We will never simply copy the system of Western countries or introduce a system of multiple parties holding office in rotation; although China\u2019s state organs have different responsibilities, they all adhere to the line, principles and policies of the party.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/7932091.stm \"China 'will not have democracy'] China will never adopt Western-style democracy with a multi-party system, its top legislator has said.\" BBC 9 March 2009, accessed October 9, 2010.</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe primary organs of state power are the [[National People's Congress]], the [[President of the People's Republic of China|President]], and the [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council]]. Members of the State Council include the [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Premier]], a variable number of [[Vice Premier of the People's Republic of China|Vice Premiers]], five [[State councillor (China)|State Councilors]] (protocol equal of vice premiers but with narrower portfolios), the [[Secretary-General of the State Council|Secretary-General]], and now 26 [[Ministries of the People's Republic of China|ministers and other cabinet-level department heads]].  During the 1980s there was an attempt made to separate party and state functions, with the party deciding general policy and the state carrying it out. The attempt was abandoned in the 1990s with the result that the political leadership within the state are also the leaders of the party. This dual structure thereby creates a single centralized focus of power.\n\nAt the same time there has been a move to separate party and state offices at levels other than the central government. It is not unheard of for a sub-national executive to also be party secretary.  This frequently causes conflict between the chief executive and the party secretary, and this conflict is widely seen as intentional to prevent either from becoming too powerful.  Some special cases are the [[special administrative regions of China|Special Administrative Regions]] of [[Hong Kong]] and [[Macau]], where according to constitution and respective basic law, most national laws do not apply and the [[autonomous regions of China|autonomous regions]] where, following Soviet practice, the chief executive is typically a member of the local ethnic group while the party general secretary is non-local and usually [[Han Chinese]].\n\nUnder the [[Constitution of China]], the NPC is the highest organ of state power in China. It meets annually for about two weeks to review and approve major new policy directions, laws, the budget, and major personnel changes. Most national legislation in the PRC is adopted by the [[Standing Committee of the National People's Congress]]. Most initiatives are presented to the NPCSC for consideration by the State Council after previous endorsement by the Communist Party's Politburo Standing Committee. Although the NPC generally approves State Council policy and personnel recommendations, the NPC and its standing committee has increasingly asserted its role as the national legislature and has been able to force revisions in some laws. For example, the State Council and the Party have been unable to secure passage of a fuel tax to finance the construction of [[Expressways of China|expressways]].<ref>[http://www.rsc.org/chemistryworld/Issues/2009/January/ChinaBitesTheBulletOnFuelTax.asp China bites the bullet on fuel tax]. Rsc.org (2009-01-01). Retrieved on 2013-07-21.</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/spl/hi/in_depth/china_politics/government/html/7.stm Bbc News]. BBC News. Retrieved on 2013-07-21.</ref>\n\n== Political leadership ==\n{{Main|Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of China}}\n\n[[File:Danghui.svg|thumb|upright|Emblem of the [[Communist Party of China]] ]]\n\nThe Politburo Standing Committee consists of the government's top leadership. Historically it has five to nine members, and currently has seven members. Its officially mandated purpose is to conduct policy discussions and make decisions on major issues when the Politburo, a larger decision-making body, is not in session. According to the party's [[Constitution of the Communist Party of China|Constitution]], the [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|General Secretary of the Central Committee]] must also be a member of the Politburo Standing Committee.<ref>[http://www.china.org.cn/english/features/49109.htm#4 Chapter III Central Organizations of the Party - Article 22]</ref>\n\nThe membership of the PSC is strictly ranked in [[Orders of precedence in the People's Republic of China|protocol sequence]]. Historically, the general secretary (or party chairman) has been ranked first; the rankings of other leaders have varied over time. Since the 1990s, the general secretary, premier, chairman of the [[National People's Congress]], the chairman of the [[Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference]], the secretary of the [[Central Commission for Discipline Inspection]], the party's top anti-graft body, and the first-ranked secretary of the [[Secretariat of the Communist Party of China|secretariat]] have consistently also been members of the Politburo Standing Committee.<ref name=\"CF111312\">{{cite news |title = China's Next Leaders: A Guide to What's at Stake |url = http://www.chinafile.com/china%E2%80%99s-next-leaders-guide-what%E2%80%99s-stake |access-date = 18 November 2012 |newspaper = China File |date = 13 November 2012 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130210034750/http://www.chinafile.com/china%E2%80%99s-next-leaders-guide-what%E2%80%99s-stake |archive-date = 2013-02-10 |url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\n== Paramount leader ==\n[[File:Xi Jinping March 2017.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Paramount leader]] and [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|General Secretary]] [[Xi Jinping]] ]]\n{{Main article|Paramount leader}}\n\nPower is concentrated in the [[Paramount leader]], currently [[Xi Jinping]], who heads the four most important political and state offices: He is [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|General Secretary]] of the [[Communist Party of China|Communist Party]], general secretary of the [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of China|Central Committee]], [[Chairman of the Central Military Commission]], and [[President of the People's Republic of China|President]] of the PRC.<ref>{{cite web |url =https://multimedia.scmp.com/widgets/china/cpc-primer/ |title = A simple guide to the Chinese government|publisher=[[South China Morning Post]] |quote = [[Xi Jinping]] is the most powerful figure in the Chinese political system. He is the [[President of the People's Republic of China|President of China]], but his real influence comes from his position as the [[General Secretary of the Chinese Communist Party]].}}</ref> Recently, experts have observed growing limitations to the Paramount leader's ''de facto'' control over the government.<ref>{{cite news | first = Andrew | last = Higgins | title = Hu's visit spotlights China's two faces | date = 2011-01-16 | publisher = [[The Washington Post Company]] | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/01/15/AR2011011504013.html | newspaper = [[The Washington Post]] | access-date = 2011-01-17 }}</ref>\n\n== Constitution ==\n{{Main|Constitution of the People's Republic of China}}\n\nThe Constitution was first created on September 20, 1954. Before that an interim constitution-like document created by the [[Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference]] was in force. The second promulgation in 1975 shortened the Constitution to just about 30 articles, and contained Communist slogans and revolutionary language throughout. The role of courts was slashed, and the Presidency was gone. The 3rd promulgation in 1978 expanded the number of articles, but was still under  the influence of the just-gone-by Cultural Revolution.\n\nThe current constitution is the PRC's fourth promulgation. On December 4, 1982, it was promulgated and has served as a stable constitution for 30 years. The roles of the presidency and the courts were normalized, and under the constitution, all citizens were equal. Amendments in 1988, 1993, 1999, 2004, and 2018 recognized private property, safeguarded human rights, and further promoted the non-public sector of the economy.\n\n==National People's Congress==\n{{Main|National People's Congress}}\n[[image:The 1st Session of the 12th National People's Congress open 20130305.jpg|thumb|right|270px|The 12th [[National People's Congress]] held in 2013]]\n\nThe [[National People's Congress]] (usually abbreviated NPC) is the national legislature of the People's Republic of China. With 2,924 members in 2017, it is the largest parliamentary body in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ipu.org/parline-e/mod-general.asp|title=IPU PARLINE Database: General Information|last=International Parliamentary Union|date=|website=|accessdate=2017-08-06}}</ref> Under China's current Constitution, the NPC is structured as a [[unicameral]] legislature, with the power to legislate, the power to oversee the operations of the government, and the power to elect the major officials of state. The NPC and the National Committee of the [[Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference|People's Political Consultative Conference]] (CPPCC), a consultative body whose members represent various social groups, are the main deliberative bodies of China, and are often referred to as the [[Lianghui]] (Two Assemblies).<ref>{{cite web |title = State Structure of the People's Republic of China |url = http://www.npc.gov.cn/englishnpc/stateStructure/node_3826.htm |website = \u4e2d\u56fd\u4eba\u5927\u7f51 |publisher=The National People's Congress of the People's Republic of China |access-date = 2016-09-29 }}</ref>\n\nThe NPC is elected for a term of five years. It holds annual sessions every spring, usually lasting from 10 to 14 days, in the [[Great Hall of the People]] on the west side of [[Tiananmen Square]] in Beijing. The NPC's sessions are usually timed to occur with the meetings of the CPPCC, and these annual meetings provide an opportunity for the officers of state to review past policies and present future plans to the nation. The fourth session of the 12th NPC was held from March 5 to March 16, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |title = The National People's Congress of the People's Republic of China |access-date = 2016-11-08 |url = http://www.npc.gov.cn/englishnpc/news/Events/node_2762_3.htm |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170202001035/http://www.npc.gov.cn/englishnpc/news/Events/node_2762_3.htm |archive-date = 2017-02-02 |url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\n== President ==\n{{Main|President of the People's Republic of China}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left; float:right; margin-right:9px; margin-left:2px;\"\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[File:Mao Zedong portrait.jpg|100px]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[File:LiuShaoqi Colour.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Mao Zedong]]<br /><small>[[List of Presidents of the People's Republic of China|First]] [[Chairman of the Communist Party of China|Chairman]]</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Liu Shaoqi]]<br /><small>[[List of Presidents of the People's Republic of China|2nd]] [[President of the People's Republic of China|Chairman]]</small>\n|}\nThe [[President of the People's Republic of China]] is the [[head of state]]. Under the PRC's [[Constitution of the People's Republic of China|constitution]], the presidency is a largely [[Figurehead|ceremonial office]] with limited powers.<ref name=\"auto\">[http://www.kkhsou.in/main/polscience/structure_function.html Krishna Kanta Handique State Open University], EXECUTIVE: THE PRESIDENT OF THE CHINESE REPUBLIC.</ref> However, since 1993, as a matter of convention, the presidency has been held simultaneously by the [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China]], the top [[Paramount leader|leader]] in the [[One-party state|one-party system]].<ref>{{cite news |title = Does Chinese leader Xi Jinping plan to hang on to power for more than 10 years? |url = http://www.scmp.com/news/china/policies-politics/article/2111123/does-chinese-leader-xi-jinping-plan-hang-power-more-10 |date=6 October 2017 |quote = If Xi relinquished the presidency in 2023 but remained party chief and chairman of the Central Military commission (CMC), his successor as president would be nothing more than a symbolic figure... \u201cOnce the president is neither the party\u2019s general secretary nor the CMC chairman, he or she will be hollowed out, just like a body without a soul.\u201d}}</ref> The office is officially regarded as [[Government of the People's Republic of China|an institution of the state]] rather than an administrative post; theoretically, the president serves at the pleasure of the [[National People's Congress]], the legislature, and is not legally vested to take executive action on its own prerogative.{{NoteTag|It is listed as such in the current Constitution; it is thus equivalent to organs such as the State Council, rather than to offices such as that of the premier.}} The current president is [[Xi Jinping]], who took office in March 2013.\n\nThe office was first established in the [[Constitution of the People's Republic of China]] in 1954 and successively held by [[Mao Zedong]] and [[Liu Shaoqi]]. Liu fell into political disgrace during the [[Cultural Revolution]], after which the office became vacant. The office was abolished under the Constitution of 1975, then reinstated in the Constitution of 1982, but with reduced powers. The official English-language [[translation]] of the title was \"[[Chairman]]\"; after 1982, this translation was changed to \"[[President (government title)|President]]\", although the Chinese title remains unchanged.{{NoteTag|In [[Chinese language|Chinese]] the President of the PRC is termed ''zh\u01d4x\u00ed'' (\u4e3b\u5e2d) while the Presidents of other countries are termed ''z\u01d2ngt\u01d2ng'' (\u603b\u7edf). Furthermore ''zh\u01d4x\u00ed'' continues to have the meaning of \"chairman\" in a generic context.}} In March 2018, presidential term limits were abolished.<ref>{{cite web|author=Steven Lee Myers |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/11/world/asia/china-xi-constitution-term-limits.html |title=China's Legislature Blesses Xi's Indefinite Rule. It Was 2,958 to 2. |website=The New York Times |date=March 11, 2018 |accessdate=2019-11-10}}</ref>\n\n== State Council ==\n{{Main article|State Council of the People's Republic of China}}\n{{Further|Premier of the People's Republic of China|Ministries of the People's Republic of China}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left; float:right; margin-right:9px; margin-left:2px;\"\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[File:Zhou Enlai in 1959.jpg|120px]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[File:Li Keqiang (cropped).jpg|100px]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Zhou Enlai]]<br /><small>[[List of Premiers of the People's Republic of China|First]] [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Premier]]</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Li Keqiang]]<br /><small>[[List of Premiers of the People's Republic of China|Current]] [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Premier]]</small>\n|}\n\nThe State Council is the chief authority of the People's Republic of China. It is appointed by the National People's Congress and is chaired by the [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Premier]] and includes the heads of each governmental department and agency. There are about 50 members in the council. In the politics of the People's Republic of China, the [[Central People's Government]] forms one of three interlocking branches of power, the others being the Communist Party of China and the People's Liberation Army. The State Council directly oversees the various subordinate People's Governments in the provinces, and in practice maintains an interlocking membership with the top levels of the Communist Party of China.\n\nCurrently the [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Premier of the State Council]] is [[Li Keqiang]] and the [[Vice Premier of the People's Republic of China|Vice Premiers]] are [[Han Zheng]], [[Sun Chunlan]], [[Hu Chunhua]] and [[Liu He (politician)|Liu He]]. Together with the five [[State Councilor]]s, they form the [[Li Keqiang Government|inner cabinet]] that regularly convenes for the [http://english.gov.cn/statecouncil/meetings/ State Council Executive Meeting].<ref>{{cite book |title = China's political system |last=Heilmann |first=Sebastian |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |year=2017 |isbn = 978-1-4422-7736-6 |pages=76\u201380 }}</ref>\n\n== Central Military Commission ==\n{{Main|Central Military Commission (China)}}\n\n[[File:ChinaDOD.jpg|thumb|The CMC is housed in the [[Ministry of National Defense of the People's Republic of China|Ministry of National Defense]] compound (\"August 1st Building\")]]\n\nThe Central Military Commission exercises the command and control of the [[People's Liberation Army]] and is supervised by the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress. The state CMC is nominally considered the supreme military policy-making body and its chairman, elected by the National People's Congress, is the commander-in-chief of the armed forces. In reality, command and control of the PLA, however, still resides with the Central Military Commission of the Chinese Communist Party Central Committee.\n\nCurrently the chairman of the Central Military Commission is [[Xi Jinping]].\n\n== National Supervisory Commission ==\n{{Main|National Supervisory Commission}}\n\nThe [[National Supervisory Commission]] of the People's Republic of China is the highest supervisory ([[List of anti-corruption agencies|anti-corruption]]) agency of the [[People's Republic of China]]. It supervises all public officials who exercise public power, at the same administrative ranking as the [[Supreme People's Court]] and [[Supreme People's Procuratorate]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chinalawtranslate.com/\u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u76d1\u5bdf\u6cd5\uff08\u8349\u6848\uff09/?lang=en |location=China |title=People's Republic of China Supervision Law (draft) |website=China Law Translate |publisher= |date=6 November 2017 |access-date=27 January 2018 }}</ref> Its operations are merged with the [[Central Commission for Discipline Inspection]] of the [[Communist Party of China]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.ccdi.gov.cn/special/zmsjd/zm19da_zm19da/201802/t20180202_163176.html |trans-title = Why should the National Supervisory Commission merges its operations with the Central Commission for Discipline Inspection of CPC? |script-title = zh:\u4e3a\u4ec0\u4e48\u4e2d\u592e\u7eaa\u59d4\u4e0e\u56fd\u5bb6\u76d1\u5bdf\u59d4\u5458\u4f1a\u8981\u5408\u7f72\u529e\u516c\uff1f |language = zh-CN |website = Website of CCDI&NSC |date = 2 Feb 2018 |access-date = 2 April 2018 }}</ref> It replaces the former [[Ministry of Supervision]].\n \nCurrently the director of National Supervisory Commission is [[Yang Xiaodu]].\n\n== Supreme People's Court and Supreme People's Procuratorate ==\n{{Main article|Supreme People's Court|Supreme People's Procuratorate}}\n\n[[File:Supreme People's Court of P.R.China's badge.svg|thumb|100px|Emblem of the [[Supreme People's Court|People's Court]]s]]\n[[File:Supreme People's Procuratorate of P.R.China's badge .svg|thumb|100px|Emblem of the [[People's Procuratorate]] ]]\n\nThe Supreme People's Court is of the People's Republic of China. Hong Kong and Macau, as special administrative regions, have separate judicial systems based on British common law traditions and Portuguese civil-law traditions respectively, and are out of the jurisdiction of the Supreme People's Court. The judges of the Supreme People's Court are appointed by the National People's Congress.\n\n{{As of|2018}}, the President of Supreme People's Court and the Procurator-General of Supreme People's Procuratorate are [[Zhou Qiang]] and [[Zhang Jun (politician)|Zhang Jun]] separately.\n\n== Provincial and local government ==\n{{Main|Administrative divisions of the People's Republic of China}}\nThe governors of China's [[Provinces of China|provinces]] and [[Autonomous regions of China|autonomous regions]] and mayors of its [[Direct-controlled municipalities of China|centrally controlled municipalities]] are appointed by the central government in Beijing after receiving the nominal consent of the [[National People's Congress]] (NPC). The [[Hong Kong]] and [[Macau]] special administrative regions (SARS) have some local autonomy since they have separate governments, legal systems, and basic constitutional laws, but they come under Beijing's control in matters of [[foreign policy]] and [[national security]], and their chief executives are handpicked by the central government. Below the provincial level in 2004 there were 50 rural prefectures, 283 prefecture-level cities, 374 county-level cities, 852 county-level districts under the jurisdiction of nearby cities, and 1,636 counties. There also were 662 cities (including those incorporated into the four centrally controlled municipalities), 808 urban districts, and 43,258 township-level regions. \n\nCounties are divided into townships and villages. While most have appointed officials running them, some lower-level jurisdictions have direct popular elections. The organs of self-governing ethnic autonomous areas (regions, prefectures, and counties)\u2014people's congresses and people's governments\u2014exercise the same powers as their provincial-level counterparts but are guided additionally by the Law on Regional Ethnic Autonomy and require NPC Standing Committee approval for regulations they enact \"in the exercise of autonomy\" and \"in light of the political, economic, and cultural characteristics of the ethnic group or ethnic groups in the areas.\"{{cn|date=January 2019}}\n\nWhile operating under strict control and supervision by the central government, China's local governments manage relatively high share of fiscal revenues and expenditures.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kadochnikov|first=Denis V.|date=2019-12-29|title=Fiscal decentralization and regional budgets' changing roles: a comparative case study of Russia and China|journal=Area Development and Policy|language=en|volume=|pages=1\u201319|doi=10.1080/23792949.2019.1705171|issn=2379-2949}}</ref>\n\n== Civil service ==\n{{Main|Civil service of the People's Republic of China}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Political systems of Imperial China]]\n* [[Government of the Republic of China|Five Yuans of the Republic of China]]\n* [[Central People's Government of the People's Republic of China (1949\u201354)]]\n* [[History of political parties in China]]\n* [[Politics of China|Politics of the People's Republic of China]]\n** [[Elections in China]]\n** [[Orders of precedence in China]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{NoteFoot}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Country study |country = China |abbr = cn |section = Government and Politics }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://english.gov.cn/ Official website of the Chinese Central Government] {{in lang|en}}  \n* [http://www.e-gov.org.cn/ China e-Government Network]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081224110923/http://www.chinainnovations.org/ China Government Innovation Network]\n* [http://www.ccgp.gov.cn/ China Government Procurement Information Network]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090504140432/http://govinfo.nlc.gov.cn/ Chinese Government Public Information Online Service Platform]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090830033427/http://www.prcgovernment.org/ Guide to Chinese Government Agencies]\n* [http://english.people.com.cn/data/organs/home.html Links to information regarding branches and departments of the PRC]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080518042419/http://www.uschina.org/public/china/govstructure/ US-China Business Council's PRC Central Government Structure Report]\n\n{{-}}\n\n{{PRC State Organs}}\n{{Separation of powers}}\n{{People's Republic of China politics}}\n{{China topics |state = autocollapse }}\n{{Asia topic |Government of |title = Governments of Asia }}\n{{Portal bar|Politics|China}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Government Of The People's Republic Of China}}\n\n[[Category:Government of China| ]]\n", "name_user": "Kenwick", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Government_of_China"}
{"title_page": "Louth, Lincolnshire", "text_new": "{{Short description|Large market town and civil parish in the East Lindsey district of Lincolnshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country                 = England\n|coordinates             = {{coord|53.3669|-0.0061|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name           = Louth\n|static_image_name       = St James\u2019 Church.jpg\n| population             = 16,419\n| population_ref         = ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]])<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=1170215530|title=Louth Parish|accessdate=4 March 2018}}</ref>\n|civil_parish            = Louth\n|shire_district          = [[East Lindsey]]\n|region                  = East Midlands\n|shire_county            = [[Lincolnshire]]\n|constituency_westminster= [[Louth and Horncastle (UK Parliament constituency)|Louth and Horncastle]]\n|post_town               = LOUTH\n|postcode_district       = LN11\n|postcode_area           = LN\n|dial_code               = 01507\n|os_grid_reference       = TF326874\n|map_type                = Lincolnshire\n|london_distance_mi      = 130<!-- straight line per MOS \u2013 constant and comparable with other place distances -->\n|london_direction        = S\n}}\n\n'''Louth''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=En-louth.ogg|l|a\u028a|\u03b8}}) is a large [[market town]] and [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] in the [[East Lindsey]] district of [[Lincolnshire]], England.<ref name=EX283>OS Explorer map 283:Louth and Mablethorpe: (1:25 000):\n{{ISBN|978 0319238240}}</ref> Louth is the principal town and centre for a large rural area of eastern Lincolnshire. Visitor attractions include St. James' Church, Hubbard's Hills, the market, many independent retailers, and Lincolnshire's last remaining cattle market.<ref>{{cite news|title=Farmers have mixed views over future of Lincolnshire's only surviving cattle market|url=http://www.lincolnshirelive.co.uk/farmers-mixed-views-future-lincolnshire-s/story-28467705-detail/story.html|accessdate=20 March 2017|publisher=Lincolnshire Live|date=7 January 2016}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n==History==\n[[File:St James' Church Louth.jpg|thumb|St James' Church Louth]]\nThree handaxes have been found on the [[The Wolds|wolds]] surrounding Louth, dating from between 424,000 and 191,000 years ago, indicating inhabitation in [[Paleolithic]] era.<ref name=\"Green2011\">{{cite book|author=Tom Green|title=The Origins of Louth: Archaeology and History in East Lincolnshire 400,000 BC-AD 1086|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NhkHYntyRwYC|year=2011|publisher=Tom Green|isbn=978-0-9570336-0-3|pages=4\u20137}}</ref> [[Bronze Age]] archeological finds include a 'barbed and tanged' arrowhead found in the grounds of [[Monks' Dyke Tennyson College]].<ref name=\"Green2011b\">{{cite book|author=Tom Green|title=The Origins of Louth: Archaeology and History in East Lincolnshire 400,000 BC-AD 1086|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NhkHYntyRwYC|year=2011|publisher=Tom Green|isbn=978-0-9570336-0-3|page=33}}</ref>\n\nSt Helen's Spring, at the Gatherums, off Aswell Street, is dedicated to a popular medieval saint, the [[Helena (empress)|mother]] of [[Constantine the Great]], the first [[Roman Emperor]] to become a Christian,<ref name=\"Historical Significance\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gatherumsandspringside.org.uk/history.html |title=Historical Significance |accessdate=9 November 2013 |publisher=Gatherums and Springside |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109072647/http://www.gatherumsandspringside.org.uk/history.html |archivedate=9 November 2013 }}</ref> but is thought to be a Christianised [[Romano-British culture|Romano-British]] site for veneration of the pagan water-goddess Alauna.<ref name=\"Green2011c\">{{cite book|author=Tom Green|title=The Origins of Louth: Archaeology and History in East Lincolnshire 400,000 BC-AD 1086|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NhkHYntyRwYC|year=2011|publisher=Tom Green|isbn=978-0-9570336-0-3|pages=52\u201353}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Anglo-Saxon]] pagan burial ground, northwest of Louth, dates from the fifth to sixth centuries, and was first excavated in 1946.<ref name=\"Historical Significance\"/> With an estimated 1200 urn burials it is one of the largest [[Anglo-Saxon]] cremation cemeteries in England.<ref name=\"Green2011a\">{{cite book|author=Tom Green|title=The Origins of Louth: Archaeology and History in East Lincolnshire 400,000 BC-AD 1086|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NhkHYntyRwYC|year=2011|publisher=Tom Green|isbn=978-0-9570336-0-3|page=68}}</ref>\n\n[[\u00c6thelhard]], a [[Bishop of Winchester]] who was made [[Archbishop of Canterbury]] in 793, was an [[abbot]] of Louth in his early life.<ref name=DNB>Williams \"[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/8910 \u00c6thelheard (d. 805)]\" ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography''</ref>\n\nLouth is listed in the 1086 ''[[Domesday Book]]'' as a town of 124 households.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://domesdaymap.co.uk/place/TF3287/louth/ | title = Louth | accessdate = 9 November 2013 | work = Open Domesday}}</ref>\n\n[[Louth Park Abbey]] was founded in 1139 by the [[Bishop of Lincoln|Bishop]] [[Alexander of Lincoln]] as a daughter-house of the [[Cistercian]] [[Fountains Abbey]] in [[Yorkshire]].<ref>David M. Smith, \u2018Alexander (d. 1148)\u2019, ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'', Oxford University Press, 2004.</ref> Following its dissolution in 1536 it fell into ruin and, today, only earthworks survive, on private land, between Louth and [[Keddington]].<ref>{{cite PastScape|mnumber=354511 |mname=Louth Abbey |accessdate=13 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://cistercians.shef.ac.uk/abbeys/louth_park.php | title = Cistercian Abbeys: LOUTH PARK | accessdate = 13 November 2013 | work = The Cistercian In Yorkshire}}</ref> Monks' Dyke, now a ditch, was originally dug to supply the abbey with water from the springs of Ashwell and St. Helen's at Louth.<ref>{{cite PastScape|mnumber=354511 |mname=Monks Dyke |accessdate=13 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1643, Sir Charles Bolles, a resident of Louth, raised a 'hastily-got-up soldiery' for the [[Cavalier|Royalist]] cause in the [[English Civil War]]. Fighting took place in, and around the town and, at one point, Bolles was forced to take refuge under the Ramsgate bridge.<ref name=\"BAYLEY1834\">{{cite book|author=Robert Slater BAYLEY|title=Notiti\u00e6 Lud\u00e6, Or Notices of Louth. &#91;By Robert S. Bayley. With Plates.&#93;|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_GdZUAAAAcAAJ|year=1834|publisher=The Author|pages=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_GdZUAAAAcAAJ/page/n93 77]\u201378}}</ref> By the battle's end 'Three strangers, being souldgeres, was slain at a skirmish at Lowth, and was buryed'.<ref name=\"BAYLEY1834\"/> Human remains, found during archaeological visits to [[Louth Park Abbey]] during the 1800s, in 'a little space surrounded by a ditch', were believed to date from the [[English Civil War|Civil War]] as two cannonballs, from that era, were found with the bodies.<ref name=\"trollope\">{{cite book | last1 = Trollope | first1 = Edward | title = Reports and papers of the architectural and archaeological societies of the counties of Lincoln and Northampton | chapter = The Architectural remains of Louth Park Abbey | publisher = James Williamson | location = Lincoln | year = 1873 | url = https://archive.org/stream/reportspapersofa12asso#page/n7/mode/2up | accessdate = 12 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Louth-flood.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|left|A stone plaque on Bridge Street showing the flood water level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.louthleader.co.uk/news/local/planning-enforcement-to-investigate-bridge-street-flood-marker-1-6864366|title=Planning Enforcement to investigate Bridge Street flood marker|publisher=}}</ref>]]\nThe [[Louth flood of 1920]] occurred in the town on 29 May 1920, causing 23 deaths. One woman climbed a chimney to survive, another was the only survivor from a row of twelve terrace houses, which were destroyed by the flood waters.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article27777450 |title=A CLOUDBURST. |newspaper=[[The West Australian]] |location=Perth |date=1 June 1920 |accessdate=12 November 2013 |page=7 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Four stone plaques exist in the town to show how high the water level reached. Other, less devastating floods occurred in July 1968 and on 25 June and 20 July in [[2007 United Kingdom floods|2007]].\n\n[[Margaret Wintringham]] succeeded her [[Thomas Wintringham (Liberal politician)|dead husband]] at the [[1921 Louth by-election|Louth by-election]] in September 1921, to become the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberals]]' first female MP, and Britain's third female MP.<ref>{{cite news|title=Women in the House of Commons House of Commons Information Office Factsheet M4 Appendix B|url=http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons-information-office/m04b.pdf|accessdate=3 January 2017|publisher=parliament.uk}}</ref>\n\n===St Herefrith of Louth===\nSt Herefrith,<ref>{{PASE|20747|Herefrith 10|cw=1}}</ref> or Herefrid, is Louth's 'forgotten saint',<ref>{{cite news|title=The forgotten Saint of Louth is remembered |date=2 November 2011 |url=http://www.thisislincolnshire.co.uk/forgotten-Saint-Louth-remembered/story-13730118-detail/story.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20131112043551/http://www.thisislincolnshire.co.uk/forgotten-Saint-Louth-remembered/story-13730118-detail/story.html |url-status=dead |archivedate=12 November 2013 |work=This Is Lincolnshire |accessdate=12 November 2013 }}</ref> whose feast day is 27 February.<ref>{{cite news | title = ANNIVERSARIES | date = 27 February 1995 | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/anniversaries-1575080.html | work = The Independent | accessdate = 12 November 2013}}</ref> He was a bishop, who died around 873, possibly killed by the [[Danes (Germanic tribe)|Danes]].<ref name=\"Farmer2011\">{{cite book|author=David Farmer|title=The Oxford Dictionary of Saints, Fifth Edition Revised|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_zJJtvK2_KsC&pg=PA209|date=14 April 2011|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-959660-7|page=209}}</ref> An 11th-century text describes Herefrith as [[Bishop of Lincoln]], but as the bishopric there dates to 1072, Lincoln more probably refers to [[Kingdom of Lindsey|Lindsey]],<ref name=\"GreenHerefrith\">{{cite book|author=Tom Green|title=The Origins of Louth: Archaeology and History in East Lincolnshire 400,000 BC-AD 1086|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NhkHYntyRwYC&pg=PA84|year=2011|publisher=Tom Green|isbn=978-0-9570336-0-3|pages=82\u201385}}</ref> the early name for [[Lincolnshire]].<ref name=\"Farmer2011\"/> Similar confusion exists in an inventory of Louth's [[St. James Church, Louth|St. James Church]], written in 1486 and transcribed in 1512, where he is referred to as a [[Ancient Diocese of Auxerre|Bishop of Auxerre]], France.<ref name=\"peacock\">{{cite book | last1 = Peacock | first1 = Edward | title = Reports and papers of the architectural and archaeological societies of the counties of Lincoln and Northampton | chapter = Louth in the time of Henry VIII | publisher = James Williamson | location = Lincoln | year = 1873 | url = https://archive.org/stream/reportspapersofa12asso#page/n7/mode/2up | accessdate = 12 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt some point, following his death, a [[shrine]] venerating him was established at Louth. [[\u00c6thelwold of Winchester|\u00c6thelwold]], the [[Bishop of Winchester]] from 963 to 984, was actively seeking relics for his newly rebuilt [[Thorney Abbey]] in [[Cambridgeshire]] and sent his monks to Louth to raid Herefrith's shrine.<ref name=\"GreenHerefrith\"/> From an 11th-century account, [[\u00c6thelwold of Winchester|\u00c6thelwold]] had:\n<blockquote>...heard of the merits of the blessed Herefrid bishop of Lincoln resting in Louth a chief town of the same church. When all those dwelling there had been put to sleep by a cunning ruse, a trusty servant took him out of the ground, wrapped him in fine line cloth, and with all his fellows rejoicing brought him to the monastery of Thorney and re-interred him.<ref name=\"GreenHerefrith\"/></blockquote>\nA church dedicated to St. Herefrith, at Louth, appears in accounts from the 13th to 15th centuries,<ref name=\"Farmer2011\"/> and one of his relics, an ivory comb, is recorded among the possessions of Louth's [[St. James Church, Louth|St. James Church]] in 1486.<ref name=\"peacock\"/> Suggestions that the shrine, and later church, of St. Herefrith, were earlier incarnations of St. James has 'no supportive evidence' but St James' is the site of two earlier churches of which little is known.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.lincstothepast.com/St-James--Church--Louth/228093.record?pt=S | title = St James' Church, Louth | accessdate = 12 November 2013 | work = Lincs To The Past}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n\n[[File:The site of Louth station, goods yard and the former kilns..jpg|thumb|The site of Louth station, goods yard and the former kilns. The last trains here were in 1980 before complete closure. The entire area is now a mix of housing, retail and industrial outlets. The station building can be seen in the distance with the chimneys.]]\n\n[[Louth railway station]] was a major intermediate station on the [[East Lincolnshire Railway]] which ran from [[Boston railway station|Boston]] to [[Grimsby railway station|Grimsby]] from 1848 and was also once served by [[rail motor]] services.\n\nLouth was the northern terminus of the [[Mablethorpe loop railway|Mablethorpe Loop]]. The line which ran through the nearby villages and seaside towns of [[Mablethorpe]], [[Sutton-on-Sea]], [[Grimoldby]], [[Saltfleetby]], [[Theddlethorpe]], [[Mumby]] and [[Willoughby, Lincolnshire|Willoughby]]. The station was the terminus on the [[Louth to Bardney Line]] which opened in 1876 but closed in 1951 to passengers and to freight traffic in 1960. Bardney was the terminus of the branch line and was on the [[Lincolnshire Loop Line]]\n\nThe station closed to passengers in 1970 along with the Mablethorpe Loop Line and the section from [[Firsby railway station|Firsby]] to Louth of the East Lincolnshire Railway. The section to Grimsby remained in use for freight traffic until December 1980 when it closed and was later removed.\n\nThe station building and Louth North Signal Box remain in situ to this day as private dwellings. All of the station site has been built on by residential and commercial outlets.\n\nThere are plans to eventually have Louth as the southern terminus of the [[Lincolnshire Wolds Railway]] which would utilise the trackbed from Louth to Holton-Le-Clay, although it will be to the north of Louth due to the station building now being occupied and the station site around it built over. This would mean Louth would have a rail connection for the first time in almost 50 years, since the closure to passengers in 1970, but at a new station site.\n\nA canal was built between 1765 and 1770 to connect Louth to the sea at Tetney. It was formally abandoned in 1924.\nA fuller account is at [[Louth Canal]].\n\nThere are regular buses connecting Louth with the nearby Grimsby, Skegness, Mablethorpe and Lincoln. There is also a direct service once a month to [[York]] and National Express coaches call at Louth bus station. All services are operated by different companies but the main one is [[Stagecoach]]. However, unlike other towns. The town is not served by late-night services with the last bus departing the town at 7:00 pm.\n\nThe nearest active railway station is now Grimsby and Skegness.\n\n==St James' Church==\n[[File:Lincolnshire Rising plaque - geograph.org.uk - 860306.jpg|thumb|Lincolnshire Rising plaque in Louth]]\n{{see also|St James' Church, Louth|Lincolnshire Rising}}\n\nThe town was the origin of the [[Lincolnshire Rising]], which started on 1 October 1536 in [[St. James Church, Louth|St James Church]]. The rising began after Rev. Thomas Kendall, the incumbent, gave an 'emotive sermon',<ref name=\"FletcherStevenson1987\">{{cite book|author1=Anthony Fletcher|author2=John Stevenson|title=Order and Disorder in Early Modern England|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6_Cq4-WFX6cC&pg=PA71|date=4 June 1987|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-34932-1|page=71}}</ref> the evening before the King's Commissioners were due to arrive and assess the church's wealth.<ref name=\"Porter2010\">{{cite book|author=Linda Porter|title=Katherine the Queen|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WbQmKuq_ZHoC&pg=PT60|date=10 March 2010|publisher=Pan Macmillan UK|isbn=978-1-74303-570-2|page=60}}</ref> Some of the townspeople, fearful that the [[church treasury]] would be seized by the men of the Crown, demanded the building's keys.<ref name=\"FletcherStevenson1987\"/> The townspeople kept vigil that night, and, the following day, rang the church bells, 'an ancient call to rebellion', to gather a crowd.<ref name=\"Porter2010\"/> Having begun marching from Louth, 50,000 supporters converged to camp at Hembleton Hill, the following evening, before they continued to Lincoln to confront the King's Commissioners.\n\nThe town's skyline is dominated by [[St James' Church, Louth]], the spire.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/481423|title=St.James' church (C) Richard Croft|website=www.geograph.org.uk}}</ref> A recent survey has confirmed the height of the stonework as {{convert|287|ft|6|in|m}} and to the top of the cockerel weather vane as {{convert|293|ft|1|in|m}}. It also confirms it as one of the very finest medieval steeples in the country<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thamesandhudson.com/Fifty_English_Steeples/9780500343142|title=Thames & Hudson Publishers  {{!}}  Essential illustrated art books {{!}}  Fifty English Steeples {{!}} The Finest Medieval Parish Church Towers and Spires in England|website=www.thamesandhudson.com|accessdate=29 October 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161030080913/http://www.thamesandhudson.com/Fifty_English_Steeples/9780500343142|archivedate=30 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Though shorter than both [[Norwich Cathedral]] {{convert|315|ft|m|0}}, and [[Salisbury Cathedral]] {{convert|404|ft|m|0}}, in terms of spire height it is the tallest medieval parish church in the United Kingdom. The building of the spire commenced in 1501 and was finally completed in 1515.\n\nIn 2015 came a remarkable discovery from the adjoining Rectory garden in the form of two pieces of a pre-Conquest standing stone Cross dating to c950. In form the Cross is of the 'ring' or 'wheel head' type, the central design being of Christ crucified. The type is more commonly seen today in Ireland. The Cross and its implications for the archaeology, history and the early church in Louth are discussed in a major article by Everson and Stocker ''The Cros in the Markitte Stede'. The Louth Cross, its Monastery and its Town''. (Medieval Archaeology Journal, vol. 61/2, 2017).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-lincolnshire-36070551|title=Anglo-Saxon cross fragments found|date=18 April 2016|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> The Louth Cross is on display within the church and a small booklet is available from the gift shop.\n\nIn 2017 funding was raised to fit a viewing door to the cell just below the spire floor that holds the original medieval treadwheel that was used to haul up the stone and mortar for the building of the spire (1501\u20131515). Substantial records exist in the churchwardens' accounts from 1501 onward for the construction and use of the wheel which was to become known as ''The Wild Mare.'' A small booklet about this rare survival is available from the church gift shop.\n\n==Landmarks and places of interest==\nMuch of the town centre is lined with brick buildings from the 17th and 18th centuries.\n[[File:ABM Pauls Malt Kiln - geograph.org.uk - 597153 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|Former ABM Pauls Malt Kiln]]\nLouth Museum has a Panorama Gallery, which features two back-lit replicas of William Brown's ''Panorama of Louth'' viewed from the top of St James' spire in 1844. The two original paintings that together form the panorama hang side-by-side in the Louth Town Council building - the Sessions House - on Eastgate. The panorama gives a unique and vivid representation of the streets, businesses, homes and people of the town and the landscape as far as the [[North Sea]] to the east and northwards to the [[Humber Estuary]] and beyond.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.louthmuseum.co.uk/|title=Louth Museum|accessdate=23 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nABM Pauls used to have a large malt kiln, which was the first of its kind built in Europe to an American design out of reinforced concrete in 1949. The site had been the location of a maltings since 1870 which was destroyed by German bombs in 1940, and had to be built on the old site to qualify for war compensation.<ref>{{cite news|title=American design made Louth malt kiln unique|url=http://www.louthleader.co.uk/news/features/american-design-made-louth-malt-kiln-unique-1-1009564|accessdate=16 July 2015|publisher=Louth Leader|date=26 March 2003}}</ref> At its height the maltings processed 50,000 tonnes of barley per year, with exports handled through the nearby port of [[Immingham]]. The maltings closed in 1998 and the {{convert|120|ft|m}} tall structure was left derelict for many years. The German supermarket chain [[Aldi]] was granted permission to build a new store on the site, and it was demolished in 2014/15.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Aldi supermarket in Louth will be chain's biggest in country|url=http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/New-Aldi-supermarket-Louth-chain-s-biggest/story-25881058-detail/story.html|accessdate=16 July 2015|publisher=Grimsby Telegraph|date=17 January 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722074245/http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/New-Aldi-supermarket-Louth-chain-s-biggest/story-25881058-detail/story.html|archivedate=22 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Hubbard's Hills]] is one of the town's main attractions. It was opened to the public in 1907. The park is dedicated to the memory of Annie Pahud, the central figure of a historic, tragic love affair.{{clarify|date=November 2017}} The park is in a [[glacial overspill channel]] that forged the course for a small river, the Lud. It meanders along the deep, flat valley bottom between steep, wooded slopes on either side.\n[[File:Louth from the Air - geograph.org.uk - 625313.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.8|Aerial view of part of Louth]]\nThe [[Belmont transmitting station|Belmont]] television and radio mast, once one of the tallest structures in the [[European Union]] (until its height was reduced in 2010), is in the nearby village of [[Donington on Bain]], {{convert|5|mi|km|0}} west of the town.\n\nLouth will be the eventual southern terminus of the [[Lincolnshire Wolds Railway]], based at nearby [[Ludborough]]. The town was formerly on the East Lincolnshire Railway from [[Peterborough]] to [[Grimsby]], an important north-south route especially for holidaymakers in the summer. It opened in 1848. The line to [[Mablethorpe]] started in the town from 1877, closing in 1960. The section to [[Wainfleet, Lincolnshire|Wainfleet]] closed in 1961, with the Louth to Grimsby section later continuing for passengers until October 1970, with freight stopping in 1980. The former station<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/134019|title=Louth Station (C) Richard Croft|website=www.geograph.org.uk}}</ref> is now residential flats; there are other reminders<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/134326|title=Level Crossing Gone! (C) Michael Patterson|website=www.geograph.org.uk}}</ref> still standing.\n\n[[Alfred Lord Tennyson]] was educated at [[King Edward VI Grammar School, Louth|King Edward VI Grammar School]]. A stone inscription to commemorate this forms part of a wall on Schoolhouse Lane in Louth.\n\n==Shopping and local economy==\n[[File:New Lane - geograph.org.uk - 481369.jpg|thumb|Shops on New Street]]\n\nLouth is noted for the wide selection of independent retailers, with around 70% of businesses independently owned.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.lincolnshirelife.co.uk/posts/view/luscious-louth | title = Luscious Louth | accessdate = 9 November 2013 | last = Burton | first = Melanie | work = Lincolnshire Life}}</ref> In 2012, it was named 'Britain's Favourite market town' by the [[BBC]]'s ''[[Countryfile]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.countryfile.com/countryside/countryfile-magazine-awards-results-2012 | title = Countryfile Magazine Awards: The results 2012 | accessdate = 9 November 2013 | work = CountryFile | publisher = [[Countryfile]]}}</ref>\n\nThe town's long retail history is represented by a number of longstanding businesses, including the department store Eve and Ranshaw, whose history can be traced back to 1781,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.lincolnshirelife.co.uk/shop/view-product/adam-eve-and-louth-carpets | title = Adam Eve and Louth Carpets | accessdate = 9 November 2013 | work = Lincolnshire Life}}</ref> Dales & Sons, poulterers since 1896,<ref name=\"shoplocal\">{{cite news | first = Rose | last = Prince | title = Shop Local: Louth | date = 30 June 2007 | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/foodanddrink/healthyeating/3338353/Shop-local.html | work = The Telegraph | accessdate = 9 November 2013}}</ref> and the century-old butchers, Lakings of Louth.<ref name=\"shoplocal\"/>\n\nThe first building society branch office was opened by the Peterborough Building Society (now [[Norwich & Peterborough]]) in 1973. The town was also the headquarters of the former Louth, Mablethorpe and Sutton Building Society, a local society with several branches and agents in Lincolnshire, which was taken over by the [[Bradford and Bingley Building Society|Bradford & Bingley]] in 1990.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.bsa.org.uk/consumer/factsheets/mergerschrono.htm | title = Building society mergers and conversions since 1980 | accessdate = 9 November 2013 | work = Building Societies Association}}</ref>\n\nLouth is also known for its specialist grocers,<ref name=\"shoplocal\"/> and local butchers, Meridian Meats, have won numerous awards.<ref>{{cite news | title = Louth butcher wins gold award at international food contest | date = 9 April 2013 | url = http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/Louth-butcher-wins-gold-award-international-food/story-18653564-detail/story.html | work = Grimsby Telegraph | accessdate = 9 November 2013 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131109040404/http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/Louth-butcher-wins-gold-award-international-food/story-18653564-detail/story.html | archivedate = 9 November 2013 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> It is also home to [[The Cheese Shop, Louth|The Cheese Shop]], which has gained nationwide recognition, including in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'',<ref>Davies, Paul; [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/lifestyle/shopawards/8318165/Small-wonders-the-winners-of-our-Best-Small-Shops-in-Britain-Awards.html \"Small wonders: the winners of our Best Small Shops in Britain Awards\"]; ''The Telegraph'', 11 February 2011. Retrieved 3 May 2012</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref>Cook, William; [https://www.theguardian.com/enjoy-england/lincolnshire-foodie-tour \"Keeping it real\"]; ''[[Guardian.co.uk]]'', 15 October 2010. Retrieved 3 May 2012</ref> and on ''[[The Hairy Bikers' Food Tour of Britain]]''.<ref>{{cite web|date=March 2009 |url=http://www.louthleader.co.uk/news/local/photo_hairy_bikers_film_new_tv_show_in_louth_1_1013404 |title=PHOTO: Hairy Bikers film new TV show in Louth \u2013 Local |publisher=Louth Leader |accessdate=11 March 2011}}</ref>\n[[File:Street Market-Louth - geograph.org.uk - 697817.jpg|thumb|Street market in Louth]]\nLouth holds market days on Wednesdays, Fridays and Saturdays. There is a [[farmers' market]] on the fourth Wednesday of each month. A cattle market is held each Thursday at the Louth Livestock Centre on Newmarket.\n\nThere is a small [[Morrisons]], formerly a [[Somerfield]] store,<ref>{{cite news | title = Jobs could be cut at Louth's Morrisons supermarket | date = 10 April 2013 | url = http://www.louthleader.co.uk/news/business/business-news/jobs-could-be-cut-at-louth-s-morrisons-supermarket-1-4983120 | work = Louth Leader | accessdate = 9 November 2013}}</ref> which opened in 1985, and a [[Co-operative Group|Co-operative supermarket]], which opened in 1989. The Co-op was given approval for an additional smaller store in 2013.<ref>{{cite news | first = Sam | last = Kinnaird | title = Councillor left frustrated as planning inspector gives go ahead for new Co-op supermarket in Louth | date = 31 May 2013 | url = http://www.louthleader.co.uk/news/business/business-news/councillor-left-frustrated-as-planning-inspector-gives-go-ahead-for-new-co-op-supermarket-in-louth-1-5148164 | work = Louth Leader | accessdate = 9 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, a local [[Advocacy group|pressure group]], Keep Louth Special, was formed by residents, shoppers and business owners, to lobby against a proposal for a major supermarket on the former cattle market site.<ref>{{cite news | title = Keep Louth Special group formed to stop supermarket | date = 28 November 2008 | url = http://www.louthleader.co.uk/news/local/keep-louth-special-group-formed-to-stop-supermarket-1-1012392 | work = Louth Leader | accessdate = 9 November 2013}}</ref> The group was criticised by a town councillor, the following year, as 'outsiders' who wanted to live in a 'museum town',<ref>{{cite news | title = Keep Louth Special group blasted | date = 9 February 2009 | url = http://www.louthleader.co.uk/news/local/keep-louth-special-group-blasted-1-1013195 | work = Louth Leader | accessdate = 9 November 2013}}</ref> but a 2012 council report, while recommending a 'large retail development' as \u2018necessary\u2019, acknowledged that 'a majority 50 per cent' of surveyed residents opposed it.<ref>{{cite news | first = Sam | last = Kinnaird | title = Food store development could kill small Louth shops | date = 29 November 2012 | url = http://www.louthleader.co.uk/news/local/food-store-development-could-kill-small-louth-shops-1-4532479 | work = Louth Leader | accessdate = 9 November 2013}}</ref>\nAn initial 2009 planning application by [[Sainsbury's]] for a new {{convert|30000|sqft|m2}} store,<ref>{{cite news | title = Sainsbury's arrival 'do or die' for town | date = 10 July 2009 | url = http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/Sainsbury-s-arrival-die-town/story-11536469-detail/story.html | work = Grimsby Telegraph | accessdate = 9 November 2013 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150924041355/http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/Sainsbury-s-arrival-die-town/story-11536469-detail/story.html | archivedate = 24 September 2015 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> was rejected by the Council, after appeal, in 2012.<ref>{{cite news | title = Sainsbury's store plan for Louth thrown out by councillors | date = 4 July 2012 | url = http://www.thisislincolnshire.co.uk/Sainsbury-s-store-plan-Louth-thrown-councillors/story-16478573-detail/story.html | archive-url = https://archive.is/20131109044700/http://www.thisislincolnshire.co.uk/Sainsbury-s-store-plan-Louth-thrown-councillors/story-16478573-detail/story.html | url-status = dead | archivedate = 9 November 2013 | work = This Is Lincolnshire | accessdate = 9 November 2013 }}</ref>\nKeep Louth Special described a 2013 proposal for an [[Aldi]] store as 'not bad news' because it was intended for an 'eyesore' site,<ref>{{cite news | title = Keep Louth Special says Aldi plans 'not bad news' | date = 12 July 2013 | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-lincolnshire-23245424 | work = BBC | accessdate = 9 November 2013}}</ref> and as [[Aldi]] stocks 'own brands and a limited fresh-food offering', it would not be 'going head-to-head' with the town market or independent retailers.<ref>{{cite news | title = Louth Aldi store proposal is scrutinised | date = 2 August 2013 | url = http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/Louth-Aldi-store-proposal-scrutinised/story-19604997-detail/story.html | work = Grimsby Telegraph | accessdate = 9 November 2013 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150924041028/http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/Louth-Aldi-store-proposal-scrutinised/story-19604997-detail/story.html | archivedate = 24 September 2015 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n[[File:Old Market Hall - geograph.org.uk - 481364.jpg|thumb|Old Market Hall, Louth]]\n\nMany national food campaigning organisations are based on ''Eastgate'' under the umbrella organisation the Processed Vegetable Growers Association,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pvga.co.uk|title=British Growers Association|website=www.pvga.co.uk}}</ref> notably:\n*The Asparagus Growers Association<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.british-asparagus.co.uk|title=Page Redirection|website=www.british-asparagus.co.uk}}</ref>\n*The Brassica Growers Association<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081030031455/http://www.brassicas.org/|title=Brassica Growers Association|date=30 October 2008|publisher=}}</ref>\n*The British Herb Trade Association<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhta.org.uk|title=British Herbs - Home|website=www.bhta.org.uk}}</ref>\n*The British Onion Producers Association<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishonions.co.uk|title=Home - British Onions|website=www.britishonions.co.uk}}</ref>\n*The Leek Growers Association<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.british-leeks.co.uk|title=British Leeks|website=www.british-leeks.co.uk}}</ref> \n*The Radish Growers Association\n*The Turfgrass Association<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.turfgrass.co.uk|title=The TGA - Turfgrass Growers Association|website=www.turfgrass.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Community and culture==\n[[File:Playhouse Cinema - geograph.org.uk - 479995.jpg|thumb|Playhouse Cinema, Louth.]]\n\nThe town's ''Playhouse Cinema'' is on ''[https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/780566 Cannon Street]'', and is home to Louth Film Club, which won the British Federation of Film Societies' ''Film Society of the Year Award'' in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bffs.org.uk/awards/abouttheawards.html |archive-url=https://www.webarchive.org.uk/wayback/archive/20091212210133/http://www.bffs.org.uk/awards/abouttheawards.html |url-status=dead |archivedate=12 December 2009 |title=Film Society of the Year Awards 2008 |accessdate=15 November 2009 }}</ref> Louth Playgoers Society's  ''Riverhead Theatre''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.louthplaygoers.com|title=2018 SPRING SEASON|website=Louth Riverhead Theatre}}</ref> is on ''Victoria Road'', to the east of the town.\n\nLouth is home to The New Orleans Club,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.louthjazzclub.org.uk/|title=welcome|website=www.louthjazzclub.org.uk}}</ref> a not-for-profit members' club dedicated to keeping alive the music of jazz.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.louthjazzclub.org.uk/|title=New Orleans Club's Website|last=|first=|date=|website=www.louthjazzclub.org.uk|accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref> There are several other local bands, apart from jazz, in and around the town. {{citation needed|date=November 2011}}\n\n[[Corinne Drewery]] of [[Swing Out Sister]], grew up in the area and [[Robert Wyatt]] is a resident.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/interview-robert-wyatt-the-only-way-is-up-when-youve-hit-rock-bottom-1241992.html|title=Interview: Robert Wyatt The only way is up when you've hit rock bottom|date=30 September 1997|work=The Independent|accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nTransition Town Louth<ref>http://www.transitiontownlouth.org.uk/</ref> is a community project, which organizes various events in and around the town aimed at promoting awareness of climate change and unsustainable resources. Part of a large social movement, many [[Transition Towns]] are now developing. A sub-group, the Community Food Gardens<ref>{{cite web|url=http://louthcfg.blogspot.com|title=Louth Community Food Gardens|website=louthcfg.blogspot.com}}</ref> are encouraging a shift towards sustainable communities.\n\n==Sport and leisure==\n===Meridian Leisure Centre===\n[[File:Louth Golf Course - geograph.org.uk - 416977.jpg|thumb|Louth Golf Course]]\n\nThe Centre opened on 6 February 2010, and, by 2013, had received almost one million visits, and was home to over 20 clubs.<ref>{{cite news | title = Meridian Leisure Centre nears one million visits | date = 29 January 2013 | url = http://www.louthleader.co.uk/news/local/meridian-leisure-centre-nears-one-million-visits-1-4728985 | work = Louth Leader | accessdate = 9 November 2013}}</ref> It cost \u00a312&nbsp;million and consists of an 8 lane, 25 metre swimming pool and a two level gym with over 80 pieces of equipment, along with a sports hall and other facilities. The Louth Technology Hub, which is using 3D display technology, with a focus on sports groups and clubs, opened on the Centre's upper floor in October 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.onlincolnshire.org/news/local-broadband-news/technology-hub-opening-in-louth-this-month | title = Technology hub opening in Louth this month | accessdate = 9 November 2013 | work = On Lincolnshire}}</ref>\n\n===Louth Tennis Centre===\nLouth Tennis Centre is situated on Fairfield Industrial Estate to the north of the town and has indoor and outdoor tennis facilities.\n\n===London Road Sports Pavilion===\nThere is a multiuse sports pavilion on London Road, which includes football pitches, a cricket pitch and a multi-use astroturf pitch.\n\n===Cricket===\nLouth Cricket Club was formed in 1822 and play their home games at the London Road sports pavilion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://louth.play-cricket.com/|title=Louth CC|website=louth.play-cricket.com}}</ref>\n\n===Football===\nLouth is home to [[Louth Town F.C.|Louth Town Football Club]] which plays in the [[Lincolnshire Football League]].\n\n===Cadwell Park===\nIn the Wolds to the south-west of the town, around four miles (6&nbsp;km) away, is [[Cadwell Park]] [[auto racing|motor racing]] circuit between the villages of [[Scamblesby]] and [[Tathwell]].\n\n===Other pursuits===\nLouth also hosts Louth Swimming Club, Louth Old Boys (Football), Yom Chi Taekwondo, Kendojo Martial Arts, Louth Storm Basketball, Louth Chess Club, Louth Golf Course (Crowtree Lane) and Kenwick Park Golf Course (on the outskirts of the town) as well as archery, a model aircraft club which uses [[Strubby]] and [[Manby]] Airfields and a model radio controlled car club which uses Cordeaux Academy.\n\n==Education==\n\n===Primary schools===\n*Kidgate Primary School<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kidgate.lincs.sch.uk|title=Home - Kidgate Primary Academy|website=www.kidgate.lincs.sch.uk}}</ref>\n*Lacey Gardens Junior School<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laceygardens.lincs.sch.uk|title=Lacey Gardens Junior School Louth - Home Page|website=www.laceygardens.lincs.sch.uk}}</ref>\n* St. Michael's C of E Primary School<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.st-michaels.lincs.sch.uk|title=St. Michael\u2019s C of E Primary School Louth - Home Page|website=www.st-michaels.lincs.sch.uk}}</ref>\n*Eastfield Infants and Nursery School<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastfield.lincs.sch.uk|title=Welcome to Eastfield Infants' and Nursery School|website=www.eastfield.lincs.sch.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Secondary schools===\n*[[King Edward VI Grammar School, Louth|King Edward VI Grammar School]]\n*[[Cordeaux Academy]] (closed in 2017)\n*[[Monks' Dyke Tennyson College]] (closed in 2017)\nBoth of the above merged to become:\n*Louth Academy<ref>{{cite web | url =https://lincolnshirereporter.co.uk/2017/09/schools-merger-approved-form-one-louth-academy-september-2018/ | title =Schools merger approved to form one Louth Academy from September 2018 | last =Pidluznyj | first =Stefan | website =Lincolnshire Reporter | publisher =Stonebow Media | accessdate =24 February 2018 | quote =Two comprehensive schools will merge to form one Louth Academy from September 2018. }}</ref>\n\n===Further education===\nA \u00a33-million further education college, called [[Wolds College]], was next to the Cordeaux School.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/lincolnshire/7252741.stm Worries over major college build], '' [[BBC|BBC News]]'', 19 February 2008. Retrieved 23 November 2017</ref> Construction by the Lindum Group started in November 2007, and the college officially opened in October 2008. Unlike many Lincolnshire [[secondary modern school]]s, both Cordeaux and Monks' Dyke have their own sixth forms; East Lindsey's only other secondary modern with a sixth form is at Skegness. Although the town is well served for [[Advanced Level (UK)|A-level]] provision, vocational courses were less well served until the college opened in this part of East Lindsey in September 2008, although there is the [[Grimsby Institute of Further & Higher Education|Grimsby Institute]] some fifteen miles (24&nbsp;km) away.\n\n==Twin town==\nLouth's [[Twin towns and sister cities|twin town]] is [[La Fert\u00e9-Bernard]], close to [[Le Mans]] in [[Pays-de-la-Loire]], France.\n\n==Ludensians==\nInhabitants of Louth are known as ''Ludensians'', taken from the Latin name of the town (''Lude'', ''Luda'').\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Jeffrey Archer]] was elected the town's Member of Parliament in a by-election [[1969 Louth by-election|in 1969]]. He stood down at the [[October 1974 United Kingdom general election|October 1974 general election]].\n*[[Jim Broadbent]], actor, lives in a small village just outside Louth.\n*[[Bridget Brophy]] writer, lived in Louth for many years.\n*[[Roy 'Chubby' Brown]], [[Blue comedy|adult comedian]], (real name ''Royston Vasey'') lives in nearby [[Fulstow]].\n*[[Leanda Cave]], triathlete, was born in Louth\n*[[Julie Christie]], actress, has a home in Louth, and sometimes works with the local Film Club.\n*[[Daniel Craig]], actor noted for his role as [[James Bond]], has a house between [[Legbourne, Lincolnshire|Legbourne]] and Louth.\n*[[George Davenport]], Anglo/American frontiersman, US Army officer, was born in Louth\n*[[Barbara Dickson]], singer and actress, lived in Louth\n*[[Corinne Drewery]], lead singer of the band [[Swing Out Sister]], attended schools in the town whilst growing up in the village of [[Authorpe]], between Louth and [[Alford, Lincolnshire|Alford]].\n*[[Graham Fellows]], also known as John Shuttleworth and Jilted John, a singer-songwriter and comedian lives in the town.\n*[[Michael Foale]], [[astronaut]] from the [[International Space Station]] was born at Crowtree Lane Hospital, now the Humanities block of [[King Edward VI Grammar School, Louth|King Edward VI Grammar School]]. His father was stationed at a nearby [[Royal Air Force]] base at [[Manby]].\n*[[Dave Formula]], member of [[New wave music|New Wave]] pioneers [[Magazine (band)|Magazine]], lives in Louth and often plays locally with other [[The Finks]].\n*[[James Gillick]] Figurative artist, works from his studio in Louth and lives nearby.\n*[[Ron Grant (motorcyclist)|Ron Grant]], former motorcycle [[road racing|road racer]] and tuner.\n*[[Dan Haigh]], bass guitarist in rock band [[Fightstar]], born in [[Grimsby]], was brought up near the town.\n*[[Simon Hanson]], drummer with the band Squeeze lived in Louth and attended King Edward VI school.\n*[[Graham Higman]], mathematician, was born in Louth.\n*[[Augustus Charles Hobart-Hampden]], (1 April 1822 \u2013 19 June 1886), English naval captain and [[Ottoman Empire|Turkish]] admiral, was educated at [[King Edward VI Grammar School, Louth|King Edward VI Grammar School]]. {{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}\n*[[Andreas Kalvos]] (1792 \u2013 3 November 1869), Greek writer, lived in Louth from 1852 until his death. He was the first national Greek poet. In 1960, Greece's ambassador to the UK and Nobel Prize-Winner for poetry,George Seferis, arranged for his remains to be reburied in Calvos' native Zakinthos.\n*Rev. Thomas Kendall, incumbent of [[St. James Church, Louth]] and leader of [[Lincolnshire Rising]], 1 October 1536.\n*[[Cate Kennedy]], author\n*[[Thomas Louth]], [[Lord Chief Justice of Ireland]] in the 1330s, was born in the town and took his surname from it.\n*[[Matthew Macfadyen]], actor, spent his childhood in the town.\n*[[Harry Mallett]], cricketer, was born in Louth.\n*[[Patrick Mower]], actor, currently seen in TV soap-opera [[Emmerdale]] lives in the area in [[Little Carlton]].\n*[[Philip Norton, Baron Norton of Louth]] ''(born 5 March 1951)'', leading expert on the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|British Parliament]], [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician, author and Professor of Politics at the [[University of Hull]]\n*[[Jim Payne (golfer)|Jim Payne]], professional golfer who won two [[European Tour]] tournaments.\n*[[Adrian Royle]], retired long distance runner, lives in Louth.\n*[[Ted Savage (footballer)|Ted Savage]], footballer, was born in Louth.\n*[[Edith Sharpley]], Classical Lecturer at [[Newnham College, Cambridge]], was born in Louth.\n*[[Captain John Smith]], English, soldier, sailor and founder of the Commonwealth of Virginia, although born in [[Willoughby, Lincolnshire|Willoughby]], attended the [[King Edward VI Grammar School, Louth|King Edward VI Grammar School]], where his name is adorned upon a tablet in the school's 'Edward Street Hall'. A cast iron bust of him also stands within the school's canteen.\n*[[Stuart Storey]], BBC sports commentator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/olympics2000/bbc_team/856110.stm|title=BBC SPORT - BBC TEAM - Stuart Storey|website=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n*[[Alfred, Lord Tennyson]], was born in [[Somersby, Lincolnshire|Somersby]], between Louth and [[Horncastle, Lincolnshire|Horncastle]], and was educated at [[King Edward VI Grammar School, Louth|King Edward VI Grammar School]].\n*Lieutenant Colonel [[Thomas Colclough Watson|Thomas Watson]] [[Victoria Cross|VC]], also educated at the King Edward VI Grammar<ref>{{Cite news\n  |title=Victoria Cross and medals from Lincolnshire hero to be auctioned\n  |date=4 December 2014\n  |newspaper=Lincolnshire Echo\n  |url=http://www.lincolnshireecho.co.uk/Victoria-Cross-medals-Lincolnshire-hero-auctioned/story-25152299-detail/story.html\n}}</ref>\n*[[Graham Winteringham]], architect, was born in Louth.\n*[[Margaret Wintringham]], first English woman to sit as an M.P. lived most of her life just outside the town at Little Grimsby Hall, and was elected M.P. for Louth in 1920.\n*[[Robert Wyatt]], English musician and former member of [[Soft Machine]], now lives in Louth.\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Louth, Lincolnshire}}\n{{wikivoyage|Louth, Lincolnshire|Louth}}\n*{{officila|http://www.louth.org }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20170515201218/http://louthpartnership.org.uk/ Louth Town Partnership]\n*[http://www.louthleader.co.uk Louth Leader]\n*[http://www.louthmuseum.co.uk Louth Museum]\n*[http://www.transitiontownlouth.org.uk Transition Town Louth]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130824033745/http://www.stjameschurchlouth.com/ St. James' Church]\n*[http://www.hubbardshills.co.uk Hubbard's Hills]\n*[http://www.louthtowncouncil.gov.uk Louth Town Council]\n*[http://www.louthcanal.org.uk Louth Navigation Trust]\n\n{{Lincolnshire|state=collapsed}}\n{{East Lindsey (district) |state=collapsed}}\n{{Portal bar|England|United Kingdom}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Louth, Lincolnshire| ]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Market towns in Lincolnshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Large market town and civil parish in the East Lindsey district of Lincolnshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country                 = England\n|coordinates             = {{coord|53.3669|-0.0061|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name           = Louth\n|static_image_name       = St James\u2019 Church.jpg\n| population             = 16,419\n| population_ref         = ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]])<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=1170215530|title=Louth Parish|accessdate=4 March 2018}}</ref>\n|civil_parish            = Louth\n|shire_district          = [[East Lindsey]]\n|region                  = East Midlands\n|shire_county            = [[Lincolnshire]]\n|constituency_westminster= [[Louth and Horncastle (UK Parliament constituency)|Louth and Horncastle]]\n|post_town               = LOUTH\n|postcode_district       = LN11\n|postcode_area           = LN\n|dial_code               = 01507\n|os_grid_reference       = TF326874\n|map_type                = Lincolnshire\n|london_distance_mi      = 130<!-- straight line per MOS \u2013 constant and comparable with other place distances -->\n|london_direction        = S\n}}\n\n'''Louth''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=En-louth.ogg|l|a\u028a|\u03b8}}) is a large [[market town]] and [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] in the [[East Lindsey]] district of [[Lincolnshire]], England.<ref name=EX283>OS Explorer map 283:Louth and Mablethorpe: (1:25 000):\n{{ISBN|978 0319238240}}</ref> Louth is the principal town and centre for a large rural area of eastern Lincolnshire. Visitor attractions include St. James' Church, Hubbard's Hills, the market, many independent retailers, and Lincolnshire's last remaining cattle market.<ref>{{cite news|title=Farmers have mixed views over future of Lincolnshire's only surviving cattle market|url=http://www.lincolnshirelive.co.uk/farmers-mixed-views-future-lincolnshire-s/story-28467705-detail/story.html|accessdate=20 March 2017|publisher=Lincolnshire Live|date=7 January 2016}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nLouth is at the foot of the [[Lincolnshire Wolds]] where they meet the [[Lincolnshire Marsh]] and is known as the Capital of the Lincolnshire Wolds. It developed where the ancient trackway along the Wolds, known as the Barton&nbsp;Street, crossed the [[River Lud]]. The town is east of a gorge carved into the Wolds that forms the [[Hubbard's Hills]]. This area was formed from a glacial overspill channel in the [[last glacial period]]. The River Lud meanders through the gorge before entering the town.\n\nLouth had a population of 15,930 as of 2009.<ref>[http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/viewFullDataset.do?instanceSelection=03070&productId=779&$ph=60_61&datasetInstanceId=3070&startColumn=1&numberOfColumns=8&containerAreaId=790456 Office for National Statistics : ''Census 2001 : Parish Headcounts : East Lindsey''] Retrieved 18 September 2009</ref>\n[[File:Busy Louth by-pass - geograph.org.uk - 417257.jpg|thumb|Louth Bypass]]\nThe [[Greenwich Meridian]] passes through the town and is marked on Eastgate with plaques on the north and south sides of the street, just east of the junction with Northgate, although this location is known to be incorrect as the line actually passes through a point just west of Eastgate's junction with Church Street. A three-mile (5&nbsp;km) \u00a36.6&nbsp;million{{Citation needed|date=April 2014}} [[A16 road (England)|A16]] Louth Bypass opened in 1991. The former route through the town is now designated as the B1520.\n\n==History==\n[[File:St James' Church Louth.jpg|thumb|St James' Church Louth]]\nThree handaxes have been found on the [[The Wolds|wolds]] surrounding Louth, dating from between 424,000 and 191,000 years ago, indicating inhabitation in [[Paleolithic]] era.<ref name=\"Green2011\">{{cite book|author=Tom Green|title=The Origins of Louth: Archaeology and History in East Lincolnshire 400,000 BC-AD 1086|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NhkHYntyRwYC|year=2011|publisher=Tom Green|isbn=978-0-9570336-0-3|pages=4\u20137}}</ref> [[Bronze Age]] archeological finds include a 'barbed and tanged' arrowhead found in the grounds of [[Monks' Dyke Tennyson College]].<ref name=\"Green2011b\">{{cite book|author=Tom Green|title=The Origins of Louth: Archaeology and History in East Lincolnshire 400,000 BC-AD 1086|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NhkHYntyRwYC|year=2011|publisher=Tom Green|isbn=978-0-9570336-0-3|page=33}}</ref>\n\nSt Helen's Spring, at the Gatherums, off Aswell Street, is dedicated to a popular medieval saint, the [[Helena (empress)|mother]] of [[Constantine the Great]], the first [[Roman Emperor]] to become a Christian,<ref name=\"Historical Significance\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gatherumsandspringside.org.uk/history.html |title=Historical Significance |accessdate=9 November 2013 |publisher=Gatherums and Springside |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109072647/http://www.gatherumsandspringside.org.uk/history.html |archivedate=9 November 2013 }}</ref> but is thought to be a Christianised [[Romano-British culture|Romano-British]] site for veneration of the pagan water-goddess Alauna.<ref name=\"Green2011c\">{{cite book|author=Tom Green|title=The Origins of Louth: Archaeology and History in East Lincolnshire 400,000 BC-AD 1086|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NhkHYntyRwYC|year=2011|publisher=Tom Green|isbn=978-0-9570336-0-3|pages=52\u201353}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Anglo-Saxon]] pagan burial ground, northwest of Louth, dates from the fifth to sixth centuries, and was first excavated in 1946.<ref name=\"Historical Significance\"/> With an estimated 1200 urn burials it is one of the largest [[Anglo-Saxon]] cremation cemeteries in England.<ref name=\"Green2011a\">{{cite book|author=Tom Green|title=The Origins of Louth: Archaeology and History in East Lincolnshire 400,000 BC-AD 1086|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NhkHYntyRwYC|year=2011|publisher=Tom Green|isbn=978-0-9570336-0-3|page=68}}</ref>\n\n[[\u00c6thelhard]], a [[Bishop of Winchester]] who was made [[Archbishop of Canterbury]] in 793, was an [[abbot]] of Louth in his early life.<ref name=DNB>Williams \"[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/8910 \u00c6thelheard (d. 805)]\" ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography''</ref>\n\nLouth is listed in the 1086 ''[[Domesday Book]]'' as a town of 124 households.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://domesdaymap.co.uk/place/TF3287/louth/ | title = Louth | accessdate = 9 November 2013 | work = Open Domesday}}</ref>\n\n[[Louth Park Abbey]] was founded in 1139 by the [[Bishop of Lincoln|Bishop]] [[Alexander of Lincoln]] as a daughter-house of the [[Cistercian]] [[Fountains Abbey]] in [[Yorkshire]].<ref>David M. Smith, \u2018Alexander (d. 1148)\u2019, ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'', Oxford University Press, 2004.</ref> Following its dissolution in 1536 it fell into ruin and, today, only earthworks survive, on private land, between Louth and [[Keddington]].<ref>{{cite PastScape|mnumber=354511 |mname=Louth Abbey |accessdate=13 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://cistercians.shef.ac.uk/abbeys/louth_park.php | title = Cistercian Abbeys: LOUTH PARK | accessdate = 13 November 2013 | work = The Cistercian In Yorkshire}}</ref> Monks' Dyke, now a ditch, was originally dug to supply the abbey with water from the springs of Ashwell and St. Helen's at Louth.<ref>{{cite PastScape|mnumber=354511 |mname=Monks Dyke |accessdate=13 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1643, Sir Charles Bolles, a resident of Louth, raised a 'hastily-got-up soldiery' for the [[Cavalier|Royalist]] cause in the [[English Civil War]]. Fighting took place in, and around the town and, at one point, Bolles was forced to take refuge under the Ramsgate bridge.<ref name=\"BAYLEY1834\">{{cite book|author=Robert Slater BAYLEY|title=Notiti\u00e6 Lud\u00e6, Or Notices of Louth. &#91;By Robert S. Bayley. With Plates.&#93;|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_GdZUAAAAcAAJ|year=1834|publisher=The Author|pages=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_GdZUAAAAcAAJ/page/n93 77]\u201378}}</ref> By the battle's end 'Three strangers, being souldgeres, was slain at a skirmish at Lowth, and was buryed'.<ref name=\"BAYLEY1834\"/> Human remains, found during archaeological visits to [[Louth Park Abbey]] during the 1800s, in 'a little space surrounded by a ditch', were believed to date from the [[English Civil War|Civil War]] as two cannonballs, from that era, were found with the bodies.<ref name=\"trollope\">{{cite book | last1 = Trollope | first1 = Edward | title = Reports and papers of the architectural and archaeological societies of the counties of Lincoln and Northampton | chapter = The Architectural remains of Louth Park Abbey | publisher = James Williamson | location = Lincoln | year = 1873 | url = https://archive.org/stream/reportspapersofa12asso#page/n7/mode/2up | accessdate = 12 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Louth-flood.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|left|A stone plaque on Bridge Street showing the flood water level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.louthleader.co.uk/news/local/planning-enforcement-to-investigate-bridge-street-flood-marker-1-6864366|title=Planning Enforcement to investigate Bridge Street flood marker|publisher=}}</ref>]]\nThe [[Louth flood of 1920]] occurred in the town on 29 May 1920, causing 23 deaths. One woman climbed a chimney to survive, another was the only survivor from a row of twelve terrace houses, which were destroyed by the flood waters.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article27777450 |title=A CLOUDBURST. |newspaper=[[The West Australian]] |location=Perth |date=1 June 1920 |accessdate=12 November 2013 |page=7 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Four stone plaques exist in the town to show how high the water level reached. Other, less devastating floods occurred in July 1968 and on 25 June and 20 July in [[2007 United Kingdom floods|2007]].\n\n[[Margaret Wintringham]] succeeded her [[Thomas Wintringham (Liberal politician)|dead husband]] at the [[1921 Louth by-election|Louth by-election]] in September 1921, to become the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberals]]' first female MP, and Britain's third female MP.<ref>{{cite news|title=Women in the House of Commons House of Commons Information Office Factsheet M4 Appendix B|url=http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons-information-office/m04b.pdf|accessdate=3 January 2017|publisher=parliament.uk}}</ref>\n\n===St Herefrith of Louth===\nSt Herefrith,<ref>{{PASE|20747|Herefrith 10|cw=1}}</ref> or Herefrid, is Louth's 'forgotten saint',<ref>{{cite news|title=The forgotten Saint of Louth is remembered |date=2 November 2011 |url=http://www.thisislincolnshire.co.uk/forgotten-Saint-Louth-remembered/story-13730118-detail/story.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20131112043551/http://www.thisislincolnshire.co.uk/forgotten-Saint-Louth-remembered/story-13730118-detail/story.html |url-status=dead |archivedate=12 November 2013 |work=This Is Lincolnshire |accessdate=12 November 2013 }}</ref> whose feast day is 27 February.<ref>{{cite news | title = ANNIVERSARIES | date = 27 February 1995 | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/anniversaries-1575080.html | work = The Independent | accessdate = 12 November 2013}}</ref> He was a bishop, who died around 873, possibly killed by the [[Danes (Germanic tribe)|Danes]].<ref name=\"Farmer2011\">{{cite book|author=David Farmer|title=The Oxford Dictionary of Saints, Fifth Edition Revised|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_zJJtvK2_KsC&pg=PA209|date=14 April 2011|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-959660-7|page=209}}</ref> An 11th-century text describes Herefrith as [[Bishop of Lincoln]], but as the bishopric there dates to 1072, Lincoln more probably refers to [[Kingdom of Lindsey|Lindsey]],<ref name=\"GreenHerefrith\">{{cite book|author=Tom Green|title=The Origins of Louth: Archaeology and History in East Lincolnshire 400,000 BC-AD 1086|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NhkHYntyRwYC&pg=PA84|year=2011|publisher=Tom Green|isbn=978-0-9570336-0-3|pages=82\u201385}}</ref> the early name for [[Lincolnshire]].<ref name=\"Farmer2011\"/> Similar confusion exists in an inventory of Louth's [[St. James Church, Louth|St. James Church]], written in 1486 and transcribed in 1512, where he is referred to as a [[Ancient Diocese of Auxerre|Bishop of Auxerre]], France.<ref name=\"peacock\">{{cite book | last1 = Peacock | first1 = Edward | title = Reports and papers of the architectural and archaeological societies of the counties of Lincoln and Northampton | chapter = Louth in the time of Henry VIII | publisher = James Williamson | location = Lincoln | year = 1873 | url = https://archive.org/stream/reportspapersofa12asso#page/n7/mode/2up | accessdate = 12 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt some point, following his death, a [[shrine]] venerating him was established at Louth. [[\u00c6thelwold of Winchester|\u00c6thelwold]], the [[Bishop of Winchester]] from 963 to 984, was actively seeking relics for his newly rebuilt [[Thorney Abbey]] in [[Cambridgeshire]] and sent his monks to Louth to raid Herefrith's shrine.<ref name=\"GreenHerefrith\"/> From an 11th-century account, [[\u00c6thelwold of Winchester|\u00c6thelwold]] had:\n<blockquote>...heard of the merits of the blessed Herefrid bishop of Lincoln resting in Louth a chief town of the same church. When all those dwelling there had been put to sleep by a cunning ruse, a trusty servant took him out of the ground, wrapped him in fine line cloth, and with all his fellows rejoicing brought him to the monastery of Thorney and re-interred him.<ref name=\"GreenHerefrith\"/></blockquote>\nA church dedicated to St. Herefrith, at Louth, appears in accounts from the 13th to 15th centuries,<ref name=\"Farmer2011\"/> and one of his relics, an ivory comb, is recorded among the possessions of Louth's [[St. James Church, Louth|St. James Church]] in 1486.<ref name=\"peacock\"/> Suggestions that the shrine, and later church, of St. Herefrith, were earlier incarnations of St. James has 'no supportive evidence' but St James' is the site of two earlier churches of which little is known.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.lincstothepast.com/St-James--Church--Louth/228093.record?pt=S | title = St James' Church, Louth | accessdate = 12 November 2013 | work = Lincs To The Past}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n\n[[File:The site of Louth station, goods yard and the former kilns..jpg|thumb|The site of Louth station, goods yard and the former kilns. The last trains here were in 1980 before complete closure. The entire area is now a mix of housing, retail and industrial outlets. The station building can be seen in the distance with the chimneys.]]\n\n[[Louth railway station]] was a major intermediate station on the [[East Lincolnshire Railway]] which ran from [[Boston railway station|Boston]] to [[Grimsby railway station|Grimsby]] from 1848 and was also once served by [[rail motor]] services.\n\nLouth was the northern terminus of the [[Mablethorpe loop railway|Mablethorpe Loop]]. The line which ran through the nearby villages and seaside towns of [[Mablethorpe]], [[Sutton-on-Sea]], [[Grimoldby]], [[Saltfleetby]], [[Theddlethorpe]], [[Mumby]] and [[Willoughby, Lincolnshire|Willoughby]]. The station was the terminus on the [[Louth to Bardney Line]] which opened in 1876 but closed in 1951 to passengers and to freight traffic in 1960. Bardney was the terminus of the branch line and was on the [[Lincolnshire Loop Line]]\n\nThe station closed to passengers in 1970 along with the Mablethorpe Loop Line and the section from [[Firsby railway station|Firsby]] to Louth of the East Lincolnshire Railway. The section to Grimsby remained in use for freight traffic until December 1980 when it closed and was later removed.\n\nThe station building and Louth North Signal Box remain in situ to this day as private dwellings. All of the station site has been built on by residential and commercial outlets.\n\nThere are plans to eventually have Louth as the southern terminus of the [[Lincolnshire Wolds Railway]] which would utilise the trackbed from Louth to Holton-Le-Clay, although it will be to the north of Louth due to the station building now being occupied and the station site around it built over. This would mean Louth would have a rail connection for the first time in almost 50 years, since the closure to passengers in 1970, but at a new station site.\n\nA canal was built between 1765 and 1770 to connect Louth to the sea at Tetney. It was formally abandoned in 1924.\nA fuller account is at [[Louth Canal]].\n\nThere are regular buses connecting Louth with the nearby Grimsby, Skegness, Mablethorpe and Lincoln. There is also a direct service once a month to [[York]] and National Express coaches call at Louth bus station. All services are operated by different companies but the main one is [[Stagecoach]]. However, unlike other towns. The town is not served by late-night services with the last bus departing the town at 7:00 pm.\n\nThe nearest active railway station is now Grimsby and Skegness.\n\n==St James' Church==\n[[File:Lincolnshire Rising plaque - geograph.org.uk - 860306.jpg|thumb|Lincolnshire Rising plaque in Louth]]\n{{see also|St James' Church, Louth|Lincolnshire Rising}}\n\nThe town was the origin of the [[Lincolnshire Rising]], which started on 1 October 1536 in [[St. James Church, Louth|St James Church]]. The rising began after Rev. Thomas Kendall, the incumbent, gave an 'emotive sermon',<ref name=\"FletcherStevenson1987\">{{cite book|author1=Anthony Fletcher|author2=John Stevenson|title=Order and Disorder in Early Modern England|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6_Cq4-WFX6cC&pg=PA71|date=4 June 1987|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-34932-1|page=71}}</ref> the evening before the King's Commissioners were due to arrive and assess the church's wealth.<ref name=\"Porter2010\">{{cite book|author=Linda Porter|title=Katherine the Queen|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WbQmKuq_ZHoC&pg=PT60|date=10 March 2010|publisher=Pan Macmillan UK|isbn=978-1-74303-570-2|page=60}}</ref> Some of the townspeople, fearful that the [[church treasury]] would be seized by the men of the Crown, demanded the building's keys.<ref name=\"FletcherStevenson1987\"/> The townspeople kept vigil that night, and, the following day, rang the church bells, 'an ancient call to rebellion', to gather a crowd.<ref name=\"Porter2010\"/> Having begun marching from Louth, 50,000 supporters converged to camp at Hembleton Hill, the following evening, before they continued to Lincoln to confront the King's Commissioners.\n\nThe town's skyline is dominated by [[St James' Church, Louth]], the spire.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/481423|title=St.James' church (C) Richard Croft|website=www.geograph.org.uk}}</ref> A recent survey has confirmed the height of the stonework as {{convert|287|ft|6|in|m}} and to the top of the cockerel weather vane as {{convert|293|ft|1|in|m}}. It also confirms it as one of the very finest medieval steeples in the country<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thamesandhudson.com/Fifty_English_Steeples/9780500343142|title=Thames & Hudson Publishers  {{!}}  Essential illustrated art books {{!}}  Fifty English Steeples {{!}} The Finest Medieval Parish Church Towers and Spires in England|website=www.thamesandhudson.com|accessdate=29 October 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161030080913/http://www.thamesandhudson.com/Fifty_English_Steeples/9780500343142|archivedate=30 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Though shorter than both [[Norwich Cathedral]] {{convert|315|ft|m|0}}, and [[Salisbury Cathedral]] {{convert|404|ft|m|0}}, in terms of spire height it is the tallest medieval parish church in the United Kingdom. The building of the spire commenced in 1501 and was finally completed in 1515.\n\nIn 2015 came a remarkable discovery from the adjoining Rectory garden in the form of two pieces of a pre-Conquest standing stone Cross dating to c950. In form the Cross is of the 'ring' or 'wheel head' type, the central design being of Christ crucified. The type is more commonly seen today in Ireland. The Cross and its implications for the archaeology, history and the early church in Louth are discussed in a major article by Everson and Stocker ''The Cros in the Markitte Stede'. The Louth Cross, its Monastery and its Town''. (Medieval Archaeology Journal, vol. 61/2, 2017).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-lincolnshire-36070551|title=Anglo-Saxon cross fragments found|date=18 April 2016|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> The Louth Cross is on display within the church and a small booklet is available from the gift shop.\n\nIn 2017 funding was raised to fit a viewing door to the cell just below the spire floor that holds the original medieval treadwheel that was used to haul up the stone and mortar for the building of the spire (1501\u20131515). Substantial records exist in the churchwardens' accounts from 1501 onward for the construction and use of the wheel which was to become known as ''The Wild Mare.'' A small booklet about this rare survival is available from the church gift shop.\n\n==Landmarks and places of interest==\nMuch of the town centre is lined with brick buildings from the 17th and 18th centuries.\n[[File:ABM Pauls Malt Kiln - geograph.org.uk - 597153 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|Former ABM Pauls Malt Kiln]]\nLouth Museum has a Panorama Gallery, which features two back-lit replicas of William Brown's ''Panorama of Louth'' viewed from the top of St James' spire in 1844. The two original paintings that together form the panorama hang side-by-side in the Louth Town Council building - the Sessions House - on Eastgate. The panorama gives a unique and vivid representation of the streets, businesses, homes and people of the town and the landscape as far as the [[North Sea]] to the east and northwards to the [[Humber Estuary]] and beyond.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.louthmuseum.co.uk/|title=Louth Museum|accessdate=23 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nABM Pauls used to have a large malt kiln, which was the first of its kind built in Europe to an American design out of reinforced concrete in 1949. The site had been the location of a maltings since 1870 which was destroyed by German bombs in 1940, and had to be built on the old site to qualify for war compensation.<ref>{{cite news|title=American design made Louth malt kiln unique|url=http://www.louthleader.co.uk/news/features/american-design-made-louth-malt-kiln-unique-1-1009564|accessdate=16 July 2015|publisher=Louth Leader|date=26 March 2003}}</ref> At its height the maltings processed 50,000 tonnes of barley per year, with exports handled through the nearby port of [[Immingham]]. The maltings closed in 1998 and the {{convert|120|ft|m}} tall structure was left derelict for many years. The German supermarket chain [[Aldi]] was granted permission to build a new store on the site, and it was demolished in 2014/15.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Aldi supermarket in Louth will be chain's biggest in country|url=http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/New-Aldi-supermarket-Louth-chain-s-biggest/story-25881058-detail/story.html|accessdate=16 July 2015|publisher=Grimsby Telegraph|date=17 January 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722074245/http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/New-Aldi-supermarket-Louth-chain-s-biggest/story-25881058-detail/story.html|archivedate=22 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Hubbard's Hills]] is one of the town's main attractions. It was opened to the public in 1907. The park is dedicated to the memory of Annie Pahud, the central figure of a historic, tragic love affair.{{clarify|date=November 2017}} The park is in a [[glacial overspill channel]] that forged the course for a small river, the Lud. It meanders along the deep, flat valley bottom between steep, wooded slopes on either side.\n[[File:Louth from the Air - geograph.org.uk - 625313.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.8|Aerial view of part of Louth]]\nThe [[Belmont transmitting station|Belmont]] television and radio mast, once one of the tallest structures in the [[European Union]] (until its height was reduced in 2010), is in the nearby village of [[Donington on Bain]], {{convert|5|mi|km|0}} west of the town.\n\nLouth will be the eventual southern terminus of the [[Lincolnshire Wolds Railway]], based at nearby [[Ludborough]]. The town was formerly on the East Lincolnshire Railway from [[Peterborough]] to [[Grimsby]], an important north-south route especially for holidaymakers in the summer. It opened in 1848. The line to [[Mablethorpe]] started in the town from 1877, closing in 1960. The section to [[Wainfleet, Lincolnshire|Wainfleet]] closed in 1961, with the Louth to Grimsby section later continuing for passengers until October 1970, with freight stopping in 1980. The former station<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/134019|title=Louth Station (C) Richard Croft|website=www.geograph.org.uk}}</ref> is now residential flats; there are other reminders<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/134326|title=Level Crossing Gone! (C) Michael Patterson|website=www.geograph.org.uk}}</ref> still standing.\n\n[[Alfred Lord Tennyson]] was educated at [[King Edward VI Grammar School, Louth|King Edward VI Grammar School]]. A stone inscription to commemorate this forms part of a wall on Schoolhouse Lane in Louth.\n\n==Shopping and local economy==\n[[File:New Lane - geograph.org.uk - 481369.jpg|thumb|Shops on New Street]]\n\nLouth is noted for the wide selection of independent retailers, with around 70% of businesses independently owned.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.lincolnshirelife.co.uk/posts/view/luscious-louth | title = Luscious Louth | accessdate = 9 November 2013 | last = Burton | first = Melanie | work = Lincolnshire Life}}</ref> In 2012, it was named 'Britain's Favourite market town' by the [[BBC]]'s ''[[Countryfile]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.countryfile.com/countryside/countryfile-magazine-awards-results-2012 | title = Countryfile Magazine Awards: The results 2012 | accessdate = 9 November 2013 | work = CountryFile | publisher = [[Countryfile]]}}</ref>\n\nThe town's long retail history is represented by a number of longstanding businesses, including the department store Eve and Ranshaw, whose history can be traced back to 1781,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.lincolnshirelife.co.uk/shop/view-product/adam-eve-and-louth-carpets | title = Adam Eve and Louth Carpets | accessdate = 9 November 2013 | work = Lincolnshire Life}}</ref> Dales & Sons, poulterers since 1896,<ref name=\"shoplocal\">{{cite news | first = Rose | last = Prince | title = Shop Local: Louth | date = 30 June 2007 | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/foodanddrink/healthyeating/3338353/Shop-local.html | work = The Telegraph | accessdate = 9 November 2013}}</ref> and the century-old butchers, Lakings of Louth.<ref name=\"shoplocal\"/>\n\nThe first building society branch office was opened by the Peterborough Building Society (now [[Norwich & Peterborough]]) in 1973. The town was also the headquarters of the former Louth, Mablethorpe and Sutton Building Society, a local society with several branches and agents in Lincolnshire, which was taken over by the [[Bradford and Bingley Building Society|Bradford & Bingley]] in 1990.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.bsa.org.uk/consumer/factsheets/mergerschrono.htm | title = Building society mergers and conversions since 1980 | accessdate = 9 November 2013 | work = Building Societies Association}}</ref>\n\nLouth is also known for its specialist grocers,<ref name=\"shoplocal\"/> and local butchers, Meridian Meats, have won numerous awards.<ref>{{cite news | title = Louth butcher wins gold award at international food contest | date = 9 April 2013 | url = http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/Louth-butcher-wins-gold-award-international-food/story-18653564-detail/story.html | work = Grimsby Telegraph | accessdate = 9 November 2013 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131109040404/http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/Louth-butcher-wins-gold-award-international-food/story-18653564-detail/story.html | archivedate = 9 November 2013 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> It is also home to [[The Cheese Shop, Louth|The Cheese Shop]], which has gained nationwide recognition, including in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'',<ref>Davies, Paul; [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/lifestyle/shopawards/8318165/Small-wonders-the-winners-of-our-Best-Small-Shops-in-Britain-Awards.html \"Small wonders: the winners of our Best Small Shops in Britain Awards\"]; ''The Telegraph'', 11 February 2011. Retrieved 3 May 2012</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref>Cook, William; [https://www.theguardian.com/enjoy-england/lincolnshire-foodie-tour \"Keeping it real\"]; ''[[Guardian.co.uk]]'', 15 October 2010. Retrieved 3 May 2012</ref> and on ''[[The Hairy Bikers' Food Tour of Britain]]''.<ref>{{cite web|date=March 2009 |url=http://www.louthleader.co.uk/news/local/photo_hairy_bikers_film_new_tv_show_in_louth_1_1013404 |title=PHOTO: Hairy Bikers film new TV show in Louth \u2013 Local |publisher=Louth Leader |accessdate=11 March 2011}}</ref>\n[[File:Street Market-Louth - geograph.org.uk - 697817.jpg|thumb|Street market in Louth]]\nLouth holds market days on Wednesdays, Fridays and Saturdays. There is a [[farmers' market]] on the fourth Wednesday of each month. A cattle market is held each Thursday at the Louth Livestock Centre on Newmarket.\n\nThere is a small [[Morrisons]], formerly a [[Somerfield]] store,<ref>{{cite news | title = Jobs could be cut at Louth's Morrisons supermarket | date = 10 April 2013 | url = http://www.louthleader.co.uk/news/business/business-news/jobs-could-be-cut-at-louth-s-morrisons-supermarket-1-4983120 | work = Louth Leader | accessdate = 9 November 2013}}</ref> which opened in 1985, and a [[Co-operative Group|Co-operative supermarket]], which opened in 1989. The Co-op was given approval for an additional smaller store in 2013.<ref>{{cite news | first = Sam | last = Kinnaird | title = Councillor left frustrated as planning inspector gives go ahead for new Co-op supermarket in Louth | date = 31 May 2013 | url = http://www.louthleader.co.uk/news/business/business-news/councillor-left-frustrated-as-planning-inspector-gives-go-ahead-for-new-co-op-supermarket-in-louth-1-5148164 | work = Louth Leader | accessdate = 9 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, a local [[Advocacy group|pressure group]], Keep Louth Special, was formed by residents, shoppers and business owners, to lobby against a proposal for a major supermarket on the former cattle market site.<ref>{{cite news | title = Keep Louth Special group formed to stop supermarket | date = 28 November 2008 | url = http://www.louthleader.co.uk/news/local/keep-louth-special-group-formed-to-stop-supermarket-1-1012392 | work = Louth Leader | accessdate = 9 November 2013}}</ref> The group was criticised by a town councillor, the following year, as 'outsiders' who wanted to live in a 'museum town',<ref>{{cite news | title = Keep Louth Special group blasted | date = 9 February 2009 | url = http://www.louthleader.co.uk/news/local/keep-louth-special-group-blasted-1-1013195 | work = Louth Leader | accessdate = 9 November 2013}}</ref> but a 2012 council report, while recommending a 'large retail development' as \u2018necessary\u2019, acknowledged that 'a majority 50 per cent' of surveyed residents opposed it.<ref>{{cite news | first = Sam | last = Kinnaird | title = Food store development could kill small Louth shops | date = 29 November 2012 | url = http://www.louthleader.co.uk/news/local/food-store-development-could-kill-small-louth-shops-1-4532479 | work = Louth Leader | accessdate = 9 November 2013}}</ref>\nAn initial 2009 planning application by [[Sainsbury's]] for a new {{convert|30000|sqft|m2}} store,<ref>{{cite news | title = Sainsbury's arrival 'do or die' for town | date = 10 July 2009 | url = http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/Sainsbury-s-arrival-die-town/story-11536469-detail/story.html | work = Grimsby Telegraph | accessdate = 9 November 2013 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150924041355/http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/Sainsbury-s-arrival-die-town/story-11536469-detail/story.html | archivedate = 24 September 2015 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> was rejected by the Council, after appeal, in 2012.<ref>{{cite news | title = Sainsbury's store plan for Louth thrown out by councillors | date = 4 July 2012 | url = http://www.thisislincolnshire.co.uk/Sainsbury-s-store-plan-Louth-thrown-councillors/story-16478573-detail/story.html | archive-url = https://archive.is/20131109044700/http://www.thisislincolnshire.co.uk/Sainsbury-s-store-plan-Louth-thrown-councillors/story-16478573-detail/story.html | url-status = dead | archivedate = 9 November 2013 | work = This Is Lincolnshire | accessdate = 9 November 2013 }}</ref>\nKeep Louth Special described a 2013 proposal for an [[Aldi]] store as 'not bad news' because it was intended for an 'eyesore' site,<ref>{{cite news | title = Keep Louth Special says Aldi plans 'not bad news' | date = 12 July 2013 | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-lincolnshire-23245424 | work = BBC | accessdate = 9 November 2013}}</ref> and as [[Aldi]] stocks 'own brands and a limited fresh-food offering', it would not be 'going head-to-head' with the town market or independent retailers.<ref>{{cite news | title = Louth Aldi store proposal is scrutinised | date = 2 August 2013 | url = http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/Louth-Aldi-store-proposal-scrutinised/story-19604997-detail/story.html | work = Grimsby Telegraph | accessdate = 9 November 2013 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150924041028/http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/Louth-Aldi-store-proposal-scrutinised/story-19604997-detail/story.html | archivedate = 24 September 2015 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n[[File:Old Market Hall - geograph.org.uk - 481364.jpg|thumb|Old Market Hall, Louth]]\n\nMany national food campaigning organisations are based on ''Eastgate'' under the umbrella organisation the Processed Vegetable Growers Association,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pvga.co.uk|title=British Growers Association|website=www.pvga.co.uk}}</ref> notably:\n*The Asparagus Growers Association<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.british-asparagus.co.uk|title=Page Redirection|website=www.british-asparagus.co.uk}}</ref>\n*The Brassica Growers Association<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081030031455/http://www.brassicas.org/|title=Brassica Growers Association|date=30 October 2008|publisher=}}</ref>\n*The British Herb Trade Association<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhta.org.uk|title=British Herbs - Home|website=www.bhta.org.uk}}</ref>\n*The British Onion Producers Association<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishonions.co.uk|title=Home - British Onions|website=www.britishonions.co.uk}}</ref>\n*The Leek Growers Association<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.british-leeks.co.uk|title=British Leeks|website=www.british-leeks.co.uk}}</ref> \n*The Radish Growers Association\n*The Turfgrass Association<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.turfgrass.co.uk|title=The TGA - Turfgrass Growers Association|website=www.turfgrass.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Community and culture==\n[[File:Playhouse Cinema - geograph.org.uk - 479995.jpg|thumb|Playhouse Cinema, Louth.]]\n\nThe town's ''Playhouse Cinema'' is on ''[https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/780566 Cannon Street]'', and is home to Louth Film Club, which won the British Federation of Film Societies' ''Film Society of the Year Award'' in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bffs.org.uk/awards/abouttheawards.html |archive-url=https://www.webarchive.org.uk/wayback/archive/20091212210133/http://www.bffs.org.uk/awards/abouttheawards.html |url-status=dead |archivedate=12 December 2009 |title=Film Society of the Year Awards 2008 |accessdate=15 November 2009 }}</ref> Louth Playgoers Society's  ''Riverhead Theatre''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.louthplaygoers.com|title=2018 SPRING SEASON|website=Louth Riverhead Theatre}}</ref> is on ''Victoria Road'', to the east of the town.\n\nLouth is home to The New Orleans Club,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.louthjazzclub.org.uk/|title=welcome|website=www.louthjazzclub.org.uk}}</ref> a not-for-profit members' club dedicated to keeping alive the music of jazz.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.louthjazzclub.org.uk/|title=New Orleans Club's Website|last=|first=|date=|website=www.louthjazzclub.org.uk|accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref> There are several other local bands, apart from jazz, in and around the town. {{citation needed|date=November 2011}}\n\n[[Corinne Drewery]] of [[Swing Out Sister]], grew up in the area and [[Robert Wyatt]] is a resident.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/interview-robert-wyatt-the-only-way-is-up-when-youve-hit-rock-bottom-1241992.html|title=Interview: Robert Wyatt The only way is up when you've hit rock bottom|date=30 September 1997|work=The Independent|accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nTransition Town Louth<ref>http://www.transitiontownlouth.org.uk/</ref> is a community project, which organizes various events in and around the town aimed at promoting awareness of climate change and unsustainable resources. Part of a large social movement, many [[Transition Towns]] are now developing. A sub-group, the Community Food Gardens<ref>{{cite web|url=http://louthcfg.blogspot.com|title=Louth Community Food Gardens|website=louthcfg.blogspot.com}}</ref> are encouraging a shift towards sustainable communities.\n\n==Sport and leisure==\n===Meridian Leisure Centre===\n[[File:Louth Golf Course - geograph.org.uk - 416977.jpg|thumb|Louth Golf Course]]\n\nThe Centre opened on 6 February 2010, and, by 2013, had received almost one million visits, and was home to over 20 clubs.<ref>{{cite news | title = Meridian Leisure Centre nears one million visits | date = 29 January 2013 | url = http://www.louthleader.co.uk/news/local/meridian-leisure-centre-nears-one-million-visits-1-4728985 | work = Louth Leader | accessdate = 9 November 2013}}</ref> It cost \u00a312&nbsp;million and consists of an 8 lane, 25 metre swimming pool and a two level gym with over 80 pieces of equipment, along with a sports hall and other facilities. The Louth Technology Hub, which is using 3D display technology, with a focus on sports groups and clubs, opened on the Centre's upper floor in October 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.onlincolnshire.org/news/local-broadband-news/technology-hub-opening-in-louth-this-month | title = Technology hub opening in Louth this month | accessdate = 9 November 2013 | work = On Lincolnshire}}</ref>\n\n===Louth Tennis Centre===\nLouth Tennis Centre is situated on Fairfield Industrial Estate to the north of the town and has indoor and outdoor tennis facilities.\n\n===London Road Sports Pavilion===\nThere is a multiuse sports pavilion on London Road, which includes football pitches, a cricket pitch and a multi-use astroturf pitch.\n\n===Cricket===\nLouth Cricket Club was formed in 1822 and play their home games at the London Road sports pavilion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://louth.play-cricket.com/|title=Louth CC|website=louth.play-cricket.com}}</ref>\n\n===Football===\nLouth is home to [[Louth Town F.C.|Louth Town Football Club]] which plays in the [[Lincolnshire Football League]].\n\n===Cadwell Park===\nIn the Wolds to the south-west of the town, around four miles (6&nbsp;km) away, is [[Cadwell Park]] [[auto racing|motor racing]] circuit between the villages of [[Scamblesby]] and [[Tathwell]].\n\n===Other pursuits===\nLouth also hosts Louth Swimming Club, Louth Old Boys (Football), Yom Chi Taekwondo, Kendojo Martial Arts, Louth Storm Basketball, Louth Chess Club, Louth Golf Course (Crowtree Lane) and Kenwick Park Golf Course (on the outskirts of the town) as well as archery, a model aircraft club which uses [[Strubby]] and [[Manby]] Airfields and a model radio controlled car club which uses Cordeaux Academy.\n\n==Education==\n\n===Primary schools===\n*Kidgate Primary School<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kidgate.lincs.sch.uk|title=Home - Kidgate Primary Academy|website=www.kidgate.lincs.sch.uk}}</ref>\n*Lacey Gardens Junior School<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laceygardens.lincs.sch.uk|title=Lacey Gardens Junior School Louth - Home Page|website=www.laceygardens.lincs.sch.uk}}</ref>\n* St. Michael's C of E Primary School<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.st-michaels.lincs.sch.uk|title=St. Michael\u2019s C of E Primary School Louth - Home Page|website=www.st-michaels.lincs.sch.uk}}</ref>\n*Eastfield Infants and Nursery School<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastfield.lincs.sch.uk|title=Welcome to Eastfield Infants' and Nursery School|website=www.eastfield.lincs.sch.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Secondary schools===\n*[[King Edward VI Grammar School, Louth|King Edward VI Grammar School]]\n*[[Cordeaux Academy]] (closed in 2017)\n*[[Monks' Dyke Tennyson College]] (closed in 2017)\nBoth of the above merged to become:\n*Louth Academy<ref>{{cite web | url =https://lincolnshirereporter.co.uk/2017/09/schools-merger-approved-form-one-louth-academy-september-2018/ | title =Schools merger approved to form one Louth Academy from September 2018 | last =Pidluznyj | first =Stefan | website =Lincolnshire Reporter | publisher =Stonebow Media | accessdate =24 February 2018 | quote =Two comprehensive schools will merge to form one Louth Academy from September 2018. }}</ref>\n\n===Further education===\nA \u00a33-million further education college, called [[Wolds College]], was next to the Cordeaux School.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/lincolnshire/7252741.stm Worries over major college build], '' [[BBC|BBC News]]'', 19 February 2008. Retrieved 23 November 2017</ref> Construction by the Lindum Group started in November 2007, and the college officially opened in October 2008. Unlike many Lincolnshire [[secondary modern school]]s, both Cordeaux and Monks' Dyke have their own sixth forms; East Lindsey's only other secondary modern with a sixth form is at Skegness. Although the town is well served for [[Advanced Level (UK)|A-level]] provision, vocational courses were less well served until the college opened in this part of East Lindsey in September 2008, although there is the [[Grimsby Institute of Further & Higher Education|Grimsby Institute]] some fifteen miles (24&nbsp;km) away.\n\n==Twin town==\nLouth's [[Twin towns and sister cities|twin town]] is [[La Fert\u00e9-Bernard]], close to [[Le Mans]] in [[Pays-de-la-Loire]], France.\n\n==Ludensians==\nInhabitants of Louth are known as ''Ludensians'', taken from the Latin name of the town (''Lude'', ''Luda'').\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Jeffrey Archer]] was elected the town's Member of Parliament in a by-election [[1969 Louth by-election|in 1969]]. He stood down at the [[October 1974 United Kingdom general election|October 1974 general election]].\n*[[Jim Broadbent]], actor, lives in a small village just outside Louth.\n*[[Bridget Brophy]] writer, lived in Louth for many years.\n*[[Roy 'Chubby' Brown]], [[Blue comedy|adult comedian]], (real name ''Royston Vasey'') lives in nearby [[Fulstow]].\n*[[Leanda Cave]], triathlete, was born in Louth\n*[[Julie Christie]], actress, has a home in Louth, and sometimes works with the local Film Club.\n*[[Daniel Craig]], actor noted for his role as [[James Bond]], has a house between [[Legbourne, Lincolnshire|Legbourne]] and Louth.\n*[[George Davenport]], Anglo/American frontiersman, US Army officer, was born in Louth\n*[[Barbara Dickson]], singer and actress, lived in Louth\n*[[Corinne Drewery]], lead singer of the band [[Swing Out Sister]], attended schools in the town whilst growing up in the village of [[Authorpe]], between Louth and [[Alford, Lincolnshire|Alford]].\n*[[Graham Fellows]], also known as John Shuttleworth and Jilted John, a singer-songwriter and comedian lives in the town.\n*[[Michael Foale]], [[astronaut]] from the [[International Space Station]] was born at Crowtree Lane Hospital, now the Humanities block of [[King Edward VI Grammar School, Louth|King Edward VI Grammar School]]. His father was stationed at a nearby [[Royal Air Force]] base at [[Manby]].\n*[[Dave Formula]], member of [[New wave music|New Wave]] pioneers [[Magazine (band)|Magazine]], lives in Louth and often plays locally with other [[The Finks]].\n*[[James Gillick]] Figurative artist, works from his studio in Louth and lives nearby.\n*[[Ron Grant (motorcyclist)|Ron Grant]], former motorcycle [[road racing|road racer]] and tuner.\n*[[Dan Haigh]], bass guitarist in rock band [[Fightstar]], born in [[Grimsby]], was brought up near the town.\n*[[Simon Hanson]], drummer with the band Squeeze lived in Louth and attended King Edward VI school.\n*[[Graham Higman]], mathematician, was born in Louth.\n*[[Augustus Charles Hobart-Hampden]], (1 April 1822 \u2013 19 June 1886), English naval captain and [[Ottoman Empire|Turkish]] admiral, was educated at [[King Edward VI Grammar School, Louth|King Edward VI Grammar School]]. {{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}\n*[[Andreas Kalvos]] (1792 \u2013 3 November 1869), Greek writer, lived in Louth from 1852 until his death. He was the first national Greek poet. In 1960, Greece's ambassador to the UK and Nobel Prize-Winner for poetry,George Seferis, arranged for his remains to be reburied in Calvos' native Zakinthos.\n*Rev. Thomas Kendall, incumbent of [[St. James Church, Louth]] and leader of [[Lincolnshire Rising]], 1 October 1536.\n*[[Cate Kennedy]], author\n*[[Thomas Louth]], [[Lord Chief Justice of Ireland]] in the 1330s, was born in the town and took his surname from it.\n*[[Matthew Macfadyen]], actor, spent his childhood in the town.\n*[[Harry Mallett]], cricketer, was born in Louth.\n*[[Patrick Mower]], actor, currently seen in TV soap-opera [[Emmerdale]] lives in the area in [[Little Carlton]].\n*[[Philip Norton, Baron Norton of Louth]] ''(born 5 March 1951)'', leading expert on the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|British Parliament]], [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician, author and Professor of Politics at the [[University of Hull]]\n*[[Jim Payne (golfer)|Jim Payne]], professional golfer who won two [[European Tour]] tournaments.\n*[[Adrian Royle]], retired long distance runner, lives in Louth.\n*[[Ted Savage (footballer)|Ted Savage]], footballer, was born in Louth.\n*[[Edith Sharpley]], Classical Lecturer at [[Newnham College, Cambridge]], was born in Louth.\n*[[Captain John Smith]], English, soldier, sailor and founder of the Commonwealth of Virginia, although born in [[Willoughby, Lincolnshire|Willoughby]], attended the [[King Edward VI Grammar School, Louth|King Edward VI Grammar School]], where his name is adorned upon a tablet in the school's 'Edward Street Hall'. A cast iron bust of him also stands within the school's canteen.\n*[[Stuart Storey]], BBC sports commentator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/olympics2000/bbc_team/856110.stm|title=BBC SPORT - BBC TEAM - Stuart Storey|website=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n*[[Alfred, Lord Tennyson]], was born in [[Somersby, Lincolnshire|Somersby]], between Louth and [[Horncastle, Lincolnshire|Horncastle]], and was educated at [[King Edward VI Grammar School, Louth|King Edward VI Grammar School]].\n*Lieutenant Colonel [[Thomas Colclough Watson|Thomas Watson]] [[Victoria Cross|VC]], also educated at the King Edward VI Grammar<ref>{{Cite news\n  |title=Victoria Cross and medals from Lincolnshire hero to be auctioned\n  |date=4 December 2014\n  |newspaper=Lincolnshire Echo\n  |url=http://www.lincolnshireecho.co.uk/Victoria-Cross-medals-Lincolnshire-hero-auctioned/story-25152299-detail/story.html\n}}</ref>\n*[[Graham Winteringham]], architect, was born in Louth.\n*[[Margaret Wintringham]], first English woman to sit as an M.P. lived most of her life just outside the town at Little Grimsby Hall, and was elected M.P. for Louth in 1920.\n*[[Robert Wyatt]], English musician and former member of [[Soft Machine]], now lives in Louth.\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Louth, Lincolnshire}}\n{{wikivoyage|Louth, Lincolnshire|Louth}}\n*{{officila|http://www.louth.org }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20170515201218/http://louthpartnership.org.uk/ Louth Town Partnership]\n*[http://www.louthleader.co.uk Louth Leader]\n*[http://www.louthmuseum.co.uk Louth Museum]\n*[http://www.transitiontownlouth.org.uk Transition Town Louth]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130824033745/http://www.stjameschurchlouth.com/ St. James' Church]\n*[http://www.hubbardshills.co.uk Hubbard's Hills]\n*[http://www.louthtowncouncil.gov.uk Louth Town Council]\n*[http://www.louthcanal.org.uk Louth Navigation Trust]\n\n{{Lincolnshire|state=collapsed}}\n{{East Lindsey (district) |state=collapsed}}\n{{Portal bar|England|United Kingdom}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Louth, Lincolnshire| ]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Market towns in Lincolnshire]]\n", "name_user": "Popsters", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Louth,_Lincolnshire"}
{"title_page": "Poisoning of Sergei and Yulia Skripal", "text_new": "{{short description|2018 attempted murder in Salisbury, England, United Kingdom}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n|title=Poisoning of Sergei and Yulia Skripal\n|partof=\n|image=Forensic tent at The Maltings, Salisbury (cropped).jpg\n|caption=A [[Crime scene|forensics tent]] covers the bench where Sergei and Yulia Skripal fell unconscious\n|image_upright=1.3\n|alt=\n|map=\n|map_size=\n|map_alt=\n|map_caption=\n|location=[[Salisbury]], [[Wiltshire]], United Kingdom\n|target=[[Sergei Skripal|Sergei Viktorovich Skripal]]<br/>Yulia Sergeevna Skripal\n|coordinates=\n|date=4 March 2018\n|time=\n|timezone=\n|injuries=\n|victims= 3 admitted to hospital<br/>(subsequently discharged):<br/>The Skripals<br/>Det Sgt Nick Bailey, [[Wiltshire Police|Wilts Police]].<br/>[[2018 Amesbury poisonings|Two other people were poisoned later]], one died\n|perpetrator=\n|assailants=<!-- or | assailant = -->\n|weapons=[[A-234 (nerve agent)|A-234]] (suspected chemical weapon used)<br/>\n|numparts=<!-- or | numpart = -->\n|dfens=<!-- or | dfen = -->\n|motive=\n|inquiry=\n|coroner=\n|accused=Russian nationals \"Alexander Petrov\" (alleged alias of [[Alexander Mishkin|Dr. Alexander Mishkin]]<ref name=Mishkin>Second Skripal Poisoning Suspect Identified as Dr. Alexander Mishkin. 2018. Bellingcat. 8 Oct. https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2018/10/08/second-skripal-poisoning-suspect-identified-as-dr-alexander-mishkin/. Retrieved: 9 October 2018.</ref>)<br/> and \"Ruslan Boshirov\"<ref name=BBCnames/> (alleged alias of [[Polkovnik|Colonel]] [[Anatoliy Chepiga]])<ref>{{cite news |title=GRU colonel Chepiga revealed as Skripal suspect's 'real identity' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-45656004 |accessdate=26 September 2018 |work=BBC News |date=26 September 2018}}</ref>\n|convicted=\n|verdict=\n|convictions=\n|charges=\n|litigation=\n|website=<!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n|module=\n}}\n<!--Important, do not revert.-->\n\nOn 4 March 2018, [[Sergei Skripal]], a former Russian military officer and double agent for the UK's [[intelligence services]], and his daughter Yulia Skripal were poisoned in [[Salisbury]], [[Wiltshire]], [[England]], with a [[Novichok agent|Novichok nerve agent]], according to official UK sources<ref name=\"Guardian May\">{{cite news|last1=Asthana|first1=Anushka|last2=Roth|first2=Andrew|last3=Harding|first3=Luke|last4=MacAskill|first4=Ewen|title=May issues ultimatum to Moscow over Salisbury poisoning|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/12/russia-highly-likely-to-be-behind-poisoning-of-spy-says-theresa-may|accessdate=13 March 2018|work=The Guardian|date=12 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"graun\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/07/russian-spy-police-appeal-for-witnesses-as-cobra-meeting-takes-place|title=Sergei Skripal: former Russian spy poisoned with nerve agent, say police|last=Dodd|first=Vikram|last2=Harding|first2=Luke|last3=MacAskill|first3=Ewen|date=8 March 2018|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=8 March 2018}}</ref> and the [[Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons|Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW)]].<ref name=\"dw\">{{cite news |url=https://www.dw.com/en/salisbury-attack-chemical-weapons-watchdog-confirms-uk-findings-on-nerve-agent/a-43358224 |title=Salisbury attack: Chemical weapons watchdog confirms UK findings on nerve agent |publisher=Deutsche Welle |date=12 April 2018 |accessdate=10 June 2018}}</ref> After three weeks in a critical condition, Yulia regained consciousness and was able to speak. She was discharged on 9 April 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43588450|title=Russian spy: Yulia Skripal 'conscious and talking'|publisher=BBC News|date=29 March 2018|accessdate=29 March 2018|postscript=none}}; {{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-43652574|title=Russian spy poisoning: Yulia Skripal 'getting stronger daily'|publisher=BBC News|date=5 April 2018|accessdate=6 April 2018|postscript=none}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/britain-russia-skripal-yulia/text-yulia-skripal-daughter-of-poisoned-russian-spy-in-her-own-words-idUSL5N1SU4TZ |title=After 20 days in a coma|author=<!--Not stated--> |date=23 May 2018 |website= Reuters.com|publisher= Reuters|access-date=21 August 2018 }}</ref> Sergei was also in a critical condition until he regained consciousness one month after the attack. He was discharged from hospital on 18 May 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-russia-skripal-hospital/poisoned-russian-agent-sergei-skripal-recovering-rapidly-hospital-says-idUKKCN1HD1PB|title=Poisoned Russian agent Sergei Skripal recovering rapidly, hospital ...|first=Alistair|last=Smout}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43671958|title=Ex-spy 'improving rapidly' after poisoning|date=6 April 2018|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> A police officer was also taken into intensive care after apparent exposure to the remnants of the toxic agent at Sergei Skripal's residence. By 22 March he had recovered enough to leave the hospital.<ref name=discharged/><ref name=\"BBC20180405\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43315636|title=Russian spy: What we know so far|date=5 April 2018|accessdate=6 April 2018|work=BBC News}}</ref>{{efn|Stephen Davies of Salisbury NHS Foundation Trust wrote an open letter to ''[[The Times]]'', published on 16 March 2018, clarifying that contrary to reports, no members of the public were affected: \"Sir, Further to your report (\"Poison exposure leaves almost 40 needing treatment\", 14 March), may I clarify that no patients have experienced symptoms of nerve agent poisoning in Salisbury and there have only ever been three patients with significant poisoning. Several people have attended the emergency department concerned that they may have been exposed. None has had symptoms of poisoning and none has needed treatment. Any blood tests performed have shown no abnormality. No member of the public has been contaminated by the agent involved.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/russia-salisbury-poison-fears-allayed-by-doctor-vf9v0zg0m |title=Russia: Salisbury poison fears allayed by doctor |last=Simpson |first=John |date=16 March 2018 |last2=Haynes |first2=Deboarh |editor-last=Hamilton |editor-first= Fiona|website= |access-date=29 March 2018}}</ref>}}\n\nIn the 1990s, Sergei Skripal was an officer for Russia's [[Main Intelligence Directorate]] (GRU) and worked as a [[double agent]] for the UK's [[Secret Intelligence Service]] from 1995 until his arrest in Moscow in December 2004. In August 2006, he was convicted of [[Treason#Russia|high treason]] and sentenced to 13 years in a [[penal colony]] by a Russian court.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Russian jailed for spying for MI6|work=[[London Evening Standard]]|location=London|date=9 August 2006|page=4}}</ref> He settled in the UK in 2010 following the [[Illegals Program]] [[Prisoner exchange|spy swap]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=The great spy swap: huge exchange of agents underway after 'deep cover' ring exposed|work=[[The Guardian]]|location=London|date=9 July 2010|page=3}}</ref> Sergei holds dual Russian and British citizenship; Yulia is a Russian citizen, and was visiting her father from Moscow.<ref name=\"dw-20180406\">{{cite news |url=https://www.dw.com/en/the-curious-case-of-yulia-skripals-recorded-phone-call/a-43287554 |title=The curious case of Yulia Skripal's recorded phone call |last=Janjevic |first=Darko |newspaper=Deutsche Welle |date=6 April 2018 |accessdate=10 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nLater on 12 March, the British government accused Russia of attempted murder and announced a series of punitive measures against Russia, including the expulsion of diplomats, on the 14 March. The UK's official assessment of the incident was supported by 28 other countries which responded similarly. Altogether, an unprecedented 153 Russian diplomats were expelled.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chughtai, Petkova|title=Skripal case diplomatic expulsions in numbers|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/interactive/2018/04/skripal-case-diplomatic-expulsions-numbers-180402121217839.html|website=Al Jazeera|accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref> Russia denied the accusations and responded similarly to the expulsions and \"accused Britain of the poisoning.\"<ref name=\"independent\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/sergei-skripal-latest-salisbury-poisoning-attack-russia-nerve-agent-sergei-lavrov-a8284766.html|title=Russia claims it could have been in interests of Britain to poison Sergei Skripal|date= 2 April 2018|accessdate=3 April 2018|newspaper=[[The Independent]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 June 2018, [[2018 Amesbury poisonings|a similar poisoning]] of two British nationals in [[Amesbury]], seven miles north of Salisbury, involved the same nerve agent.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-44719639|title=Wiltshire pair poisoned by Novichok nerve agent|date=4 July 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=5 July 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-wiltshire-44707052|title=Two collapse near spy poisoning site|date=4 July 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=5 July 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> A man found the nerve agent in a perfume bottle, in a litter bin, somewhere in Salisbury and gave it to a woman who sprayed it on her wrist.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/jul/24/novichok-victim-ill-within-15-minutes-says-partner-charlie-rowley |title=Novichok victim ill within 15 minutes, says partner Charlie Rowley |author=Press Association|date= 24 July 2018 |work=The Guardian }}</ref><ref>https://www.itv.com/news/2018-07-26/novichok-charlie-rowley-amesbury-nerve-agent-exclusive/</ref> The woman, Dawn Sturgess, fell ill within 15 minutes and died on 8 July, but the man who also came into contact with the poison survived.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/jul/09/novichok-wiltshire-death-dawn-sturgess-highly-likely-same-batch-used-on-skripals |title=Novichok in Wiltshire death 'highly likely' from batch used on Skripals |authors=Vikram Dodd, Steven Morris and Caroline Bannock|date=9 July 2018 |work=The Guardian }}</ref> British police believe this incident was not a targeted attack, but a result of the way the nerve agent was disposed of after the poisoning in Salisbury.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tobin |first=Olivia |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/crime/novichok-poisoning-probe-police-say-there-is-no-doubt-novichok-victims-are-linked-and-charlie-rowley-a3928426.html |title=Novichok poisoning probe: Police say there is 'no doubt' Novichok victims are linked and Charlie Rowley and Dawn Sturgess were innocent tragic victims |work=Evening Standard |date=5 September 2018 |accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 September 2018, British authorities identified two Russian nationals, using the names Alexander Petrov and Ruslan Boshirov, as suspected of the Skripals' poisoning,<ref name=BBCnames/> and alleged that they were active officers in Russian military intelligence.<ref name=\"NYT20180905\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/05/world/europe/russia-uk-novichok-skripal.html|title=U.K. Charges 2 Men in Novichok Poisoning, Saying They're Russian Agents|last=P\u00e9rez-Pe\u00f1a|first=Richard|date=5 September 2018|work=New York Times|access-date=2018-09-05|last2=Barry|first2=Ellen|language=en}}</ref> On 26 September 2018, investigative website [[Bellingcat]] published a statement that it had positively identified the man known as Ruslan Boshirov as the highly decorated [[GRU]] [[Polkovnik|Colonel]] [[Anatoliy Chepiga]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/report-third-russian-agent-involved-in-skripal-mission-identified-/29514321.html|title=Report: Third Alleged Russian Agent Involved in Skripal Mission Identified|website=RadioFreeEurope/RadioLiberty|language=en|access-date=2018-09-29}}</ref> On 8 October 2018, Bellingcat revealed the real identity of the suspect named by police as Alexander Petrov to be [[Alexander Mishkin|Dr. Alexander Mishkin]], also of the GRU.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2018/10/08/second-skripal-poisoning-suspect-identified-as-dr-alexander-mishkin/|title=Second Skripal Poisoning Suspect Identified as Dr. Alexander Mishkin|date=8 October 2018|accessdate=9 October 2018|publisher=Bellingcat}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2018/10/09/full-report-skripal-poisoning-suspect-dr-alexander-mishkin-hero-russia/|title=Full report: Skripal Poisoning Suspect Dr. Alexander Mishkin, Hero of Russia|date=9 October 2018|accessdate=9 October 2018|publisher=Bellingcat}}</ref> A third GRU officer present in the UK during the time Sergey and Yulia Skripal fell into a coma has been identified as Denis Vyacheslavovich Sergeev, a graduate of [[Diplomatic Academy of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation|Russia's Military Diplomatic Academy]].<ref>Bellingcat, 14 February 2019 [https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2019/02/14/third-suspect-in-skripal-poisoning-identified-as-denis-sergeev-high-ranking-gru-officer/ Suspect in Scripal poisoning identified as Denis Sergeev]</ref><ref>Bellingcat 21 February 2019 [https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2019/02/21/the-search-for-denis-sergeev-photographing-a-ghost/ The search for Denis Sergeev]</ref> Denis Sergeyev is believed to hold the rank of major general in the GRU. The pattern of his communications while in the UK indicates that Maj Gen Sergeyev liaised with superior officers in Moscow.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-48801205|title=Skripal poisoning: Third man 'commanded attack'|first=Mark|last=Urban|date=28 June 2019|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> The attempted assassination was allegedly organized by a secret [[Unit 29155]] of the Russian GRU under command of Maj. Gen. Andrei V. Averyanov. The unit is allegedly responsible for destabilizing European countries and organized the [[Montenegrin coup plot|Montenegrin coup attempt]].<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/08/world/europe/unit-29155-russia-gru.html?action=click&module=Top%20Stories&pgtype=Homepage Top Secret Russian Unit Seeks to Destabilize Europe, Security Officials Say], [[New York Times]]</ref>\n\nOn 27 November 2019, the OPCW global chemical weapons watchdog added Novichok, the Soviet-era nerve agent used in the attack, to its list of banned toxins.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-019-03686-y|title=Novichok nerve agents banned by chemical-weapons treaty|date=28 November 2019|via=www.nature.com}}</ref>\n\n==Poisoning==\n*At 14:40 [[Greenwich Mean Time]] on 3 March 2018, Yulia Skripal flew to Heathrow Airport from Russia.\n*At 9:15 on 4 March Sergei Skripal's burgundy 2009 [[BMW 3 Series|BMW 320d]] was seen in the area of London Road, Churchill Way North and Wilton Road at Salisbury.\n*At 13:30 Skripal's car was seen on Devizes Road on the way towards the town centre.\n*At 13:40 the Skripals arrived in the upper level car park at the Maltings, Salisbury and then went to the Bishops Mill Pub in the town centre.\n*At 14:20 they dined at [[Zizzi]] on Castle Street.\n*At 15:35 they left the Zizzi restaurant.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ongoing investigation into incident in Salisbury on 4 March |url=https://news.met.police.uk/news/ongoing-investigation-into-incident-in-salisbury-on-4-march-309256 |website=Metropolitan Police |accessdate=6 June 2018}}</ref>\n*At 16:15 an [[emergency service]]s call reported that Sergei Skripal, a 66-year-old resident of Salisbury, and his 33-year-old daughter Yulia had been found unconscious on a public bench in the centre of [[Salisbury]] by a passing doctor and nurse.{{efn|The nurse was the Chief Nursing Officer for the Army and the commanding officer of the [[Queen Alexandra's Royal Army Nursing Corps]], Colonel Alison L McCourt OBE ARRC QHN; her teenage daughter later received an award for alerting her mother and assisting in first aid.<ref name=guardian-20190120>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/jan/20/novichok-poisoning-victims-sergei-skripal-first-helped-by-teenage-girl |title=Novichok poisoning victims first helped by teenage girl |newspaper=The Guardian |agency=Press Association |date=20 January 2019 |accessdate=17 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=qarancassociation-2018>{{cite web |url=https://www.qarancassociation.org.uk/association-news/item/293-chief-nursing-officer-colonel-a-l-mccourt-obe-arrc-qhn |title=Chief Nursing Officer - Colonel A L McCourt OBE ARRC QHN |publisher=The QARANC Association |year=2018 |accessdate=17 April 2019}}</ref>}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Russian spy: What we know so far|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43315636|publisher=BBC News|date=8 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/03/05/alleged-former-russian-spy-critically-exposure-unknown-substance/|title=Alleged former Russian spy critically ill after exposure to unknown substance in Salisbury|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=5 March 2018|access-date=8 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/06/world/europe/uk-russian-spy-counterterrorism.html|title=In Poisoning of Sergei Skripal, Russian Ex-Spy, U.K. Sees Cold War Echoes|last=Kingsley|first=Patrick|date=6 March 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=15 March 2018|last2=P\u00e9rez-Pe\u00f1a|first2=Richard|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> An eyewitness saw Yulia foaming at the mouth with her eyes wide open but completely white.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43315636|title=Russian spy: What we know so far|publisher=BBC|date=18 March 2018|accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref> According to a later British government statement they were \"slipping in and out of consciousness on a public bench\".<ref name=unsc-20180314/>\n*At 17:10, they were taken separately to [[Salisbury District Hospital]] by an ambulance and an air ambulance.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/10/salisbury-poisoning-sergei-skripal-local-news-international-incident|title=How Salisbury case went from local drama to international incident|work=The Guardian|date=10 March 2018|accessdate=20 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt 09:03 the following morning, [[Salisbury NHS Foundation Trust]] declared a major incident in response to concerns raised by medical staff; shortly afterwards this became a multi-agency incident named Operation Fairline.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tvscn.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/Christine-Blanshard.pdf|title=Responding to Recent Events in Salisbury|last=Blanshard|first=Christine|date=12 June 2018|website=Thames Valley Strategic Clinical Network|publisher=Salisbury NHS Foundation Trust|page=5|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43295134|date=5 March 2018|access-date=8 March 2018|publisher=BBC News|title=Critically ill man 'former Russian spy'}}</ref>\n\nHealth authorities checked 21 members of the emergency services and the public for possible symptoms;<ref name=\"itv-20180308\">{{cite news |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2018-03-08/nerve-agent-attack-state-russian-spy-daughter/ |title=Up to 21 people treated after nerve agent attack on Russian spy Sergei Skripal |publisher=ITV News |date=8 March 2018 |access-date=9 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"bbcr4wato-20180309\">{{cite AV media|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b09tc4xr|title=World at One|date=9 March 2018|last=Casciani|first=Dominic|publisher=BBC Radio 4|time=21m47s|access-date=9 March 2018|quote=There was some erroneous reporting that there were 21 other people being treated, that is not true, there has only been these three casualties and they are all still in hospital}}</ref> two police officers were treated for minor symptoms, said to be itchy eyes and wheezing, while one, Detective Sergeant Nick Bailey, who had been sent to Sergei Skripal's house, had been in a serious condition.<ref name=\"Mendick\">{{cite news|author=Robert Mendick|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/03/09/russian-spy-may-have-poisoned-home-police-believe|website=The Daily Telegraph|title=Russian spy may have been poisoned at home, police believe, as military deployed to Salisbury|date=9 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Russian spy 'attacked with nerve agent'|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43323847|publisher=BBC News|date=7 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March 2018, Detective Sergeant Nick Bailey was discharged from the hospital. In a statement he said \"normal life for me will probably never be the same\" and also thanked the hospital staff.<ref name=\"discharged\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43506232|title=Policeman discharged after ex-spy attack|publisher=BBC News|access-date=23 March 2018}}</ref> {{as of|2018| March|26}}, Skripal and his daughter remained critically ill.<ref name=\"march26\">{{cite news|title=More than 130 people could have been exposed to novichok, PM says |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/26/130-people-feared-exposed-to-novichok-in-spy-attack-says-pm|work=The Guardian|date=26 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=A poisoned Russian spy and his daughter may never recover their full mental functions, a British judge said|url=https://www.newsweek.com/poisoned-russian-spy-may-never-recover-mental-functions-british-judge-says-858925|website=Newsweek|date=23 March 2018}}</ref> On 29 March 2018 it was announced that Yulia Skripal's condition was improving and she was no longer in a critical condition.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43588450|title=Ex-spy's daughter 'improving rapidly'|date=29 March 2018|publisher=BBC News|access-date=29 March 2018}}</ref> On 5 April 2018 doctors said that Sergei Skripal was no longer in critical condition and was responding well to treatment.<ref name=\"Sergei_improvement\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43671958|title=Russian spy poisoning: Sergei Skripal 'improving rapidly'|publisher=BBC News|access-date=5 April 2018}}</ref> On 9 April 2018, Yulia Skripal was discharged from hospital and taken to a secure location.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43710126|title=Russian spy: Daughter discharged from hospital|publisher=BBC News|access-date=10 April 2018|date=10 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43733765|title=No-one speaks for me \u2013 Yulia Skripal|date=12 April 2018|publisher=BBC News|access-date=12 April 2018}}</ref> On 18 May 2018, Sergei Skripal was discharged from the hospital too.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ex-spy Sergei Skripal discharged after poisoning|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-44165718|accessdate=18 May 2018|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> On 23 May 2018, a handwritten letter and a video statement by Yulia Skripal were released to the Reuters news agency for the first time after the poisoning. She stated that she was lucky to be alive after the poisoning and thanked the staff of the Salisbury hospital. She described her treatment as slow, heavy and extremely painful and she had a scar on her neck, apparently from a [[tracheotomy]]. She expressed her hope that someday she would return to Russia. She thanked the Russian embassy for its offer of assistance but said she and her father were \"not ready to take it\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-russia-skripal-yulia-exclusiv/exclusive-yulia-skripal-attempted-assassination-turned-my-world-upside-down-idUSKCN1IO2LT |title=Exclusive: Yulia Skripal - Attempted assassination turned my world upside down|date=23 May 2018|publisher=[[Reuters]]|access-date=25 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April 2018, British authorities said that inside Sergey Skripal's house, which had been sealed by the police, two guinea pigs were found dead by [[Veterinary physician|vets]], when they were allowed in, along with a cat in a distressed state.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/04/06/europe/sergei-skripal-cat-guinea-pigs-dead-intl/index.html|title=Sergei Skripal's cat and guinea pigs are dead, UK says|date=6 April 2018|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 November the first interview with DS Bailey was released in which he reported that he had been poisoned, despite the fact that he inspected the Skripals' house using [[Personal protective equipment|a forensic suit]]. In addition to the poisoning, Bailey and his family had lost their home and all their possessions, because of contamination. Investigators said that the perfume bottle containing Novichok, which was later found in a bin, had contained enough of the nerve agent to potentially kill thousands of people.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-46290989|title=Skripal poisoning: Policeman's family 'lost everything' because of Novichok|last1=Corbin|first1=Jane|date=22 November 2018|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=23 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Sergey Skripal made a phone call and left a voice message to his niece living in Russia. Thus, insinuations that the UK \"abducted\" the Skripals and kept them from speaking with the Russian embassy were challenged.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Luhn |first1=Alec |title=Sergei Skripal heard for the first time since poisoning in phone call, relatives say |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/05/23/sergei-skripal-heard-first-time-since-poisoning-phone-call-relatives/ |accessdate=29 May 2019 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |date=23 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019 it was confirmed that a second police officer had been poisoned when investigating, but only in trace amounts.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-wiltshire-49361327|title=Salisbury Novichok attack poisoned second officer, Met confirms|agency=BBC|date=15 August 2019|accessdate=16 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\nThe first public response to the poisoning came on 6 March. It was agreed under the [[National Counter Terrorism Policing Network]] that the [[Counter Terrorism Command]] based within the [[Metropolitan Police Service|Metropolitan Police]] would take over the investigation from [[Wiltshire Police]]. Assistant Commissioner Mark Rowley, head of Counter Terrorism Policing, appealed for witnesses to the incident following a [[Cabinet Office Briefing Rooms|COBR]] meeting chaired by [[Home Secretary]] [[Amber Rudd]].<ref name=\"BBC43312625\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43312625|title='More known' about substance in spy case|date=7 March 2018|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nSamples of the nerve agent used in the attack tested positive at the [[Defence Science and Technology Laboratory]] at [[Porton Down]] for a \"very rare\" nerve agent, according to the UK Home Secretary.<ref name=\"Merrick\">{{cite news|author=Rob Merrick |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/russian-spy-poison-sergei-skripal-wife-murder-son-mp-tom-tugendhat-nerve-agent-kremlin-a8246381.html|title=Russian spy: Poisoned Sergei Skripal's wife and son were murdered, alleges Conservative MP|website=Independent|date=8 March 2018|access-date=8 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n180 military experts in chemical warfare defence and decontamination, as well as 18 vehicles, were deployed on 9 March to assist the Metropolitan Police to remove vehicles and objects from the scene and look for any further traces of the nerve agent. The personnel were drawn mostly from the Army, including instructors from the [[Defence CBRN Centre]] and the [[8th Engineer Brigade (United Kingdom)|29 Explosive Ordnance Disposal and Search Group]], as well as from the [[Royal Marines]] and [[Royal Air Force]]. The vehicles included [[TPz Fuchs]] operated by Falcon Squadron from the [[Royal Tank Regiment]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43344725|title=Military deployed after spy poisoning|date=9 March 2018|publisher=BBC News|access-date=9 March 2018}}</ref> On 11 March, the UK government advised those present at either The Mill pub or the [[Zizzi]] restaurant in Salisbury on 4 and 5 March to wash or wipe their possessions, emphasising that the risk to the general public was low.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/687273/PHE_public_advice_leaflet_-_Salisbury_nerve_agent_incident.pdf|title=Public health advice for those who were in The Mill pub or Zizzi restaurant in Salisbury on Sunday 4th or Monday 5th March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43362673|title=Salisbury diners told to wash possessions|date=11 March 2018|publisher=BBC News|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nSeveral days later, on 12 March, Prime Minister [[Theresa May]] said the agent had been identified as one of the [[Novichok agent|Novichok family of agents]], believed to have been developed in the 1980s by the [[Soviet Union]].<ref name=\"mayspeech12march\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43377856|title=Russian spy: Highly likely Moscow behind attack, says Theresa May|publisher=BBC News|date=12 March 2018|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref> According to the Russian ambassador to the UK, [[Alexander Vladimirovich Yakovenko|Alexander Yakovenko]], the British authorities identified the agent as [[A-234 (nerve agent)|A-234]],<ref name=\"bbcnovichok\">{{cite web |title=Russian spy: What are Novichok agents and what do they do? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-43377698 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=10 June 2018 |date=19 March 2018}}</ref> derived from an earlier version known as A-232.<ref name=\"reut0504\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-russia-explainer/what-is-known-and-not-known-about-poisoning-of-ex-spy-in-britain-idUSKCN1HC148|title=Explainer: What is known, and not known, about poisoning of ex-spy in Britain|publisher=Reuters|date=5 April 2018|accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nBy 14 March, the investigation was focused on Skripal's home and car, a bench where the two fell unconscious, a restaurant in which they dined and a pub where they had drinks.<ref name=\"The Guardian (2)\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/14/police-five-key-locations-salisbury-in-skripal-attempted-case|title=Police home in on five key locations in Skripal attempted murder case|last=Morris|first=Steven|date=14 March 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref> A recovery vehicle was removed by the military from [[Gillingham, Dorset|Gillingham]] in Dorset on 14 March, in connection with the poisoning.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/westcountry/update/2018-03-14/police-cordon-off-road-in-gillingham-following-poisoning-in-salisbury/|title=Police cordon off road in Gillingham following poisoning in Salisbury|work=ITV News|access-date=16 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.somersetlive.co.uk/news/local-news/gillingham-dorset-becomes-latest-town-1337253|title=Local reveals van in new spy poison cordon area has been there for days|last=Trim|first=Liam|date=14 March 2018|work=somersetlive|access-date=16 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nSubsequently, there was speculation within the British media that the nerve agent had been planted in one of the personal items in Yulia Skripal's suitcase before she left Moscow for London,<ref>{{cite news |author1=Mendick, Robert |author2=Sawer, Patrick |author3=Ward, Victoria |title=Suitcase spy poisoning plot: nerve agent 'was planted in luggage of Sergei Skripal's daughter' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/03/15/suitcase-spy-poisoning-plot-nerve-agent-planted-luggage-sergei/ |accessdate=10 June 2018 |work=The Telegraph |date=15 March 2018}}</ref> and in US media that it had been planted in their car.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/18/ex-russian-spy-may-have-been-poisoned-by-cars-ventilation-says-us-media|title=Sergei Skripal possibly poisoned through car's air vents, say US media|last=Association|first=Press|date=18 March 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=29 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/russian-spys-poisoning-uk-believed-nerve-agent-car/story?id=53832515|title=Russian ex-spy's poisoning in UK believed from nerve agent in car vents: Sources|date=18 March 2018|publisher=ABC News|access-date=29 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Ahmet \u00dcz\u00fcmc\u00fc]], Director-General of the [[Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons]] (OPCW), said on 20 March that it will take \"another two to three weeks to finalise the analysis\" of samples taken from the poisoning of Skripal.<ref>\"[https://www.afp.com/en/news/826/two-three-weeks-analyze-samples-salisbury-attack-opcw-doc-12w0he1 Two to three weeks to analyze samples from Salisbury attack: OPCW]\". Agence France-Presse. 20 March 2018.</ref> On 22 March, the [[Court of Protection]] gave permission for new blood samples to be obtained from Yulia and Sergei Skripal for use by the OPCW.<ref>[https://www.judiciary.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/sshd-v-skripal-and-another-20180322.pdf Justice Williams, High Court Judgement, Royal Courts of Justice, 22 March 2018]. judiciary.gov.uk.</ref><ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/mar/22/salisbury-attack-medical-staff-contacted-police-when-antidotes-failed-to-work |title=Judge gives permission for blood samples to be taken from the Skripals |author=Morris, Steven |date=22 March 2018 |work=The Guardian |access-date=28 March 2018}}</ref> By 28 March, the police investigation concluded that the Skripals were poisoned at Sergei's home, with the highest concentration being found on the handle of his front door.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43577987|title=Spy poisoning: Highest amount of nerve agent was on door|date=28 March 2018|accessdate=28 March 2018|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> On 12 April the OPCW confirmed the UK's analysis of the type of nerve agent and reported it was of a \"high purity\", stating that the \"name and structure of the identified toxic chemical are contained in the full classified report of the Secretariat, available to States Parties.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43741140|title=Inspectors back UK in spy poisoning row|date=12 April 2018|publisher=BBC News|access-date=12 April 2018}}; {{Cite news|url=https://www.afp.com/en/news/824/watchdog-confirms-uk-findings-nerve-agent-used-russian-ex-spy-doc-13y6ti1|title=Watchdog confirms UK findings on nerve agent used on Russian ex-spy|agency=AFP|access-date=12 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.opcw.org/news/article/opcw-issues-report-on-technical-assistance-requested-by-the-united-kingdom/|title=OPCW Issues Report on Technical Assistance Requested by the United Kingdom|publisher=OPCW|access-date=12 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.opcw.org/fileadmin/OPCW/S_series/2018/en/s-1612-2018_e_.pdf |title=Summary of the Report on Activities Carried Out in Support of a Request for Technical Assistance by the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland (Technical Assistance Visit TAV/02/18) |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=12 April 2018 |publisher=OPCW |access-date=12 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nA declassified letter from the UK's national security adviser, Sir Mark Sedwill, to NATO Secretary General [[Jens Stoltenberg]], stated Russian military intelligence hacked Yulia Skripal's email account since at least 2013 and tested methods for delivering nerve agents including on door handles.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2018/04/13/russia-hacked-yulia-skripals-emails-five-years-tested-novichok/|title=Russia hacked Yulia Skripal's emails for five years and tested Novichok on door handles, bombshell intelligence dossier reveals|last=Rayner|first=Gordon|date=13 April 2018|work=The Telegraph|access-date=13 April 2018|last2=Maidment |first2=Jack}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Department for Environment]] confirmed the nerve agent was delivered \"in a liquid form\". They said eight sites require decontamination, which will take several months to complete and cost millions of pounds. The BBC reported experts said the nerve agent does not evaporate or disappear over time. Intense cleaning with caustic chemicals is required to get rid of it.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43798068|title=Skripal nerve agent 'was in liquid form'|date=17 April 2018|publisher=BBC News|access-date=18 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43833582|title=Salisbury toxic hotspots clean-up begins|date=20 April 2018|publisher=BBC News|access-date=20 April 2018}}</ref> The Skripals' survival was possibly due to the weather&nbsp;\u2013 there had been heavy fog and high humidity, and according to its inventor and other scientists, moisture weakens the potency of this type of toxin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/3600889|title=\u0412 \u0443\u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438\u044f\u0445 \u0432\u043b\u0430\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u0435\u043d\u044f\u0442\u044c \u044d\u0442\u043e \u0432\u0435\u0449\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u043c\u043e\u0433 \u0442\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043a\u043e \u0438\u0434\u0438\u043e\u0442|date=4 December 2018|work=Kommersant}}</ref><ref name=\"independent1203\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/novichok-nerve-agent-what-is-it-russian-spy-poisoning-sergei-skripal-a8252426.html|title=What is Novichok? The powerful nerve agent that makes it 'highly likely' Russia poisoned former spy|author=Andrew Griffin |date=12 March 2018|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=14 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"smc83\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sciencemediacentre.org/expert-reaction-to-nerve-agent-being-substance-identified-in-case-of-russian-ex-spy-and-his-daughter/|title=expert reaction to nerve agent being substance identified in case of Russian ex-spy and his daughter|date=8 March 2018|publisher=Science Media Centre|accessdate=14 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 April 2018, it was reported that British counter-terror police have identified a suspect in the poisoning of Sergei and Yulia Skripal. The suspect is a former FSB officer (reportedly a 54-year-old former FSB captain) who acted under several code names including \"Gordon\" and \"Mihails Savickis\". According to detectives, he led a team of six Russian assassins who organized the chemical weapons attack.<ref name=\"Gordon2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.svoboda.org/a/29185223.html|title=British media: Skripal was poisoned by former FSB officer \"Gordon\" |language=Russian |website=svoboda.org}}</ref> Sir [[Mark Sedwill]], [[National Security Adviser (United Kingdom)|UK national security adviser]], reported on 1 May 2018 however that UK intelligence and police agencies had failed to identify the individual or individuals who carried out the attack.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/may/01/no-suspects-yet-in-skripal-nerve-agent-attack-mps-told|title= No suspects yet in Skripal nerve agent attack, MPs told |last=MacAskill |first=Ewan |date=1 May 2018 |work=The Guardian |access-date=1 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 May 2018, the head of the OPCW, [[Ahmet \u00dcz\u00fcmc\u00fc]], informed the ''[[New York Times]]'' that he had been told that about 50\u2013100 g of the nerve agent was thought to have been used in the attack, which indicated it was likely created for use as a weapon and was enough to kill a large number of people.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/may/04/skripals-poisoned-by-novichok-in-liquid-form-watchdog-says|title=Skripals poisoned by novichok dose of up to 100g, watchdog says|last=Slawson|first=Nicola|date=3 May 2018 |work=The Guardian|language=en|access-date=25 May 2018 }}</ref> The next day however the OPCW made a correcting statement that the \"quantity should probably be characterised in milligrams\", though \"the OPCW would not be able to estimate or determine the amount of the nerve agent that was used\".<ref name=\"guardian-20180504\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/may/04/chemical-weapons-watchdog-amends-claim-over-salisbury-novichok |title=Chemical weapons watchdog amends claim over Salisbury novichok |last=Wintour |first=Patrick |work=The Guardian |date=4 May 2018 |accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"opcw-20180504\">{{cite web |url=https://www.opcw.org/news/article/opcw-spokespersons-statement-on-amount-of-nerve-agent-used-in-salisbury/ |title=OPCW Spokesperson's Statement on Amount of Nerve Agent Used in Salisbury |publisher=OPCW |date=4 May 2018 |accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 July the [[Press Association]] reported that police believed they had identified \"several Russians\" as the suspected perpetrators of the attack. They had been identified through [[CCTV]], cross-checked with [[Border Force|border entry data]].<ref name=\"bbc-20180719\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-44883803|publisher=BBC |title=Salisbury poisoning: Police 'identify Novichok suspects'|date=19 July 2018 |accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 August 2018, it was reported that the British government was \"poised to submit an extradition request to Moscow for two Russians suspected of carrying out the Salisbury nerve agent attack\". The Metropolitan Police used two [[super recogniser]]s to identify the suspects after trawling through up to 5,000 hours of CCTV footage from Salisbury and numerous airports across the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/aug/06/uk-poised-to-ask-russia-to-extradite-salisbury-attack-suspects|title=UK poised to ask Russia to extradite Salisbury attack suspects|first1=Nick|last1=Hopkins|first2=Luke|last2=Harding|first3=Ewen|last3=MacAskill|date=6 August 2018|website=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/super-recognisers-help-identify-skripal-suspects-11483995|title=Super recogniser squad tracks Skripal novichok attackers|date=28 August 2018|accessdate=6 September 2018|publisher=Sky News}}</ref>\n\n===Suspects and attack timeline===\nOn 5 September 2018, the [[Crown Prosecution Service]] announced charges in absentia against two alleged Russian agents. The two Russian nationals were believed to have been traveling under aliases, although they had genuine Russian passports with the identities of Alexander Petrov and Ruslan Boshirov when applying for visas and entering the UK. CPS said there was enough evidence to charge the men, but is not applying to Russia for the [[extradition]] of the two suspects. [[Interpol Red Notice]]s and domestic and [[European Arrest Warrant]]s were issued in case the suspects travel to the [[EU]].<ref name=\"BBCnames\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-45421445|title=Salisbury Novichok poisoning: Two Russian nationals named as suspects|date=5 September 2018|publisher=BBC News|access-date=5 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> As part of the announcement Scotland Yard and the [[Counter Terrorism Command]] released a detailed track of the individuals' 48 hours in the UK.<ref name=\"news-20180905\">{{cite web |url=http://news.met.police.uk/news/counter-terrorism-police-release-images-of-two-suspects-in-connection-with-salisbury-attack-320534 |title=Counter-terrorism police release images of two suspects in connection with Salisbury attack |publisher=Metropolitan Police |date=5 September 2018 |accessdate=9 September 2018}}</ref> This covered their arrival from Moscow in the UK at [[Gatwick Airport]], a trip to Salisbury by train the day before the attack, stated by police to be for [[reconnaissance]], a trip to Salisbury by train on the day of the attack, and return to Moscow via [[Heathrow Airport]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://home.bt.com/news/uk-news/novichock-suspects-the-48-hour-mission-to-kill-caught-on-camera-11364293544847|title=Novichok suspects \u2013 the 48-hour mission to kill caught on camera|date=5 September 2018|work=BT News|access-date=5 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT20180905\" /> The two men stayed both nights in the City Stay Hotel located next to [[Bow Church DLR station]] in [[Bow, London|Bow]] in the [[London Borough of Tower Hamlets]], East London. Novichok was found in their hotel room after police sealed it off on 4 May 2018. Neil Basu, National Lead for [[National Counter Terrorism Policing Network|Counter Terrorism Policing]] said that tests were carried out on their hotel room and it was \"deemed safe\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/russian-suspects-named-in-novichok-poisoning-probe-a3927811.html|title=Salisbury Novichok poisoning: Russian 'hit men' charged over nerve agent attack|date=5 September 2018|work=The Evening Standard|access-date=5 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/09/05/guests-two-star-london-hotel-salisbury-suspects-stayed-told/|title=Guests of two-star London hotel where Salisbury suspects stayed discover Novichok was found in bedroom|work=The Telegraph|access-date=5 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nBritish Prime Minister Theresa May announced in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|Commons]] the same day that British intelligence services had identified the two suspects as officers in the [[Main Intelligence Directorate|G. U. Intelligence Service]] (formerly known as GRU) and the assassination attempt was not a rogue operation and was \"almost certainly\" approved at a senior level of the Russian government.<ref name=\"BBCnames\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/09/05/russias-gru-murky-spy-agency-behind-salisbury-poisoning-failed/|title=Russia's GRU: The murky spy agency behind the Salisbury poisoning, a failed coup and US election hack|work=The Telegraph|access-date=5 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> May also said Britain will push for the EU to agree new sanctions against Russia.\n\nOn 5 September 2018, the Russian news site Fontanka reported that the numbers on leaked passport files for Petrov and Boshirov are only three digits apart, and fall in a range that includes the passport files for a Russian military official expelled from Poland for spying.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.fontanka.ru/2018/09/05/075/ |title=\u0427\u0442\u043e \"\u0424\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0435\" \u0438\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043d\u043e \u043e \u043f\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0437\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0430\u0435\u043c\u044b\u0445 \u0432 \u043e\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u0421\u043a\u0440\u0438\u043f\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0439 |trans-title=What \"Fontanka\" know about the suspected poisoning of the Skripals|last=\u0415\u0440\u043c\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432|first=\u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440|date=5 September 2018|work=Fontanka.ru|access-date=25 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.fontanka.ru/2018/09/22/009/|title=\u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043e \u0442\u0443\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e. \u041f\u043e\u0447\u0435\u043c\u0443 \u043a\u0442\u043e-\u0442\u043e \u043c\u043e\u0433 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u043d\u044f\u0442\u044c \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0438 \u0411\u043e\u0448\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0437\u0430 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0447\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432|last=\u0415\u0440\u043c\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432|first=\u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440|date=22 September 2018|work=Fontanka.ru|access-date=25 September 2018}}</ref> It is not known how the passport files were obtained, but Andrew Roth, the Moscow correspondent for ''[[The Guardian]]'', commented that \"If the reporting is confirmed, it would be a major blunder by the intelligence agency, allowing any country to check passport data for Russians requesting visas or entering the country against a list of nearly 40 passport files of suspected GRU officers.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/sep/23/russian-passport-leak-after-salisbury-may-reveal-spy-methods|title=Russian passport leak after Salisbury may reveal spy methods|last=Roth|first=Andrew|date=23 September 2018|website=The Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-09-25}}</ref> On 14 September 2018, the online platform [[Bellingcat]] and the Russian publication The Insider noted that in Petrov's leaked passport files, there is no record of a residential address or any identification papers prior to 2009, suggesting that the name is an alias created that year; the analysis also noted that Petrov's dossier is stamped \"Do not provide any information\" and has the handwritten annotation \"S.S.,\" a common abbreviation in Russian for \"top secret.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2018/09/14/skripal-poisoning-suspects-passport-data-shows-link-security-services/|title=Skripal Poisoning Suspect's Passport Data Shows Link to Security Services|date=14 September 2018|publisher=Bellingcat|access-date=25 September 2018}}</ref> On 15 September 2018, the Russian opposition newspaper ''[[Novaya Gazeta]]'' reported finding in Petrov's passport files a cryptic number that seems to be a [[Telephone numbers in Russia|telephone number]] associated with the [[Ministry of Defence (Russia)|Russian Defense Ministry]], most likely the Military Intelligence Directorate.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/18/world/europe/skripal-poisoning-russia.html|title=Tragedy? Farce? Confusion? The Method Behind That Russian Poisoning Interview |last=Higgins|first=Andrew|date=18 September 2018|work=New York Times|access-date=19 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 September 2018, the real identity of the suspect named by police as Ruslan Boshirov was revealed as [[Polkovnik|Colonel]] [[Anatoliy Vladimirovich Chepiga]] by ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', citing reporting by itself and Bellingcat, with Petrov having a more junior rank in the GRU.<ref>''Newsnight'', BBC2, 26 September 2018</ref> The 39-year-old was made a [[Hero of the Russian Federation]] by decree of the President in 2014. Two European security sources confirmed that the details were accurate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.trust.org//item/20180926171507-6mtxt/|title=Salisbury poisoning suspect named as a Russian colonel by UK media|publisher=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=26 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/09/26/revealed-battle-hardened-spetsnaz-brigade-special-forces-unit/|title=Revealed: The battle-hardened Spetsnaz Brigade special forces unit that trained Skripal 'hitman'|first1=Robert|last1=Mendick|first2=Hayley|last2=Dixon|date=26 September 2018|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=26 September 2018}}</ref> The BBC commented: \"The BBC understands there is no dispute over the identification.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-45656004|title=Skripal suspect 'real identity revealed'|date=26 September 2018|publisher=BBC|accessdate=26 September 2018}}</ref> The [[Secretary of State for Defence|British defense minister]] [[Gavin Williamson]] wrote: \"The true identity of one of the Salisbury suspects has been revealed to be a Russian Colonel. I want to thank all the people who are working so tirelessly on this case.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-russia-skripal-williamson/true-identity-of-salisbury-suspect-revealed-uk-defense-minister-says-idUSKCN1M62QG|title='True identity' of Salisbury suspect revealed, UK defense minister says |publisher=[[Reuters]]|date=26 September 2018|accessdate=26 September 2018}}</ref> However, that statement was subsequently deleted from Twitter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/anatoliy-chepiga-who-is-the-hero-russian-colonel-suspected-of-the-salisbury-attack-11509974|title=Anatoliy Chepiga: Who is the 'hero' Russian colonel suspected of the Salisbury attack?|publisher=Sky News|access-date=2018-10-03|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 October 2018, the real identity of the suspect named by police as Alexander Petrov was revealed as [[Alexander Mishkin|Dr. Alexander Mishkin]].<ref name=Mishkin/><ref name=\"Indy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/salisbury-attack-dr-alexander-mishkin-putin-handshake-russia-suspect-novichok-skripals-a8575846.html|title=Salisbury novichok suspect Dr Alexander Mishkin 'photographed shaking Vladimir Putin's hand'|work=Independent}}</ref><ref name=\"Mendick2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/10/09/russian-hitmans-grandmother-vanishes-telling-friends-putin-gave/|title=Russian spy's grandmother vanishes after telling friends Putin gave him a hero's medal|first1=Robert|last1=Mendick |first2=Alec|last2=Luhn|date=9 October 2018|work=Telegraph}}</ref><ref name=\"Goryashko\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-45799037|title=Novichok suspect traced to tiny village|first=Sergei Goryashko, Andrei Soshnikov and Andrei|last=Zakharov|date=9 October 2018|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 November 2018, more CCTV footage, with the two suspects walking in Salisbury, was published by the police.<ref>{{cite news |title=Skripal poisoning: CCTV shows suspects 'on way to victims' home' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/uk-46312222/skripal-poisoning-cctv-shows-suspects-on-way-to-victims-home |accessdate=23 November 2018 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 December 2018, Mishkin (a.k.a. Petrov) and Chepiga (a.k.a. Boshirov) were added to the sanctions list of [[United States Department of the Treasury|USA Treasury Department]] along with other 13 members of the GRU agency.<ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. targets GRU officers linked to hacking, Skripal poisoning with new sanctions |url=https://www.unian.info/world/10384068-u-s-targets-gru-officers-linked-to-hacking-skripal-poisoning-with-new-sanctions.html |accessdate=20 December 2018 |work=Unian |date=19 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Treasury Targets Russian Operatives over Election Interference, World Anti-Doping Agency Hacking, and Other Malign Activities|url=https://home.treasury.gov/news/press-releases/sm577|work=U. S. Department of the Treasury|date=19 December 2018|accessdate=20 December 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Notice of Intended Removals; Ukraine-/Russia-related Designations; Cyber-related Designations |url=https://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/OFAC-Enforcement/Pages/20181219_33.aspx|work=U. S. Department of the Treasury|date=19 December 2018|accessdate=20 December 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 January 2019, [[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] reported that the British authorities had established all the essential details of the assassination attempt, including the chain of command that leads up to [[Vladimir Putin]].<ref name=\"telegraph_06012019\">{{cite web|first=Robert |last=Mendick|title=How the UK joined the dots from Salisbury Novichok attack to Vladimir Putin|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/01/06/uk-joined-dots-salisbury-novichok-attack-vladimir-putin/|date=6 January 2019|work=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n==Response of the United Kingdom==\nWithin days of the attack, political pressure began to mount on [[Second May ministry|Theresa May's government]] to take action against the perpetrators, and most politicians appeared to believe that the Russian government was behind the attack.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43367515 Russian spy: May under pressure to take firm action] BBC, 12 March 2018.</ref><ref name=\"ftunanswered\">Neil Buckley, David Bond, Henry Foy. [https://www.ft.com/content/c713dd5e-238b-11e8-ae48-60d3531b7d11 The unanswered questions over the attack on a Russian double agent] ''Financial Times'', 9 March 2018 (print edition of 10 March 2018)</ref> The situation was additionally sensitive for Russia as Russian president Vladimir Putin was facing his [[2018 Russian presidential election|fourth presidential election]] in mid-March, and Russia was to host the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] football competition in June.<ref name=\"ftunanswered\" /><ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/theresa-may-vladimir-putin-russia-spy-attack-novichok-nerve-agent-sergei-skripal-yulia-salisbury-a8252741.html Russia spy attack: Theresa May has tried to back Vladimir Putin into a corner \u2013 the Kremlin will kick back] The Independent, 12 March 2018.</ref> When giving a response to an urgent question from [[Tom Tugendhat]], the chairman of the [[Foreign Affairs Select Committee]] of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]], who suggested that Moscow was conducting \"a form of soft war against the West\", Foreign Secretary [[Boris Johnson]] on 6 March said the government would \"respond appropriately and robustly\" if the Russian state was found to have been involved in the poisoning.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/mar/06/boris-johnson-uk-will-respond-robustly-if-russia-poisoned-spy Boris Johnson: UK will respond robustly if Russia poisoned spy] The Guardian, 6 March 2018.</ref><ref>[https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2018-03-06/debates/E416F6C5-50D9-47FF-8C3E-0946CE99E6CA/GovernmentPolicyOnRussia Government Policy on Russia] House of Commons Hansard, 6 March 2018.</ref> UK Home Secretary [[Amber Rudd]] said on 8 March 2018 that the use of a nerve agent on UK soil was a \"brazen and reckless act\" of attempted murder \"in the most cruel and public way\".<ref name=\"bbc43326734\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43326734 |title=Russian spy: Salisbury attack was 'brazen and reckless' |work=BBC News|date=8 March 2018 |accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nPrime Minister [[Theresa May]] said in the House of Commons on 12 March:\n{{quote|It is now clear that Mr Skripal and his daughter were poisoned with a military-grade nerve agent of a type developed by Russia. This is part of a group of nerve agents known as 'Novichok'. Based on the positive identification of this chemical agent by world-leading experts at the Defence Science and Technology Laboratory at Porton Down; our knowledge that Russia has previously produced this agent and would still be capable of doing so; Russia's record of conducting state-sponsored assassinations; and our assessment that Russia views some defectors as legitimate targets for assassinations; the Government has concluded that it is highly likely that Russia was responsible for the act against Sergei and Yulia Skripal. Mr Speaker, there are therefore only two plausible explanations for what happened in Salisbury on 4 March. Either this was a direct act by the Russian State against our country. Or the Russian government lost control of this potentially catastrophically damaging nerve agent and allowed it to get into the hands of others.<ref name=\"mayspeech12march\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/pm-commons-statement-on-salisbury-incident-12-march-2018|title=PM Commons statement on Salisbury incident: 12 March 2018|publisher=Government of the United Kingdom|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref>}}\n\nMay also said that the UK government requested that Russia explain which of these two possibilities it was by the end of 13 March 2018.<ref name=\"mayspeech12march\" /> She also said: \"[T]he extra-judicial killing of terrorists and dissidents outside Russia were given legal sanction by the Russian Parliament in 2006. And of course Russia used radiological substances in its barbaric [[Poisoning of Alexander Litvinenko|assault on Mr Litvinenko]].\"&nbsp; She said that the UK government would \"consider in detail the response from the Russian State\" and in the event that there was no credible response, the government would \"conclude that this action amounts to an unlawful use of force by the Russian State against the United Kingdom\" and measures would follow.<ref name=\"mayspeech12march\"/> British media billed the statement as \"Theresa May's ultimatum to Putin.\"<ref name=\"Guardian May\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2018/03/12/russia-could-target-england-fans-world-cup-uk-retaliates-salisbury/|title=Theresa May's ultimatum to Vladimir Putin: Russian leader given 24 hours to answer for nerve agent attack on spy|last=Rayner|first=Gordon|date=12 March 2018|work=The Telegraph|access-date=15 March 2018|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March 2018, UK Home Secretary [[Amber Rudd]] ordered an inquiry by the police and security services into alleged Russian state involvement in 14 previous suspicious deaths of Russian exiles and businessmen in the UK.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/13/amber-rudd-orders-inquiry-into-russia-linked-deaths-in-uk Amber Rudd orders inquiry into Russia-linked deaths in UK: Home secretary responds to calls to examine alleged Russian involvement in up to 14 deaths] ''The Guardian'', 13 March 2018.</ref>\n\nPrime Minister May unveiled a series of measures on 14 March 2018 in retaliation for the poisoning attack, after the Russian government refused to meet the UK's request for an account of the incident. One of the chief measures was the expulsion of 23 Russian diplomats which she presented as \"actions to dismantle the Russian espionage network in the UK\", as these diplomats had been identified by the UK as \"undeclared intelligence agents\".<ref name=\"maydismantle\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/theresa-may-russian-spy-network-expel-diplomats-cold-war-a8256411.html Russian spy incident: Theresa May moves to dismantle Russian spy 'network' expelling 23 diplomats: Defence Secretary Gavin Williamson will announce new investment in chemical weapons facilities in the wake of the Salisbury attack] The Independent, 15 March 2018.</ref><ref name=\"russthreatretal\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/14/may-expels-23-russian-diplomats-response-spy-poisoning|title=Russia threatens retaliation after Britain expels 23 diplomats|last1=Stewart|first1=Heather|last2=Walker|first2=Peter|last3=Borger|first3=Julian|date=14 March 2018|work=The Guardian}}</ref> The BBC reported other responses, including:<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43402506|title=UK to expel 23 Russian diplomats|date=14 March 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-43380378|title=How is the UK retaliating against Russia?|date=14 March 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref>\n* Increasing checks on private flights, customs and freight\n* Freezing Russian state assets where there is evidence that they may be used to threaten the life or property of UK nationals or residents\n* Plans to consider new laws to increase defences against \"hostile state activity\"\n* Ministers and the [[British royal family]] boycotting the 2018 FIFA World Cup in Russia\n* Suspending all high-level bilateral contacts between the UK and Russia\n* Retraction of the state invitation to Russian's foreign minister [[Sergey Lavrov]]<ref name=\"BBC20180405\" />\n* A new \u00a348-million chemical weapons defence centre<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-43405686|title=UK to build new chemical defence centre|date=15 March 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=15 March 2018|quote=UK Defence Secretary Gavin Williamson ... said the UK leads the world in research into chemical, biological and radiological warfare but said this expertise needed to be developed further to confront potential hostile activity by states and individuals.}}</ref>\n* Offering voluntary vaccinations against [[anthrax]] to British troops who are held at high readiness so that they are ready to deploy to areas where there is risk of this type of attack<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-43405686|title=Defence secretary tells Russia: Shut up|date=15 March 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref>\nThe Prime Minister said that some measures which the government planned could \"not be shared publicly for reasons of national security\".<ref name=\"maydismantle\"/> [[Jeremy Corbyn]] cast doubt in his parliamentary response to May's statement concerning blaming the attack on Russia prior to the results of an independent investigation, which provoked criticism from some MPs, including members of his own party.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/jeremy-corbyn-russia-spy-poisoning-response-mps-furious-sailsbury-sergei-skripal-a8255731.html Russian spy poisoning: Furious MPs condemn Jeremy Corbyn's response to statement on Sailsbury attack: Labour leader accused of 'policy of appeasement' after refusing to directly blame Russia for poisoning former spy] The Independent, 14 March 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-43405680 Russian spy: Jeremy Corbyn aide queries proof of Russian guilt] BBC, 14 March 2018.</ref> A few days later, Corbyn was satisfied that the evidence pointed to Russia.<ref>BBC, '[https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/jeremy-corbyn-sergei-skripal-theresa-may-novichok-russia-spy-poisoning-moscow-a8288826.html Jeremy Corbyn was right to be cautious about blaming Moscow for the Skripal poisoning']' (15 March 2018)</ref> He supported the expulsion but argued that a crackdown on [[money laundering]] by UK financial firms on behalf of [[Russian oligarch]]s would be a more effective measure against \"the Putin regime\" than the Tory government's plans.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/mar/15/corbyn-defies-critics-calls-for-calm-over-russia-nerve-agent-attack|title=Jeremy Corbyn defies critics and calls for calm over Russia|date=15 March 2018|work=The Guardian}}</ref> Corbyn pointed to the pre-[[Iraq War]] judgements about [[Iraq and weapons of mass destruction]] as reason to be suspicious.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/jeremy-corbyn-russia-spy-nerve-agent-iraq-war-wmd-labour-theresa-may-a8256021.html \"Jeremy Corbyn points to Iraq WMDs mistake as he casts doubt on Russian culpability for nerve agent attack\"], ''The Independent'', 15 March 2018.</ref>\n\nThe [[United Nations Security Council]] called an urgent meeting on 14 March 2018 on the initiative of the UK to discuss the Salisbury incident.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-russia-un/uk-calls-for-urgent-u-n-security-council-meeting-over-nerve-attack-idUSKCN1GQ1I5 UK calls for urgent U.N. Security Council meeting over nerve attack] Reuters, 14 March 2018.</ref><ref name=\"unsc-20180314\">{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/press/en/2018/sc13247.doc.htm |title=Moscow 'Highly Likely' Behind Salisbury Chemical Attack, Prime Minister of United Kingdom Says in Letter to Security Council \u2013 Russian Federation Calls Statement Irresponsible, Threatening |id=SC/13247 |publisher=United Nations |date=14 March 2018 |accessdate=9 April 2018}}</ref> According to the Russian mission's press secretary, the draft press statement introduced by Russia at the United Nations Security Council meeting was blocked by the UK.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tass.com/politics/994184 |title=UK blocks Russia-initiated UNSC statement on Skripal incident|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 15 March 2018 |website=TASS.com |access-date= 6 September 2018}}</ref> The UK and the US blamed Russia for the incident during the meeting, with the UK accusing Russia of breaking its obligations under the [[Chemical Weapons Convention]].<ref>[https://www.ft.com/content/135d21d0-27c3-11e8-b27e-cc62a39d57a0 US blames Russia for Skripal attack, in \u2018absolute solidarity\u2019 with UK], ''Financial Times'', 14 March 2018.</ref> Separately, the White House fully supported the UK in attributing the attack to Russia, as well as the punitive measures taken against Russia. The White House also accused Russia of undermining the security of countries worldwide.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43411332 Russian spy: White House backs UK decision to expel diplomats] BBC, 15 March 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/statement-press-secretary-united-kingdoms-decision-expel-russian-diplomats/ Statement by the Press Secretary on the United Kingdom's Decision to Expel Russian Diplomats] The White House, 14 March 2018.</ref>\n\nThe UK, and subsequently [[NATO]], requested Russia provide \"full and complete disclosure\" of the Novichok programme to the [[Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/organisation-for-the-prohibition-of-chemical-weapons-87th-executive-council-session-statement-on-the-salisbury-incident|title=Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons 87th Executive Council session: statement on the Salisbury incident|publisher=Government of the United Kingdom|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/news_152787.htm|title=Statement by the North Atlantic Council on the use of a nerve agent in Salisbury|last=NATO|website=NATO|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-russia-nato/nato-calls-on-russia-to-give-full-details-on-nerve-agent-program-idUSKCN1GQ1O1|title=NATO calls on Russia to give full details on nerve agent program|date=14 March 2018|agency=Reuters|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref> On 14 March 2018, the government stated it would supply a sample of the substance used to the [[Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons]] once UK legal obligations from the criminal investigation permitted.<ref name=\"opcw-20180314\">{{cite web |url=https://www.opcw.org/fileadmin/OPCW/EC/87/en/UK_Statement_EC-87.pdf |title=Update on the use of Nerve Agent in Salisbury, United Kingdom |last=Wilson |first=Peter |publisher=Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons |date=14 March 2018 |accessdate=16 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nBritish foreign secretary Boris Johnson said on 16 March that it was \"overwhelmingly likely\" that the poisoning had been ordered directly by Russian president Putin, which marked the first time the British government accused Vladimir Putin of personally ordering the poisoning.<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/world-news/europe/putin-personally-ordered-attack-on-spy-says-uk-36714143.html Putin personally ordered attack on spy, says UK] The Independent, 17 March 2018.</ref> According to the [[UK Foreign Office]], the UK attributed the attack to Russia based on [[Porton Down]]'s determination that the chemical was Novichok, additional intelligence, and a lack of alternative explanations from Russia.<ref>{{cite web |last=Waugh |first=Paul |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/boris-johnson-under-fire-over-salisbury-russia-claim-as-foreign-office-tweet-blaming-moscow-deleted-russian-embassy_uk_5ac4b1efe4b063ce2e5799c7 |title=Johnson Under Fire As Foreign Office Deletes Russia Tweet |date=4 April 2018 |work=HuffPost |accessdate=4 April 2018 |quote=The Foreign Secretary was making clear that Porton Down were sure it was a Novichok \u2013 a point they have reinforced. He goes on in the same interview to make clear why based on that information, additional intelligence and the lack of alternative explanation from the Russians, we have reached the conclusion we have.}}</ref> The [[Defence Science and Technology Laboratory]] announced that it was \"completely confident\" that the agent used was Novichok, but they still did not know the \"precise source\" of the agent.<ref name=\"Laschet\">\"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-russia-salisbury-nerve-agent-porton-down-diane-abbot-moscow-sergei-skripal-a8287696.html Labour says it deserves 'credit' for questioning if Russia was to blame for Salisbury nerve agent]\". ''The Independent''. 4 April 2018.</ref><ref name=wp-20180404/>\n\nThe UK had held an intelligence briefing with its allies in which it stated that the Novichok chemical used in the Salisbury poisoning was produced at a chemical facility in the town of [[Shikhany]], [[Saratov Oblast]], Russia.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-russia-skripal-nerveagent/agent-used-in-salisbury-made-at-russias-shikhany-military-research-base-times-idUSKCN1HC2WE|title=Agent used in Salisbury made at Russia's Shikhany military research base: Times|date=6 April 2018 |work=Reuters}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a government source, in April 2018 the UK refused to grant a visa to Yulia's cousin, Viktoria Skripal, to visit her, saying that it appears Russia is \"trying to use Viktoria as a pawn\".<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\n== Response of Russia ==\n\n=== Russian government ===\nOn 6 March 2018 [[Andrey Lugovoy]], [[Member of Parliament|deputy]] of Russia's [[State Duma]] (the [[Liberal Democratic Party of Russia]]) and alleged killer of [[Alexander Litvinenko]], in his interview with the [[Echo of Moscow]] said: \"Something constantly happens to Russian citizens who either run away from Russian justice, or for some reason choose for themselves a way of life they call a change of their Motherland. So the more Britain accepts on its territory every good-for-nothing, every scum from all over the world, the more problems they will have.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Knight|first1=Amy|title=Vladimir Putin's Re-Election Strategy: Nukes and Assassins|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/vladimir-putins-re-election-strategy-nukes-and-assassins?ref=scroll|accessdate=8 March 2018|work=Daily Beast}}</ref><ref>[https://echo.msk.ru/programs/beseda/2160198-echo/ \u041e\u0431 \u043e\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u044f \u0421\u043a\u0440\u0438\u043f\u0430\u043b\u044f] [[Echo of Moscow]], 6 March 2018.</ref>\n\nRussian Foreign Minister [[Sergey Lavrov]] on 9 March rejected Britain's claim of Russia's involvement in Skripal's poisoning and accused the United Kingdom of spreading \"propaganda\".<ref>\"[https://www.cnbc.com/2018/03/09/russia-lavrov-says-uk-is-spreading-propaganda-over-spy-poisoning.html Russia says London spreading propaganda over spy poisoning]\". CNBC. 11 March 2018.</ref><ref>\"[https://themoscowtimes.com/news/russia-says-london-spreading-propaganda-over-spy-poisoning-60758 Russia Says London Spreading Propaganda Over Spy Poisoning]\". ''[[The Moscow Times]]''. 9 March 2018.</ref> Lavrov said that Russia was \"ready to cooperate\" and demanded access to the samples of the nerve-agent which was used to poison Skripal. The request was rejected by the British government.<ref>\"[https://www.ndtv.com/world-news/russia-rejects-britains-ultimatum-wants-access-to-nerve-agent-1823359?ndtv_nextstory Russia Says \"Not Guilty\" Of Ex-Spy Poisoning As UK Deadline Looms]\". [[NDTV]]. 13 March 2018.</ref>\n\nFollowing Theresa May's 12 March statement in Parliament \u2013 in which she gave President Putin's administration until midnight of the following day to explain how a former spy was poisoned in Salisbury, otherwise she would conclude it was an \"unlawful use of force\" by the Russian state against the UK<ref>\"[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/12/russia-highly-likely-to-be-behind-poisoning-of-spy-says-theresa-may Russian spy poisoning: Theresa May issues ultimatum to Moscow]\". ''The Guardian''. 13 March 2018.</ref> \u2013 Russian foreign minister Sergey Lavrov, talking to the Russian press on 13 March, referred to the statement as \"an ultimatum from London\" and endorsed remarks made by the ministry's spokesperson the day prior, who called May's statement \"a circus show in the British parliament\";<ref name=\"lavrovotvet\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newsru.com/russia/13mar2018/lavrov.html|title=\u041b\u0430\u0432\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0438\u043b \u043d\u0430&nbsp; \u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0443\u043c \u041c\u044d\u0439&nbsp; \u0441\u0441\u044b\u043b\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043d\u0430&nbsp; &nbsp;\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0432\u0435\u043d\u0446\u0438\u044e \u043e&nbsp; \u0445\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0438\u0438|work=NEWSru.com|access-date=15 March 2018|language=Russian}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newsru.com/russia/12mar2018/midmay.html|script-title=ru:\u0412 \u041c\u0418\u0414 \u0420\u0424 \u0437\u0430\u044f\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u041c\u044d\u0439 \u043e \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u043a \u043e\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044e \u0421\u043a\u0440\u0438\u043f\u0430\u043b\u044f \u0441\u043e\u0447\u043b\u0438 \"\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0437\u043a\u0430\u043c\u0438\" \u0438 \"\u0446\u0438\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432\u044b\u043c \u0448\u043e\u0443\"|work=NEWSru.com |access-date=15 March 2018|language=Russian}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/russia-theresa-mays-comments-on-salisbury-spy-a-circus-show-11287517|title=Russia: Theresa May's comments on Salisbury spy a 'circus show'|publisher=Sky News|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref> he added that the procedure stipulated by the [[Chemical Weapons Convention]] should be followed whereunder Russia was entitled to have access to the substance in question and 10 days to respond.<ref name=\"lavrovotvet\" /><ref>\"[https://www.channelstv.com/2018/03/13/russia-rejects-britains-ultimatum-wants-access-to-nerve-agent/ Russia Rejects Britain\u2019s Ultimatum, Wants Access To Nerve Agent]\". Channels TV. 13 March 2018.</ref><ref name=\"guarddemands\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/13/russia-demands-nerve-agent-samples-uk-deadline-spy-poisoning|title=Russia demands nerve agent samples in standoff with UK over poisoned spy|last=Roth|first=Andrew|date=13 March 2018|website=The Guardian|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref> He called allegations about Russia's complicity \"balderdash\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/russian/news-43385817|script-title=ru:\u041b\u0430\u0432\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u043e \u0434\u0435\u043b\u0435 \u0421\u043a\u0440\u0438\u043f\u0430\u043b\u044f: \u0411\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043d\u0435 \u0441\u043e\u0431\u043b\u044e\u0434\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u043c\u0435\u0436\u0434\u0443\u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043d\u043e\u0440\u043c\u044b|date=13 March 2018|publisher=BBC \u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430|access-date=15 March 2018|language=Russian}}</ref> The Russian foreign ministry spokesperson, speaking on a Russian state television channel on the evening of 13 March, said that no one had the right to present Russia with 24-hour ultimatums.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tass.ru/politika/5027376|script-title=ru:\u0417\u0430\u0445\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430: \u043d\u0438\u043a\u0442\u043e \u043d\u0435 \u043c\u043e\u0436\u0435\u0442 \u0432\u044b\u0434\u0432\u0438\u0433\u0430\u0442\u044c \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 24-\u0447\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0435 \u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0443\u043c\u044b|agency=\u0422\u0410\u0421\u0421|access-date=15 March 2018|language=ru}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tass.com/politics/993859|title=No one can deliver any 24-hour ultimatums to Russia \u2013 Foreign Ministry spokeswoman|agency=TASS|access-date=15 March 2018|language=ru}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=60 \u043c\u0438\u043d\u0443\u0442. \u042d\u0444\u0438\u0440 \u043e\u0442 13.03.2018 (19:00). \u041e\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0421\u043a\u0440\u0438\u043f\u0430\u043b\u044f: \u0434\u043e\u0439\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u043b\u0438 \u0434\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0440\u044b\u0432\u0430 \u0434\u0438\u043f\u043e\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0441 \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435\u0439|url=https://russia.tv/video/show/brand_id/60851/episode_id/1719029/|language=ru|accessdate=15 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, Russia announced that it was expelling 23 British diplomats and ordered the closure of the UK's [[Consulate-General of the United Kingdom, Saint Petersburg|consulate in St Petersburg]] and the [[British Council]] office in Moscow, stopping all British Council activities in Russia.<ref name=\"indeprusexp\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/russia-spy-poison-british-diplomats-expelled-sergei-skripal-nerve-agent-a8260671.html \"Russia expels 23 British diplomats in retaliation as diplomatic spat over Sergei Skripal poisoning intensifies\"], ''The Independent'', 17 March 2018.</ref>\n\nThe poisoning has been officially declared to be a fabrication and a \"grotesque provocation rudely staged by the British and U.S. intelligence agencies\" to undermine Russia.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/russia-points-finger-at-uk-and-us-agencies-over-poisoning/2018/04/04/94f984ea-37e0-11e8-af3c-2123715f78df_story.html UK rejects joint probe with Russia into spy poisoning] The Washington Post, 4 April 2018.</ref><ref>[https://iz.ru/728161/2018-04-04/naryshkin-nazval-delo-skripalia-grotesknoi-provokatciei-britanii-i-ssha \u041d\u0430\u0440\u044b\u0448\u043a\u0438\u043d \u043d\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0430\u043b \u00ab\u0434\u0435\u043b\u043e \u0421\u043a\u0440\u0438\u043f\u0430\u043b\u044f\u00bb \u0433\u0440\u043e\u0442\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0435\u0439 \u0411\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u0438 \u0421\u0428\u0410] [[Izvestia]], 4 April 2018.</ref><ref name=\"RT News\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/uk/422911-uk-staged-skripal-poisoning-theory|title=UK may have staged Skripal poisoning to rally people against Russia, Moscow believes}}</ref><ref name=\"DailyStar\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dailystar.co.uk/news/latest-news/693066/russia-spy-poisoning-britain-vladimir-putin-sergei-skripal-war-mi6-salisbury-uk-evidence|title=Russia claims Britain 'STAGED poisoning of Skripal to turn people against Putin'|date=1 April 2018|work=Daily Star}}</ref><ref name=\"RT News-UK Fabricated\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/news/422871-russia-questions-uk-skripal-case|title=Moscow confronts London with 14 questions on 'fabricated' Skripal case|publisher=RT}}</ref>\n\nThe Russian government and [[Embassy of Russia, London|embassy of Russia in the United Kingdom]] have repeatedly requested access to the Skripals, and have sought to offer consular assistance. These requests and offers have been denied or declined.<ref name=\"tass0409\">{{cite news|url=https://tass.com/politics/1019919|title=Russian embassy comments on Scripal case|agency=TASS|date=4 September 2018|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/jun/07/putin-demands-russian-consular-access-to-yulia-skripal|title=Putin demands Russian consular access to Yulia Skripal|newspaper=The Guardian|date=7 June 2018|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/03/31/russia-demands-know-has-denied-access-skripals/|title=Russia demands to know why it has been denied access to the Skripals|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=31 March 2018|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/31/foreign-office-considers-russian-consular-access-to-yulia-skripal|title=Foreign Office considers Russian consular access to Yulia Skripal|newspaper=The Guardian|date=31 March 2018|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/yulia-skripal-russian-embassy-uk-consular-access-salisbury-poisoning-spy-a8255071.html|title=Yulia Skripal: Russian embassy 'to ask UK for consular access to daughter of poisoned spy'|newspaper=The Independent|date=14 March 2018|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn September, Russia described the Skripals' situation as \"de-facto deprivation of liberty\", claiming that several diplomatic and human rights conventions were violated.<ref name=tass0409 /> On 5 September the Russian government rejected the accusations \"against Russia and two allegedly Russian citizens.\"<ref name=\"mid-20180905\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mid.ru/en/foreign_policy/news/-/asset_publisher/cKNonkJE02Bw/content/id/3337611 |title=Russian Foreign Ministry Statement |publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation |date=5 September 2018 |accessdate=9 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 September 2018 the Press Secretary for the President of Russia, [[Dmitry Peskov]], stated that May's accusations from that day were \"unacceptable\". Peskov asserted Russia had not received any official request from Britain for assistance in identifying the two suspected Russian GRU military intelligence officers that Scotland Yard believes carried out the Skripal attack. The same day, the [[Foreign Ministry of Russia]] asserted that [[List of ambassadors of the United Kingdom to Russia|UK ambassador in Moscow]], [[Laurie Bristow]], had said that London would not provide Russia with the suspects' fingerprints, passport numbers, visa numbers, or any extra data.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://tass.com/politics/1020130|title=London declines to provide fingerprints of suspects in Skripal case \u2013 Foreign Ministry|agency=TASS|date=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 September 2018, President Putin, while answering questions at the plenary meeting of the 4th [[Eastern Economic Forum]] in [[Russian Far East|Russia's Far Eastern]] [[port city]] of [[Vladivostok]] said that the identities of both men London suspected of involvement in the Skripal case were known to the Russian authorities and that both were civilians, who had done nothing criminal. He also said he would like the men to come forward to tell their story.<ref>[http://tass.com/world/1021524 Skripal suspects expressed their opinion, but this does not put lid on case]. TASS, 13 September 2018</ref><ref>[https://www.memri.org/reports/russia-week-%E2%80%93-focus-skripal-case-%E2%80%93-september-16-2018 Russia This Week \u2013 Focus On The Skripal Case]. MEMRI Russian Media Studies Project, Special Dispatch No.7673, 16 September 2018</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Skripal poisoning: Putin says suspects 'civilians, not criminals' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-45494627 |accessdate=12 September 2018 |publisher=BBC News |date=12 September 2018}}</ref> In a 13 September 2018 interview on the state-funded television channel RT, the accused claimed to be sports nutritionists who had gone to Salisbury merely to see the sights and scout for nutrition products, saying that they took a second day-trip to Salisbury because slush had dampened their first one.<ref name=\"Higgins\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/13/world/europe/russia-salisbury-skripal-novichok.html|title=We Were Tourists, Not Assassins, Novichok Attack Suspects Say|last=Higgins|first=Andrew|date=13 September 2018|work=New York Times|access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 September, [[Sergey Lavrov|Lavrov]] stated: \"Our proposal of putting into operation existing mechanisms between London and Moscow on the legal assistance in criminal cases is still in force. Since there is no response to our proposal, we have all grounds to believe that there had been no crime, which these ladies and gentlemen are trying to attribute to our citizens.\"<ref>[http://tass.com/politics/1021708 Lavrov blasts London\u2019s reaction to interview with Skripal case suspects as illogical]. TASS, 14 September 2018</ref> On 26 September, the same day one of the suspects was identified as the Colonel of GRU, Lavrov once again urged the British authorities to cooperate in the investigation of the case, said Britain had given no proof of Russia's guilt and suggested that Britain had something to hide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/video/world/lavrov-does-britain-have-something-to-hide-about-novichok-attack/2018/09/26/3d50f320-c1ad-11e8-9451-e878f96be19b_video.html|title=Lavrov: Does Britain 'have something to hide' about Novichok attack?|website=Washington Post|accessdate=27 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Barry |first1=Ellen |title=Russian Officer Is Named as Suspect in Salisbury Poisoning |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/26/world/europe/uk-skripal-suspect.html |accessdate=27 September 2018 |work=The New York Times |date=26 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 September, the Russian [[Federal Security Service|FSB]] began searching for [[Ministry of Internal Affairs (Russia)|Ministry of Internal Affairs (MVD)]] officers who had provided journalists with foreign passport and flight information about the suspects.<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u0421\u043b\u0438\u0432 \u0434\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445: \u0424\u0421\u0411 \u043e\u0442\u043e\u043c\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442 \u0437\u0430 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0438 \u0411\u043e\u0448\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430|url=https://www.gazeta.ru/social/2018/09/25/11996089.shtml|work=\u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430.Ru|accessdate=27 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Russian state media===\nFor a few days following the poisoning, the story was discussed by web sites, radio stations and newspapers, but Russian state-run main national TV channels largely ignored the incident.<ref name=\"radiolibwarn\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/russia-skripal-poisoning-russia-tv-warning-traitors-kleimenov/29087407.html|title=Russian State TV Host Warns 'Traitors' After Skripal Poisoning|publisher=[[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]]|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-43330498|title=Russian state TV anchor warns 'traitors'|date=8 March 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nEventually, on 7 March, anchor [[Kirill Kleimyonov]] of the state television station [[Channel One Russia]]'s current affairs programme ''[[Vremya]]'' mentioned the incident by attributing the allegation to foreign secretary [[Boris Johnson]].<ref name=\"1tvkleim\" /> After speaking of Boris Johnson disparagingly, Kleimyonov said that being \"a traitor to the motherland\" was one of the most hazardous professions and warned: \"Don't choose England as a next country to live in. Whatever the reasons, whether you're a professional traitor to the motherland or you just hate your country in your spare time, I repeat, no matter, don't move to England. Something is not right there. Maybe it's the climate, but in recent years there have been too many strange incidents with a grave outcome. People get hanged, poisoned, they die in helicopter crashes and fall out of windows in industrial quantities.\"<ref name=\"1tvkleim\">{{Citation|script-title=ru:\u0413\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0430 \u041c\u0418\u0414 \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441 \u0414\u0436\u043e\u043d\u0441\u043e\u043d \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0438\u043b, \u0447\u0442\u043e \u0437\u0430 \u043e\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435\u043c \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u044f \u0421\u043a\u0440\u0438\u043f\u0430\u043b\u044f \u0441\u0442\u043e\u0438\u0442 \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430.|url=https://www.1tv.ru/news/2018-03-07/342100-glava_mid_velikobritanii_boris_dzhonson_predpolozhil_chto_za_otravleniem_sergeya_skripalya_stoit_moskva|website=[[Channel One Russia]]|language=ru-RU|date=7 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/mar/09/russian-state-tv-warns-traitors-not-to-settle-in-england|title=Russian state TV warns 'traitors' not to settle in England|last=Bennetts|first=Marc|date=9 March 2018|website=The Guardian|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/video/News/sergei-skripal-russian-state-tv-anchor-kirill-kleimenov-rare-traitors-live-old-age-a8246666.html|title=Russian state TV anchor says it is 'rare that traitors live to old age'|date=8 March 2018|work=The Independent|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"radiolibwarn\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/mar/06/boris-johnson-uk-will-respond-robustly-if-russia-poisoned-spy|title=Boris Johnson: UK will respond robustly if Russia poisoned spy|last=Elgot|first=Jessica|date=6 March 2018|website=The Guardian|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref> Kleimyonov's commentary was accompanied by a report highlighting previous suspicious Russia-related deaths in the UK, namely those of financier [[Alexander Perepilichny]], businessman [[Boris Berezovsky (businessman)|Boris Berezovsky]], ex-FSB officer [[Alexander Litvinenko]] and radiation expert Matthew Puncher.<ref name=\"1tvkleim\" /> Puncher discovered that [[Poisoning of Alexander Litvinenko|Litvinenko was poisoned]] by [[polonium]]; he died in 2006, five months after a trip to Russia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/list-alleged-russian-assassinations-in-britain-litvinenko-2018-3|title=All the times Russia allegedly carried out assassinations on British soil|work=Business Insider|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe host of the ''[[Vesti (VGTRK)|Vesti Nedeli]]'' on Russian state television ([[Russia-1]] channel of [[All-Russia State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company|VGTRK]]), [[Dmitry Kiselyov]], said on 11 March that the poisoning of Sergei Skripal, who was \"completely wrung out and of little interest\" as a source, was only advantageous to the British to \"nourish [[Anti-Russian sentiment#United Kingdom|their Russophobia]]\" and [[List of 2018 FIFA World Cup controversies#UK government boycott|organise the boycott]] of the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|FIFA World Cup]] scheduled for June 2018. Kiselyov referred to London as a \"pernicious place for Russian exiles\".<ref name=\"vestikisel\">[https://xn--b1agj9af.xn--80aswg/video/-rossija-1/vesti-nedeli-s-dmitriem-kiselevym-ot-11--35-41.html \u0412\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u043d\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0438 \u0441 \u0414\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0435\u043c \u041a\u0438\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0432\u044b\u043c \u043e\u0442 11.03.18] (the relevant footage begins at 1:27:20), ''[[Vesti (VGTRK)|Vesti Nedeli]]'', 11 March 2018.</ref><ref name=\"moscowtimes\">[https://themoscowtimes.com/news/britain-poisoned-double-agent-skripal-to-nourish-russophobia-russian-state-media-60769 Britain Poisoned Double Agent Skripal to 'Nourish Russophobia' \u2014 Russian State Media] [[The Moscow Times]], 12 March 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-russia-plot/russian-state-tv-accuses-britain-of-poisoning-spy-in-special-operation-idUSKCN1GO15H Russian state TV accuses Britain of poisoning spy in special operation] Reuters, 12 March 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.buzzfeed.com/patricksmith/the-russian-embassy-in-london-has-accused-the-uk-of-an-anti Russia Wants Samples Of The Nerve Agent Believed To Have Poisoned A Former Russian Spy And His Daughter] Buzzfeed.com, 12 March 2018.</ref>\n\nThe prominent Russian television hosts' warnings to Russians living in the UK were echoed by a similar direct warning from a senior member of the [[Federation Council (Russia)|Russian Federation Council]], [[:ru:\u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0432, \u0410\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0435\u0439 \u0410\u0440\u043a\u0430\u0434\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447|Andrey Klimov]], who said: \"It's going to be very unsafe for you.\"<ref name=\"guarddemands\" />\n\nClaims made by Russian media were fact-checked by UK media organisations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-43835774|title=Reality Check: Russian TV's claims about Salisbury attack|last=Kuzmenkova|first=Olga|date=22 April 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=23 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.channel4.com/news/factcheck/long-read-does-the-uks-case-against-russia-stack-up|title=Long read: Does the UK's case against Russia stack up?|work=Channel 4 News|access-date=23 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nAn interview with two men claiming to be the suspects named by the UK was aired on [[RT (TV network)|RT]] on 13 September 2018 with RT editor [[Margarita Simonyan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AczGFsnNKRA|title=Suspects: We went to Salisbury as tourists to see the cathedral|quote=UK's suspects in the Skripal case talk exclusively with RT's editor-in-chief.|last=RT UK|date=13 September 2018|accessdate=15 October 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref> They said they were ordinary tourists who had wished to see [[Stonehenge]], [[Old Sarum]], and the \"famous ... 123-metre spire\" of [[Salisbury Cathedral]]. They also said that they \"maybe approached Skripal's house, but we didn't know where it was located,\" and denied using Novichok, which they had allegedly transported in a fake perfume bottle, saying, \"Is it silly for decent lads to have women's perfume? The customs are checking everything, they would have questions as to why men have women's perfume in their luggage.\"<ref name=\"Roth Dodd\">{{cite news |last1=Roth |first1=Andrew |last2=Dodd |first2=Vikram |title=Salisbury novichok suspects say they were only visiting cathedral |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/sep/13/russian-television-channel-rt-says-it-is-to-air-interview-with-skripal-salisbury-attack-suspects |accessdate=13 September 2018 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=13 September 2018}}</ref> Although Simonyan avoided most questions about the two men's backgrounds, she hinted that they might be gay by asking, \"All footage features you two together ... What do you have in common that you spend so much time together?\"<ref name=\"Roth Dodd\" /> ''[[The New York Times]]'' interpreted the hint by noting that \"The possibility that Mr. Petrov and Mr. Boshirov could be gay would, for a Russian audience, immediately rule out the possibility that they serve as military intelligence officers.\"<ref name=\"Higgins\" />\n\n==Chemical weapons experts and intelligence==\n\n===Porton Down===\nOn 3 April 2018 Gary Aitkenhead, the chief executive of the Government's [[Defence Science and Technology Laboratory]] (Dstl) at [[Porton Down]] responsible for testing the substance involved in the case, said they had established the agent was Novichok or from that family but had been unable to verify the \"precise source\" of the nerve agent and that they had \"provided the scientific info to Government who have then used a number of other sources to piece together the conclusions you have come to.\"<ref name=\"sky-20180403\">{{Cite AV media |url=https://twitter.com/SkyNews/status/981190172925616128/video/1 |title=Salisbury: 'Precise source' of nerve agent not known |people=Aitkenhead, Gary |publisher=Twitter |work=Sky News |type=full video interview [3mins 49sec] |date=3 April 2018 |accessdate=4 April 2018 |quote=[1m:24s] we have been able to establish it is Novichok or from that family ... [3m:26s] it is a military grade nerve agent which requires extremely sophisticated methods in order to create something that is probably only within the capabilities of a state actor}}</ref><ref name=\"sky-20180404\">{{cite news |url=https://news.sky.com/story/porton-down-experts-unable-to-identify-precise-source-of-novichok-that-poisoned-spy-11315387 |title=Porton Down experts unable to identify 'precise source' of novichok that poisoned spy |last=Kelso |first=Paul |publisher=Sky News |date=4 April 2018 |accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref> Aitkenhead refused to comment on whether the laboratory had developed or maintains stocks of Novichok.<ref name=sky-20180404/> He also dismissed speculations the substance could have come from Porton Down: \"There is no way anything like that could have come from us or left the four walls of our facility.\"<ref name=sky-20180404/> Aitkenhead stated the creation of the nerve agent was \"probably only within the capabilities of a state actor\" and there was no known antidote.<ref name=sky-20180403/><ref name=\"wp-20180404\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2018/04/04/britains-boris-johnson-accused-of-misleading-public-over-skripal-poisoning-evidence/ |title=Britain's Boris Johnson accused of misleading public over Skripal poisoning evidence |last=Taylor |first=Adam |newspaper=Washington Post |date=4 April 2018 |accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Former Russian scientists and intelligence officers===\n[[Vil Mirzayanov]], a former Soviet Union scientist who worked at the research institute that developed the Novichok class of nerve agents and lives in the United States, believes that hundreds of people could have been affected by residual contamination in Salisbury. He said that Sergei and Yulia Skripal, if poisoned with a Novichok, would be left with debilitating health issues for the rest of their lives. He also criticised the response of [[Public Health England]], saying that washing personal belongings was insufficient to remove traces of the chemical.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/russian-spy-attack-cure-nerve-agent-salisbury-poisoning-sergei-skripal-infection-risk-year-a8253771.html|title=Russian spy attack: Hundreds in Salisbury could be poisoned in years to come with 'no cure', says nerve agent developer|date=13 March 2018|accessdate=15 March 2018|work=Independent|author1=Deardon, Lizzie |author2=Sharman, Jon }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/russian/features-43429973|title=\u0412\u0438\u043b \u041c\u0438\u0440\u0437\u0430\u044f\u043d\u043e\u0432: \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0440\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u043a\u0430 \"\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0430\" \u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0433\u0434\u0430 \u043d\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0449\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0441\u044c|first=\u041d\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043b\u043a\u0430|last=\u041f\u0438\u0441\u043d\u044f|date=16 March 2018|publisher=BBC|access-date=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nTwo other Russian scientists who now live in Russia and have been involved in Soviet-era chemical weapons development, Vladimir Uglev and Leonid Rink, were quoted as saying that [[Novichok agent]]s had been developed in the 1970s\u20131980s within the programme that was officially titled [[FOLIANT]] and the term Novichok referred to a whole system of chemical weapons use; they, as well as Mirzayanov, who published Novichok's formula in 2008, also noted that Novichok-type agents might be synthesised in other countries.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/russian/features-43476312 \u0427\u0442\u043e \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0435 \"\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447\u043e\u043a\"? \u0412\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u0442\u0440\u0435\u0445 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0440\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u0447\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432] BBC, 20 March 2018.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/novichok-nerve-agent-poison-soviet-russia-salisbury-attack-leonid-rink-vladimir-uglev-the-bell-a8265626.html|title=Soviet-era scientists contradict Moscow's claims Russia never made Novichok nerve agent|date=20 March 2018|work=The Independent}}</ref><ref>[https://www.rferl.org/a/russian-scientist-says-other-countries-may-have-novichok/29105937.html Russian Scientist Says Other Countries May Have Novichok Samples]. Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty. 17 March 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-russia-novichok-creator/soviet-era-scientist-says-he-helped-create-poison-in-uk-spy-attack-row-idUSKBN1GW1E1 Soviet-era scientist says he helped create poison in UK spy attack row] Reuters, 20 March 2018.</ref> In 1995, Leonid Rink received a one-year suspended sentence for selling Novichok agents to unnamed buyers, soon after the fatal [[Novichok agent#Poisoning of Ivan Kivelidi and Zara Ismailova|poisoning of Russian banker Ivan Kivilidi]] by Novichok.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.novayagazeta.ru/articles/2018/03/22/75896-rezhim-novichka|title=\"\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447\u043e\u043a\" \u0443\u0436\u0435 \u0443\u0431\u0438\u0432\u0430\u043b}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.trust.org/item/20180314181331-8936f|title=Secret trial shows risks of nerve agent theft in post-Soviet chaos \u2013 experts|first=Thomson Reuters|last=Foundation|publisher=trust.org}}</ref><ref>[https://www.lefigaro.fr/international/2018/03/21/01003-20180321ARTFIG00328-quand-un-banquier-russe-etait-tue-au-novitchok-dans-le-moscou-des-annees-1990.php?redirect_premium Quand un banquier russe \u00e9tait tu\u00e9 au Novitchok dans le Moscou des ann\u00e9es 1990], ''Le Figaro'', 21 March 2018.{{in lang|fr}}</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.com/ukrainian/features-russian-43398713 \u0412 1995 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0443 \u044f\u0434\u043e\u043c, \u043f\u043e\u0445\u043e\u0436\u0438\u043c \u043d\u0430 \"\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447\u043e\u043a\", \u043e\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0431\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0438\u0440\u0430 \u0418\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u041a\u0438\u0432\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0434\u0438], BBC, 14 March 2018.{{in lang|ru}}</ref>\n\nA former KGB and FSB officer, Boris Karpichkov, who operated in Latvia in the 1990s and fled to the UK in 1998,<ref name=\"delfihit\">[https://rus.delfi.lv/news/daily/abroad/byvshij-dvojnoj-agent-fcb-v-latvii-menya-atakovali-neizvestnym-veschestvom.d?id=49843319 \u0411\u044b\u0432\u0448\u0438\u0439 \u0434\u0432\u043e\u0439\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0430\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0442 \u0424C\u0411 \u0432 \u041b\u0430\u0442\u0432\u0438\u0438: \u043c\u0435\u043d\u044f \u0442\u043e\u0436\u0435 \u0430\u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u043d\u0435\u0438\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043d\u044b\u043c \u0432\u0435\u0449\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u043c] [[Delfi (web portal)|Delfi]], 15 March 2018.</ref> told [[ITV (TV network)|ITV's]] ''[[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]]'' that on 12 February 2018, three weeks before the Salisbury attack and exactly on his birthday, he received a message over the [[burner phone]] from \"a very reliable source\" in the FSB telling Karpichkov that \"something bad [wa]s going to happen with [him] and seven other people, including Mr. Skripal\", whom he then knew nothing about.<ref name=\"itvkarpichkov\">[https://www.itv.com/goodmorningbritain/former-kgb-agent-says-he-was-warned-of-skripal-poisoning Former KGB agent says he was warned of Skripal poisoning] [[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]], 12 March 2018.</ref> Karpichkov said he disregarded the message at the time, thinking it was not serious, as he had previously received such messages.<ref name=\"itvkarpichkov\" /> According to Karpichkov, the FSB's list includes the names of [[Oleg Gordievsky]] and [[Bill Browder|William Browder]].<ref name=\"delfihit\" /><ref>Kitty Donaldson, Henry Meyer, and Irina Reznik. [https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-29/finding-your-name-on-russia-s-hit-list Finding Your Name on Russia\u2019s Hit List: The nerve-gas poisoning of a former KGB agent in the U.K. has Moscow\u2019s foes spooked.] Bloomberg, 29 March 2018.</ref>\n\n===Spiez Laboratory in Switzerland===\nThe Swiss Federal Intelligence Service asserted on 14 September 2018 that two Russian spies had been caught in the [[Netherlands]] and expelled, earlier in the year, for attempting to hack into the [[Spiez Laboratory]] in the Swiss town of [[Spiez]], a designated lab of the [[OPCW]] that had been tasked with confirming that the samples of poison collected in Salisbury were Novichok. The spies were discovered through a joint investigation by the Swiss, Dutch, and British intelligence services. The two men expelled were not the same as the Salisbury suspects.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/dutch-kicked-out-russian-spies-over-alleged-plot-to-hack-lab-investigating-salisbury-novichok-11497884|title=Dutch kicked out 'Russian spies' over alleged plot to hack lab investigating Salisbury novichok|work=Sky News|access-date=2018-09-14|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/14/world/europe/russians-salisbury-swiss-lab-sabotage.html|title=Russians Planned Attack on Lab Testing Salisbury Nerve Agent, Swiss Say|last=Schreuer|first=Milan|date=14 September 2018|work=New York Times|access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Response from other countries and organisations ==\n\n=== US government ===\nFollowing Theresa May's statement in [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]], the US Secretary of State [[Rex Tillerson]] released a statement on 12 March that fully supported the stance of the UK government on the poisoning attack, including \"its assessment that Russia was likely responsible for the nerve agent attack that took place in Salisbury\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.state.gov/secretary/remarks/2018/03/279201.htm|title=Attributing Responsibility for the Nerve Agent Attack in the U.K.|work=U.S. Department of State|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref> The following day, US President [[Donald Trump]] said that Russia was likely responsible.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/03/13/europe/trump-russia-spy-intl/index.html|title=Trump: Russia likely poisoned ex-spy, 'based on all the evidence'|last=Vonberg|first=Judith|publisher=CNN|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[United States Ambassador to the United Nations]] [[Nikki Haley]] at the Security Council briefing on 14 March 2018 stated: \"The United States believes that Russia is responsible for the attack on two people in the United Kingdom using a military-grade nerve agent\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Haley|first1=Nikki|title=Remarks at an Emergency UN Security Council Briefing on Chemical Weapons Use by Russia in the United Kingdom|url=https://usun.state.gov/remarks/8336|website=United States Mission to the United Nations|publisher=Department of State|date=14 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[United States National Security Council]]'s recommendation,<ref name=\"cnndiplomats\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/03/23/politics/trump-russian-diplomats-national-security-council/index.html|title=Trump's National Security Council recommends expelling Russian diplomats|first=Michelle |last=Kosinski|publisher=CNN|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref> President Trump, on 26 March, ordered the expulsion of sixty Russian diplomats (referred to by the White House as \"Russian intelligence officers\"<ref name=\"whitehouseexpul\">[https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/statement-press-secretary-expulsion-russian-intelligence-officers/ Statement from the Press Secretary on the Expulsion of Russian Intelligence Officers] The White House, 26 March 2018.</ref>) and the closure of the Russian consulate in Seattle.<ref name=\"wptrump\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-administration-expels-60-russian-officers-shuts-seattle-consulate-in-response-to-attack-on-former-spy-in-britain/2018/03/26/8ada3d8e-30f0-11e8-8bdd-cdb33a5eef83_story.html|title=Trump administration expels 60 Russian officers, shuts Seattle consulate in response to attack on former spy in Britain|last=Rucker|first=Philip|date=26 March 2018|work=The Washington Post|access-date=26 March 2018|last2=Nakashima|first2=Ellen|issn=0190-8286}}</ref><ref>[https://tass.ru/mezhdunarodnaya-panorama/5066974 \u0421\u0428\u0410 \u0432\u044b\u0441\u044b\u043b\u0430\u044e\u0442 \u0438\u0437 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u044b 60 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0434\u0438\u043f\u043b\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0432] TASS, 26 March 2018.</ref> The action was cast as being \"in response to Russia's use of a military-grade chemical weapon on the soil of the United Kingdom, the latest in its ongoing pattern of destabilising activities around the world.\"<ref name=\"whitehouseexpul\" />\n\nOn 8 August,<ref name=\"aug8\">{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2018/08/285043.htm|title=Imposition of Chemical and Biological Weapons Control and Warfare Elimination Act Sanctions on Russia}}</ref> five months after the poisoning,<ref name=aug9 /> the US government agreed to place sanctions on Russian banks and exports.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/401236-russia-threatens-retaliation-against-new-us-sanctions|title=Russia: New US sanctions a 'declaration of economic war'|first=Tal|last=Axelrod|date=10 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://time.com/5363719/russia-banking-sanctions-skripal-medvedev/|title=Russia Warns U.S. Against Ramping Up Sanctions|website=Time}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2018/08/09/u-s-sanctions-russia-putin-critics-poisoned-dead/944476002/|title=As U.S. sanctions Russia for ex-spy, Moscow adds to list of critics found poisoned or dead}}</ref><ref name=\"aug9\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2018/08/us-russia-sanctions-novichok-attack/567119/|title=The U.S. Sanctions Russia for Skripal Poisoning\u2014Five Months Later|first=Yasmeen|last=Serhan|date=9 August 2018}}</ref> On 6 August,<ref name=aug8 /> the US State Department concluded that Russia was behind the poisoning.<ref name=aug8 /> The sanctions, which are enforced under the [[Chemical and Biological Weapons Control and Warfare Elimination Act of 1991]] (CBW Act),<ref name=aug8 /> were planned to come into effect on 27 August.<ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. sanctions tied to nerve agent attack in effect Monday: federal notice |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-russia-novichok/u-s-sanctions-tied-to-nerve-agent-attack-in-effect-monday-federal-notice-idUSKCN1L91CY?il=0 |accessdate=24 August 2018 |work=[[Reuters]] |date=24 August 2018}}</ref> However, these sanctions were not implemented by the Trump administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/trump-admin-has-not-imposed-new-sanctions-russia-required-law-n962216|title=U.S. has not imposed new Russia sanctions sparked by Skripal poisoning|website=NBC News}}</ref>\n\n===European Union and member states===\n[[Vice-President of the European Commission|European Commission Vice-President]] [[Frans Timmermans]] argued for \"unequivocal, unwavering and very strong\" European solidarity with the United Kingdom when speaking to lawmakers in Strasburg on 13 March.<ref name=\"ap180313143500\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/5f4189f2-26aa-11e8-a227-fd2b009466bc_story.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180313191949/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/the-latest-russia-demands-samples-of-nerve-agent/2018/03/13/5f4189f2-26aa-11e8-a227-fd2b009466bc_story.html |archive-date=13 March 2018 |title=The Latest: Trump, May agree on consequences for poison use |agency=Associated Press |date=13 March 2018 |accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref> [[Federica Mogherini]], the [[High Representative of the Union for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy]], expressed shock and offered the bloc's support.<ref name=\"reuters180313085900\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-russia-eu/despite-brexit-britain-wins-eu-support-on-nerve-agent-attack-idUSKCN1GP0R9 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20180313192407/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-russia-eu/despite-brexit-britain-wins-eu-support-on-nerve-agent-attack-idUSKCN1GP0R9 |archive-date=13 March 2018 |title=Despite Brexit, Britain wins EU support on nerve agent attack |agency=Reuters |date=13 March 2018 |accessdate=13 March 2018 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]] and leader of the [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe]] in the European Parliament [[Guy Verhofstadt]] proclaimed solidarity with the British people.<ref name=\"guardian180313151400\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/13/sergei-skripal-spy-poisoning-russia-uk-sanctions-eu-lack-consensus |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180313192633/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/13/sergei-skripal-spy-poisoning-russia-uk-sanctions-eu-lack-consensus |archive-date=13 March 2018 |title=UK's effort to rally allies over Sergei Skripal poisoning may fall short |work=The Guardian |date=13 March 2018 |accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring a meeting in the [[Foreign Affairs Council]] on 19 March, all foreign ministers of the European Union declared in a joint statement that the \"European Union expresses its unqualified solidarity with the UK and its support, including for the UK's efforts to bring those responsible for this crime to justice.\" In addition, the statement also pointed out that \"The European Union takes extremely seriously the UK Government's assessment that it is highly likely that the Russian Federation is responsible.\"<ref name=\"eu-20180319\">{{cite press release  |url=https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2018/03/19/statement-by-the-foreign-affairs-council-on-the-salisbury-attack/ |title= Statement by the Foreign Affairs Council on the Salisbury attack |date= 19 March 2018 |publisher=[[Council of the European Union]]|access-date= 19 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Norbert R\u00f6ttgen]], a former [[Federal Ministry of the Environment, Nature Conservation and Nuclear Safety|federal minister]] in Angela Merkel's government and current chairman of Germany's parliamentary foreign affairs committee, said the incident demonstrated the need for Britain to review its open-door policy towards Russian capital of dubious origin.<ref name=\"rottgen\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/13/sergei-skripal-spy-poisoning-russia-uk-sanctions-eu-lack-consensus|title=UK's effort to rally allies over Sergei Skripal poisoning may fall short|last=Wintour|first=Patrick|date=13 March 2018|website=The Guardian|access-date=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nSixteen EU countries expelled 33 Russian diplomats on 26 March.<ref name=\"expulsionbbc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-43545565|title=Spy poisoning: Russian diplomats expelled across US and Europe|publisher=BBC News|date=26 March 2017|accessdate=26 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"expulsionguardian\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/26/four-eu-states-set-to-expel-russian-diplomats-over-skripal-attack|title=US and EU expel scores of Russian diplomats over Skripal attack|last=Borger|first=Julian|last2=Wintour|first2=Patrick|last3=Stewart|first3=Heather|date=26 March 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[European Union]] officially sanctioned 4 Russians that were suspected of carrying out the attack on 21 January 2019. The head of the GRU Igor Kostyukov and the deputy head Vladimir Alexseyev were both sanctioned along with Mishkin and Chepiga. The sanctions banned them from traveling to the EU and froze any assets they may have there along with banning any person or company in the EU providing any financial support to those sanctioned.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-46949162|title=EU sanctions Russian suspects over Salisbury|date=21 January 2019|access-date=2019-01-21|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===Other non-EU countries===\nAlbania, Australia, Canada, Georgia, Macedonia, Moldova, Norway and Ukraine expelled a total of 27 Russian diplomats who were believed to have been intelligence officers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/03/26/europe/full-list-of-russian-diplomats-expelled-over-s-intl/index.html|title=These are all the countries that are expelling Russian diplomats|last=Dewan|first=Angela|date=27 March 2018|publisher=CNN|access-date=27 March 2018}}</ref> The New Zealand Government also issued a statement supporting the actions, noting that it would have expelled any Russian intelligence agents who had been detected in the country.<ref>{{cite news|title=PM Jacinda Ardern: Why NZ is not expelling Russia diplomats|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12020803|accessdate=28 March 2018|work=The New Zealand Herald|date=27 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===NATO===\n[[NATO]] issued an official response to the attack on 14 March. The alliance expressed its deep concern over the first offensive use of a nerve agent on its territory since its foundation and said that the attack was in breach of international treaties. It called on Russia to fully disclose its research of the Novichok agent to the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/news_152787.htm|title=Statement by the North Atlantic Council on the use of a nerve agent in Salisbury|website=nato.int|date=14 March 2018|access-date=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Jens Stoltenberg]], [[Secretary General of NATO|NATO Secretary General]], announced on 27 March that NATO would be expelling seven Russian diplomats from the [[Russia\u2013NATO relations|Russian mission to NATO]] in Brussels. In addition, 3 unfilled positions at the mission have been denied accreditation from NATO. Russia blamed the US for the NATO response.<ref name = NATOexpulsions/>\n\n=== Joint responses ===\nThe leaders of France, Germany, the United States and the United Kingdom released a joint statement on 15 March which supported the UK's stance on the incident, stating that it was \"highly likely that Russia was responsible\" and calling on Russia to provide complete disclosure to the [[Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons]] concerning its Novichok nerve agent program.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/15/salisbury-poisoning-uk-us-germany-and-france-issue-joint-statement|title=UK, US, Germany and France unite to condemn spy attack|last=Walker|first=Peter|last2=Roth|first2=Andrew|date=15 March 2018|website=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/salisbury-attack-joint-statement-from-the-leaders-of-france-germany-the-united-states-and-the-united-kingdom|title=Salisbury attack: Joint statement from the leaders of France, Germany, the United States and the United Kingdom|publisher=Government of the United Kingdom|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref> On 19 March, the [[European Union]] also issued a statement strongly condemning the attack and stating it \"takes extremely seriously the UK Government's assessment that it is highly likely that the Russian Federation is responsible\".<ref name=eu-20180319/>\n\nOn 6 September 2018, Canada, France, Germany and the United States issued a joint statement saying they had \"full confidence\" that the Salisbury attack was orchestrated by Russia's [[Main Intelligence Directorate]] and \"almost certainly approved at a senior government level\" and urged Russia to provide full disclosure of its Novichok programme to the OPCW.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/d8e6df42-b1d2-11e8-99ca-68cf89602132|title=Key western allies back UK over Salisbury attack|author1=Henry Mance|author2=Michael Peel|author3=Guy Chazan|date=6 September 2018|accessdate=6 September 2018|website=Financial Times}}</ref>\n\n==Expulsion of diplomats==\n[[File:Map of sanctions - Expelled Russian diplomats.svg|thumb|Expelled Russian diplomats]]\nBy the end of March 2018 a number of countries and other organisations expelled a total of more than 150 Russian diplomats in a show of solidarity with the UK. According to the BBC it was \"the largest collective expulsion of Russian intelligence officers in history\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-43545565|title=Russia faces wave of diplomatic expulsions|date=26 March 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=27 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"NATOexpulsions\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-43550938|title=Nato slashes Russia staff after poisoning|date=27 March 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=27 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Montenegro to expel Russian diplomat over UK nerve gas attack|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-russia-montenegro/montenegro-to-expel-russian-diplomat-over-uk-nerve-gas-attack-idUSKBN1H41GH|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=28 March 2018|date=28 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe UK expelled 23 Russian diplomats on 14 March 2018. Three days later, Russia expelled an equal number of British diplomats and ordered closure of the UK consulate in St. Petersburg and closure of the British Council in Russia.<ref name=\"indeprusexp\" /> Nine countries expelled Russian diplomats on 26 March: along with 6 other EU nations, the US, Canada, Ukraine and Albania. The following day, several nations inside and outside of the EU, and NATO responded similarly. By 30 March, Russia expelled an equal number of diplomats of most nations who had expelled Russian diplomats. By that time, Belgium, Montenegro, Hungary and Georgia had also expelled one or more Russian diplomats. Additionally on 30 March, Russia reduced the size of the total UK mission's personnel in Russia to match that of the Russian mission to the UK.\n\nBulgaria, Luxembourg, Malta, Portugal, Slovakia, Slovenia and the European Union itself have not expelled any Russian diplomats but have recalled their ambassadors from Russia for consultations.<ref>[https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2018-03-27/bulgaria-recalls-ambassador-from-russia-to-discuss-nerve-agent-attack Bulgaria Recalls Ambassador From Russia to Discuss Nerve Agent Attack]. Reuters via US News. 27 March 2018.</ref><ref>[https://newsnow.tasr.sk/foreign/slovakia-to-call-ambassador-to-russia-back-home-for-consultation/ Slovakia to Call Ambassador to Russia Back Home for Consultation]. TASR.sk. 28 March 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-russia-luxembourg/luxembourg-recalls-ambassador-from-russia-over-salisbury-attack-idUSKBN1H40YA Luxembourg recalls ambassador from Russia over Salisbury attack]. Reuters. 28 March 2018.</ref><ref>Diacono, Tim. [https://lovinmalta.com/news/news-international/malta-has-just-recalled-its-ambassador-to-russia Malta Has Just Recalled Its Ambassador To Russia]. Lovin Malta. Retrieved on 18 May 2018.</ref><ref>[https://finance.yahoo.com/news/state-play-over-russian-envoy-expulsions-001133000.html State of play over Russian envoy expulsions]. Finance.yahoo.com (28 March 2018). Retrieved on 18 May 2018.</ref><ref>[https://tass.com/world/996694 Slovenia recalling its ambassador to Russia for consultations]. Tass. 29 March 2018.</ref> Furthermore, Iceland decided to diplomatically boycott the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] held in Russia.<ref>[https://www.rt.com/sport/422397-iceland-boycott-fifa-russia/ Iceland to diplomatically boycott 2018 World Cup in Russia]. Rt.com. 26 March 2018.</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Country or<br />organisation\n!Diplomats expelled\n!Date announced\n!Response by Russia\n!Date announced\n|-\n|{{flag|Albania}}\n|2\n|26 March\n|2 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name=\"moreUKexpel\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-43604053|title=Spy poisoning: Russia expels more UK diplomats|date=31 March 2018|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Australia}}\n|2\n|27 March\n|2 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Belgium}}\n|1\n|27 March\n|1 diplomat expelled (the economic ''attach\u00e9'').<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nieuws.vtm.be/binnenland/deze-diplomaat-wijst-rusland-uit|title=Deze diplomaat wijst Rusland uit|publisher=[[VTM (TV channel)|VTM]]|date=4 April 2018|accessdate=4 April 2018|language=Dutch}}</ref>\n|4 April\n|-\n|{{flag|Canada}}\n|4{{ref|a|[a]}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.canada.ca/en/global-affairs/news/2018/03/canada-expels-russian-diplomats-in-solidarity-with-united-kingdom.html |title=Canada expels Russian diplomats in solidarity with United Kingdom |website=www.canada.ca|date=26 March 2018}}</ref>\n|26 March\n|4 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Croatia}}\n|1\n|26 March\n|1 diplomat based in [[Zagreb]] declared [[Persona non-grata|PNG]].<ref>[https://www.vecernji.hr/vijesti/mvep-hrvatski-diplomat-rusija-moskva-1236214 Nepo\u017eeljna \u0161efica ureda ministrice, k\u0107er po\u010dasnog konzula Moskve] [[Ve\u010dernji list]], 30 March 2018.</ref>\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Czech Republic}}\n|3\n|26 March\n|3 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Denmark}}\n|2\n|26 March\n|2 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Estonia}}\n|1\n|26 March\n|1 diplomat expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Finland}}\n|1\n|26 March\n|1 diplomat expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|France}}\n|4\n|26 March\n|4 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Germany}}\n|4\n|26 March\n|4 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Georgia}}\n|1<ref name=\"georgiaExpel\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-georgia-russia/georgia-expels-one-russian-diplomat-over-uk-nerve-agent-attack-idUSKBN1H61BC?il=0|title=Georgia expels one Russian diplomat over UK nerve agent attack|date=30 March 2018|publisher=Reuters|language=ru}}</ref>\n|30 March\n|1 diplomat expelled by Russia.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ria.ru/politics/20180413/1518574392.html |title=\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044f \u043e\u0431\u044a\u044f\u0432\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u0433\u0440\u0443\u0437\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0434\u0438\u043f\u043b\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0441\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u043d\u043e\u043d \u0433\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0430 |publisher=[[\u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438]] |date=13 April 2018 |accessdate=15 April 2018}}</ref>\n|13 April\n|-\n|{{flag|Hungary}}\n|1\n|26 March\n|1 diplomat expelled by Russia.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-russia-hungary-expulsion/russia-says-expels-one-hungarian-diplomat-over-skripal-case-idUSKCN1HB1EE |title=Russia says expels one Hungarian diplomat over Skripal case |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=4 April 2018 |website= |publisher= Reuters |access-date= 20 April 2018}}</ref>\n|4 April\n|-\n|{{flag|Ireland}}\n|1\n|27 March\n|1 diplomat expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Italy}}\n|2\n|26 March\n|2 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Latvia}}\n|1\n|26 March\n|1 diplomat expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Lithuania}}\n|3\n|26 March\n|3 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Macedonia}}\n|1\n|26 March\n|1 diplomat expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Moldova}}\n|3\n|27 March\n|3 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Montenegro}}\n|1<ref name=\"montExpel\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.rt.com/newsline/422558-slovakia-ambassador-russia-montenegro/|title=Slovakia recalls ambassador from Moscow, Montenegro to expel Russian diplomat|date=28 March 2018|publisher=[[RT (TV network)|RT]]}}</ref>\n|28 March\n|1 diplomat expelled by Russia.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ria.ru/politics/20180402/1517770018.html |script-title=ru:\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044f \u0432\u044b\u0448\u043b\u0435\u0442 \u0447\u0435\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0434\u0438\u043f\u043b\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0430 |publisher=[[\u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438]] |date=2 April 2018 |accessdate=15 April 2018|language=ru}}</ref>\n|2 April\n|-\n|{{flag|NATO}}\n|7{{ref|b|[b]}}<ref name =NATOexpulsions />\n|27 March\n|\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Netherlands}}\n|2\n|26 March\n|2 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Norway}}\n|1\n|26 March\n|1 diplomat expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Poland}}\n|4\n|26 March\n|4 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Romania}}\n|1\n|26 March\n|1 diplomat expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Spain}}\n|2\n|26 March\n|2 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Sweden}}\n|1\n|26 March\n|1 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Ukraine}}\n|13\n|26 March\n|13 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |{{flag|United Kingdom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |23\n| rowspan=\"2\" |14 March\n|23 UK diplomats expelled by Russia.<br />British consulate in St Petersburg closed. Russian office of the [[British Council]] closed.\n|17 March\n|-\n|UK diplomatic mission to Russia reduced in size to match Russian mission to UK. Requires the UK to recall a further 27 officials. \n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|United States}}\n|60,{{ref|c|[c]}} Russian consulates in [[Consulate-General of Russia in San Francisco|San Francisco]] and Seattle closed.\n|26 March\n|60 US diplomats expelled by Russia.<br />US consulate in St Petersburg closed.\n|30 March\n|}\n\n'''Notes'''\n* {{sup|{{note|a|[a]}}}} 4 diplomats expelled. 3 pending applications declined.\n* {{sup|{{note|b|[b]}}}} 7 expelled and 3 pending applications declined. Maximum delegation reduced by 10 (from 30 to 20).\n* {{sup|{{note|c|[c]}}}} 48 Russian diplomats expelled from Washington D.C. and 12 expelled from New York.\n\n==Aftermath==\nSome of the emergency vehicles used in the response to the poisoning have been buried in a [[landfill]] site near [[Cheltenham]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-wiltshire-45362840|title=Novichok 999 vehicles buried in landfill|date=31 August 2018|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 September, [[Chris Busby]], a retired research scientist, who is regular expert on the [[Russian government]] controlled [[RT (TV network)|RT]] television network, was arrested after his home in [[Bideford]] was raided by police.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/police-fall-ill-at-chemical-expert-s-home-l2cmh6xb7|title=Police fall ill at chemical expert's home|first=Gurpreet|last=Narwan|date=14 September 2018|work=The Times|url-access=subscription |accessdate=20 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/dr-chris-busby-police-become-unwell-at-chemical-weapons-experts-devon-home-11496768|title=Dr Chris Busby: Police become unwell at chemical weapons expert's Devon home|publisher=Sky News|accessdate=20 September 2018}}</ref> Busby was an outspoken critic of the British Government's handling of the Salisbury poisoning.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nachdenkseiten.de/?p=43331|title= Alternative Fakten und nationale Alleing\u00e4nge \u2013 Gro\u00dfbritannien und Deutschland blamieren sich im Fall Skripal bis auf die Knochen|date=6 April 2018|accessdate=20 September 2018|via=www.nachdenkseiten.de}}</ref> In one video he stated: \"Just to make it perfectly clear, there's no way that there's any proof that the material that poisoned the Skripals came from Russia.\" Busby was held for 19 hours under the [[Explosive Substances Act 1883]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.devonlive.com/news/devon-news/police-chris-busby-russia-today-2005659|title=Inside the bomb scare lab that belongs to Russia Today nuclear expert|first=Joel|last=Cooper|date=14 September 2018|accessdate=20 September 2018}}</ref> before being released with no further action.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/09/13/chemical-weapons-expert-arrested-police-taken-devon-home/|title=Chemical weapons expert arrested after police 'taken ill' at Devon home|first=Telegraph|last=Reporters|date=13 September 2018|accessdate=20 September 2018|work=The Telegraph}}</ref> Following his release, Busby told the BBC he believed that the fact that two of the officers who had raided his property had felt unwell was explained by \"psychological problems associated with their knowledge of the Skripal poisoning\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-devon-45516797|title=Bideford radiation expert held over home chemicals|date=13 September 2018|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=20 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 September, fears of Novichok contamination flared up again after two people fell ill at a [[Prezzo (restaurant)|Prezzo]] restaurant, {{convert|300|m}} from the Zizzi location where the Skripals had eaten before collapsing. The restaurant, a nearby pub, and surrounding streets were cordoned off, with some patrons under observation or unable to leave the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbs8.com/story/39100286/roads-shut-after-2-fall-ill-in-uk-city-where-ex-spy-poisoned|title=Roads shut after 2 fall ill in UK city where ex-spy poisoned|agency=Associated Press|publisher=CBS8 News}}</ref> The next day, the police said there was \"nothing to suggest that Novichok\" was the cause of the two people falling ill.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-45543606|title='No Novichok link' to Salisbury incident|date=17 September 2018|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=17 September 2018}}</ref> However, on 19 September, one of the apparent victims, Anna Shapiro, claimed in ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' newspaper that the incident had been an attempted assassination against her and her husband by Russia.<ref name=\"GuardianShapiro\">{{cite web |title=Rat poison, Prezzo and the Russian model: odd Salisbury subplot begins to unravel |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/sep/19/salisburys-saga-the-spy-the-supermodel-the-strychnine-and-thats-just-the-sub-plot |work=The Guardian |accessdate=20 September 2018}}</ref> This article was later removed from ''The Sun'' \"for legal reasons\"<ref name=\"GuardianShapiro\" /> and the police began to investigate the incident as a \"possible hoax\" after the couple were discharged from hospital.<ref>{{cite web |title=Salisbury Prezzo novichok poisoning scare may be a hoax, say police |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/salisbury-prezzo-couple-ill-russia-rat-poison-anna-shapiro-alex-king-skripal-novichok-a8546001.html |work=The Independent |accessdate=20 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that then deputy CIA director [[Gina Haspel]] advised Donald Trump in a discussion that young children had been hospitalised and ducks killed after exposure to the Novichok nerve agent that poisoned the Skripals. She showed him photos of these victims which the ''New York Times'' reported had been provided by British officials.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Barnes |first1=Julian E. |last2=Goldman |first2=Adam |title=Gina Haspel Relies on Spy Skills to Connect With Trump. He Doesn't Always Listen. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/16/us/politics/gina-haspel-trump.html |accessdate=20 April 2019 |work=New York Times|date=16 April 2019}}</ref> The incident was cited as an example of the \"''persuasive skills''\" of the then CIA director Gina Haspel. In response the director of public health at Wiltshire council said: \"There were no other casualties other than those previously stated. No wildlife were impacted by the incident and no children were exposed to or became ill as a result of either incident\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/apr/18/no-children-ducks-harmed-novichok-attack-wiltshire-health-officials|title=No children or ducks harmed by novichok, say health officials|last=Morris|first=Steven|date=18 April 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-04-21|last2=Bannock|first2=Caroline|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/apr/16/trump-novichok-attack-skripal-poisoning-spy-game Trump wrote off novichok attack of defector as 'spy games' \u2013 report], The Guardian, 16 April 2019</ref>\n\n===Russian public opinion===\nThe ''Moscow Times'' reported that \"The results of the survey published by the independent [[Levada Center]] pollster [in October 2018] say that 28 percent of Russians believe that British intelligence services were behind Skripals' poisoning, with only 3 percent saying they believe their own intelligence officers carried out the attack. Another 56 percent said that \"it could have been anyone.\" Meanwhile, 37 percent of respondents said they knew about the case in detail and 33 percent said they had \"heard something\" about it, with another 20 percent saying they had heard nothing about the poisoning.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Only 3% of Russians Believe Moscow Was Behind Skripal Attack, Poll Says |url=https://themoscowtimes.com/news/only-3-percent-russians-believe-moscow-was-behind-skripal-attack-poll-says-63297 |work=[[The Moscow Times]] |date=25 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Recovery money==\nAs of 17 October 2018, a total of \u00a37.5 million had been pledged by government in support of the city and to support businesses, boost tourism and to cover unexpected costs. [[Wiltshire Council]] had spent or pledged \u00a37,338,974 on recovery, and a further half million \"was in the pipeline\":\n* \u00a3733,381 towards unexpected closure and loss of footfall to businesses\n* \u00a3404,024 in revenue grants for 74 businesses\n* \u00a399,891 in capital grants\n* \u00a3229,446 in business rate relief for 56 businesses\n* \u00a3210,491 on events to boost tourism\n* \u00a3500,000 from the Department of Digital, Culture, Media and Sport\n* \u00a34,000 on dry cleaning or disposal of clothes believed to be contaminated by Novichock\n* \u00a31 million towards keeping contaminated sites safe\n* \u00a3570,000 recovery money to cover costs of free parking, and free park and ride services\n* \u00a34.1 million of the money pledged by the [[Home Office]] to cover Wiltshire Police's costs. A council commissioner said total policing cost had exceeded \u00a310 million. Having \u00a36.6 million allocated for funding the police force, he said he hoped to \"recoup the full amount from central government\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.salisburyjournal.co.uk/news/16989675.breakdown-of-wiltshire-council-spend-on-salisbury-recovery/ | title=Breakdown of Wiltshire Council spend on Salisbury recovery | date=17 October 2018 | first=Rebecca | last=Hudson | newspaper=Salisbury Journal | accessdate=27 March 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{commonscat|Nerve agent attack 2018}}\n* [[Intelligence agencies of Russia]]\n* [[2018 Amesbury poisonings]]\n* [[Assassination of Kim Jong-nam]] by North Korea with VX nerve agent \n*[[Poisoning of Alexander Litvinenko]] putatively by Russian intelligence agents with Polonium-210\n*[[Bulgarian umbrella]] used to assassinate [[Georgi Markov]] in London\n*[[List of poisonings]]\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Russia}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Noteslist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* Report from The Russian Embassy to the UK, ''Salisbury: Unanswered questions'' [https://rusemb.org.uk/fnapr/6762 SALISBURY: UNANSWERED QUESTIONS (4 March 2019)], 4 March 2019\n* [https://www.counterterrorism.police.uk/salisbury/ \"Salisbury & Amesbury Investigation - UK Counter Terrorism Policing\"], 5 September 2018 \n* [https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43315636 \"Russian spy: What we know so far\"], [[BBC]], 19 March 2018 \n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2018/03/06/the-long-terrifying-history-of-russian-dissidents-being-poisoned-abroad/ \"Amanda Erickson: The long, terrifying history of Russian dissidents being poisoned abroad\"], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', 7 March 2018 \n* [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-43299598 \"Joel Gunter: Sergei Skripal and the 14 deaths under scrutiny\"], bbc.com, 7 March 2018\n* [[Bellingcat]]'s investigative page for the Chepiga identification [https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2018/09/26/skripal-suspect-boshirov-identified-gru-colonel-anatoliy-chepiga Skripal Suspect Boshirov Identified as GRU Colonel Anatoliy Chepiga]\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Skripal, Sergei and Yulia}}\n[[Category:2018 controversies]]\n[[Category:2018 crimes in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2018 in British politics]]\n[[Category:2018 in international relations]]\n[[Category:21st century in Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:Attacks in 2018]]\n[[Category:Crime in Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:Diplomatic incidents]]\n[[Category:Failed assassination attempts]]\n[[Category:Forensic toxicology]]<!-- Suggest this article is about the poisoning, the article on Reactions has the foreign relations component -->\n[[Category:History of Salisbury]]\n[[Category:March 2018 crimes in Europe]]\n[[Category:March 2018 events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Poisoning by drugs, medicaments and biological substances]]\n[[Category:Russia intelligence operations]]\n[[Category:Russia\u2013United Kingdom relations]]\n[[Category:Russia\u2013United States relations]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2018 attempted murder in Salisbury, England, United Kingdom}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n|title=Poisoning of Sergei and Yulia Skripal\n|partof=\n|image=Forensic tent at The Maltings, Salisbury (cropped).jpg\n|caption=A [[Crime scene|forensics tent]] covers the bench where Sergei and Yulia Skripal fell unconscious\n|image_upright=1.3\n|alt=\n|map=\n|map_size=\n|map_alt=\n|map_caption=\n|location=[[Salisbury]], [[Wiltshire]], United Kingdom\n|target=[[Sergei Skripal|Sergei Viktorovich Skripal]]<br/>Yulia Sergeevna Skripal\n|coordinates=\n|date=4 March 2018\n|time=\n|timezone=\n|injuries=\n|victims= 3 admitted to hospital<br/>(subsequently discharged):<br/>The Skripals<br/>Det Sgt Nick Bailey, [[Wiltshire Police|Wilts Police]].<br/>[[2018 Amesbury poisonings|Two other people were poisoned later]], one died\n|perpetrator=\n|assailants=<!-- or | assailant = -->\n|weapons=[[A-234 (nerve agent)|A-234]] (suspected chemical weapon used)<br/>\n|numparts=<!-- or | numpart = -->\n|dfens=<!-- or | dfen = -->\n|motive=\n|inquiry=\n|coroner=\n|accused=Russian nationals \"Alexander Petrov\" (alleged alias of [[Alexander Mishkin|Dr. Alexander Mishkin]]<ref name=Mishkin>Second Skripal Poisoning Suspect Identified as Dr. Alexander Mishkin. 2018. Bellingcat. 8 Oct. https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2018/10/08/second-skripal-poisoning-suspect-identified-as-dr-alexander-mishkin/. Retrieved: 9 October 2018.</ref>)<br/> and \"Ruslan Boshirov\"<ref name=BBCnames/> (alleged alias of [[Polkovnik|Colonel]] [[Anatoliy Chepiga]])<ref>{{cite news |title=GRU colonel Chepiga revealed as Skripal suspect's 'real identity' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-45656004 |accessdate=26 September 2018 |work=BBC News |date=26 September 2018}}</ref>\n|convicted=\n|verdict=\n|convictions=\n|charges=\n|litigation=\n|website=<!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n|module=\n}}\n<!--Important, do not revert.-->\n\nOn 4 March 2018, [[Sergei Skripal]], a former Russian military officer and double agent for the UK's [[intelligence services]], and his daughter Yulia Skripal were poisoned in [[Salisbury]], [[Wiltshire]], [[England]], with a [[Novichok agent|Novichok nerve agent]], according to official UK sources<ref name=\"Guardian May\">{{cite news|last1=Asthana|first1=Anushka|last2=Roth|first2=Andrew|last3=Harding|first3=Luke|last4=MacAskill|first4=Ewen|title=May issues ultimatum to Moscow over Salisbury poisoning|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/12/russia-highly-likely-to-be-behind-poisoning-of-spy-says-theresa-may|accessdate=13 March 2018|work=The Guardian|date=12 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"graun\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/07/russian-spy-police-appeal-for-witnesses-as-cobra-meeting-takes-place|title=Sergei Skripal: former Russian spy poisoned with nerve agent, say police|last=Dodd|first=Vikram|last2=Harding|first2=Luke|last3=MacAskill|first3=Ewen|date=8 March 2018|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=8 March 2018}}</ref> and the [[Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons|Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW)]].<ref name=\"dw\">{{cite news |url=https://www.dw.com/en/salisbury-attack-chemical-weapons-watchdog-confirms-uk-findings-on-nerve-agent/a-43358224 |title=Salisbury attack: Chemical weapons watchdog confirms UK findings on nerve agent |publisher=Deutsche Welle |date=12 April 2018 |accessdate=10 June 2018}}</ref> After three weeks in a critical condition, Yulia regained consciousness and was able to speak. She was discharged on 9 April 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43588450|title=Russian spy: Yulia Skripal 'conscious and talking'|publisher=BBC News|date=29 March 2018|accessdate=29 March 2018|postscript=none}}; {{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-43652574|title=Russian spy poisoning: Yulia Skripal 'getting stronger daily'|publisher=BBC News|date=5 April 2018|accessdate=6 April 2018|postscript=none}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/britain-russia-skripal-yulia/text-yulia-skripal-daughter-of-poisoned-russian-spy-in-her-own-words-idUSL5N1SU4TZ |title=After 20 days in a coma|author=<!--Not stated--> |date=23 May 2018 |website= Reuters.com|publisher= Reuters|access-date=21 August 2018 }}</ref> Sergei was also in a critical condition until he regained consciousness one month after the attack. He was discharged from hospital on 18 May 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-russia-skripal-hospital/poisoned-russian-agent-sergei-skripal-recovering-rapidly-hospital-says-idUKKCN1HD1PB|title=Poisoned Russian agent Sergei Skripal recovering rapidly, hospital ...|first=Alistair|last=Smout}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43671958|title=Ex-spy 'improving rapidly' after poisoning|date=6 April 2018|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> A police officer was also taken into intensive care after apparent exposure to the remnants of the toxic agent at Sergei Skripal's residence. By 22 March he had recovered enough to leave the hospital.<ref name=discharged/><ref name=\"BBC20180405\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43315636|title=Russian spy: What we know so far|date=5 April 2018|accessdate=6 April 2018|work=BBC News}}</ref>{{efn|Stephen Davies of Salisbury NHS Foundation Trust wrote an open letter to ''[[The Times]]'', published on 16 March 2018, clarifying that contrary to reports, no members of the public were affected: \"Sir, Further to your report (\"Poison exposure leaves almost 40 needing treatment\", 14 March), may I clarify that no patients have experienced symptoms of nerve agent poisoning in Salisbury and there have only ever been three patients with significant poisoning. Several people have attended the emergency department concerned that they may have been exposed. None has had symptoms of poisoning and none has needed treatment. Any blood tests performed have shown no abnormality. No member of the public has been contaminated by the agent involved.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/russia-salisbury-poison-fears-allayed-by-doctor-vf9v0zg0m |title=Russia: Salisbury poison fears allayed by doctor |last=Simpson |first=John |date=16 March 2018 |last2=Haynes |first2=Deboarh |editor-last=Hamilton |editor-first= Fiona|website= |access-date=29 March 2018}}</ref>}}\n\nIn the 1990s, Sergei Skripal was an officer for Russia's [[Main Intelligence Directorate]] (GRU) and worked as a [[double agent]] for the UK's [[Secret Intelligence Service]] from 1995 until his arrest in Moscow in December 2004. In August 2006, he was convicted of [[Treason#Russia|high treason]] and sentenced to 13 years in a [[penal colony]] by a Russian court.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Russian jailed for spying for MI6|work=[[London Evening Standard]]|location=London|date=9 August 2006|page=4}}</ref> He settled in the UK in 2010 following the [[Illegals Program]] [[Prisoner exchange|spy swap]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=The great spy swap: huge exchange of agents underway after 'deep cover' ring exposed|work=[[The Guardian]]|location=London|date=9 July 2010|page=3}}</ref> Sergei holds dual Russian and British citizenship; Yulia is a Russian citizen, and was visiting her father from Moscow.<ref name=\"dw-20180406\">{{cite news |url=https://www.dw.com/en/the-curious-case-of-yulia-skripals-recorded-phone-call/a-43287554 |title=The curious case of Yulia Skripal's recorded phone call |last=Janjevic |first=Darko |newspaper=Deutsche Welle |date=6 April 2018 |accessdate=10 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nLater on 12 March, the British government accused Russia of attempted murder and announced a series of punitive measures against Russia, including the expulsion of diplomats, on the 14 March. The UK's official assessment of the incident was supported by 28 other countries which responded similarly. Altogether, an unprecedented 153 Russian diplomats were expelled.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chughtai, Petkova|title=Skripal case diplomatic expulsions in numbers|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/interactive/2018/04/skripal-case-diplomatic-expulsions-numbers-180402121217839.html|website=Al Jazeera|accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref> Russia denied the accusations and responded similarly to the expulsions and \"accused Britain of the poisoning.\"<ref name=\"independent\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/sergei-skripal-latest-salisbury-poisoning-attack-russia-nerve-agent-sergei-lavrov-a8284766.html|title=Russia claims it could have been in interests of Britain to poison Sergei Skripal|date= 2 April 2018|accessdate=3 April 2018|newspaper=[[The Independent]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 June 2018, [[2018 Amesbury poisonings|a similar poisoning]] of two British nationals in [[Amesbury]], seven miles north of Salisbury, involved the same nerve agent.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-44719639|title=Wiltshire pair poisoned by Novichok nerve agent|date=4 July 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=5 July 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-wiltshire-44707052|title=Two collapse near spy poisoning site|date=4 July 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=5 July 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> A man found the nerve agent in a perfume bottle, in a litter bin, somewhere in Salisbury and gave it to a woman who sprayed it on her wrist.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/jul/24/novichok-victim-ill-within-15-minutes-says-partner-charlie-rowley |title=Novichok victim ill within 15 minutes, says partner Charlie Rowley |author=Press Association|date= 24 July 2018 |work=The Guardian }}</ref><ref>https://www.itv.com/news/2018-07-26/novichok-charlie-rowley-amesbury-nerve-agent-exclusive/</ref> The woman, Dawn Sturgess, fell ill within 15 minutes and died on 8 July, but the man who also came into contact with the poison survived.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/jul/09/novichok-wiltshire-death-dawn-sturgess-highly-likely-same-batch-used-on-skripals |title=Novichok in Wiltshire death 'highly likely' from batch used on Skripals |authors=Vikram Dodd, Steven Morris and Caroline Bannock|date=9 July 2018 |work=The Guardian }}</ref> British police believe this incident was not a targeted attack, but a result of the way the nerve agent was disposed of after the poisoning in Salisbury.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tobin |first=Olivia |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/crime/novichok-poisoning-probe-police-say-there-is-no-doubt-novichok-victims-are-linked-and-charlie-rowley-a3928426.html |title=Novichok poisoning probe: Police say there is 'no doubt' Novichok victims are linked and Charlie Rowley and Dawn Sturgess were innocent tragic victims |work=Evening Standard |date=5 September 2018 |accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 September 2018, British authorities identified two Russian nationals, using the names Alexander Petrov and Ruslan Boshirov, as suspected of the Skripals' poisoning,<ref name=BBCnames/> and alleged that they were active officers in Russian military intelligence.<ref name=\"NYT20180905\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/05/world/europe/russia-uk-novichok-skripal.html|title=U.K. Charges 2 Men in Novichok Poisoning, Saying They're Russian Agents|last=P\u00e9rez-Pe\u00f1a|first=Richard|date=5 September 2018|work=New York Times|access-date=2018-09-05|last2=Barry|first2=Ellen|language=en}}</ref> On 26 September 2018, investigative website [[Bellingcat]] published a statement that it had positively identified the man known as Ruslan Boshirov as the highly decorated [[GRU]] [[Polkovnik|Colonel]] [[Anatoliy Chepiga]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/report-third-russian-agent-involved-in-skripal-mission-identified-/29514321.html|title=Report: Third Alleged Russian Agent Involved in Skripal Mission Identified|website=RadioFreeEurope/RadioLiberty|language=en|access-date=2018-09-29}}</ref> On 8 October 2018, Bellingcat revealed the real identity of the suspect named by police as Alexander Petrov to be [[Alexander Mishkin|Dr. Alexander Mishkin]], also of the GRU.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2018/10/08/second-skripal-poisoning-suspect-identified-as-dr-alexander-mishkin/|title=Second Skripal Poisoning Suspect Identified as Dr. Alexander Mishkin|date=8 October 2018|accessdate=9 October 2018|publisher=Bellingcat}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2018/10/09/full-report-skripal-poisoning-suspect-dr-alexander-mishkin-hero-russia/|title=Full report: Skripal Poisoning Suspect Dr. Alexander Mishkin, Hero of Russia|date=9 October 2018|accessdate=9 October 2018|publisher=Bellingcat}}</ref> A third GRU officer present in the UK during the time Sergey and Yulia Skripal fell into a coma has been identified as Denis Vyacheslavovich Sergeev, a graduate of [[Diplomatic Academy of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation|Russia's Military Diplomatic Academy]].<ref>Bellingcat, 14 February 2019 [https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2019/02/14/third-suspect-in-skripal-poisoning-identified-as-denis-sergeev-high-ranking-gru-officer/ Suspect in Scripal poisoning identified as Denis Sergeev]</ref><ref>Bellingcat 21 February 2019 [https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2019/02/21/the-search-for-denis-sergeev-photographing-a-ghost/ The search for Denis Sergeev]</ref> Denis Sergeyev is believed to hold the rank of major general in the GRU. The pattern of his communications while in the UK indicates that Maj Gen Sergeyev liaised with superior officers in Moscow.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-48801205|title=Skripal poisoning: Third man 'commanded attack'|first=Mark|last=Urban|date=28 June 2019|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> The attempted assassination was allegedly organized by a secret [[Unit 29155]] of the Russian GRU under command of Maj. Gen. Andrei V. Averyanov. The unit is allegedly responsible for destabilizing European countries and organized the [[Montenegrin coup plot|Montenegrin coup attempt]].<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/08/world/europe/unit-29155-russia-gru.html?action=click&module=Top%20Stories&pgtype=Homepage Top Secret Russian Unit Seeks to Destabilize Europe, Security Officials Say], [[New York Times]]</ref>\n\nOn 27 November 2019, the OPCW global chemical weapons watchdog added Novichok, the Soviet-era nerve agent used in the attack, to its list of banned toxins.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-019-03686-y|title=Novichok nerve agents banned by chemical-weapons treaty|date=28 November 2019|via=www.nature.com}}</ref>\n\n==Poisoning==\n*At 14:40 [[Greenwich Mean Time|GMT]] on 3 March 2018, Yulia Skripal flew to Heathrow Airport from Russia.\n*At 9:15 on 4 March Sergei Skripal's burgundy 2009 [[BMW 3 Series|BMW 320d]] was seen in the area of London Road, Churchill Way North and Wilton Road at Salisbury.\n*At 13:30 Skripal's car was seen on Devizes Road on the way towards the town centre.\n*At 13:40 the Skripals arrived in the upper level car park at the Maltings, Salisbury and then went to the Bishops Mill Pub in the town centre.\n*At 14:20 they dined at [[Zizzi]] on Castle Street.\n*At 15:35 they left the Zizzi restaurant.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ongoing investigation into incident in Salisbury on 4 March |url=https://news.met.police.uk/news/ongoing-investigation-into-incident-in-salisbury-on-4-march-309256 |website=Metropolitan Police |accessdate=6 June 2018}}</ref>\n*At 16:15 an [[emergency service]]s call reported that Sergei Skripal, a 66-year-old resident of Salisbury, and his 33-year-old daughter Yulia had been found unconscious on a public bench in the centre of [[Salisbury]] by a passing doctor and nurse.{{efn|The nurse was the Chief Nursing Officer for the Army and the commanding officer of the [[Queen Alexandra's Royal Army Nursing Corps]], Colonel Alison L McCourt OBE ARRC QHN; her teenage daughter later received an award for alerting her mother and assisting in first aid.<ref name=guardian-20190120>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/jan/20/novichok-poisoning-victims-sergei-skripal-first-helped-by-teenage-girl |title=Novichok poisoning victims first helped by teenage girl |newspaper=The Guardian |agency=Press Association |date=20 January 2019 |accessdate=17 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=qarancassociation-2018>{{cite web |url=https://www.qarancassociation.org.uk/association-news/item/293-chief-nursing-officer-colonel-a-l-mccourt-obe-arrc-qhn |title=Chief Nursing Officer - Colonel A L McCourt OBE ARRC QHN |publisher=The QARANC Association |year=2018 |accessdate=17 April 2019}}</ref>}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Russian spy: What we know so far|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43315636|publisher=BBC News|date=8 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/03/05/alleged-former-russian-spy-critically-exposure-unknown-substance/|title=Alleged former Russian spy critically ill after exposure to unknown substance in Salisbury|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=5 March 2018|access-date=8 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/06/world/europe/uk-russian-spy-counterterrorism.html|title=In Poisoning of Sergei Skripal, Russian Ex-Spy, U.K. Sees Cold War Echoes|last=Kingsley|first=Patrick|date=6 March 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=15 March 2018|last2=P\u00e9rez-Pe\u00f1a|first2=Richard|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> An eyewitness saw Yulia foaming at the mouth with her eyes wide open but completely white.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43315636|title=Russian spy: What we know so far|publisher=BBC|date=18 March 2018|accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref> According to a later British government statement they were \"slipping in and out of consciousness on a public bench\".<ref name=unsc-20180314/>\n*At 17:10, they were taken separately to [[Salisbury District Hospital]] by an ambulance and an air ambulance.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/10/salisbury-poisoning-sergei-skripal-local-news-international-incident|title=How Salisbury case went from local drama to international incident|work=The Guardian|date=10 March 2018|accessdate=20 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt 09:03 the following morning, [[Salisbury NHS Foundation Trust]] declared a major incident in response to concerns raised by medical staff; shortly afterwards this became a multi-agency incident named Operation Fairline.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tvscn.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/Christine-Blanshard.pdf|title=Responding to Recent Events in Salisbury|last=Blanshard|first=Christine|date=12 June 2018|website=Thames Valley Strategic Clinical Network|publisher=Salisbury NHS Foundation Trust|page=5|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43295134|date=5 March 2018|access-date=8 March 2018|publisher=BBC News|title=Critically ill man 'former Russian spy'}}</ref>\n\nHealth authorities checked 21 members of the emergency services and the public for possible symptoms;<ref name=\"itv-20180308\">{{cite news |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2018-03-08/nerve-agent-attack-state-russian-spy-daughter/ |title=Up to 21 people treated after nerve agent attack on Russian spy Sergei Skripal |publisher=ITV News |date=8 March 2018 |access-date=9 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"bbcr4wato-20180309\">{{cite AV media|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b09tc4xr|title=World at One|date=9 March 2018|last=Casciani|first=Dominic|publisher=BBC Radio 4|time=21m47s|access-date=9 March 2018|quote=There was some erroneous reporting that there were 21 other people being treated, that is not true, there has only been these three casualties and they are all still in hospital}}</ref> two police officers were treated for minor symptoms, said to be itchy eyes and wheezing, while one, Detective Sergeant Nick Bailey, who had been sent to Sergei Skripal's house, had been in a serious condition.<ref name=\"Mendick\">{{cite news|author=Robert Mendick|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/03/09/russian-spy-may-have-poisoned-home-police-believe|website=The Daily Telegraph|title=Russian spy may have been poisoned at home, police believe, as military deployed to Salisbury|date=9 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Russian spy 'attacked with nerve agent'|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43323847|publisher=BBC News|date=7 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March 2018, Detective Sergeant Nick Bailey was discharged from the hospital. In a statement he said \"normal life for me will probably never be the same\" and also thanked the hospital staff.<ref name=\"discharged\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43506232|title=Policeman discharged after ex-spy attack|publisher=BBC News|access-date=23 March 2018}}</ref> {{as of|2018| March|26}}, Skripal and his daughter remained critically ill.<ref name=\"march26\">{{cite news|title=More than 130 people could have been exposed to novichok, PM says |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/26/130-people-feared-exposed-to-novichok-in-spy-attack-says-pm|work=The Guardian|date=26 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=A poisoned Russian spy and his daughter may never recover their full mental functions, a British judge said|url=https://www.newsweek.com/poisoned-russian-spy-may-never-recover-mental-functions-british-judge-says-858925|website=Newsweek|date=23 March 2018}}</ref> On 29 March 2018 it was announced that Yulia Skripal's condition was improving and she was no longer in a critical condition.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43588450|title=Ex-spy's daughter 'improving rapidly'|date=29 March 2018|publisher=BBC News|access-date=29 March 2018}}</ref> On 5 April 2018 doctors said that Sergei Skripal was no longer in critical condition and was responding well to treatment.<ref name=\"Sergei_improvement\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43671958|title=Russian spy poisoning: Sergei Skripal 'improving rapidly'|publisher=BBC News|access-date=5 April 2018}}</ref> On 9 April 2018, Yulia Skripal was discharged from hospital and taken to a secure location.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43710126|title=Russian spy: Daughter discharged from hospital|publisher=BBC News|access-date=10 April 2018|date=10 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43733765|title=No-one speaks for me \u2013 Yulia Skripal|date=12 April 2018|publisher=BBC News|access-date=12 April 2018}}</ref> On 18 May 2018, Sergei Skripal was discharged from the hospital too.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ex-spy Sergei Skripal discharged after poisoning|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-44165718|accessdate=18 May 2018|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> On 23 May 2018, a handwritten letter and a video statement by Yulia Skripal were released to the Reuters news agency for the first time after the poisoning. She stated that she was lucky to be alive after the poisoning and thanked the staff of the Salisbury hospital. She described her treatment as slow, heavy and extremely painful and she had a scar on her neck, apparently from a [[tracheotomy]]. She expressed her hope that someday she would return to Russia. She thanked the Russian embassy for its offer of assistance but said she and her father were \"not ready to take it\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-russia-skripal-yulia-exclusiv/exclusive-yulia-skripal-attempted-assassination-turned-my-world-upside-down-idUSKCN1IO2LT |title=Exclusive: Yulia Skripal - Attempted assassination turned my world upside down|date=23 May 2018|publisher=[[Reuters]]|access-date=25 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April 2018, British authorities said that inside Sergey Skripal's house, which had been sealed by the police, two guinea pigs were found dead by [[Veterinary physician|vets]], when they were allowed in, along with a cat in a distressed state.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/04/06/europe/sergei-skripal-cat-guinea-pigs-dead-intl/index.html|title=Sergei Skripal's cat and guinea pigs are dead, UK says|date=6 April 2018|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 November the first interview with DS Bailey was released in which he reported that he had been poisoned, despite the fact that he inspected the Skripals' house using [[Personal protective equipment|a forensic suit]]. In addition to the poisoning, Bailey and his family had lost their home and all their possessions, because of contamination. Investigators said that the perfume bottle containing Novichok, which was later found in a bin, had contained enough of the nerve agent to potentially kill thousands of people.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-46290989|title=Skripal poisoning: Policeman's family 'lost everything' because of Novichok|last1=Corbin|first1=Jane|date=22 November 2018|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=23 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Sergey Skripal made a phone call and left a voice message to his niece living in Russia. Thus, insinuations that the UK \"abducted\" the Skripals and kept them from speaking with the Russian embassy were challenged.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Luhn |first1=Alec |title=Sergei Skripal heard for the first time since poisoning in phone call, relatives say |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/05/23/sergei-skripal-heard-first-time-since-poisoning-phone-call-relatives/ |accessdate=29 May 2019 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |date=23 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019 it was confirmed that a second police officer had been poisoned when investigating, but only in trace amounts.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-wiltshire-49361327|title=Salisbury Novichok attack poisoned second officer, Met confirms|agency=BBC|date=15 August 2019|accessdate=16 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\nThe first public response to the poisoning came on 6 March. It was agreed under the [[National Counter Terrorism Policing Network]] that the [[Counter Terrorism Command]] based within the [[Metropolitan Police Service|Metropolitan Police]] would take over the investigation from [[Wiltshire Police]]. Assistant Commissioner Mark Rowley, head of Counter Terrorism Policing, appealed for witnesses to the incident following a [[Cabinet Office Briefing Rooms|COBR]] meeting chaired by [[Home Secretary]] [[Amber Rudd]].<ref name=\"BBC43312625\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43312625|title='More known' about substance in spy case|date=7 March 2018|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nSamples of the nerve agent used in the attack tested positive at the [[Defence Science and Technology Laboratory]] at [[Porton Down]] for a \"very rare\" nerve agent, according to the UK Home Secretary.<ref name=\"Merrick\">{{cite news|author=Rob Merrick |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/russian-spy-poison-sergei-skripal-wife-murder-son-mp-tom-tugendhat-nerve-agent-kremlin-a8246381.html|title=Russian spy: Poisoned Sergei Skripal's wife and son were murdered, alleges Conservative MP|website=Independent|date=8 March 2018|access-date=8 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n180 military experts in chemical warfare defence and decontamination, as well as 18 vehicles, were deployed on 9 March to assist the Metropolitan Police to remove vehicles and objects from the scene and look for any further traces of the nerve agent. The personnel were drawn mostly from the Army, including instructors from the [[Defence CBRN Centre]] and the [[8th Engineer Brigade (United Kingdom)|29 Explosive Ordnance Disposal and Search Group]], as well as from the [[Royal Marines]] and [[Royal Air Force]]. The vehicles included [[TPz Fuchs]] operated by Falcon Squadron from the [[Royal Tank Regiment]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43344725|title=Military deployed after spy poisoning|date=9 March 2018|publisher=BBC News|access-date=9 March 2018}}</ref> On 11 March, the UK government advised those present at either The Mill pub or the [[Zizzi]] restaurant in Salisbury on 4 and 5 March to wash or wipe their possessions, emphasising that the risk to the general public was low.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/687273/PHE_public_advice_leaflet_-_Salisbury_nerve_agent_incident.pdf|title=Public health advice for those who were in The Mill pub or Zizzi restaurant in Salisbury on Sunday 4th or Monday 5th March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43362673|title=Salisbury diners told to wash possessions|date=11 March 2018|publisher=BBC News|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nSeveral days later, on 12 March, Prime Minister [[Theresa May]] said the agent had been identified as one of the [[Novichok agent|Novichok family of agents]], believed to have been developed in the 1980s by the [[Soviet Union]].<ref name=\"mayspeech12march\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43377856|title=Russian spy: Highly likely Moscow behind attack, says Theresa May|publisher=BBC News|date=12 March 2018|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref> According to the Russian ambassador to the UK, [[Alexander Vladimirovich Yakovenko|Alexander Yakovenko]], the British authorities identified the agent as [[A-234 (nerve agent)|A-234]],<ref name=\"bbcnovichok\">{{cite web |title=Russian spy: What are Novichok agents and what do they do? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-43377698 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=10 June 2018 |date=19 March 2018}}</ref> derived from an earlier version known as A-232.<ref name=\"reut0504\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-russia-explainer/what-is-known-and-not-known-about-poisoning-of-ex-spy-in-britain-idUSKCN1HC148|title=Explainer: What is known, and not known, about poisoning of ex-spy in Britain|publisher=Reuters|date=5 April 2018|accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nBy 14 March, the investigation was focused on Skripal's home and car, a bench where the two fell unconscious, a restaurant in which they dined and a pub where they had drinks.<ref name=\"The Guardian (2)\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/14/police-five-key-locations-salisbury-in-skripal-attempted-case|title=Police home in on five key locations in Skripal attempted murder case|last=Morris|first=Steven|date=14 March 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref> A recovery vehicle was removed by the military from [[Gillingham, Dorset|Gillingham]] in Dorset on 14 March, in connection with the poisoning.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/westcountry/update/2018-03-14/police-cordon-off-road-in-gillingham-following-poisoning-in-salisbury/|title=Police cordon off road in Gillingham following poisoning in Salisbury|work=ITV News|access-date=16 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.somersetlive.co.uk/news/local-news/gillingham-dorset-becomes-latest-town-1337253|title=Local reveals van in new spy poison cordon area has been there for days|last=Trim|first=Liam|date=14 March 2018|work=somersetlive|access-date=16 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nSubsequently, there was speculation within the British media that the nerve agent had been planted in one of the personal items in Yulia Skripal's suitcase before she left Moscow for London,<ref>{{cite news |author1=Mendick, Robert |author2=Sawer, Patrick |author3=Ward, Victoria |title=Suitcase spy poisoning plot: nerve agent 'was planted in luggage of Sergei Skripal's daughter' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/03/15/suitcase-spy-poisoning-plot-nerve-agent-planted-luggage-sergei/ |accessdate=10 June 2018 |work=The Telegraph |date=15 March 2018}}</ref> and in US media that it had been planted in their car.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/18/ex-russian-spy-may-have-been-poisoned-by-cars-ventilation-says-us-media|title=Sergei Skripal possibly poisoned through car's air vents, say US media|last=Association|first=Press|date=18 March 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=29 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/russian-spys-poisoning-uk-believed-nerve-agent-car/story?id=53832515|title=Russian ex-spy's poisoning in UK believed from nerve agent in car vents: Sources|date=18 March 2018|publisher=ABC News|access-date=29 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Ahmet \u00dcz\u00fcmc\u00fc]], Director-General of the [[Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons]] (OPCW), said on 20 March that it will take \"another two to three weeks to finalise the analysis\" of samples taken from the poisoning of Skripal.<ref>\"[https://www.afp.com/en/news/826/two-three-weeks-analyze-samples-salisbury-attack-opcw-doc-12w0he1 Two to three weeks to analyze samples from Salisbury attack: OPCW]\". Agence France-Presse. 20 March 2018.</ref> On 22 March, the [[Court of Protection]] gave permission for new blood samples to be obtained from Yulia and Sergei Skripal for use by the OPCW.<ref>[https://www.judiciary.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/sshd-v-skripal-and-another-20180322.pdf Justice Williams, High Court Judgement, Royal Courts of Justice, 22 March 2018]. judiciary.gov.uk.</ref><ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/mar/22/salisbury-attack-medical-staff-contacted-police-when-antidotes-failed-to-work |title=Judge gives permission for blood samples to be taken from the Skripals |author=Morris, Steven |date=22 March 2018 |work=The Guardian |access-date=28 March 2018}}</ref> By 28 March, the police investigation concluded that the Skripals were poisoned at Sergei's home, with the highest concentration being found on the handle of his front door.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43577987|title=Spy poisoning: Highest amount of nerve agent was on door|date=28 March 2018|accessdate=28 March 2018|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> On 12 April the OPCW confirmed the UK's analysis of the type of nerve agent and reported it was of a \"high purity\", stating that the \"name and structure of the identified toxic chemical are contained in the full classified report of the Secretariat, available to States Parties.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43741140|title=Inspectors back UK in spy poisoning row|date=12 April 2018|publisher=BBC News|access-date=12 April 2018}}; {{Cite news|url=https://www.afp.com/en/news/824/watchdog-confirms-uk-findings-nerve-agent-used-russian-ex-spy-doc-13y6ti1|title=Watchdog confirms UK findings on nerve agent used on Russian ex-spy|agency=AFP|access-date=12 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.opcw.org/news/article/opcw-issues-report-on-technical-assistance-requested-by-the-united-kingdom/|title=OPCW Issues Report on Technical Assistance Requested by the United Kingdom|publisher=OPCW|access-date=12 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.opcw.org/fileadmin/OPCW/S_series/2018/en/s-1612-2018_e_.pdf |title=Summary of the Report on Activities Carried Out in Support of a Request for Technical Assistance by the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland (Technical Assistance Visit TAV/02/18) |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=12 April 2018 |publisher=OPCW |access-date=12 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nA declassified letter from the UK's national security adviser, Sir Mark Sedwill, to NATO Secretary General [[Jens Stoltenberg]], stated Russian military intelligence hacked Yulia Skripal's email account since at least 2013 and tested methods for delivering nerve agents including on door handles.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2018/04/13/russia-hacked-yulia-skripals-emails-five-years-tested-novichok/|title=Russia hacked Yulia Skripal's emails for five years and tested Novichok on door handles, bombshell intelligence dossier reveals|last=Rayner|first=Gordon|date=13 April 2018|work=The Telegraph|access-date=13 April 2018|last2=Maidment |first2=Jack}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Department for Environment]] confirmed the nerve agent was delivered \"in a liquid form\". They said eight sites require decontamination, which will take several months to complete and cost millions of pounds. The BBC reported experts said the nerve agent does not evaporate or disappear over time. Intense cleaning with caustic chemicals is required to get rid of it.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43798068|title=Skripal nerve agent 'was in liquid form'|date=17 April 2018|publisher=BBC News|access-date=18 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43833582|title=Salisbury toxic hotspots clean-up begins|date=20 April 2018|publisher=BBC News|access-date=20 April 2018}}</ref> The Skripals' survival was possibly due to the weather&nbsp;\u2013 there had been heavy fog and high humidity, and according to its inventor and other scientists, moisture weakens the potency of this type of toxin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/3600889|title=\u0412 \u0443\u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438\u044f\u0445 \u0432\u043b\u0430\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u0435\u043d\u044f\u0442\u044c \u044d\u0442\u043e \u0432\u0435\u0449\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u043c\u043e\u0433 \u0442\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043a\u043e \u0438\u0434\u0438\u043e\u0442|date=4 December 2018|work=Kommersant}}</ref><ref name=\"independent1203\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/novichok-nerve-agent-what-is-it-russian-spy-poisoning-sergei-skripal-a8252426.html|title=What is Novichok? The powerful nerve agent that makes it 'highly likely' Russia poisoned former spy|author=Andrew Griffin |date=12 March 2018|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=14 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"smc83\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sciencemediacentre.org/expert-reaction-to-nerve-agent-being-substance-identified-in-case-of-russian-ex-spy-and-his-daughter/|title=expert reaction to nerve agent being substance identified in case of Russian ex-spy and his daughter|date=8 March 2018|publisher=Science Media Centre|accessdate=14 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 April 2018, it was reported that British counter-terror police have identified a suspect in the poisoning of Sergei and Yulia Skripal. The suspect is a former FSB officer (reportedly a 54-year-old former FSB captain) who acted under several code names including \"Gordon\" and \"Mihails Savickis\". According to detectives, he led a team of six Russian assassins who organized the chemical weapons attack.<ref name=\"Gordon2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.svoboda.org/a/29185223.html|title=British media: Skripal was poisoned by former FSB officer \"Gordon\" |language=Russian |website=svoboda.org}}</ref> Sir [[Mark Sedwill]], [[National Security Adviser (United Kingdom)|UK national security adviser]], reported on 1 May 2018 however that UK intelligence and police agencies had failed to identify the individual or individuals who carried out the attack.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/may/01/no-suspects-yet-in-skripal-nerve-agent-attack-mps-told|title= No suspects yet in Skripal nerve agent attack, MPs told |last=MacAskill |first=Ewan |date=1 May 2018 |work=The Guardian |access-date=1 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 May 2018, the head of the OPCW, [[Ahmet \u00dcz\u00fcmc\u00fc]], informed the ''[[New York Times]]'' that he had been told that about 50\u2013100 g of the nerve agent was thought to have been used in the attack, which indicated it was likely created for use as a weapon and was enough to kill a large number of people.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/may/04/skripals-poisoned-by-novichok-in-liquid-form-watchdog-says|title=Skripals poisoned by novichok dose of up to 100g, watchdog says|last=Slawson|first=Nicola|date=3 May 2018 |work=The Guardian|language=en|access-date=25 May 2018 }}</ref> The next day however the OPCW made a correcting statement that the \"quantity should probably be characterised in milligrams\", though \"the OPCW would not be able to estimate or determine the amount of the nerve agent that was used\".<ref name=\"guardian-20180504\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/may/04/chemical-weapons-watchdog-amends-claim-over-salisbury-novichok |title=Chemical weapons watchdog amends claim over Salisbury novichok |last=Wintour |first=Patrick |work=The Guardian |date=4 May 2018 |accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"opcw-20180504\">{{cite web |url=https://www.opcw.org/news/article/opcw-spokespersons-statement-on-amount-of-nerve-agent-used-in-salisbury/ |title=OPCW Spokesperson's Statement on Amount of Nerve Agent Used in Salisbury |publisher=OPCW |date=4 May 2018 |accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 July the [[Press Association]] reported that police believed they had identified \"several Russians\" as the suspected perpetrators of the attack. They had been identified through [[CCTV]], cross-checked with [[Border Force|border entry data]].<ref name=\"bbc-20180719\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-44883803|publisher=BBC |title=Salisbury poisoning: Police 'identify Novichok suspects'|date=19 July 2018 |accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 August 2018, it was reported that the British government was \"poised to submit an extradition request to Moscow for two Russians suspected of carrying out the Salisbury nerve agent attack\". The Metropolitan Police used two [[super recogniser]]s to identify the suspects after trawling through up to 5,000 hours of CCTV footage from Salisbury and numerous airports across the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/aug/06/uk-poised-to-ask-russia-to-extradite-salisbury-attack-suspects|title=UK poised to ask Russia to extradite Salisbury attack suspects|first1=Nick|last1=Hopkins|first2=Luke|last2=Harding|first3=Ewen|last3=MacAskill|date=6 August 2018|website=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/super-recognisers-help-identify-skripal-suspects-11483995|title=Super recogniser squad tracks Skripal novichok attackers|date=28 August 2018|accessdate=6 September 2018|publisher=Sky News}}</ref>\n\n===Suspects and attack timeline===\nOn 5 September 2018, the [[Crown Prosecution Service]] announced charges in absentia against two alleged Russian agents. The two Russian nationals were believed to have been traveling under aliases, although they had genuine Russian passports with the identities of Alexander Petrov and Ruslan Boshirov when applying for visas and entering the UK. CPS said there was enough evidence to charge the men, but is not applying to Russia for the [[extradition]] of the two suspects. [[Interpol Red Notice]]s and domestic and [[European Arrest Warrant]]s were issued in case the suspects travel to the [[EU]].<ref name=\"BBCnames\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-45421445|title=Salisbury Novichok poisoning: Two Russian nationals named as suspects|date=5 September 2018|publisher=BBC News|access-date=5 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> As part of the announcement Scotland Yard and the [[Counter Terrorism Command]] released a detailed track of the individuals' 48 hours in the UK.<ref name=\"news-20180905\">{{cite web |url=http://news.met.police.uk/news/counter-terrorism-police-release-images-of-two-suspects-in-connection-with-salisbury-attack-320534 |title=Counter-terrorism police release images of two suspects in connection with Salisbury attack |publisher=Metropolitan Police |date=5 September 2018 |accessdate=9 September 2018}}</ref> This covered their arrival from Moscow in the UK at [[Gatwick Airport]], a trip to Salisbury by train the day before the attack, stated by police to be for [[reconnaissance]], a trip to Salisbury by train on the day of the attack, and return to Moscow via [[Heathrow Airport]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://home.bt.com/news/uk-news/novichock-suspects-the-48-hour-mission-to-kill-caught-on-camera-11364293544847|title=Novichok suspects \u2013 the 48-hour mission to kill caught on camera|date=5 September 2018|work=BT News|access-date=5 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT20180905\" /> The two men stayed both nights in the City Stay Hotel located next to [[Bow Church DLR station]] in [[Bow, London|Bow]] in the [[London Borough of Tower Hamlets]], East London. Novichok was found in their hotel room after police sealed it off on 4 May 2018. Neil Basu, National Lead for [[National Counter Terrorism Policing Network|Counter Terrorism Policing]] said that tests were carried out on their hotel room and it was \"deemed safe\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/russian-suspects-named-in-novichok-poisoning-probe-a3927811.html|title=Salisbury Novichok poisoning: Russian 'hit men' charged over nerve agent attack|date=5 September 2018|work=The Evening Standard|access-date=5 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/09/05/guests-two-star-london-hotel-salisbury-suspects-stayed-told/|title=Guests of two-star London hotel where Salisbury suspects stayed discover Novichok was found in bedroom|work=The Telegraph|access-date=5 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nBritish Prime Minister Theresa May announced in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|Commons]] the same day that British intelligence services had identified the two suspects as officers in the [[Main Intelligence Directorate|G. U. Intelligence Service]] (formerly known as GRU) and the assassination attempt was not a rogue operation and was \"almost certainly\" approved at a senior level of the Russian government.<ref name=\"BBCnames\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/09/05/russias-gru-murky-spy-agency-behind-salisbury-poisoning-failed/|title=Russia's GRU: The murky spy agency behind the Salisbury poisoning, a failed coup and US election hack|work=The Telegraph|access-date=5 September 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> May also said Britain will push for the EU to agree new sanctions against Russia.\n\nOn 5 September 2018, the Russian news site Fontanka reported that the numbers on leaked passport files for Petrov and Boshirov are only three digits apart, and fall in a range that includes the passport files for a Russian military official expelled from Poland for spying.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.fontanka.ru/2018/09/05/075/ |title=\u0427\u0442\u043e \"\u0424\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0435\" \u0438\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043d\u043e \u043e \u043f\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0437\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0430\u0435\u043c\u044b\u0445 \u0432 \u043e\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u0421\u043a\u0440\u0438\u043f\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0439 |trans-title=What \"Fontanka\" know about the suspected poisoning of the Skripals|last=\u0415\u0440\u043c\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432|first=\u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440|date=5 September 2018|work=Fontanka.ru|access-date=25 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.fontanka.ru/2018/09/22/009/|title=\u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043e \u0442\u0443\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e. \u041f\u043e\u0447\u0435\u043c\u0443 \u043a\u0442\u043e-\u0442\u043e \u043c\u043e\u0433 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u043d\u044f\u0442\u044c \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0438 \u0411\u043e\u0448\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0437\u0430 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0447\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432|last=\u0415\u0440\u043c\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432|first=\u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440|date=22 September 2018|work=Fontanka.ru|access-date=25 September 2018}}</ref> It is not known how the passport files were obtained, but Andrew Roth, the Moscow correspondent for ''[[The Guardian]]'', commented that \"If the reporting is confirmed, it would be a major blunder by the intelligence agency, allowing any country to check passport data for Russians requesting visas or entering the country against a list of nearly 40 passport files of suspected GRU officers.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/sep/23/russian-passport-leak-after-salisbury-may-reveal-spy-methods|title=Russian passport leak after Salisbury may reveal spy methods|last=Roth|first=Andrew|date=23 September 2018|website=The Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-09-25}}</ref> On 14 September 2018, the online platform [[Bellingcat]] and the Russian publication The Insider noted that in Petrov's leaked passport files, there is no record of a residential address or any identification papers prior to 2009, suggesting that the name is an alias created that year; the analysis also noted that Petrov's dossier is stamped \"Do not provide any information\" and has the handwritten annotation \"S.S.,\" a common abbreviation in Russian for \"top secret.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2018/09/14/skripal-poisoning-suspects-passport-data-shows-link-security-services/|title=Skripal Poisoning Suspect's Passport Data Shows Link to Security Services|date=14 September 2018|publisher=Bellingcat|access-date=25 September 2018}}</ref> On 15 September 2018, the Russian opposition newspaper ''[[Novaya Gazeta]]'' reported finding in Petrov's passport files a cryptic number that seems to be a [[Telephone numbers in Russia|telephone number]] associated with the [[Ministry of Defence (Russia)|Russian Defense Ministry]], most likely the Military Intelligence Directorate.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/18/world/europe/skripal-poisoning-russia.html|title=Tragedy? Farce? Confusion? The Method Behind That Russian Poisoning Interview |last=Higgins|first=Andrew|date=18 September 2018|work=New York Times|access-date=19 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 September 2018, the real identity of the suspect named by police as Ruslan Boshirov was revealed as [[Polkovnik|Colonel]] [[Anatoliy Vladimirovich Chepiga]] by ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', citing reporting by itself and Bellingcat, with Petrov having a more junior rank in the GRU.<ref>''Newsnight'', BBC2, 26 September 2018</ref> The 39-year-old was made a [[Hero of the Russian Federation]] by decree of the President in 2014. Two European security sources confirmed that the details were accurate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.trust.org//item/20180926171507-6mtxt/|title=Salisbury poisoning suspect named as a Russian colonel by UK media|publisher=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=26 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/09/26/revealed-battle-hardened-spetsnaz-brigade-special-forces-unit/|title=Revealed: The battle-hardened Spetsnaz Brigade special forces unit that trained Skripal 'hitman'|first1=Robert|last1=Mendick|first2=Hayley|last2=Dixon|date=26 September 2018|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=26 September 2018}}</ref> The BBC commented: \"The BBC understands there is no dispute over the identification.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-45656004|title=Skripal suspect 'real identity revealed'|date=26 September 2018|publisher=BBC|accessdate=26 September 2018}}</ref> The [[Secretary of State for Defence|British defense minister]] [[Gavin Williamson]] wrote: \"The true identity of one of the Salisbury suspects has been revealed to be a Russian Colonel. I want to thank all the people who are working so tirelessly on this case.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-russia-skripal-williamson/true-identity-of-salisbury-suspect-revealed-uk-defense-minister-says-idUSKCN1M62QG|title='True identity' of Salisbury suspect revealed, UK defense minister says |publisher=[[Reuters]]|date=26 September 2018|accessdate=26 September 2018}}</ref> However, that statement was subsequently deleted from Twitter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/anatoliy-chepiga-who-is-the-hero-russian-colonel-suspected-of-the-salisbury-attack-11509974|title=Anatoliy Chepiga: Who is the 'hero' Russian colonel suspected of the Salisbury attack?|publisher=Sky News|access-date=2018-10-03|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 October 2018, the real identity of the suspect named by police as Alexander Petrov was revealed as [[Alexander Mishkin|Dr. Alexander Mishkin]].<ref name=Mishkin/><ref name=\"Indy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/salisbury-attack-dr-alexander-mishkin-putin-handshake-russia-suspect-novichok-skripals-a8575846.html|title=Salisbury novichok suspect Dr Alexander Mishkin 'photographed shaking Vladimir Putin's hand'|work=Independent}}</ref><ref name=\"Mendick2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/10/09/russian-hitmans-grandmother-vanishes-telling-friends-putin-gave/|title=Russian spy's grandmother vanishes after telling friends Putin gave him a hero's medal|first1=Robert|last1=Mendick |first2=Alec|last2=Luhn|date=9 October 2018|work=Telegraph}}</ref><ref name=\"Goryashko\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-45799037|title=Novichok suspect traced to tiny village|first=Sergei Goryashko, Andrei Soshnikov and Andrei|last=Zakharov|date=9 October 2018|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 November 2018, more CCTV footage, with the two suspects walking in Salisbury, was published by the police.<ref>{{cite news |title=Skripal poisoning: CCTV shows suspects 'on way to victims' home' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/uk-46312222/skripal-poisoning-cctv-shows-suspects-on-way-to-victims-home |accessdate=23 November 2018 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 December 2018, Mishkin (a.k.a. Petrov) and Chepiga (a.k.a. Boshirov) were added to the sanctions list of [[United States Department of the Treasury|USA Treasury Department]] along with other 13 members of the GRU agency.<ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. targets GRU officers linked to hacking, Skripal poisoning with new sanctions |url=https://www.unian.info/world/10384068-u-s-targets-gru-officers-linked-to-hacking-skripal-poisoning-with-new-sanctions.html |accessdate=20 December 2018 |work=Unian |date=19 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Treasury Targets Russian Operatives over Election Interference, World Anti-Doping Agency Hacking, and Other Malign Activities|url=https://home.treasury.gov/news/press-releases/sm577|work=U. S. Department of the Treasury|date=19 December 2018|accessdate=20 December 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Notice of Intended Removals; Ukraine-/Russia-related Designations; Cyber-related Designations |url=https://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/OFAC-Enforcement/Pages/20181219_33.aspx|work=U. S. Department of the Treasury|date=19 December 2018|accessdate=20 December 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 January 2019, [[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] reported that the British authorities had established all the essential details of the assassination attempt, including the chain of command that leads up to [[Vladimir Putin]].<ref name=\"telegraph_06012019\">{{cite web|first=Robert |last=Mendick|title=How the UK joined the dots from Salisbury Novichok attack to Vladimir Putin|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/01/06/uk-joined-dots-salisbury-novichok-attack-vladimir-putin/|date=6 January 2019|work=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n==Response of the United Kingdom==\nWithin days of the attack, political pressure began to mount on [[Second May ministry|Theresa May's government]] to take action against the perpetrators, and most politicians appeared to believe that the Russian government was behind the attack.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43367515 Russian spy: May under pressure to take firm action] BBC, 12 March 2018.</ref><ref name=\"ftunanswered\">Neil Buckley, David Bond, Henry Foy. [https://www.ft.com/content/c713dd5e-238b-11e8-ae48-60d3531b7d11 The unanswered questions over the attack on a Russian double agent] ''Financial Times'', 9 March 2018 (print edition of 10 March 2018)</ref> The situation was additionally sensitive for Russia as Russian president Vladimir Putin was facing his [[2018 Russian presidential election|fourth presidential election]] in mid-March, and Russia was to host the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] football competition in June.<ref name=\"ftunanswered\" /><ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/theresa-may-vladimir-putin-russia-spy-attack-novichok-nerve-agent-sergei-skripal-yulia-salisbury-a8252741.html Russia spy attack: Theresa May has tried to back Vladimir Putin into a corner \u2013 the Kremlin will kick back] The Independent, 12 March 2018.</ref> When giving a response to an urgent question from [[Tom Tugendhat]], the chairman of the [[Foreign Affairs Select Committee]] of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]], who suggested that Moscow was conducting \"a form of soft war against the West\", Foreign Secretary [[Boris Johnson]] on 6 March said the government would \"respond appropriately and robustly\" if the Russian state was found to have been involved in the poisoning.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/mar/06/boris-johnson-uk-will-respond-robustly-if-russia-poisoned-spy Boris Johnson: UK will respond robustly if Russia poisoned spy] The Guardian, 6 March 2018.</ref><ref>[https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2018-03-06/debates/E416F6C5-50D9-47FF-8C3E-0946CE99E6CA/GovernmentPolicyOnRussia Government Policy on Russia] House of Commons Hansard, 6 March 2018.</ref> UK Home Secretary [[Amber Rudd]] said on 8 March 2018 that the use of a nerve agent on UK soil was a \"brazen and reckless act\" of attempted murder \"in the most cruel and public way\".<ref name=\"bbc43326734\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43326734 |title=Russian spy: Salisbury attack was 'brazen and reckless' |work=BBC News|date=8 March 2018 |accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nPrime Minister [[Theresa May]] said in the House of Commons on 12 March:\n{{quote|It is now clear that Mr Skripal and his daughter were poisoned with a military-grade nerve agent of a type developed by Russia. This is part of a group of nerve agents known as 'Novichok'. Based on the positive identification of this chemical agent by world-leading experts at the Defence Science and Technology Laboratory at Porton Down; our knowledge that Russia has previously produced this agent and would still be capable of doing so; Russia's record of conducting state-sponsored assassinations; and our assessment that Russia views some defectors as legitimate targets for assassinations; the Government has concluded that it is highly likely that Russia was responsible for the act against Sergei and Yulia Skripal. Mr Speaker, there are therefore only two plausible explanations for what happened in Salisbury on 4 March. Either this was a direct act by the Russian State against our country. Or the Russian government lost control of this potentially catastrophically damaging nerve agent and allowed it to get into the hands of others.<ref name=\"mayspeech12march\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/pm-commons-statement-on-salisbury-incident-12-march-2018|title=PM Commons statement on Salisbury incident: 12 March 2018|publisher=Government of the United Kingdom|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref>}}\n\nMay also said that the UK government requested that Russia explain which of these two possibilities it was by the end of 13 March 2018.<ref name=\"mayspeech12march\" /> She also said: \"[T]he extra-judicial killing of terrorists and dissidents outside Russia were given legal sanction by the Russian Parliament in 2006. And of course Russia used radiological substances in its barbaric [[Poisoning of Alexander Litvinenko|assault on Mr Litvinenko]].\"&nbsp; She said that the UK government would \"consider in detail the response from the Russian State\" and in the event that there was no credible response, the government would \"conclude that this action amounts to an unlawful use of force by the Russian State against the United Kingdom\" and measures would follow.<ref name=\"mayspeech12march\"/> British media billed the statement as \"Theresa May's ultimatum to Putin.\"<ref name=\"Guardian May\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2018/03/12/russia-could-target-england-fans-world-cup-uk-retaliates-salisbury/|title=Theresa May's ultimatum to Vladimir Putin: Russian leader given 24 hours to answer for nerve agent attack on spy|last=Rayner|first=Gordon|date=12 March 2018|work=The Telegraph|access-date=15 March 2018|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March 2018, UK Home Secretary [[Amber Rudd]] ordered an inquiry by the police and security services into alleged Russian state involvement in 14 previous suspicious deaths of Russian exiles and businessmen in the UK.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/13/amber-rudd-orders-inquiry-into-russia-linked-deaths-in-uk Amber Rudd orders inquiry into Russia-linked deaths in UK: Home secretary responds to calls to examine alleged Russian involvement in up to 14 deaths] ''The Guardian'', 13 March 2018.</ref>\n\nPrime Minister May unveiled a series of measures on 14 March 2018 in retaliation for the poisoning attack, after the Russian government refused to meet the UK's request for an account of the incident. One of the chief measures was the expulsion of 23 Russian diplomats which she presented as \"actions to dismantle the Russian espionage network in the UK\", as these diplomats had been identified by the UK as \"undeclared intelligence agents\".<ref name=\"maydismantle\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/theresa-may-russian-spy-network-expel-diplomats-cold-war-a8256411.html Russian spy incident: Theresa May moves to dismantle Russian spy 'network' expelling 23 diplomats: Defence Secretary Gavin Williamson will announce new investment in chemical weapons facilities in the wake of the Salisbury attack] The Independent, 15 March 2018.</ref><ref name=\"russthreatretal\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/14/may-expels-23-russian-diplomats-response-spy-poisoning|title=Russia threatens retaliation after Britain expels 23 diplomats|last1=Stewart|first1=Heather|last2=Walker|first2=Peter|last3=Borger|first3=Julian|date=14 March 2018|work=The Guardian}}</ref> The BBC reported other responses, including:<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-43402506|title=UK to expel 23 Russian diplomats|date=14 March 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-43380378|title=How is the UK retaliating against Russia?|date=14 March 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref>\n* Increasing checks on private flights, customs and freight\n* Freezing Russian state assets where there is evidence that they may be used to threaten the life or property of UK nationals or residents\n* Plans to consider new laws to increase defences against \"hostile state activity\"\n* Ministers and the [[British royal family]] boycotting the 2018 FIFA World Cup in Russia\n* Suspending all high-level bilateral contacts between the UK and Russia\n* Retraction of the state invitation to Russian's foreign minister [[Sergey Lavrov]]<ref name=\"BBC20180405\" />\n* A new \u00a348-million chemical weapons defence centre<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-43405686|title=UK to build new chemical defence centre|date=15 March 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=15 March 2018|quote=UK Defence Secretary Gavin Williamson ... said the UK leads the world in research into chemical, biological and radiological warfare but said this expertise needed to be developed further to confront potential hostile activity by states and individuals.}}</ref>\n* Offering voluntary vaccinations against [[anthrax]] to British troops who are held at high readiness so that they are ready to deploy to areas where there is risk of this type of attack<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-43405686|title=Defence secretary tells Russia: Shut up|date=15 March 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref>\nThe Prime Minister said that some measures which the government planned could \"not be shared publicly for reasons of national security\".<ref name=\"maydismantle\"/> [[Jeremy Corbyn]] cast doubt in his parliamentary response to May's statement concerning blaming the attack on Russia prior to the results of an independent investigation, which provoked criticism from some MPs, including members of his own party.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/jeremy-corbyn-russia-spy-poisoning-response-mps-furious-sailsbury-sergei-skripal-a8255731.html Russian spy poisoning: Furious MPs condemn Jeremy Corbyn's response to statement on Sailsbury attack: Labour leader accused of 'policy of appeasement' after refusing to directly blame Russia for poisoning former spy] The Independent, 14 March 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-43405680 Russian spy: Jeremy Corbyn aide queries proof of Russian guilt] BBC, 14 March 2018.</ref> A few days later, Corbyn was satisfied that the evidence pointed to Russia.<ref>BBC, '[https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/jeremy-corbyn-sergei-skripal-theresa-may-novichok-russia-spy-poisoning-moscow-a8288826.html Jeremy Corbyn was right to be cautious about blaming Moscow for the Skripal poisoning']' (15 March 2018)</ref> He supported the expulsion but argued that a crackdown on [[money laundering]] by UK financial firms on behalf of [[Russian oligarch]]s would be a more effective measure against \"the Putin regime\" than the Tory government's plans.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/mar/15/corbyn-defies-critics-calls-for-calm-over-russia-nerve-agent-attack|title=Jeremy Corbyn defies critics and calls for calm over Russia|date=15 March 2018|work=The Guardian}}</ref> Corbyn pointed to the pre-[[Iraq War]] judgements about [[Iraq and weapons of mass destruction]] as reason to be suspicious.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/jeremy-corbyn-russia-spy-nerve-agent-iraq-war-wmd-labour-theresa-may-a8256021.html \"Jeremy Corbyn points to Iraq WMDs mistake as he casts doubt on Russian culpability for nerve agent attack\"], ''The Independent'', 15 March 2018.</ref>\n\nThe [[United Nations Security Council]] called an urgent meeting on 14 March 2018 on the initiative of the UK to discuss the Salisbury incident.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-russia-un/uk-calls-for-urgent-u-n-security-council-meeting-over-nerve-attack-idUSKCN1GQ1I5 UK calls for urgent U.N. Security Council meeting over nerve attack] Reuters, 14 March 2018.</ref><ref name=\"unsc-20180314\">{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/press/en/2018/sc13247.doc.htm |title=Moscow 'Highly Likely' Behind Salisbury Chemical Attack, Prime Minister of United Kingdom Says in Letter to Security Council \u2013 Russian Federation Calls Statement Irresponsible, Threatening |id=SC/13247 |publisher=United Nations |date=14 March 2018 |accessdate=9 April 2018}}</ref> According to the Russian mission's press secretary, the draft press statement introduced by Russia at the United Nations Security Council meeting was blocked by the UK.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tass.com/politics/994184 |title=UK blocks Russia-initiated UNSC statement on Skripal incident|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 15 March 2018 |website=TASS.com |access-date= 6 September 2018}}</ref> The UK and the US blamed Russia for the incident during the meeting, with the UK accusing Russia of breaking its obligations under the [[Chemical Weapons Convention]].<ref>[https://www.ft.com/content/135d21d0-27c3-11e8-b27e-cc62a39d57a0 US blames Russia for Skripal attack, in \u2018absolute solidarity\u2019 with UK], ''Financial Times'', 14 March 2018.</ref> Separately, the White House fully supported the UK in attributing the attack to Russia, as well as the punitive measures taken against Russia. The White House also accused Russia of undermining the security of countries worldwide.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43411332 Russian spy: White House backs UK decision to expel diplomats] BBC, 15 March 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/statement-press-secretary-united-kingdoms-decision-expel-russian-diplomats/ Statement by the Press Secretary on the United Kingdom's Decision to Expel Russian Diplomats] The White House, 14 March 2018.</ref>\n\nThe UK, and subsequently [[NATO]], requested Russia provide \"full and complete disclosure\" of the Novichok programme to the [[Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/organisation-for-the-prohibition-of-chemical-weapons-87th-executive-council-session-statement-on-the-salisbury-incident|title=Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons 87th Executive Council session: statement on the Salisbury incident|publisher=Government of the United Kingdom|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/news_152787.htm|title=Statement by the North Atlantic Council on the use of a nerve agent in Salisbury|last=NATO|website=NATO|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-russia-nato/nato-calls-on-russia-to-give-full-details-on-nerve-agent-program-idUSKCN1GQ1O1|title=NATO calls on Russia to give full details on nerve agent program|date=14 March 2018|agency=Reuters|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref> On 14 March 2018, the government stated it would supply a sample of the substance used to the [[Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons]] once UK legal obligations from the criminal investigation permitted.<ref name=\"opcw-20180314\">{{cite web |url=https://www.opcw.org/fileadmin/OPCW/EC/87/en/UK_Statement_EC-87.pdf |title=Update on the use of Nerve Agent in Salisbury, United Kingdom |last=Wilson |first=Peter |publisher=Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons |date=14 March 2018 |accessdate=16 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nBritish foreign secretary Boris Johnson said on 16 March that it was \"overwhelmingly likely\" that the poisoning had been ordered directly by Russian president Putin, which marked the first time the British government accused Vladimir Putin of personally ordering the poisoning.<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/world-news/europe/putin-personally-ordered-attack-on-spy-says-uk-36714143.html Putin personally ordered attack on spy, says UK] The Independent, 17 March 2018.</ref> According to the [[UK Foreign Office]], the UK attributed the attack to Russia based on [[Porton Down]]'s determination that the chemical was Novichok, additional intelligence, and a lack of alternative explanations from Russia.<ref>{{cite web |last=Waugh |first=Paul |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/boris-johnson-under-fire-over-salisbury-russia-claim-as-foreign-office-tweet-blaming-moscow-deleted-russian-embassy_uk_5ac4b1efe4b063ce2e5799c7 |title=Johnson Under Fire As Foreign Office Deletes Russia Tweet |date=4 April 2018 |work=HuffPost |accessdate=4 April 2018 |quote=The Foreign Secretary was making clear that Porton Down were sure it was a Novichok \u2013 a point they have reinforced. He goes on in the same interview to make clear why based on that information, additional intelligence and the lack of alternative explanation from the Russians, we have reached the conclusion we have.}}</ref> The [[Defence Science and Technology Laboratory]] announced that it was \"completely confident\" that the agent used was Novichok, but they still did not know the \"precise source\" of the agent.<ref name=\"Laschet\">\"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-russia-salisbury-nerve-agent-porton-down-diane-abbot-moscow-sergei-skripal-a8287696.html Labour says it deserves 'credit' for questioning if Russia was to blame for Salisbury nerve agent]\". ''The Independent''. 4 April 2018.</ref><ref name=wp-20180404/>\n\nThe UK had held an intelligence briefing with its allies in which it stated that the Novichok chemical used in the Salisbury poisoning was produced at a chemical facility in the town of [[Shikhany]], [[Saratov Oblast]], Russia.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-russia-skripal-nerveagent/agent-used-in-salisbury-made-at-russias-shikhany-military-research-base-times-idUSKCN1HC2WE|title=Agent used in Salisbury made at Russia's Shikhany military research base: Times|date=6 April 2018 |work=Reuters}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a government source, in April 2018 the UK refused to grant a visa to Yulia's cousin, Viktoria Skripal, to visit her, saying that it appears Russia is \"trying to use Viktoria as a pawn\".<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\n== Response of Russia ==\n\n=== Russian government ===\nOn 6 March 2018 [[Andrey Lugovoy]], [[Member of Parliament|deputy]] of Russia's [[State Duma]] (the [[Liberal Democratic Party of Russia]]) and alleged killer of [[Alexander Litvinenko]], in his interview with the [[Echo of Moscow]] said: \"Something constantly happens to Russian citizens who either run away from Russian justice, or for some reason choose for themselves a way of life they call a change of their Motherland. So the more Britain accepts on its territory every good-for-nothing, every scum from all over the world, the more problems they will have.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Knight|first1=Amy|title=Vladimir Putin's Re-Election Strategy: Nukes and Assassins|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/vladimir-putins-re-election-strategy-nukes-and-assassins?ref=scroll|accessdate=8 March 2018|work=Daily Beast}}</ref><ref>[https://echo.msk.ru/programs/beseda/2160198-echo/ \u041e\u0431 \u043e\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u044f \u0421\u043a\u0440\u0438\u043f\u0430\u043b\u044f] [[Echo of Moscow]], 6 March 2018.</ref>\n\nRussian Foreign Minister [[Sergey Lavrov]] on 9 March rejected Britain's claim of Russia's involvement in Skripal's poisoning and accused the United Kingdom of spreading \"propaganda\".<ref>\"[https://www.cnbc.com/2018/03/09/russia-lavrov-says-uk-is-spreading-propaganda-over-spy-poisoning.html Russia says London spreading propaganda over spy poisoning]\". CNBC. 11 March 2018.</ref><ref>\"[https://themoscowtimes.com/news/russia-says-london-spreading-propaganda-over-spy-poisoning-60758 Russia Says London Spreading Propaganda Over Spy Poisoning]\". ''[[The Moscow Times]]''. 9 March 2018.</ref> Lavrov said that Russia was \"ready to cooperate\" and demanded access to the samples of the nerve-agent which was used to poison Skripal. The request was rejected by the British government.<ref>\"[https://www.ndtv.com/world-news/russia-rejects-britains-ultimatum-wants-access-to-nerve-agent-1823359?ndtv_nextstory Russia Says \"Not Guilty\" Of Ex-Spy Poisoning As UK Deadline Looms]\". [[NDTV]]. 13 March 2018.</ref>\n\nFollowing Theresa May's 12 March statement in Parliament \u2013 in which she gave President Putin's administration until midnight of the following day to explain how a former spy was poisoned in Salisbury, otherwise she would conclude it was an \"unlawful use of force\" by the Russian state against the UK<ref>\"[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/12/russia-highly-likely-to-be-behind-poisoning-of-spy-says-theresa-may Russian spy poisoning: Theresa May issues ultimatum to Moscow]\". ''The Guardian''. 13 March 2018.</ref> \u2013 Russian foreign minister Sergey Lavrov, talking to the Russian press on 13 March, referred to the statement as \"an ultimatum from London\" and endorsed remarks made by the ministry's spokesperson the day prior, who called May's statement \"a circus show in the British parliament\";<ref name=\"lavrovotvet\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newsru.com/russia/13mar2018/lavrov.html|title=\u041b\u0430\u0432\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0438\u043b \u043d\u0430&nbsp; \u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0443\u043c \u041c\u044d\u0439&nbsp; \u0441\u0441\u044b\u043b\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043d\u0430&nbsp; &nbsp;\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0432\u0435\u043d\u0446\u0438\u044e \u043e&nbsp; \u0445\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0438\u0438|work=NEWSru.com|access-date=15 March 2018|language=Russian}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newsru.com/russia/12mar2018/midmay.html|script-title=ru:\u0412 \u041c\u0418\u0414 \u0420\u0424 \u0437\u0430\u044f\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u041c\u044d\u0439 \u043e \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u043a \u043e\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044e \u0421\u043a\u0440\u0438\u043f\u0430\u043b\u044f \u0441\u043e\u0447\u043b\u0438 \"\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0437\u043a\u0430\u043c\u0438\" \u0438 \"\u0446\u0438\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432\u044b\u043c \u0448\u043e\u0443\"|work=NEWSru.com |access-date=15 March 2018|language=Russian}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/russia-theresa-mays-comments-on-salisbury-spy-a-circus-show-11287517|title=Russia: Theresa May's comments on Salisbury spy a 'circus show'|publisher=Sky News|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref> he added that the procedure stipulated by the [[Chemical Weapons Convention]] should be followed whereunder Russia was entitled to have access to the substance in question and 10 days to respond.<ref name=\"lavrovotvet\" /><ref>\"[https://www.channelstv.com/2018/03/13/russia-rejects-britains-ultimatum-wants-access-to-nerve-agent/ Russia Rejects Britain\u2019s Ultimatum, Wants Access To Nerve Agent]\". Channels TV. 13 March 2018.</ref><ref name=\"guarddemands\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/13/russia-demands-nerve-agent-samples-uk-deadline-spy-poisoning|title=Russia demands nerve agent samples in standoff with UK over poisoned spy|last=Roth|first=Andrew|date=13 March 2018|website=The Guardian|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref> He called allegations about Russia's complicity \"balderdash\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/russian/news-43385817|script-title=ru:\u041b\u0430\u0432\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u043e \u0434\u0435\u043b\u0435 \u0421\u043a\u0440\u0438\u043f\u0430\u043b\u044f: \u0411\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043d\u0435 \u0441\u043e\u0431\u043b\u044e\u0434\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u043c\u0435\u0436\u0434\u0443\u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043d\u043e\u0440\u043c\u044b|date=13 March 2018|publisher=BBC \u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430|access-date=15 March 2018|language=Russian}}</ref> The Russian foreign ministry spokesperson, speaking on a Russian state television channel on the evening of 13 March, said that no one had the right to present Russia with 24-hour ultimatums.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tass.ru/politika/5027376|script-title=ru:\u0417\u0430\u0445\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430: \u043d\u0438\u043a\u0442\u043e \u043d\u0435 \u043c\u043e\u0436\u0435\u0442 \u0432\u044b\u0434\u0432\u0438\u0433\u0430\u0442\u044c \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 24-\u0447\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0435 \u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0443\u043c\u044b|agency=\u0422\u0410\u0421\u0421|access-date=15 March 2018|language=ru}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tass.com/politics/993859|title=No one can deliver any 24-hour ultimatums to Russia \u2013 Foreign Ministry spokeswoman|agency=TASS|access-date=15 March 2018|language=ru}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=60 \u043c\u0438\u043d\u0443\u0442. \u042d\u0444\u0438\u0440 \u043e\u0442 13.03.2018 (19:00). \u041e\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0421\u043a\u0440\u0438\u043f\u0430\u043b\u044f: \u0434\u043e\u0439\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u043b\u0438 \u0434\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0440\u044b\u0432\u0430 \u0434\u0438\u043f\u043e\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0441 \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435\u0439|url=https://russia.tv/video/show/brand_id/60851/episode_id/1719029/|language=ru|accessdate=15 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, Russia announced that it was expelling 23 British diplomats and ordered the closure of the UK's [[Consulate-General of the United Kingdom, Saint Petersburg|consulate in St Petersburg]] and the [[British Council]] office in Moscow, stopping all British Council activities in Russia.<ref name=\"indeprusexp\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/russia-spy-poison-british-diplomats-expelled-sergei-skripal-nerve-agent-a8260671.html \"Russia expels 23 British diplomats in retaliation as diplomatic spat over Sergei Skripal poisoning intensifies\"], ''The Independent'', 17 March 2018.</ref>\n\nThe poisoning has been officially declared to be a fabrication and a \"grotesque provocation rudely staged by the British and U.S. intelligence agencies\" to undermine Russia.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/russia-points-finger-at-uk-and-us-agencies-over-poisoning/2018/04/04/94f984ea-37e0-11e8-af3c-2123715f78df_story.html UK rejects joint probe with Russia into spy poisoning] The Washington Post, 4 April 2018.</ref><ref>[https://iz.ru/728161/2018-04-04/naryshkin-nazval-delo-skripalia-grotesknoi-provokatciei-britanii-i-ssha \u041d\u0430\u0440\u044b\u0448\u043a\u0438\u043d \u043d\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0430\u043b \u00ab\u0434\u0435\u043b\u043e \u0421\u043a\u0440\u0438\u043f\u0430\u043b\u044f\u00bb \u0433\u0440\u043e\u0442\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0435\u0439 \u0411\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u0438 \u0421\u0428\u0410] [[Izvestia]], 4 April 2018.</ref><ref name=\"RT News\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/uk/422911-uk-staged-skripal-poisoning-theory|title=UK may have staged Skripal poisoning to rally people against Russia, Moscow believes}}</ref><ref name=\"DailyStar\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dailystar.co.uk/news/latest-news/693066/russia-spy-poisoning-britain-vladimir-putin-sergei-skripal-war-mi6-salisbury-uk-evidence|title=Russia claims Britain 'STAGED poisoning of Skripal to turn people against Putin'|date=1 April 2018|work=Daily Star}}</ref><ref name=\"RT News-UK Fabricated\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/news/422871-russia-questions-uk-skripal-case|title=Moscow confronts London with 14 questions on 'fabricated' Skripal case|publisher=RT}}</ref>\n\nThe Russian government and [[Embassy of Russia, London|embassy of Russia in the United Kingdom]] have repeatedly requested access to the Skripals, and have sought to offer consular assistance. These requests and offers have been denied or declined.<ref name=\"tass0409\">{{cite news|url=https://tass.com/politics/1019919|title=Russian embassy comments on Scripal case|agency=TASS|date=4 September 2018|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/jun/07/putin-demands-russian-consular-access-to-yulia-skripal|title=Putin demands Russian consular access to Yulia Skripal|newspaper=The Guardian|date=7 June 2018|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/03/31/russia-demands-know-has-denied-access-skripals/|title=Russia demands to know why it has been denied access to the Skripals|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=31 March 2018|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/31/foreign-office-considers-russian-consular-access-to-yulia-skripal|title=Foreign Office considers Russian consular access to Yulia Skripal|newspaper=The Guardian|date=31 March 2018|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/yulia-skripal-russian-embassy-uk-consular-access-salisbury-poisoning-spy-a8255071.html|title=Yulia Skripal: Russian embassy 'to ask UK for consular access to daughter of poisoned spy'|newspaper=The Independent|date=14 March 2018|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn September, Russia described the Skripals' situation as \"de-facto deprivation of liberty\", claiming that several diplomatic and human rights conventions were violated.<ref name=tass0409 /> On 5 September the Russian government rejected the accusations \"against Russia and two allegedly Russian citizens.\"<ref name=\"mid-20180905\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mid.ru/en/foreign_policy/news/-/asset_publisher/cKNonkJE02Bw/content/id/3337611 |title=Russian Foreign Ministry Statement |publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation |date=5 September 2018 |accessdate=9 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 September 2018 the Press Secretary for the President of Russia, [[Dmitry Peskov]], stated that May's accusations from that day were \"unacceptable\". Peskov asserted Russia had not received any official request from Britain for assistance in identifying the two suspected Russian GRU military intelligence officers that Scotland Yard believes carried out the Skripal attack. The same day, the [[Foreign Ministry of Russia]] asserted that [[List of ambassadors of the United Kingdom to Russia|UK ambassador in Moscow]], [[Laurie Bristow]], had said that London would not provide Russia with the suspects' fingerprints, passport numbers, visa numbers, or any extra data.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://tass.com/politics/1020130|title=London declines to provide fingerprints of suspects in Skripal case \u2013 Foreign Ministry|agency=TASS|date=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 September 2018, President Putin, while answering questions at the plenary meeting of the 4th [[Eastern Economic Forum]] in [[Russian Far East|Russia's Far Eastern]] [[port city]] of [[Vladivostok]] said that the identities of both men London suspected of involvement in the Skripal case were known to the Russian authorities and that both were civilians, who had done nothing criminal. He also said he would like the men to come forward to tell their story.<ref>[http://tass.com/world/1021524 Skripal suspects expressed their opinion, but this does not put lid on case]. TASS, 13 September 2018</ref><ref>[https://www.memri.org/reports/russia-week-%E2%80%93-focus-skripal-case-%E2%80%93-september-16-2018 Russia This Week \u2013 Focus On The Skripal Case]. MEMRI Russian Media Studies Project, Special Dispatch No.7673, 16 September 2018</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Skripal poisoning: Putin says suspects 'civilians, not criminals' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-45494627 |accessdate=12 September 2018 |publisher=BBC News |date=12 September 2018}}</ref> In a 13 September 2018 interview on the state-funded television channel RT, the accused claimed to be sports nutritionists who had gone to Salisbury merely to see the sights and scout for nutrition products, saying that they took a second day-trip to Salisbury because slush had dampened their first one.<ref name=\"Higgins\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/13/world/europe/russia-salisbury-skripal-novichok.html|title=We Were Tourists, Not Assassins, Novichok Attack Suspects Say|last=Higgins|first=Andrew|date=13 September 2018|work=New York Times|access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 September, [[Sergey Lavrov|Lavrov]] stated: \"Our proposal of putting into operation existing mechanisms between London and Moscow on the legal assistance in criminal cases is still in force. Since there is no response to our proposal, we have all grounds to believe that there had been no crime, which these ladies and gentlemen are trying to attribute to our citizens.\"<ref>[http://tass.com/politics/1021708 Lavrov blasts London\u2019s reaction to interview with Skripal case suspects as illogical]. TASS, 14 September 2018</ref> On 26 September, the same day one of the suspects was identified as the Colonel of GRU, Lavrov once again urged the British authorities to cooperate in the investigation of the case, said Britain had given no proof of Russia's guilt and suggested that Britain had something to hide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/video/world/lavrov-does-britain-have-something-to-hide-about-novichok-attack/2018/09/26/3d50f320-c1ad-11e8-9451-e878f96be19b_video.html|title=Lavrov: Does Britain 'have something to hide' about Novichok attack?|website=Washington Post|accessdate=27 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Barry |first1=Ellen |title=Russian Officer Is Named as Suspect in Salisbury Poisoning |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/26/world/europe/uk-skripal-suspect.html |accessdate=27 September 2018 |work=The New York Times |date=26 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 September, the Russian [[Federal Security Service|FSB]] began searching for [[Ministry of Internal Affairs (Russia)|Ministry of Internal Affairs (MVD)]] officers who had provided journalists with foreign passport and flight information about the suspects.<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u0421\u043b\u0438\u0432 \u0434\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445: \u0424\u0421\u0411 \u043e\u0442\u043e\u043c\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442 \u0437\u0430 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0438 \u0411\u043e\u0448\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430|url=https://www.gazeta.ru/social/2018/09/25/11996089.shtml|work=\u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430.Ru|accessdate=27 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Russian state media===\nFor a few days following the poisoning, the story was discussed by web sites, radio stations and newspapers, but Russian state-run main national TV channels largely ignored the incident.<ref name=\"radiolibwarn\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/russia-skripal-poisoning-russia-tv-warning-traitors-kleimenov/29087407.html|title=Russian State TV Host Warns 'Traitors' After Skripal Poisoning|publisher=[[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]]|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-43330498|title=Russian state TV anchor warns 'traitors'|date=8 March 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nEventually, on 7 March, anchor [[Kirill Kleimyonov]] of the state television station [[Channel One Russia]]'s current affairs programme ''[[Vremya]]'' mentioned the incident by attributing the allegation to foreign secretary [[Boris Johnson]].<ref name=\"1tvkleim\" /> After speaking of Boris Johnson disparagingly, Kleimyonov said that being \"a traitor to the motherland\" was one of the most hazardous professions and warned: \"Don't choose England as a next country to live in. Whatever the reasons, whether you're a professional traitor to the motherland or you just hate your country in your spare time, I repeat, no matter, don't move to England. Something is not right there. Maybe it's the climate, but in recent years there have been too many strange incidents with a grave outcome. People get hanged, poisoned, they die in helicopter crashes and fall out of windows in industrial quantities.\"<ref name=\"1tvkleim\">{{Citation|script-title=ru:\u0413\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0430 \u041c\u0418\u0414 \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441 \u0414\u0436\u043e\u043d\u0441\u043e\u043d \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0438\u043b, \u0447\u0442\u043e \u0437\u0430 \u043e\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435\u043c \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u044f \u0421\u043a\u0440\u0438\u043f\u0430\u043b\u044f \u0441\u0442\u043e\u0438\u0442 \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430.|url=https://www.1tv.ru/news/2018-03-07/342100-glava_mid_velikobritanii_boris_dzhonson_predpolozhil_chto_za_otravleniem_sergeya_skripalya_stoit_moskva|website=[[Channel One Russia]]|language=ru-RU|date=7 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/mar/09/russian-state-tv-warns-traitors-not-to-settle-in-england|title=Russian state TV warns 'traitors' not to settle in England|last=Bennetts|first=Marc|date=9 March 2018|website=The Guardian|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/video/News/sergei-skripal-russian-state-tv-anchor-kirill-kleimenov-rare-traitors-live-old-age-a8246666.html|title=Russian state TV anchor says it is 'rare that traitors live to old age'|date=8 March 2018|work=The Independent|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"radiolibwarn\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/mar/06/boris-johnson-uk-will-respond-robustly-if-russia-poisoned-spy|title=Boris Johnson: UK will respond robustly if Russia poisoned spy|last=Elgot|first=Jessica|date=6 March 2018|website=The Guardian|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref> Kleimyonov's commentary was accompanied by a report highlighting previous suspicious Russia-related deaths in the UK, namely those of financier [[Alexander Perepilichny]], businessman [[Boris Berezovsky (businessman)|Boris Berezovsky]], ex-FSB officer [[Alexander Litvinenko]] and radiation expert Matthew Puncher.<ref name=\"1tvkleim\" /> Puncher discovered that [[Poisoning of Alexander Litvinenko|Litvinenko was poisoned]] by [[polonium]]; he died in 2006, five months after a trip to Russia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/list-alleged-russian-assassinations-in-britain-litvinenko-2018-3|title=All the times Russia allegedly carried out assassinations on British soil|work=Business Insider|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe host of the ''[[Vesti (VGTRK)|Vesti Nedeli]]'' on Russian state television ([[Russia-1]] channel of [[All-Russia State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company|VGTRK]]), [[Dmitry Kiselyov]], said on 11 March that the poisoning of Sergei Skripal, who was \"completely wrung out and of little interest\" as a source, was only advantageous to the British to \"nourish [[Anti-Russian sentiment#United Kingdom|their Russophobia]]\" and [[List of 2018 FIFA World Cup controversies#UK government boycott|organise the boycott]] of the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|FIFA World Cup]] scheduled for June 2018. Kiselyov referred to London as a \"pernicious place for Russian exiles\".<ref name=\"vestikisel\">[https://xn--b1agj9af.xn--80aswg/video/-rossija-1/vesti-nedeli-s-dmitriem-kiselevym-ot-11--35-41.html \u0412\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u043d\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0438 \u0441 \u0414\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0435\u043c \u041a\u0438\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0432\u044b\u043c \u043e\u0442 11.03.18] (the relevant footage begins at 1:27:20), ''[[Vesti (VGTRK)|Vesti Nedeli]]'', 11 March 2018.</ref><ref name=\"moscowtimes\">[https://themoscowtimes.com/news/britain-poisoned-double-agent-skripal-to-nourish-russophobia-russian-state-media-60769 Britain Poisoned Double Agent Skripal to 'Nourish Russophobia' \u2014 Russian State Media] [[The Moscow Times]], 12 March 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-russia-plot/russian-state-tv-accuses-britain-of-poisoning-spy-in-special-operation-idUSKCN1GO15H Russian state TV accuses Britain of poisoning spy in special operation] Reuters, 12 March 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.buzzfeed.com/patricksmith/the-russian-embassy-in-london-has-accused-the-uk-of-an-anti Russia Wants Samples Of The Nerve Agent Believed To Have Poisoned A Former Russian Spy And His Daughter] Buzzfeed.com, 12 March 2018.</ref>\n\nThe prominent Russian television hosts' warnings to Russians living in the UK were echoed by a similar direct warning from a senior member of the [[Federation Council (Russia)|Russian Federation Council]], [[:ru:\u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0432, \u0410\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0435\u0439 \u0410\u0440\u043a\u0430\u0434\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447|Andrey Klimov]], who said: \"It's going to be very unsafe for you.\"<ref name=\"guarddemands\" />\n\nClaims made by Russian media were fact-checked by UK media organisations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-43835774|title=Reality Check: Russian TV's claims about Salisbury attack|last=Kuzmenkova|first=Olga|date=22 April 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=23 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.channel4.com/news/factcheck/long-read-does-the-uks-case-against-russia-stack-up|title=Long read: Does the UK's case against Russia stack up?|work=Channel 4 News|access-date=23 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nAn interview with two men claiming to be the suspects named by the UK was aired on [[RT (TV network)|RT]] on 13 September 2018 with RT editor [[Margarita Simonyan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AczGFsnNKRA|title=Suspects: We went to Salisbury as tourists to see the cathedral|quote=UK's suspects in the Skripal case talk exclusively with RT's editor-in-chief.|last=RT UK|date=13 September 2018|accessdate=15 October 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref> They said they were ordinary tourists who had wished to see [[Stonehenge]], [[Old Sarum]], and the \"famous ... 123-metre spire\" of [[Salisbury Cathedral]]. They also said that they \"maybe approached Skripal's house, but we didn't know where it was located,\" and denied using Novichok, which they had allegedly transported in a fake perfume bottle, saying, \"Is it silly for decent lads to have women's perfume? The customs are checking everything, they would have questions as to why men have women's perfume in their luggage.\"<ref name=\"Roth Dodd\">{{cite news |last1=Roth |first1=Andrew |last2=Dodd |first2=Vikram |title=Salisbury novichok suspects say they were only visiting cathedral |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/sep/13/russian-television-channel-rt-says-it-is-to-air-interview-with-skripal-salisbury-attack-suspects |accessdate=13 September 2018 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=13 September 2018}}</ref> Although Simonyan avoided most questions about the two men's backgrounds, she hinted that they might be gay by asking, \"All footage features you two together ... What do you have in common that you spend so much time together?\"<ref name=\"Roth Dodd\" /> ''[[The New York Times]]'' interpreted the hint by noting that \"The possibility that Mr. Petrov and Mr. Boshirov could be gay would, for a Russian audience, immediately rule out the possibility that they serve as military intelligence officers.\"<ref name=\"Higgins\" />\n\n==Chemical weapons experts and intelligence==\n\n===Porton Down===\nOn 3 April 2018 Gary Aitkenhead, the chief executive of the Government's [[Defence Science and Technology Laboratory]] (Dstl) at [[Porton Down]] responsible for testing the substance involved in the case, said they had established the agent was Novichok or from that family but had been unable to verify the \"precise source\" of the nerve agent and that they had \"provided the scientific info to Government who have then used a number of other sources to piece together the conclusions you have come to.\"<ref name=\"sky-20180403\">{{Cite AV media |url=https://twitter.com/SkyNews/status/981190172925616128/video/1 |title=Salisbury: 'Precise source' of nerve agent not known |people=Aitkenhead, Gary |publisher=Twitter |work=Sky News |type=full video interview [3mins 49sec] |date=3 April 2018 |accessdate=4 April 2018 |quote=[1m:24s] we have been able to establish it is Novichok or from that family ... [3m:26s] it is a military grade nerve agent which requires extremely sophisticated methods in order to create something that is probably only within the capabilities of a state actor}}</ref><ref name=\"sky-20180404\">{{cite news |url=https://news.sky.com/story/porton-down-experts-unable-to-identify-precise-source-of-novichok-that-poisoned-spy-11315387 |title=Porton Down experts unable to identify 'precise source' of novichok that poisoned spy |last=Kelso |first=Paul |publisher=Sky News |date=4 April 2018 |accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref> Aitkenhead refused to comment on whether the laboratory had developed or maintains stocks of Novichok.<ref name=sky-20180404/> He also dismissed speculations the substance could have come from Porton Down: \"There is no way anything like that could have come from us or left the four walls of our facility.\"<ref name=sky-20180404/> Aitkenhead stated the creation of the nerve agent was \"probably only within the capabilities of a state actor\" and there was no known antidote.<ref name=sky-20180403/><ref name=\"wp-20180404\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2018/04/04/britains-boris-johnson-accused-of-misleading-public-over-skripal-poisoning-evidence/ |title=Britain's Boris Johnson accused of misleading public over Skripal poisoning evidence |last=Taylor |first=Adam |newspaper=Washington Post |date=4 April 2018 |accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Former Russian scientists and intelligence officers===\n[[Vil Mirzayanov]], a former Soviet Union scientist who worked at the research institute that developed the Novichok class of nerve agents and lives in the United States, believes that hundreds of people could have been affected by residual contamination in Salisbury. He said that Sergei and Yulia Skripal, if poisoned with a Novichok, would be left with debilitating health issues for the rest of their lives. He also criticised the response of [[Public Health England]], saying that washing personal belongings was insufficient to remove traces of the chemical.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/russian-spy-attack-cure-nerve-agent-salisbury-poisoning-sergei-skripal-infection-risk-year-a8253771.html|title=Russian spy attack: Hundreds in Salisbury could be poisoned in years to come with 'no cure', says nerve agent developer|date=13 March 2018|accessdate=15 March 2018|work=Independent|author1=Deardon, Lizzie |author2=Sharman, Jon }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/russian/features-43429973|title=\u0412\u0438\u043b \u041c\u0438\u0440\u0437\u0430\u044f\u043d\u043e\u0432: \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0440\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u043a\u0430 \"\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0430\" \u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0433\u0434\u0430 \u043d\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0449\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0441\u044c|first=\u041d\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043b\u043a\u0430|last=\u041f\u0438\u0441\u043d\u044f|date=16 March 2018|publisher=BBC|access-date=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nTwo other Russian scientists who now live in Russia and have been involved in Soviet-era chemical weapons development, Vladimir Uglev and Leonid Rink, were quoted as saying that [[Novichok agent]]s had been developed in the 1970s\u20131980s within the programme that was officially titled [[FOLIANT]] and the term Novichok referred to a whole system of chemical weapons use; they, as well as Mirzayanov, who published Novichok's formula in 2008, also noted that Novichok-type agents might be synthesised in other countries.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/russian/features-43476312 \u0427\u0442\u043e \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0435 \"\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447\u043e\u043a\"? \u0412\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u0442\u0440\u0435\u0445 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0440\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u0447\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432] BBC, 20 March 2018.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/novichok-nerve-agent-poison-soviet-russia-salisbury-attack-leonid-rink-vladimir-uglev-the-bell-a8265626.html|title=Soviet-era scientists contradict Moscow's claims Russia never made Novichok nerve agent|date=20 March 2018|work=The Independent}}</ref><ref>[https://www.rferl.org/a/russian-scientist-says-other-countries-may-have-novichok/29105937.html Russian Scientist Says Other Countries May Have Novichok Samples]. Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty. 17 March 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-russia-novichok-creator/soviet-era-scientist-says-he-helped-create-poison-in-uk-spy-attack-row-idUSKBN1GW1E1 Soviet-era scientist says he helped create poison in UK spy attack row] Reuters, 20 March 2018.</ref> In 1995, Leonid Rink received a one-year suspended sentence for selling Novichok agents to unnamed buyers, soon after the fatal [[Novichok agent#Poisoning of Ivan Kivelidi and Zara Ismailova|poisoning of Russian banker Ivan Kivilidi]] by Novichok.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.novayagazeta.ru/articles/2018/03/22/75896-rezhim-novichka|title=\"\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447\u043e\u043a\" \u0443\u0436\u0435 \u0443\u0431\u0438\u0432\u0430\u043b}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.trust.org/item/20180314181331-8936f|title=Secret trial shows risks of nerve agent theft in post-Soviet chaos \u2013 experts|first=Thomson Reuters|last=Foundation|publisher=trust.org}}</ref><ref>[https://www.lefigaro.fr/international/2018/03/21/01003-20180321ARTFIG00328-quand-un-banquier-russe-etait-tue-au-novitchok-dans-le-moscou-des-annees-1990.php?redirect_premium Quand un banquier russe \u00e9tait tu\u00e9 au Novitchok dans le Moscou des ann\u00e9es 1990], ''Le Figaro'', 21 March 2018.{{in lang|fr}}</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.com/ukrainian/features-russian-43398713 \u0412 1995 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0443 \u044f\u0434\u043e\u043c, \u043f\u043e\u0445\u043e\u0436\u0438\u043c \u043d\u0430 \"\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447\u043e\u043a\", \u043e\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0431\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0438\u0440\u0430 \u0418\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u041a\u0438\u0432\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0434\u0438], BBC, 14 March 2018.{{in lang|ru}}</ref>\n\nA former KGB and FSB officer, Boris Karpichkov, who operated in Latvia in the 1990s and fled to the UK in 1998,<ref name=\"delfihit\">[https://rus.delfi.lv/news/daily/abroad/byvshij-dvojnoj-agent-fcb-v-latvii-menya-atakovali-neizvestnym-veschestvom.d?id=49843319 \u0411\u044b\u0432\u0448\u0438\u0439 \u0434\u0432\u043e\u0439\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0430\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0442 \u0424C\u0411 \u0432 \u041b\u0430\u0442\u0432\u0438\u0438: \u043c\u0435\u043d\u044f \u0442\u043e\u0436\u0435 \u0430\u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u043d\u0435\u0438\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043d\u044b\u043c \u0432\u0435\u0449\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u043c] [[Delfi (web portal)|Delfi]], 15 March 2018.</ref> told [[ITV (TV network)|ITV's]] ''[[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]]'' that on 12 February 2018, three weeks before the Salisbury attack and exactly on his birthday, he received a message over the [[burner phone]] from \"a very reliable source\" in the FSB telling Karpichkov that \"something bad [wa]s going to happen with [him] and seven other people, including Mr. Skripal\", whom he then knew nothing about.<ref name=\"itvkarpichkov\">[https://www.itv.com/goodmorningbritain/former-kgb-agent-says-he-was-warned-of-skripal-poisoning Former KGB agent says he was warned of Skripal poisoning] [[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]], 12 March 2018.</ref> Karpichkov said he disregarded the message at the time, thinking it was not serious, as he had previously received such messages.<ref name=\"itvkarpichkov\" /> According to Karpichkov, the FSB's list includes the names of [[Oleg Gordievsky]] and [[Bill Browder|William Browder]].<ref name=\"delfihit\" /><ref>Kitty Donaldson, Henry Meyer, and Irina Reznik. [https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-29/finding-your-name-on-russia-s-hit-list Finding Your Name on Russia\u2019s Hit List: The nerve-gas poisoning of a former KGB agent in the U.K. has Moscow\u2019s foes spooked.] Bloomberg, 29 March 2018.</ref>\n\n===Spiez Laboratory in Switzerland===\nThe Swiss Federal Intelligence Service asserted on 14 September 2018 that two Russian spies had been caught in the [[Netherlands]] and expelled, earlier in the year, for attempting to hack into the [[Spiez Laboratory]] in the Swiss town of [[Spiez]], a designated lab of the [[OPCW]] that had been tasked with confirming that the samples of poison collected in Salisbury were Novichok. The spies were discovered through a joint investigation by the Swiss, Dutch, and British intelligence services. The two men expelled were not the same as the Salisbury suspects.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/dutch-kicked-out-russian-spies-over-alleged-plot-to-hack-lab-investigating-salisbury-novichok-11497884|title=Dutch kicked out 'Russian spies' over alleged plot to hack lab investigating Salisbury novichok|work=Sky News|access-date=2018-09-14|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/14/world/europe/russians-salisbury-swiss-lab-sabotage.html|title=Russians Planned Attack on Lab Testing Salisbury Nerve Agent, Swiss Say|last=Schreuer|first=Milan|date=14 September 2018|work=New York Times|access-date=15 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Response from other countries and organisations ==\n\n=== US government ===\nFollowing Theresa May's statement in [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]], the US Secretary of State [[Rex Tillerson]] released a statement on 12 March that fully supported the stance of the UK government on the poisoning attack, including \"its assessment that Russia was likely responsible for the nerve agent attack that took place in Salisbury\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.state.gov/secretary/remarks/2018/03/279201.htm|title=Attributing Responsibility for the Nerve Agent Attack in the U.K.|work=U.S. Department of State|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref> The following day, US President [[Donald Trump]] said that Russia was likely responsible.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/03/13/europe/trump-russia-spy-intl/index.html|title=Trump: Russia likely poisoned ex-spy, 'based on all the evidence'|last=Vonberg|first=Judith|publisher=CNN|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[United States Ambassador to the United Nations]] [[Nikki Haley]] at the Security Council briefing on 14 March 2018 stated: \"The United States believes that Russia is responsible for the attack on two people in the United Kingdom using a military-grade nerve agent\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Haley|first1=Nikki|title=Remarks at an Emergency UN Security Council Briefing on Chemical Weapons Use by Russia in the United Kingdom|url=https://usun.state.gov/remarks/8336|website=United States Mission to the United Nations|publisher=Department of State|date=14 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[United States National Security Council]]'s recommendation,<ref name=\"cnndiplomats\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/03/23/politics/trump-russian-diplomats-national-security-council/index.html|title=Trump's National Security Council recommends expelling Russian diplomats|first=Michelle |last=Kosinski|publisher=CNN|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref> President Trump, on 26 March, ordered the expulsion of sixty Russian diplomats (referred to by the White House as \"Russian intelligence officers\"<ref name=\"whitehouseexpul\">[https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/statement-press-secretary-expulsion-russian-intelligence-officers/ Statement from the Press Secretary on the Expulsion of Russian Intelligence Officers] The White House, 26 March 2018.</ref>) and the closure of the Russian consulate in Seattle.<ref name=\"wptrump\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-administration-expels-60-russian-officers-shuts-seattle-consulate-in-response-to-attack-on-former-spy-in-britain/2018/03/26/8ada3d8e-30f0-11e8-8bdd-cdb33a5eef83_story.html|title=Trump administration expels 60 Russian officers, shuts Seattle consulate in response to attack on former spy in Britain|last=Rucker|first=Philip|date=26 March 2018|work=The Washington Post|access-date=26 March 2018|last2=Nakashima|first2=Ellen|issn=0190-8286}}</ref><ref>[https://tass.ru/mezhdunarodnaya-panorama/5066974 \u0421\u0428\u0410 \u0432\u044b\u0441\u044b\u043b\u0430\u044e\u0442 \u0438\u0437 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u044b 60 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0434\u0438\u043f\u043b\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0432] TASS, 26 March 2018.</ref> The action was cast as being \"in response to Russia's use of a military-grade chemical weapon on the soil of the United Kingdom, the latest in its ongoing pattern of destabilising activities around the world.\"<ref name=\"whitehouseexpul\" />\n\nOn 8 August,<ref name=\"aug8\">{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2018/08/285043.htm|title=Imposition of Chemical and Biological Weapons Control and Warfare Elimination Act Sanctions on Russia}}</ref> five months after the poisoning,<ref name=aug9 /> the US government agreed to place sanctions on Russian banks and exports.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/401236-russia-threatens-retaliation-against-new-us-sanctions|title=Russia: New US sanctions a 'declaration of economic war'|first=Tal|last=Axelrod|date=10 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://time.com/5363719/russia-banking-sanctions-skripal-medvedev/|title=Russia Warns U.S. Against Ramping Up Sanctions|website=Time}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2018/08/09/u-s-sanctions-russia-putin-critics-poisoned-dead/944476002/|title=As U.S. sanctions Russia for ex-spy, Moscow adds to list of critics found poisoned or dead}}</ref><ref name=\"aug9\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2018/08/us-russia-sanctions-novichok-attack/567119/|title=The U.S. Sanctions Russia for Skripal Poisoning\u2014Five Months Later|first=Yasmeen|last=Serhan|date=9 August 2018}}</ref> On 6 August,<ref name=aug8 /> the US State Department concluded that Russia was behind the poisoning.<ref name=aug8 /> The sanctions, which are enforced under the [[Chemical and Biological Weapons Control and Warfare Elimination Act of 1991]] (CBW Act),<ref name=aug8 /> were planned to come into effect on 27 August.<ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. sanctions tied to nerve agent attack in effect Monday: federal notice |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-russia-novichok/u-s-sanctions-tied-to-nerve-agent-attack-in-effect-monday-federal-notice-idUSKCN1L91CY?il=0 |accessdate=24 August 2018 |work=[[Reuters]] |date=24 August 2018}}</ref> However, these sanctions were not implemented by the Trump administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/trump-admin-has-not-imposed-new-sanctions-russia-required-law-n962216|title=U.S. has not imposed new Russia sanctions sparked by Skripal poisoning|website=NBC News}}</ref>\n\n===European Union and member states===\n[[Vice-President of the European Commission|European Commission Vice-President]] [[Frans Timmermans]] argued for \"unequivocal, unwavering and very strong\" European solidarity with the United Kingdom when speaking to lawmakers in Strasburg on 13 March.<ref name=\"ap180313143500\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/5f4189f2-26aa-11e8-a227-fd2b009466bc_story.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180313191949/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/the-latest-russia-demands-samples-of-nerve-agent/2018/03/13/5f4189f2-26aa-11e8-a227-fd2b009466bc_story.html |archive-date=13 March 2018 |title=The Latest: Trump, May agree on consequences for poison use |agency=Associated Press |date=13 March 2018 |accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref> [[Federica Mogherini]], the [[High Representative of the Union for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy]], expressed shock and offered the bloc's support.<ref name=\"reuters180313085900\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-russia-eu/despite-brexit-britain-wins-eu-support-on-nerve-agent-attack-idUSKCN1GP0R9 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20180313192407/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-russia-eu/despite-brexit-britain-wins-eu-support-on-nerve-agent-attack-idUSKCN1GP0R9 |archive-date=13 March 2018 |title=Despite Brexit, Britain wins EU support on nerve agent attack |agency=Reuters |date=13 March 2018 |accessdate=13 March 2018 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]] and leader of the [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe]] in the European Parliament [[Guy Verhofstadt]] proclaimed solidarity with the British people.<ref name=\"guardian180313151400\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/13/sergei-skripal-spy-poisoning-russia-uk-sanctions-eu-lack-consensus |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180313192633/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/13/sergei-skripal-spy-poisoning-russia-uk-sanctions-eu-lack-consensus |archive-date=13 March 2018 |title=UK's effort to rally allies over Sergei Skripal poisoning may fall short |work=The Guardian |date=13 March 2018 |accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring a meeting in the [[Foreign Affairs Council]] on 19 March, all foreign ministers of the European Union declared in a joint statement that the \"European Union expresses its unqualified solidarity with the UK and its support, including for the UK's efforts to bring those responsible for this crime to justice.\" In addition, the statement also pointed out that \"The European Union takes extremely seriously the UK Government's assessment that it is highly likely that the Russian Federation is responsible.\"<ref name=\"eu-20180319\">{{cite press release  |url=https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2018/03/19/statement-by-the-foreign-affairs-council-on-the-salisbury-attack/ |title= Statement by the Foreign Affairs Council on the Salisbury attack |date= 19 March 2018 |publisher=[[Council of the European Union]]|access-date= 19 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Norbert R\u00f6ttgen]], a former [[Federal Ministry of the Environment, Nature Conservation and Nuclear Safety|federal minister]] in Angela Merkel's government and current chairman of Germany's parliamentary foreign affairs committee, said the incident demonstrated the need for Britain to review its open-door policy towards Russian capital of dubious origin.<ref name=\"rottgen\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/13/sergei-skripal-spy-poisoning-russia-uk-sanctions-eu-lack-consensus|title=UK's effort to rally allies over Sergei Skripal poisoning may fall short|last=Wintour|first=Patrick|date=13 March 2018|website=The Guardian|access-date=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nSixteen EU countries expelled 33 Russian diplomats on 26 March.<ref name=\"expulsionbbc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-43545565|title=Spy poisoning: Russian diplomats expelled across US and Europe|publisher=BBC News|date=26 March 2017|accessdate=26 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"expulsionguardian\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/26/four-eu-states-set-to-expel-russian-diplomats-over-skripal-attack|title=US and EU expel scores of Russian diplomats over Skripal attack|last=Borger|first=Julian|last2=Wintour|first2=Patrick|last3=Stewart|first3=Heather|date=26 March 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[European Union]] officially sanctioned 4 Russians that were suspected of carrying out the attack on 21 January 2019. The head of the GRU Igor Kostyukov and the deputy head Vladimir Alexseyev were both sanctioned along with Mishkin and Chepiga. The sanctions banned them from traveling to the EU and froze any assets they may have there along with banning any person or company in the EU providing any financial support to those sanctioned.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-46949162|title=EU sanctions Russian suspects over Salisbury|date=21 January 2019|access-date=2019-01-21|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===Other non-EU countries===\nAlbania, Australia, Canada, Georgia, Macedonia, Moldova, Norway and Ukraine expelled a total of 27 Russian diplomats who were believed to have been intelligence officers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/03/26/europe/full-list-of-russian-diplomats-expelled-over-s-intl/index.html|title=These are all the countries that are expelling Russian diplomats|last=Dewan|first=Angela|date=27 March 2018|publisher=CNN|access-date=27 March 2018}}</ref> The New Zealand Government also issued a statement supporting the actions, noting that it would have expelled any Russian intelligence agents who had been detected in the country.<ref>{{cite news|title=PM Jacinda Ardern: Why NZ is not expelling Russia diplomats|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12020803|accessdate=28 March 2018|work=The New Zealand Herald|date=27 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===NATO===\n[[NATO]] issued an official response to the attack on 14 March. The alliance expressed its deep concern over the first offensive use of a nerve agent on its territory since its foundation and said that the attack was in breach of international treaties. It called on Russia to fully disclose its research of the Novichok agent to the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/news_152787.htm|title=Statement by the North Atlantic Council on the use of a nerve agent in Salisbury|website=nato.int|date=14 March 2018|access-date=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Jens Stoltenberg]], [[Secretary General of NATO|NATO Secretary General]], announced on 27 March that NATO would be expelling seven Russian diplomats from the [[Russia\u2013NATO relations|Russian mission to NATO]] in Brussels. In addition, 3 unfilled positions at the mission have been denied accreditation from NATO. Russia blamed the US for the NATO response.<ref name = NATOexpulsions/>\n\n=== Joint responses ===\nThe leaders of France, Germany, the United States and the United Kingdom released a joint statement on 15 March which supported the UK's stance on the incident, stating that it was \"highly likely that Russia was responsible\" and calling on Russia to provide complete disclosure to the [[Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons]] concerning its Novichok nerve agent program.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/15/salisbury-poisoning-uk-us-germany-and-france-issue-joint-statement|title=UK, US, Germany and France unite to condemn spy attack|last=Walker|first=Peter|last2=Roth|first2=Andrew|date=15 March 2018|website=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/salisbury-attack-joint-statement-from-the-leaders-of-france-germany-the-united-states-and-the-united-kingdom|title=Salisbury attack: Joint statement from the leaders of France, Germany, the United States and the United Kingdom|publisher=Government of the United Kingdom|access-date=15 March 2018}}</ref> On 19 March, the [[European Union]] also issued a statement strongly condemning the attack and stating it \"takes extremely seriously the UK Government's assessment that it is highly likely that the Russian Federation is responsible\".<ref name=eu-20180319/>\n\nOn 6 September 2018, Canada, France, Germany and the United States issued a joint statement saying they had \"full confidence\" that the Salisbury attack was orchestrated by Russia's [[Main Intelligence Directorate]] and \"almost certainly approved at a senior government level\" and urged Russia to provide full disclosure of its Novichok programme to the OPCW.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/d8e6df42-b1d2-11e8-99ca-68cf89602132|title=Key western allies back UK over Salisbury attack|author1=Henry Mance|author2=Michael Peel|author3=Guy Chazan|date=6 September 2018|accessdate=6 September 2018|website=Financial Times}}</ref>\n\n==Expulsion of diplomats==\n[[File:Map of sanctions - Expelled Russian diplomats.svg|thumb|Expelled Russian diplomats]]\nBy the end of March 2018 a number of countries and other organisations expelled a total of more than 150 Russian diplomats in a show of solidarity with the UK. According to the BBC it was \"the largest collective expulsion of Russian intelligence officers in history\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-43545565|title=Russia faces wave of diplomatic expulsions|date=26 March 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=27 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"NATOexpulsions\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-43550938|title=Nato slashes Russia staff after poisoning|date=27 March 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=27 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Montenegro to expel Russian diplomat over UK nerve gas attack|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-russia-montenegro/montenegro-to-expel-russian-diplomat-over-uk-nerve-gas-attack-idUSKBN1H41GH|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=28 March 2018|date=28 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe UK expelled 23 Russian diplomats on 14 March 2018. Three days later, Russia expelled an equal number of British diplomats and ordered closure of the UK consulate in St. Petersburg and closure of the British Council in Russia.<ref name=\"indeprusexp\" /> Nine countries expelled Russian diplomats on 26 March: along with 6 other EU nations, the US, Canada, Ukraine and Albania. The following day, several nations inside and outside of the EU, and NATO responded similarly. By 30 March, Russia expelled an equal number of diplomats of most nations who had expelled Russian diplomats. By that time, Belgium, Montenegro, Hungary and Georgia had also expelled one or more Russian diplomats. Additionally on 30 March, Russia reduced the size of the total UK mission's personnel in Russia to match that of the Russian mission to the UK.\n\nBulgaria, Luxembourg, Malta, Portugal, Slovakia, Slovenia and the European Union itself have not expelled any Russian diplomats but have recalled their ambassadors from Russia for consultations.<ref>[https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2018-03-27/bulgaria-recalls-ambassador-from-russia-to-discuss-nerve-agent-attack Bulgaria Recalls Ambassador From Russia to Discuss Nerve Agent Attack]. Reuters via US News. 27 March 2018.</ref><ref>[https://newsnow.tasr.sk/foreign/slovakia-to-call-ambassador-to-russia-back-home-for-consultation/ Slovakia to Call Ambassador to Russia Back Home for Consultation]. TASR.sk. 28 March 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-russia-luxembourg/luxembourg-recalls-ambassador-from-russia-over-salisbury-attack-idUSKBN1H40YA Luxembourg recalls ambassador from Russia over Salisbury attack]. Reuters. 28 March 2018.</ref><ref>Diacono, Tim. [https://lovinmalta.com/news/news-international/malta-has-just-recalled-its-ambassador-to-russia Malta Has Just Recalled Its Ambassador To Russia]. Lovin Malta. Retrieved on 18 May 2018.</ref><ref>[https://finance.yahoo.com/news/state-play-over-russian-envoy-expulsions-001133000.html State of play over Russian envoy expulsions]. Finance.yahoo.com (28 March 2018). Retrieved on 18 May 2018.</ref><ref>[https://tass.com/world/996694 Slovenia recalling its ambassador to Russia for consultations]. Tass. 29 March 2018.</ref> Furthermore, Iceland decided to diplomatically boycott the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] held in Russia.<ref>[https://www.rt.com/sport/422397-iceland-boycott-fifa-russia/ Iceland to diplomatically boycott 2018 World Cup in Russia]. Rt.com. 26 March 2018.</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Country or<br />organisation\n!Diplomats expelled\n!Date announced\n!Response by Russia\n!Date announced\n|-\n|{{flag|Albania}}\n|2\n|26 March\n|2 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name=\"moreUKexpel\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-43604053|title=Spy poisoning: Russia expels more UK diplomats|date=31 March 2018|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Australia}}\n|2\n|27 March\n|2 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Belgium}}\n|1\n|27 March\n|1 diplomat expelled (the economic ''attach\u00e9'').<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nieuws.vtm.be/binnenland/deze-diplomaat-wijst-rusland-uit|title=Deze diplomaat wijst Rusland uit|publisher=[[VTM (TV channel)|VTM]]|date=4 April 2018|accessdate=4 April 2018|language=Dutch}}</ref>\n|4 April\n|-\n|{{flag|Canada}}\n|4{{ref|a|[a]}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.canada.ca/en/global-affairs/news/2018/03/canada-expels-russian-diplomats-in-solidarity-with-united-kingdom.html |title=Canada expels Russian diplomats in solidarity with United Kingdom |website=www.canada.ca|date=26 March 2018}}</ref>\n|26 March\n|4 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Croatia}}\n|1\n|26 March\n|1 diplomat based in [[Zagreb]] declared [[Persona non-grata|PNG]].<ref>[https://www.vecernji.hr/vijesti/mvep-hrvatski-diplomat-rusija-moskva-1236214 Nepo\u017eeljna \u0161efica ureda ministrice, k\u0107er po\u010dasnog konzula Moskve] [[Ve\u010dernji list]], 30 March 2018.</ref>\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Czech Republic}}\n|3\n|26 March\n|3 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Denmark}}\n|2\n|26 March\n|2 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Estonia}}\n|1\n|26 March\n|1 diplomat expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Finland}}\n|1\n|26 March\n|1 diplomat expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|France}}\n|4\n|26 March\n|4 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Germany}}\n|4\n|26 March\n|4 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Georgia}}\n|1<ref name=\"georgiaExpel\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-georgia-russia/georgia-expels-one-russian-diplomat-over-uk-nerve-agent-attack-idUSKBN1H61BC?il=0|title=Georgia expels one Russian diplomat over UK nerve agent attack|date=30 March 2018|publisher=Reuters|language=ru}}</ref>\n|30 March\n|1 diplomat expelled by Russia.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ria.ru/politics/20180413/1518574392.html |title=\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044f \u043e\u0431\u044a\u044f\u0432\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u0433\u0440\u0443\u0437\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0434\u0438\u043f\u043b\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0441\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u043d\u043e\u043d \u0433\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0430 |publisher=[[\u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438]] |date=13 April 2018 |accessdate=15 April 2018}}</ref>\n|13 April\n|-\n|{{flag|Hungary}}\n|1\n|26 March\n|1 diplomat expelled by Russia.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-russia-hungary-expulsion/russia-says-expels-one-hungarian-diplomat-over-skripal-case-idUSKCN1HB1EE |title=Russia says expels one Hungarian diplomat over Skripal case |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=4 April 2018 |website= |publisher= Reuters |access-date= 20 April 2018}}</ref>\n|4 April\n|-\n|{{flag|Ireland}}\n|1\n|27 March\n|1 diplomat expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Italy}}\n|2\n|26 March\n|2 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Latvia}}\n|1\n|26 March\n|1 diplomat expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Lithuania}}\n|3\n|26 March\n|3 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Macedonia}}\n|1\n|26 March\n|1 diplomat expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Moldova}}\n|3\n|27 March\n|3 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Montenegro}}\n|1<ref name=\"montExpel\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.rt.com/newsline/422558-slovakia-ambassador-russia-montenegro/|title=Slovakia recalls ambassador from Moscow, Montenegro to expel Russian diplomat|date=28 March 2018|publisher=[[RT (TV network)|RT]]}}</ref>\n|28 March\n|1 diplomat expelled by Russia.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ria.ru/politics/20180402/1517770018.html |script-title=ru:\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044f \u0432\u044b\u0448\u043b\u0435\u0442 \u0447\u0435\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0434\u0438\u043f\u043b\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0430 |publisher=[[\u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438]] |date=2 April 2018 |accessdate=15 April 2018|language=ru}}</ref>\n|2 April\n|-\n|{{flag|NATO}}\n|7{{ref|b|[b]}}<ref name =NATOexpulsions />\n|27 March\n|\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Netherlands}}\n|2\n|26 March\n|2 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Norway}}\n|1\n|26 March\n|1 diplomat expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Poland}}\n|4\n|26 March\n|4 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Romania}}\n|1\n|26 March\n|1 diplomat expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Spain}}\n|2\n|26 March\n|2 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Sweden}}\n|1\n|26 March\n|1 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|Ukraine}}\n|13\n|26 March\n|13 diplomats expelled by Russia.<ref name='moreUKexpel' />\n|30 March\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |{{flag|United Kingdom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |23\n| rowspan=\"2\" |14 March\n|23 UK diplomats expelled by Russia.<br />British consulate in St Petersburg closed. Russian office of the [[British Council]] closed.\n|17 March\n|-\n|UK diplomatic mission to Russia reduced in size to match Russian mission to UK. Requires the UK to recall a further 27 officials. \n|30 March\n|-\n|{{flag|United States}}\n|60,{{ref|c|[c]}} Russian consulates in [[Consulate-General of Russia in San Francisco|San Francisco]] and Seattle closed.\n|26 March\n|60 US diplomats expelled by Russia.<br />US consulate in St Petersburg closed.\n|30 March\n|}\n\n'''Notes'''\n* {{sup|{{note|a|[a]}}}} 4 diplomats expelled. 3 pending applications declined.\n* {{sup|{{note|b|[b]}}}} 7 expelled and 3 pending applications declined. Maximum delegation reduced by 10 (from 30 to 20).\n* {{sup|{{note|c|[c]}}}} 48 Russian diplomats expelled from Washington D.C. and 12 expelled from New York.\n\n==Aftermath==\nSome of the emergency vehicles used in the response to the poisoning have been buried in a [[landfill]] site near [[Cheltenham]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-wiltshire-45362840|title=Novichok 999 vehicles buried in landfill|date=31 August 2018|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 September, [[Chris Busby]], a retired research scientist, who is regular expert on the [[Russian government]] controlled [[RT (TV network)|RT]] television network, was arrested after his home in [[Bideford]] was raided by police.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/police-fall-ill-at-chemical-expert-s-home-l2cmh6xb7|title=Police fall ill at chemical expert's home|first=Gurpreet|last=Narwan|date=14 September 2018|work=The Times|url-access=subscription |accessdate=20 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/dr-chris-busby-police-become-unwell-at-chemical-weapons-experts-devon-home-11496768|title=Dr Chris Busby: Police become unwell at chemical weapons expert's Devon home|publisher=Sky News|accessdate=20 September 2018}}</ref> Busby was an outspoken critic of the British Government's handling of the Salisbury poisoning.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nachdenkseiten.de/?p=43331|title= Alternative Fakten und nationale Alleing\u00e4nge \u2013 Gro\u00dfbritannien und Deutschland blamieren sich im Fall Skripal bis auf die Knochen|date=6 April 2018|accessdate=20 September 2018|via=www.nachdenkseiten.de}}</ref> In one video he stated: \"Just to make it perfectly clear, there's no way that there's any proof that the material that poisoned the Skripals came from Russia.\" Busby was held for 19 hours under the [[Explosive Substances Act 1883]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.devonlive.com/news/devon-news/police-chris-busby-russia-today-2005659|title=Inside the bomb scare lab that belongs to Russia Today nuclear expert|first=Joel|last=Cooper|date=14 September 2018|accessdate=20 September 2018}}</ref> before being released with no further action.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/09/13/chemical-weapons-expert-arrested-police-taken-devon-home/|title=Chemical weapons expert arrested after police 'taken ill' at Devon home|first=Telegraph|last=Reporters|date=13 September 2018|accessdate=20 September 2018|work=The Telegraph}}</ref> Following his release, Busby told the BBC he believed that the fact that two of the officers who had raided his property had felt unwell was explained by \"psychological problems associated with their knowledge of the Skripal poisoning\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-devon-45516797|title=Bideford radiation expert held over home chemicals|date=13 September 2018|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=20 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 September, fears of Novichok contamination flared up again after two people fell ill at a [[Prezzo (restaurant)|Prezzo]] restaurant, {{convert|300|m}} from the Zizzi location where the Skripals had eaten before collapsing. The restaurant, a nearby pub, and surrounding streets were cordoned off, with some patrons under observation or unable to leave the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbs8.com/story/39100286/roads-shut-after-2-fall-ill-in-uk-city-where-ex-spy-poisoned|title=Roads shut after 2 fall ill in UK city where ex-spy poisoned|agency=Associated Press|publisher=CBS8 News}}</ref> The next day, the police said there was \"nothing to suggest that Novichok\" was the cause of the two people falling ill.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-45543606|title='No Novichok link' to Salisbury incident|date=17 September 2018|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=17 September 2018}}</ref> However, on 19 September, one of the apparent victims, Anna Shapiro, claimed in ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' newspaper that the incident had been an attempted assassination against her and her husband by Russia.<ref name=\"GuardianShapiro\">{{cite web |title=Rat poison, Prezzo and the Russian model: odd Salisbury subplot begins to unravel |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/sep/19/salisburys-saga-the-spy-the-supermodel-the-strychnine-and-thats-just-the-sub-plot |work=The Guardian |accessdate=20 September 2018}}</ref> This article was later removed from ''The Sun'' \"for legal reasons\"<ref name=\"GuardianShapiro\" /> and the police began to investigate the incident as a \"possible hoax\" after the couple were discharged from hospital.<ref>{{cite web |title=Salisbury Prezzo novichok poisoning scare may be a hoax, say police |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/salisbury-prezzo-couple-ill-russia-rat-poison-anna-shapiro-alex-king-skripal-novichok-a8546001.html |work=The Independent |accessdate=20 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that then deputy CIA director [[Gina Haspel]] advised Donald Trump in a discussion that young children had been hospitalised and ducks killed after exposure to the Novichok nerve agent that poisoned the Skripals. She showed him photos of these victims which the ''New York Times'' reported had been provided by British officials.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Barnes |first1=Julian E. |last2=Goldman |first2=Adam |title=Gina Haspel Relies on Spy Skills to Connect With Trump. He Doesn't Always Listen. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/16/us/politics/gina-haspel-trump.html |accessdate=20 April 2019 |work=New York Times|date=16 April 2019}}</ref> The incident was cited as an example of the \"''persuasive skills''\" of the then CIA director Gina Haspel. In response the director of public health at Wiltshire council said: \"There were no other casualties other than those previously stated. No wildlife were impacted by the incident and no children were exposed to or became ill as a result of either incident\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/apr/18/no-children-ducks-harmed-novichok-attack-wiltshire-health-officials|title=No children or ducks harmed by novichok, say health officials|last=Morris|first=Steven|date=18 April 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-04-21|last2=Bannock|first2=Caroline|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/apr/16/trump-novichok-attack-skripal-poisoning-spy-game Trump wrote off novichok attack of defector as 'spy games' \u2013 report], The Guardian, 16 April 2019</ref>\n\n===Russian public opinion===\nThe ''Moscow Times'' reported that \"The results of the survey published by the independent [[Levada Center]] pollster [in October 2018] say that 28 percent of Russians believe that British intelligence services were behind Skripals' poisoning, with only 3 percent saying they believe their own intelligence officers carried out the attack. Another 56 percent said that \"it could have been anyone.\" Meanwhile, 37 percent of respondents said they knew about the case in detail and 33 percent said they had \"heard something\" about it, with another 20 percent saying they had heard nothing about the poisoning.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Only 3% of Russians Believe Moscow Was Behind Skripal Attack, Poll Says |url=https://themoscowtimes.com/news/only-3-percent-russians-believe-moscow-was-behind-skripal-attack-poll-says-63297 |work=[[The Moscow Times]] |date=25 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Recovery money==\nAs of 17 October 2018, a total of \u00a37.5 million had been pledged by government in support of the city and to support businesses, boost tourism and to cover unexpected costs. [[Wiltshire Council]] had spent or pledged \u00a37,338,974 on recovery, and a further half million \"was in the pipeline\":\n* \u00a3733,381 towards unexpected closure and loss of footfall to businesses\n* \u00a3404,024 in revenue grants for 74 businesses\n* \u00a399,891 in capital grants\n* \u00a3229,446 in business rate relief for 56 businesses\n* \u00a3210,491 on events to boost tourism\n* \u00a3500,000 from the Department of Digital, Culture, Media and Sport\n* \u00a34,000 on dry cleaning or disposal of clothes believed to be contaminated by Novichock\n* \u00a31 million towards keeping contaminated sites safe\n* \u00a3570,000 recovery money to cover costs of free parking, and free park and ride services\n* \u00a34.1 million of the money pledged by the [[Home Office]] to cover Wiltshire Police's costs. A council commissioner said total policing cost had exceeded \u00a310 million. Having \u00a36.6 million allocated for funding the police force, he said he hoped to \"recoup the full amount from central government\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.salisburyjournal.co.uk/news/16989675.breakdown-of-wiltshire-council-spend-on-salisbury-recovery/ | title=Breakdown of Wiltshire Council spend on Salisbury recovery | date=17 October 2018 | first=Rebecca | last=Hudson | newspaper=Salisbury Journal | accessdate=27 March 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{commonscat|Nerve agent attack 2018}}\n* [[Intelligence agencies of Russia]]\n* [[2018 Amesbury poisonings]]\n* [[Assassination of Kim Jong-nam]] by North Korea with VX nerve agent \n*[[Poisoning of Alexander Litvinenko]] putatively by Russian intelligence agents with Polonium-210\n*[[Bulgarian umbrella]] used to assassinate [[Georgi Markov]] in London\n*[[List of poisonings]]\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Russia}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Noteslist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* Report from The Russian Embassy to the UK, ''Salisbury: Unanswered questions'' [https://rusemb.org.uk/fnapr/6762 SALISBURY: UNANSWERED QUESTIONS (4 March 2019)], 4 March 2019\n* [https://www.counterterrorism.police.uk/salisbury/ \"Salisbury & Amesbury Investigation - UK Counter Terrorism Policing\"], 5 September 2018 \n* [https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43315636 \"Russian spy: What we know so far\"], [[BBC]], 19 March 2018 \n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2018/03/06/the-long-terrifying-history-of-russian-dissidents-being-poisoned-abroad/ \"Amanda Erickson: The long, terrifying history of Russian dissidents being poisoned abroad\"], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', 7 March 2018 \n* [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-43299598 \"Joel Gunter: Sergei Skripal and the 14 deaths under scrutiny\"], bbc.com, 7 March 2018\n* [[Bellingcat]]'s investigative page for the Chepiga identification [https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2018/09/26/skripal-suspect-boshirov-identified-gru-colonel-anatoliy-chepiga Skripal Suspect Boshirov Identified as GRU Colonel Anatoliy Chepiga]\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Skripal, Sergei and Yulia}}\n[[Category:2018 controversies]]\n[[Category:2018 crimes in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2018 in British politics]]\n[[Category:2018 in international relations]]\n[[Category:21st century in Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:Attacks in 2018]]\n[[Category:Crime in Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:Diplomatic incidents]]\n[[Category:Failed assassination attempts]]\n[[Category:Forensic toxicology]]<!-- Suggest this article is about the poisoning, the article on Reactions has the foreign relations component -->\n[[Category:History of Salisbury]]\n[[Category:March 2018 crimes in Europe]]\n[[Category:March 2018 events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Poisoning by drugs, medicaments and biological substances]]\n[[Category:Russia intelligence operations]]\n[[Category:Russia\u2013United Kingdom relations]]\n[[Category:Russia\u2013United States relations]]\n", "name_user": "Fake News Extinguisher", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePoisoning)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poisoning_of_Sergei_and_Yulia_Skripal"}
{"title_page": "Richard Teng Wee Chen", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Peacock|date=April 2020}}\n{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Richard Teng Wee Chen\n| image         = Richard-Teng.jpg\n| alt           = Richard Teng Wee Chen\n| caption       = \n| other_names   = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{birth year and age|1970}}\n| birth_place   = [[Singapore]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| alma_mater    = [[Nanyang Technological University]]\n| occupation    = CEO, Financial Services Regulatory Authority, [[Abu Dhabi Global Market]]\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n| awards        = Singapore Institute of Banking Finance Fellowship\n}}\n\n'''Richard Teng Wee Chen''' (born October 1970) is the CEO of the Financial Services Regulatory Authority (FSRA)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adgm.com/about-adgm/leadership/richard-teng|title=ADGM Leadership, Richard Teng|last=|first=|date=|website=Abu Dhabi Global Market|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> of [[Abu Dhabi Global Market]] (ADGM), the International Financial Centre in the UAE's capital city. Born and raised as a Singaporean<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sgsme.sg/news/startups/how-one-singaporean-helping-build-international-financial-centre-overseas|title=How one Singaporean is helping to build an international financial centre overseas|last=|first=|date=|website=SGSME|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, Richard has served in key local and global roles in financial regulations and financial sector development for more than 25 years. \n\nRichard is noted for his commitment in advocating high financial regulations practice and governance which has resulted in regional and global industry recognition. During his office as the CEO of FSRA ADGM, Richard led the ADGM team in securing numerous global industry accolades \"Financial Centre of the Year (MENA)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalinvestorgroup.com/articles/3693629/global-investor-mena-awards-2019-winners-announced|title=Global Investor MENA Awards 2019 \u2013 winners announced|last=|first=|date=|website=Global Investor Group|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\" for four consecutive years since 2016, for Abu Dhabi/ADGM to be recognised as top FinTech Hub in MENA<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://gulfbusiness.com/uae-named-largest-fintech-hub-in-the-mena-region/|title=UAE named largest fintech hub in the MENA region|date=|work=Gulf Business|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> to be the Fintech Regulator of the Year MENA in 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalbankingandfinance.com/abu-dhabi-global-market-named-fintech-regulator-of-the-year/|title=Abu Dhabi Global Market Named \u201cFinTech Regulator of the Year\u201d|last=|first=|date=|website=Global Banking and Finance Review|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.\u00a0 These awards reflect the industry\u2019s endorsement of ADGM\u2019s efforts and initiatives to boost sector development and economy growth. \n\nRichard is focused on and has been featured in various global media and international platforms, sharing thought leadership<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jsbarefoot.com/podcasts/2020/1/17/leapfrogging-to-leadership-abu-dhabi-global-markets-richard-teng|title=Leapfrogging to Leadership: Abu Dhabi Global Market\u2019s Richard Teng|last=|first=|date=|website=Barefoot Innovation Group|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> on areas such as FinTech, Financial regulations<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.thenational.ae/business/comment/how-to-make-the-rules-as-technology-quickly-advances-1.926917|title=How to make the rules as technology quickly advances|date=|work=The National (UAE)|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>, Belt & Road developments<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://www.wam.ae/en/details/1395302776433|title=ADGM, Beijing Municipal Bureau to increase financial and fintech activities|date=|work=Emirates News Agency|url-status=live}}</ref> and others, throughout his career. \n\n== Career and leadership ==\n\n=== Singapore Exchange ===\nRichard was the Chief Regulatory Officer of [[Singapore Exchange]] working closely with market participants, including listed companies and member firms, as well as the Monetary Authority of Singapore (MAS) and other Singapore agencies to develop Singapore as an international financial centre that promote a fair, orderly and transparent capital market.  He was responsible for inking an agreement with China Securities Regulatory Commission for the direct listings of Chinese companies on Singapore Exchange and the launch of the highly successful Catalist Board. Richard left SGX early 2015 to join ADGM in March 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstimes.com.sg/companies-markets/sgxs-richard-teng-leaving-to-join-abu-dhabi-global-market-amended|title=SGX's Richard Teng leaving to join Abu Dhabi Global Market|last=|first=|date=|website=The Business Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Monetary Authority of Singapore (MAS) ===\nRichard started his career at [[Monetary Authority of Singapore|MAS]]\u00a0where he rose to the position of Director of Corporate Finance Division.\u00a0 During his time at MAS, Richard formulated the Real Estate Investment Trust (REIT) framework He also administers the Singapore Code of Take-overs and Mergers regulating M&A transactions.\u00a0 He was Chairman of the Asia Pacific Regional Co-operation (APRC) Working Group to achieve mutual recognition within Asia for cross-border offerings of investment products and Chief Negotiator for the financial services sector under the Singapore-Korea Free Trade Agreement.\n\n=== Capital Markets and Financial Services Examination Board ===\nRichard was the first Chairman of the Capital Markets and Financial Advisory Services Examination Board.\n\n=== Singapore Institute of Director ===\nRichard was a Council Member of the Singapore Institute of Directors.\n\n=== CPA Australia ===\nRichard was a Council Member of the Singapore Divisional Council of CPA Australia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cpaaustralia.com.au/~/media/corporate/allfiles/document/about/singapore-year-in-review-2014.pdf?la=en|title=2014 Yearn in review - CPA Australia Singapore|last=|first=|date=|website=CPA Australia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nAwarded the Singapore Institute of Banking Finance Fellowship in 2014 for contribution to the financial services sector.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibf.org.sg/honour/Pages/AwardeesDetail.aspx?awardeesid=111|title=2014 Singapore Institute of Banking Finance Fellowship Award|last=|first=|date=|website=Institute of Banking and Finance Singapore|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\n*Masters (Distinction) in Applied Finance from the [[Western Sydney University|University of Western Sydney]], Australia.\n*First Class Honours in Accountancy from the [[Nanyang Technological University]] in Singapore.\u200b\n*Scholarship by the Singapore Institute of Banking and Finance for undergraduate studies.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chen, Richard}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Biography articles of living people]]\n[[Category:Singapore]]\n[[Category:Abu Dhabi]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Financial districts in the United Arab Emirates]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Peacock|date=April 2020}}\n{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Richard Teng Wee Chen\n| image         = Richard-Teng.jpg\n| alt           = Richard Teng Wee Chen\n| caption       = \n| other_names   = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{birth year and age|1970}}\n| birth_place   = [[Singapore]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| alma_mater    = [[Nanyang Technological University]]\n| occupation    = CEO, Financial Services Regulatory Authority, [[Abu Dhabi Global Market]]\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n| awards        = Singapore Institute of Banking Finance Fellowship\n}}\n\n'''Richard Teng Wee Chen''' (born October 1970) is the CEO of the Financial Services Regulatory Authority (FSRA)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adgm.com/about-adgm/leadership/richard-teng|title=ADGM Leadership, Richard Teng|last=|first=|date=|website=Abu Dhabi Global Market|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> of [[Abu Dhabi Global Market]] (ADGM), the International Financial Centre in the UAE's capital city. Born and raised as a Singaporean<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sgsme.sg/news/startups/how-one-singaporean-helping-build-international-financial-centre-overseas|title=How one Singaporean is helping to build an international financial centre overseas|last=|first=|date=|website=SGSME|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, Richard has served in key local and global roles in financial regulations and financial sector development for more than 25 years. \n\nRichard is noted for his commitment in advocating high financial regulations practice and governance which has resulted in regional and global industry recognition. During his office as the CEO of FSRA ADGM, Richard led the ADGM team in securing numerous global industry accolades \"Financial Centre of the Year (MENA)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalinvestorgroup.com/articles/3693629/global-investor-mena-awards-2019-winners-announced|title=Global Investor MENA Awards 2019 \u2013 winners announced|last=|first=|date=|website=Global Investor Group|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\" for four consecutive years since 2016, for Abu Dhabi/ADGM to be recognised as top FinTech Hub in MENA<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://gulfbusiness.com/uae-named-largest-fintech-hub-in-the-mena-region/|title=UAE named largest fintech hub in the MENA region|date=|work=Gulf Business|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> to be the Fintech Regulator of the Year MENA in 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalbankingandfinance.com/abu-dhabi-global-market-named-fintech-regulator-of-the-year/|title=Abu Dhabi Global Market Named \u201cFinTech Regulator of the Year\u201d|last=|first=|date=|website=Global Banking and Finance Review|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.\u00a0 These awards reflect the industry\u2019s endorsement of ADGM\u2019s efforts and initiatives to boost sector development and economy growth. \n\nRichard is focused on and has been featured in various global media and international platforms, sharing thought leadership<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jsbarefoot.com/podcasts/2020/1/17/leapfrogging-to-leadership-abu-dhabi-global-markets-richard-teng|title=Leapfrogging to Leadership: Abu Dhabi Global Market\u2019s Richard Teng|last=|first=|date=|website=Barefoot Innovation Group|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> on areas such as FinTech, Financial regulations<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.thenational.ae/business/comment/how-to-make-the-rules-as-technology-quickly-advances-1.926917|title=How to make the rules as technology quickly advances|date=|work=The National (UAE)|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>, Belt & Road developments<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://www.wam.ae/en/details/1395302776433|title=ADGM, Beijing Municipal Bureau to increase financial and fintech activities|date=|work=Emirates News Agency|url-status=live}}</ref> and others, throughout his career. \n\n== Career and leadership ==\n\n=== Singapore Exchange ===\nRichard was the Chief Regulatory Officer of [[Singapore Exchange]] working closely with market participants, including listed companies and member firms, as well as the Monetary Authority of Singapore (MAS) and other Singapore agencies to develop Singapore as an international financial centre that promote a fair, orderly and transparent capital market.  He was responsible for inking an agreement with China Securities Regulatory Commission for the direct listings of Chinese companies on Singapore Exchange and the launch of the highly successful Catalist Board. Richard left SGX early 2015 to join ADGM in March 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstimes.com.sg/companies-markets/sgxs-richard-teng-leaving-to-join-abu-dhabi-global-market-amended|title=SGX's Richard Teng leaving to join Abu Dhabi Global Market|last=|first=|date=|website=The Business Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Monetary Authority of Singapore (MAS) ===\nRichard started his career at [[Monetary Authority of Singapore|MAS]]\u00a0where he rose to the position of Director of Corporate Finance Division.\u00a0 During his time at MAS, Richard formulated the Real Estate Investment Trust (REIT) framework He also administers the Singapore Code of Take-overs and Mergers regulating M&A transactions.\u00a0 He was Chairman of the Asia Pacific Regional Co-operation (APRC) Working Group to achieve mutual recognition within Asia for cross-border offerings of investment products and Chief Negotiator for the financial services sector under the Singapore-Korea Free Trade Agreement.\n\n=== Capital Markets and Financial Services Examination Board ===\nRichard was the first Chairman of the Capital Markets and Financial Advisory Services Examination Board.\n\n=== Singapore Institute of Director ===\nRichard was a Council Member of the Singapore Institute of Directors.\n\n=== CPA Australia ===\nRichard was a Council Member of the Singapore Divisional Council of CPA Australia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cpaaustralia.com.au/~/media/corporate/allfiles/document/about/singapore-year-in-review-2014.pdf?la=en|title=2014 Yearn in review - CPA Australia Singapore|last=|first=|date=|website=CPA Australia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nAwarded the Singapore Institute of Banking Finance Fellowship in 2014 for contribution to the financial services sector.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibf.org.sg/honour/Pages/AwardeesDetail.aspx?awardeesid=111|title=2014 Singapore Institute of Banking Finance Fellowship Award|last=|first=|date=|website=Institute of Banking and Finance Singapore|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\n*Masters (Distinction) in Applied Finance from the [[Western Sydney University|University of Western Sydney]], Australia.\n*First Class Honours in Accountancy from the [[Nanyang Technological University]] in Singapore.\u200b\n*Scholarship by the Singapore Institute of Banking and Finance for undergraduate studies.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chen, Richard}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Singapore]]\n[[Category:Abu Dhabi]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Financial districts in the United Arab Emirates]]\n", "name_user": "Sofine28", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Teng_Wee_Chen"}
{"title_page": "TRAK", "text_new": "\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{primary sources|date=April 2010}}\n\n[[File:TRAK enterpriseArchitectureFramework structure.jpg|thumb|480px|Structure of TRAK - formed from 1 metamodel, 5 architecture perspectives and 24 architecture viewpoints]]\n'''TRAK''' is a general [[Enterprise Architecture framework|enterprise architecture framework]] aimed at systems engineers based on [[MODAF]] 1.2.\n\n==History==\nTRAK was originally commissioned by London Underground Limited.<ref>[http://www.theiet.org/forums/forum/messageview.cfm?catid=227&threadid=32342 IET Forums - TRAK - The Rail Architecture Framework]</ref><ref name=\"rvfm_whole_system\">Rail Value for Money Study. Whole System Programme Management Report. 25 May 2011 http://www.rail-reg.gov.uk/upload/pdf/rvfm-atkins-programme-management-250511.pdf</ref> Development started in 2009 and was based on the then current views of architectural description within London Underground which were based on ISO/IEC 42010 and tied to the [[Systems Engineering|systems engineering]] lifecyle defined in [[ISO/IEC 15288]] .\n\nAlthough the original intent was to develop a rail-specific architecture framework in adapting MODAF to suit local needs any defence or domain-specific content was removed and the result was a domain-free [[#TRAK Metamodel|metamodel]] and viewpoints that were only based on representing [[complex systems]].\n\nTRAK was [[#Licensing|released under open source licenses]] in February 2010.\n\nIt has been formally adopted by the [[Department for Transport|UK Department for Transport]] who chair the TRAK Steering Group that manages the overall direction, strategy and formal releases of TRAK.\n\nThe TRAK development team received a Working Group award.<ref>INCOSE 2010 Working Group Award http://www.incose.org/practice/techactivities/wg/transport/</ref>  (photo on the [[INCOSE]] Transportation Working Group page <ref>INCOSE Transportation Working Group  http://www.incose.org/practice/techactivities/wg/transport/</ref>). TRAK was a finalist for the 2011 IET Innovation Awards.<ref>IET Innovation Awards 2001 - Finalists http://conferences.theiet.org/innovation/finalists/index.cfm</ref>\n\n==Terminology==\n;Architecture Description Tuple\n:An architectural description element with a named type which has a named relationship to either the same or another architecture description element e.g. <<Organisation>> A 'has part' <<Job>> B. It follows the natural language construct of Subject - [[Predicate (mathematical logic)|Predicate]] - Object - also used in [[Resource Description Framework|RDF]]. See [[Tuple]]. TRAK requires each tuple to be explicit.\n\n;Master Architecture View\n:Each TRAK metamodel stereotype has a master architecture view type. Within an architecture description or model each element has to be declared or shown on its master architecture view type before it can be used on any other view type.\n\n;Perspective\n:[[ISO/IEC 42010]]:2007 refers to an Architectural Perspective as 'Sharing of architectural models also facilitates an \"aspect-oriented\" style of architectural description'<ref>[http://www.iso-architecture.org/ieee-1471/ ANSI/IEEE Std 1471 :: ISO/IEC 42010 Recommended Practice for Architectural Description of Software-Intensive Systems]</ref> A grouping of related and overlapping architectural views.\n\n;View\n:[[ISO/IEC 42010]] refers to an architecture view as 'work product expressing the architecture of a system from the perspective of specific system concerns'. A TRAK view is defined as an Architecture Product in the TRAK metamodel. A TRAK view presents a set of Architecture Description Tuples in accordance with its governing viewpoint.\n\n;Viewpoint\n:[[ISO/IEC 42010]]:2007 - A viewpoint defines a set of conventions (notations, languages and model types) for constructing a certain kind of view. In TRAK a viewpoint is a specification for a single TRAK view.\n\n==TRAK Structure==\nTRAK is defined in a logical way - that is to say free of any notion of how TRAK is implemented in any tool or any architecture description language.\n\nTRAK has 24 [[ISO/IEC 42010#Architecture Viewpoint|architecture viewpoints]] which are grouped into 5 perspectives. Each viewpoint belongs to a single perspective and specifies a single [[ISO/IEC 42010#Conceptual Model Architecture View|view]] (type). Each viewpoint specifies what sets of types of architectural description element and relationships (tuples) can appear. The architectural description element types and relationships are specified by the TRAK metamodel.\n\nThe logical definition of TRAK consists of 3 documents, each of which is an open source project on [[Sourceforge]]:\n* TRAK Enterprise Architecture Framework document.<ref name=\"trak\">[http://sourceforge.net/p/trak TRAK Enterprise Architecture Framework]</ref> This controls TRAK as a whole. It defines the TRAK Architecture Perspectives, colours, bye laws (rules affecting the design of TRAK, architecture views and architecture descriptions, minimal modelling process.\n* TRAK Enterprise Architecture Framework Viewpoints document.<ref name=\"viewpoints\">[http://sourceforge.net/p/trakviewpoints TRAK00001 TRAK. Enterprise Architecture Framework. Viewpoints]</ref> This defines the TRAK architecture viewpoints.\n* TRAK Enterprise Architecture Framework Metamodel document.<ref name=\"metamodel\">[http://sourceforge.net/p/trakmetamodel TRAK00002 TRAK. Enterprise Architecture Framework. Metamodel]</ref> This defines the architecture description elements that can appear in a viewpoint definition.\n\n==TRAK Architecture Perspectives==\nTRAK has 5 architecture perspectives,<ref name=\"trak\"/> each of which groups together architecture viewpoints and views of an overlapping subject area:\n* Enterprise Perspective\n* Concept Perspective\n* Procurement Perspective\n* Solution Perspective\n* Management Perspective\n\n===Enterprise Perspective===\nThis perspective covers the enduring capabilities that are needed as part of the bigger enterprise.These are high level needs that everything else contributes to and form part of the long term strategic objectives that need to be managed.\n\n===Concept Perspective===\nThe concept perspective covers the logical view of what is needed in response to the capabilities required by the enterprise in the enterprise perspective. It covers the logical connection of nodes, for example a service control centre, to other nodes with no recognition of how this might be realised either by organisation or technology. It also implies no particular part of a life cycle \u2013 it covers everything from concept to disposal (\"lust to dust\"!).\n\n===Procurement Perspective===\nThe procurement perspective provides a top level view of the solution to the enterprise capability needs outlined in the enterprise perspective and developed in the concept perspective. It provides a way of showing how projects deliver the solutions described in the solution perspective to provide capability. It provides a way of showing time dependency between projects and is an essential for investigating capability gaps.\n\n===Solution Perspective===\nThe solution perspective provides views about the solution \u2013 whether proposed or realised. It covers the parts of \u2018systems\u2019 whether human or machine, their exchanges and protocols. The solution perspective describes how organisations and equipment are organised and governed. The solution perspective describes how the logical requirements outlined in the concept perspective are realised and shows how the solution(s) realise the capability needed by the enterprise and described in the enterprise perspective.\n\n===Management Perspective===\nThe management perspective provides views that describe the architectural task and those relationships that are common across other perspectives. It provides ways of defining the scope and findings of the architectural task - structuring the approach and modelling.\n\nThe management perspective provides ways of describing the normative standards that apply. It contains views that provide supporting information to aid the portability and understanding of the model(s).\n\n==TRAK Architecture Viewpoints & Views==\nEach [[ISO/IEC 42010#Conceptual Model - Architecture View|architecture view]] in TRAK is specified by a corresponding [[ISO/IEC 42010#Architecture Viewpoint|architecture viewpoint]]. The viewpoint is designated using a 'p' in the numbering e.g. a CVp-01 is the architecture viewpoint that specifies a CV-01 architecture view.\n\nIn general use if there is a risk of confusion with a similarly-numbered view in another framework such as [[DODAF]] or [[MODAF]] then a namespace prefix is used e.g. TRAK::SV-01\n\nTRAK defines 24 architecture viewpoints<ref name=\"viewpoints\"/> (by comparison DODAF 2.0 has 52 views/models, MODAF 1.2.004 has 47 views and NAF 3.1 has 49 subviews <ref>Trak-community.org::Wiki::Architecture Framework Comparison http://trak-community.org/index.php/wiki/Architecture_Framework_Comparison</ref>)\n* Enterprise Perspective\n** EVp-01 Enterprise Goals\n** EVp-02 Capability Hierarchy\n** EVp-03 Capability Phasing\n* Concept Perspective\n** CVp-01 Concept Need\n** CVp-03 Concept Item Exchange\n** CVp-04 Concept Activity to Capability Mapping\n** CVp-05 Concept Activity\n** CVp-06 Concept Sequence\n* Procurement Perspective\n** PrVp-01 Procurement Structure\n** PrVp-02 Procurement Timeline\n** PrVp-03 Procurement Responsibility\n* Solution Perspective\n** SVp-01 Solution Structure\n** SVp-02 Solution Resource Interaction\n** SVp-03 Solution Resource Interaction to Function Mapping\n** SVp-04 Solution Function\n** SVp-05 Solution Function to Concept Activity Mapping\n** SVp-06 Solution Competence\n** SVp-07 Solution Sequence\n** SVp-11 Solution Event Causes\n** SVp-13 Solution Risk\n* Management Perspective\n** MVp-01 Architecture Description Dictionary\n** MVp-02 Architecture Description Design Record\n** MVp-03 Requirements & Standards\n** MVp-04 Assurance\n\nThese defined in the TRAK Viewpoints specification. Additional information is provided in a community wiki.<ref>http://trak-community.org/index.php/wiki/TRAK:TRAK_Viewpoints</ref>\n\n==TRAK Metamodel==\n[[File:TRAK_metamodel_part_1.jpg|thumb|Metamodel for the TRAK enterprise architecture framework. Defines Allowed Metamodel Elements including Relationships for Use in TRAK Architecture Descriptions.]]\n[[File:TRAK_metamodel_part_2_safety_security.jpg|thumb|Defines the Architecture Description Elements (the triples / tuples that may appear in TRAK architecture views) that describe safety, security and risk.]]\n[[File:TRAK metamodel part 3 management.jpg|thumb|Part of the TRAK metamodel (used in the TRAK enterprise architecture framework). Describes the management perspective elements and their relationships (tuples).]]\n\nThe TRAK Metamodel<ref name=\"metamodel\"/> both simplifies and extends the basic concepts within the MODAF 1.2 metamodel. It has removed and redefined stereotypes and any defence-specific constructs have been removed. The TRAK Metamodel specification contains a comparison of the TRAK metamodel at initial release against MODAF 1.2.003. This is also outlined separately.<ref>http://trak-community.org/index.php/wiki/TRAK:Initial_TRAK_Baseline_vs_MODAF_-_Stereotypes</ref>\n\nThe TRAK metamodel is shown below. ''Note that this is not a controlled copy''.\n\nSignificant changes vs MODAF include:\n* the TRAK metamodel is aimed at users (the MODAF M3 is an abstract UML profile intended as a specification for tool vendors to implement MODAF - there is no metamodel for users only fragments of 'simplified metamodel' which aim to represent the more complicated M3). In TRAK the metamodel shown is the master one.\n* System is central to TRAK and can represent [[hard systems]] and [[soft systems]] (in MODAF 1.2.003 System is an artefact<ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/38715/20100426MODAFSVViewpointV1_2_004U.pdf MODAF Metamodel 1.2.004 MODAF version 1.2.004]</ref> and part of the Physical Architecture and cannot include non physical parts<ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/38715/20100426MODAFSVViewpointV1_2_004U.pdf The MODAF System Viewpoint(SV) 26 April 2010]</ref> )\n* TRAK can represent any type of interface exchange / flow - information, energy or resource\n* TRAK can represent exchange characteristics associated with human resources - Organisations, Jobs and Roles\n* TRAK includes means to represent requirements through the Standard (document/collection) and Requirement (atomic) metamodel elements and enforced by Contract\n* TRAK includes the means to plan and describe the architecture task and architecture description and its organisation as a view (MV-02 Architecture Description Design Record)\n* other types of dependency and associations can be represented - physical, membership, responsibility extent\n* TRAK includes the means to describe assurance cases (including design verification) using the Claim - Argument - Evidence construct\n* TRAK includes the means to describe safety / security - threats/hazards, vulnerabilities, mitigations and risk and causes / impacts\n* addition of ISO/IEC 42010 concepts to represent the architectural task, architecture description and architecture views - to allow a description of the task scope, purpose, findings\n* addition of consistency rules for content that apply to the entire collection of views and context to improve navigation and visibility of content\n* rules that constrain how and in what order relationships can be made to improve the consistency of the set of views that forms the architecture description\n\nStructurally there are other changes:\n* TRAK has 24 viewpoints (vs c 47 views in MODAF)\n* the each viewpoint content is defined in terms of tuples (a node - relationship - node element construct i.e. a triple or 1,[[Tuple|tuple]] ) and has allowed and minimum acceptable content and correspondence rules with respect to other views within the architecture description because this is needed to specify a uniquely addressable path in a metamodel (specifying a block metamodel element is not sufficient on its own where there are several relationships involving the element). \n* Since ISO/IEC/IEEE 42010:2011 defines architecture in terms of the relationship of a system to its environment the smallest unit of architecture description that may appear in a TRAK architecture view is therefore the Architecture Description Tuple i.e. node - relationship - node.\n\nThe way in which TRAK is managed and released via a set of open source projects is also quite different from other enterprise architecture frameworks. All change requests and feature requests and the sentencing of them are fully visible to anyone, not restricted to those who specify or develop the framework.<ref>Sourceforge. TRAK Project Bug/Change Trackers. http://sourceforge.net/tracker/?group_id=393432</ref><ref>Sourceforge. TRAK Metamodel Project Bug/Change Trackers. http://sourceforge.net/tracker/?group_id=304403</ref><ref>Sourceforge. TRAK Viewpoints Project Bug/Change Trackers. http://sourceforge.net/tracker/?group_id=304405</ref> Releases are under change control and all history is maintained by versioning software ([[Subversion (software)|Subversion (SVN)]]).\n\n==Presentation of TRAK Views==\nTRAK does not specify a notation or presentation language ([[ISO/IEC 42010#Architecture Description Language|architecture description language]] in ISO/IEC 42010 terminology) in which to present the architecture views. TRAK architecture descriptions are not therefore [[Unified Modeling Language|UML]], [[SysML]] or [[BPMN]] models although any of these notations  can be used to prepare at least some of the views (an ADL might not contain the necessary concepts/stereotypes or might not allow them to be connected in the way needed to represent a TRAK architecture view).\n\nTRAK requires the metamodel element name of every architecture description element in a TRAK architecture view to be explicitly shown so that each TRAK view can be read as a set of declarative statements e.g. \n* ''''System'''. A ''  -is configured with->  '' '''Software'''. B'\n* ''''Claim'''. System A meets the requirement to ... ''  -about->  '' '''Standard'''. Climatic Environmental Specification.'\n* ''''Physical'''. Shield Building ''  -has->   '' '''Vulnerability'''. Structural Weakness ''  <-exploits-  '' '''Threat'''. Deliberate Aircraft Impact'\n\nTuples can be presented using nodes and relationships (a graph).\n[[File:Example TRAK SV 13.jpg|frame|center|Example TRAK SV-13 Solution Risk View Presented as a Graph Showing Tuples from the TRAK Metamodel]]\n\nTRAK also allows a view to be constructed from textual statements. Since a TRAK view is a set of [[Tuple#Etymology|tuples / triples]] it is possible to use a graph or a set of [[Resource Description Framework|RDF]] triples to present a TRAK view. TRAK also requires every block to have a name. The intent of this is to ensure that a TRAK architecture view is read as the author of the view meant it and improve semantic consistency. Presentation rules that apply to all TRAK architecture views are specified in the overall TRAK specification <ref name=\"trak\"/><ref>[http://sourceforge.net/p/trak TRAK Enterprise Architecture]</ref> (as 'Bye Laws').\n\nTRAK is a logical definition - it specifies what needs to be shown and minimum acceptable content but does not mandate how you achieve it. TRAK simply defines the node and connector elements and the allowed combinations (triples) that must / may appear in each view. It does not specify or mandate any particular notation or language. For example a simple block and connector diagram (as above) is acceptable as is a set of plain text staments or a diagram using the [[Unified_Modeling_Language|UML]].\n\n==ISO 42010 Considerations==\nTRAK applies [[ISO/IEC 42010]] in the following ways:-\n* an architecture description is a response to a task which addresses a stakeholder's concerns (this is addressed using the TRAK::MVp-02 Architecture Description Design Record Viewpoint)\n* each TRAK architecture view is specified by a viewpoint within the TRAK architecture framework\n* each TRAK viewpoint identifies the stakeholders, concerns addressed, anti-concerns (things the viewpoint is not to be used for), the metamodel tuples needed, the metamodel tuples allowed, well-formedness (minimum acceptable content) and consistency rules with other views within the architecture description\n* correspondence rules are defined by viewpoints and for an architecture description using the TRAK metamodel.\n\nAn overall comparison between TRAK and [[ISO/IEC 42010]] is made in the TRAK Enterprise Architecture Framework document. A more detailed comparison against the 2011 version of the standard is made separately <ref name=\"TRAK00015\">TRAK00015 TRAK. \nArchitecture Description. Summary. Conformance Assessment \u2013 ISO/IEC/IEEE 42010:2011. http://sourceforge.net/projects/trak/files/ISO%2042010/TRAK00015_TRAK_AD_Summary_Conformance_with_42010_2011.pdf/download</ref> and is viewable as a set of web pages.<ref name=\"TRAK00013\">TRAK00013 TRAK. Architecture Description. Conformance Assessment \u2013 ISO/IEC/IEEE 42010:2011 http://trak.sourceforge.net/TRAK%20vs%20ISO_42010_AD/index.htm</ref> These, together with a compliance matrix,<ref name=\"TRAK00014\">TRAK00014 TRAK. Compliance Matrix. Conformance Assessment \u2013 ISO/IEC/IEEE 42010:2011 http://sourceforge.net/projects/trak/files/ISO%2042010/TRAK00014_TRAK_vs_ISO42010_compliance.ods/download</ref> compare:-\n# TRAK as an architecture framework against the requirements of section 6.1 (Architecture Frameworks) of ISO/IEC/IEEE 42010:2011 and; \n# a TRAK-conforming architecture description against section 5 (Architecture Descriptions) of ISO/IEC/IEEE 42010:2011.\n\n==Creating an Architecture Description Using TRAK==\nTRAK itself does not mandate process. There is an element of process introduced, however, because TRAK adheres to ISO/IEC 42010 which states that an architecture description is produced in response to a task and the task stakeholder concerns and also because TRAK has master architecture views which creates dependencies between views and results in minimum allowed architecture view sets.\n\nThis gives rise to a minimal process which is:\n* identify the task stakeholder and their [[#Conceptual Model - Concern|concerns]]\n* using the TRAK Viewpoints select the Viewpoints needed to address the stakeholder concerns\n* develop [[#Conceptual Model - Architecture View|views]] that conform to these viewpoints that address these concerns\n* these in turn may require additional views to be prepared to form a legitimate allowed view set\n* document the purpose, concerns, findings and the [[#Conceptual Model - Architecture Description|architecture description]] using a MV-02 Architecture Design Record View supplemented by a MV-01 Architecture Dictionary View\n\n==Licensing==\nTRAK is released under 2 forms of open source license:\n* GNU Free Documentation License ([[Gfdl|GFDL]]) for the logical definition - TRAK Overall, TRAK Metamodel and TRAK Viewpoints documents\n* GNU Public License ([[Gpl|GPL]]) for implementations of TRAK - UML profile for TRAK for general UML modelling tools and TRAK MDG Technology for [[Sparx Systems]] [[Enterprise Architect (software)|Enterprise Architect]] modelling tool.\n\n==Tool Support==\nTRAK supports modelling tools through the following mechanisms:\n* a [[Profile (UML)|UML profile]] for TRAK - for use with any [[UML tool|UML modelling tool]] that can import a UML profile\n* a plugin for [[Sparx Systems]] [[Enterprise Architect (software)|Enterprise Architect]] based on the UML profile for TRAK. Released as open source on Sourceforge <ref>[http://mdgfortrak.sourceforge.net MDG Technology for TRAK]</ref>\n* a template for [http://www.moodinternational.com/ MooD International's] [http://www.moodinternational.com/moodplatform.html MooD 2010 software platform] (developed by [http://vega.co.uk/ Vega Consulting Services Ltd] - part of [[Leonardo S.p.A.|Leonardo]]). Released as open source on Sourceforge.<ref>[http://sourceforge.net/projects/trakmoodtemp/ trakmoodtemp Project on Sourceforge]</ref>\n* a stencil for [[OmniGraffle]] ([[Mac OS X]], [[iPad]]). Released as open source on Sourceforge.<ref>[http://sourceforge.net/projects/trakomnigraffle/ trakomnigraffle Project on Sourceforge]</ref>\n* a template for [[Microsoft Visio]]. Released as open source on Sourceforge.<ref>[http://sourceforge.net/projects/trakforvisio/ trakforvisio Project on Sourceforge]</ref>\n\nA comparison of the stereotype (concepts) in the UML against those in the TRAK Metamodel <ref>[http://sourceforge.net/projects/trak/files/Suitability_of_Architecture_Description_Languages/UML/ trak project on Sourceforge]</ref> provides an analysis, for the UML Profile for TRAK, what TRAK Viewpoints and therefore TRAK Views UML is able to represent fully, partially and not at all. This is a consequence of the constructs available in UML and the particular implementation in the UML Profile for TRAK and arises because different architecture description languages ([[Architecture description language|ADLs]]) are often design for different purposes and sometimes different domains i.e. in ISO/IEC 42010 the concerns they address are different from those that the architecture framework, in this case TRAK, does.\n\nAs tools represent an implementation of the logical definition of TRAK they may contain limitations or errors owing to the notation language (architecture description language) used and tool-specific capabilities.\n\n==Examples of Architecture Description Using TRAK==\n* Sub Surface Upgrade Programme (SSUP). Upgrade of signalling and rolling stock for Circle, Hammersmith, Metropolitan and District lines on London Underground. Cited in Rail Value for Money Study. Whole System Programme Management Report. 25 May 2011.<ref name=\"rvfm_whole_system\"/>\n* Technical Strategy Leadership Group (TSLG). Railway Functional Architecture<ref>Technical Strategy Leadership Group (TSLG). Railway Functional Architecture. http://www.futurerailway.org/Research/Pages/Railway-Function-Architecture.aspx</ref>\n* Rail Safety & Standards Board (RSSB). UK Railway Functional Architecture. Ongoing research - RSSB Research & Development E-newsletter. Issue 66. Oct. 2010.<ref>RSSB Research & Development E-newsletter. Issue 66. Oct. 2010. Topic T912 The Railway Functional Architecture http://www.rssb.co.uk/SiteCollectionDocuments/research/enews/rd_enewsletter66.htm</ref> Justification for the selection/use of TRAK is provided in the summary report for the task.<ref>The Railway Functional Architecture Summary Report http://www.rssb.co.uk/sitecollectiondocuments/pdf/reports/research/T912_rpt_final.pdf</ref> The T912 railway functional architecture project is described separately.<ref>RSSB. Project T912 The Railway Functional Architecture. http://www.rssb.co.uk/RESEARCH/Lists/DispForm_Custom.aspx?ID=955</ref> The Railway Functional Architecture is made available as a set of HTML pages.<ref>The Railway Functional Architecture (HTML) http://www.futurerailway.org/research/Pages/EA%20HTML/index.htm</ref> \n* University of Birmingham. InfraGuidER (Infrastructure Guidelines for Environmental Railway Performance) deliverables 9 and 18.,<ref>InfraGuidER Deliverables http://www.infraguider.eu/prodotti_7.html</ref> minutes: D22: 2nd Workshop for EURNEX (European Rail Research Network of Excellence) poles of excellences <ref>Minutes: D22: 2nd Workshop for EURNEX poles of excellences  http://infraguider.eu/doc/INFRAG_WP5_NIT_DV_022_B.pdf</ref>\n* Integrated EA 2011. Managing Risk and Cost with an EA Approach. Mike Brownsword (Atego) & Joe Silmon (Centre for Railway Research and Education).,<ref>Integrated EA 2011: Managing Risk and Cost with an EA Approach http://www.integrated-ea.com/file_download/101/</ref>\n* An architecture description<ref name=\"TRAK00013\"/> describing the claims of compliance of TRAK as an architecture framework and a TRAK-conforming architecture description against the requirements of ISO/IEC/IEEE 42010:2011. Includes examples of the following views: MV-02 Architecture Description Design Record, MV-03 Requirements and Standards and MV-04 Assurance. The underlying model was then used to produce the compliance matrix<ref name=\"TRAK00014\"/> as an example of [[Model-based systems engineering|Model-Based Systems Engineering]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://sourceforge.net/p/trak TRAK Enterprise Architecture]\n* [http://trakumlprofile.sourceforge.net UML Profile for TRAK]\n* [http://trak-community.org TRAK Community support site]\n\n[[Category:Enterprise architecture frameworks]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{primary sources|date=April 2010}}\n\n[[File:TRAK enterpriseArchitectureFramework structure.jpg|thumb|480px|Structure of TRAK - formed from 1 metamodel, 5 architecture perspectives and 24 architecture viewpoints]]\n'''TRAK''' is a general [[Enterprise Architecture framework|enterprise architecture framework]] aimed at systems engineers based on [[MODAF]] 1.2.\n\n==History==\nTRAK was originally commissioned by London Underground Limited.<ref>[http://www.theiet.org/forums/forum/messageview.cfm?catid=227&threadid=32342 IET Forums - TRAK - The Rail Architecture Framework]</ref><ref name=\"rvfm_whole_system\">Rail Value for Money Study. Whole System Programme Management Report. 25 May 2011 http://www.rail-reg.gov.uk/upload/pdf/rvfm-atkins-programme-management-250511.pdf</ref> Development started in 2009 and was based on the then current views of architectural description within London Underground which were based on ISO/IEC 42010 and tied to the [[Systems Engineering|systems engineering]] lifecyle defined in [[ISO/IEC 15288]] .\n\nAlthough the original intent was to develop a rail-specific architecture framework in adapting MODAF to suit local needs any defence or domain-specific content was removed and the result was a domain-free [[#TRAK Metamodel|metamodel]] and viewpoints that were only based on representing [[complex systems]].\n\nTRAK was [[#Licensing|released under open source licenses]] in February 2010.\n\nIt has been formally adopted by the [[Department for Transport|UK Department for Transport]] who chair the TRAK Steering Group that manages the overall direction, strategy and formal releases of TRAK.\n\nThe TRAK development team received a Working Group award.<ref>INCOSE 2010 Working Group Award http://www.incose.org/practice/techactivities/wg/transport/</ref>  (photo on the [[INCOSE]] Transportation Working Group page <ref>INCOSE Transportation Working Group  http://www.incose.org/practice/techactivities/wg/transport/</ref>). TRAK was a finalist for the 2011 IET Innovation Awards.<ref>IET Innovation Awards 2001 - Finalists http://conferences.theiet.org/innovation/finalists/index.cfm</ref>\n\n==Terminology==\n;Architecture Description Tuple\n:An architectural description element with a named type which has a named relationship to either the same or another architecture description element e.g. <<Organisation>> A 'has part' <<Job>> B. It follows the natural language construct of Subject - [[Predicate (mathematical logic)|Predicate]] - Object - also used in [[Resource Description Framework|RDF]]. See [[Tuple]]. TRAK requires each tuple to be explicit.\n\n;Master Architecture View\n:Each TRAK metamodel stereotype has a master architecture view type. Within an architecture description or model each element has to be declared or shown on its master architecture view type before it can be used on any other view type.\n\n;Perspective\n:[[ISO/IEC 42010]]:2007 refers to an Architectural Perspective as 'Sharing of architectural models also facilitates an \"aspect-oriented\" style of architectural description'<ref>[http://www.iso-architecture.org/ieee-1471/ ANSI/IEEE Std 1471 :: ISO/IEC 42010 Recommended Practice for Architectural Description of Software-Intensive Systems]</ref> A grouping of related and overlapping architectural views.\n\n;View\n:[[ISO/IEC 42010]] refers to an architecture view as 'work product expressing the architecture of a system from the perspective of specific system concerns'. A TRAK view is defined as an Architecture Product in the TRAK metamodel. A TRAK view presents a set of Architecture Description Tuples in accordance with its governing viewpoint.\n\n;Viewpoint\n:[[ISO/IEC 42010]]:2007 - A viewpoint defines a set of conventions (notations, languages and model types) for constructing a certain kind of view. In TRAK a viewpoint is a specification for a single TRAK view.\n\n==TRAK Structure==\nTRAK is defined in a logical way - that is to say free of any notion of how TRAK is implemented in any tool or any architecture description language.\n\nTRAK has 24 [[ISO/IEC 42010#Architecture Viewpoint|architecture viewpoints]] which are grouped into 5 perspectives. Each viewpoint belongs to a single perspective and specifies a single [[ISO/IEC 42010#Conceptual Model Architecture View|view]] (type). Each viewpoint specifies what sets of types of architectural description element and relationships (tuples) can appear. The architectural description element types and relationships are specified by the TRAK metamodel.\n\nThe logical definition of TRAK consists of 3 documents, each of which is an open source project on [[Sourceforge]]:\n* TRAK Enterprise Architecture Framework document.<ref name=\"trak\">[http://sourceforge.net/p/trak TRAK Enterprise Architecture Framework]</ref> This controls TRAK as a whole. It defines the TRAK Architecture Perspectives, colours, bye laws (rules affecting the design of TRAK, architecture views and architecture descriptions, minimal modelling process.\n* TRAK Enterprise Architecture Framework Viewpoints document.<ref name=\"viewpoints\">[http://sourceforge.net/p/trakviewpoints TRAK00001 TRAK. Enterprise Architecture Framework. Viewpoints]</ref> This defines the TRAK architecture viewpoints.\n* TRAK Enterprise Architecture Framework Metamodel document.<ref name=\"metamodel\">[http://sourceforge.net/p/trakmetamodel TRAK00002 TRAK. Enterprise Architecture Framework. Metamodel]</ref> This defines the architecture description elements that can appear in a viewpoint definition.\n\n==TRAK Architecture Perspectives==\nTRAK has 5 architecture perspectives,<ref name=\"trak\"/> each of which groups together architecture viewpoints and views of an overlapping subject area:\n* Enterprise Perspective\n* Concept Perspective\n* Procurement Perspective\n* Solution Perspective\n* Management Perspective\n\n===Enterprise Perspective===\nThis perspective covers the enduring capabilities that are needed as part of the bigger enterprise.These are high level needs that everything else contributes to and form part of the long term strategic objectives that need to be managed.\n\n===Concept Perspective===\nThe concept perspective covers the logical view of what is needed in response to the capabilities required by the enterprise in the enterprise perspective. It covers the logical connection of nodes, for example a service control centre, to other nodes with no recognition of how this might be realised either by organisation or technology. It also implies no particular part of a life cycle \u2013 it covers everything from concept to disposal (\"lust to dust\"!).\n\n===Procurement Perspective===\nThe procurement perspective provides a top level view of the solution to the enterprise capability needs outlined in the enterprise perspective and developed in the concept perspective. It provides a way of showing how projects deliver the solutions described in the solution perspective to provide capability. It provides a way of showing time dependency between projects and is an essential for investigating capability gaps.\n\n===Solution Perspective===\nThe solution perspective provides views about the solution \u2013 whether proposed or realised. It covers the parts of \u2018systems\u2019 whether human or machine, their exchanges and protocols. The solution perspective describes how organisations and equipment are organised and governed. The solution perspective describes how the logical requirements outlined in the concept perspective are realised and shows how the solution(s) realise the capability needed by the enterprise and described in the enterprise perspective.\n\n===Management Perspective===\nThe management perspective provides views that describe the architectural task and those relationships that are common across other perspectives. It provides ways of defining the scope and findings of the architectural task - structuring the approach and modelling.\n\nThe management perspective provides ways of describing the normative standards that apply. It contains views that provide supporting information to aid the portability and understanding of the model(s).\n\n==TRAK Architecture Viewpoints & Views==\nEach [[ISO/IEC 42010#Conceptual Model - Architecture View|architecture view]] in TRAK is specified by a corresponding [[ISO/IEC 42010#Architecture Viewpoint|architecture viewpoint]]. The viewpoint is designated using a 'p' in the numbering e.g. a CVp-01 is the architecture viewpoint that specifies a CV-01 architecture view.\n\nIn general use if there is a risk of confusion with a similarly-numbered view in another framework such as [[DODAF]] or [[MODAF]] then a namespace prefix is used e.g. TRAK::SV-01\n\nTRAK defines 24 architecture viewpoints<ref name=\"viewpoints\"/> (by comparison DODAF 2.0 has 52 views/models, MODAF 1.2.004 has 47 views and NAF 3.1 has 49 subviews <ref>Trak-community.org::Wiki::Architecture Framework Comparison http://trak-community.org/index.php/wiki/Architecture_Framework_Comparison</ref>)\n* Enterprise Perspective\n** EVp-01 Enterprise Goals\n** EVp-02 Capability Hierarchy\n** EVp-03 Capability Phasing\n* Concept Perspective\n** CVp-01 Concept Need\n** CVp-03 Concept Item Exchange\n** CVp-04 Concept Activity to Capability Mapping\n** CVp-05 Concept Activity\n** CVp-06 Concept Sequence\n* Procurement Perspective\n** PrVp-01 Procurement Structure\n** PrVp-02 Procurement Timeline\n** PrVp-03 Procurement Responsibility\n* Solution Perspective\n** SVp-01 Solution Structure\n** SVp-02 Solution Resource Interaction\n** SVp-03 Solution Resource Interaction to Function Mapping\n** SVp-04 Solution Function\n** SVp-05 Solution Function to Concept Activity Mapping\n** SVp-06 Solution Competence\n** SVp-07 Solution Sequence\n** SVp-11 Solution Event Causes\n** SVp-13 Solution Risk\n* Management Perspective\n** MVp-01 Architecture Description Dictionary\n** MVp-02 Architecture Description Design Record\n** MVp-03 Requirements & Standards\n** MVp-04 Assurance\n\nThese defined in the TRAK Viewpoints specification. Additional information is provided in a community wiki.<ref>http://trak-community.org/index.php/wiki/TRAK:TRAK_Viewpoints</ref>\n\n==TRAK Metamodel==\n[[File:TRAK_metamodel_part_1.jpg|thumb|Metamodel for the TRAK enterprise architecture framework. Defines Allowed Metamodel Elements including Relationships for Use in TRAK Architecture Descriptions.]]\n[[File:TRAK_metamodel_part_2_safety_security.jpg|thumb|Defines the Architecture Description Elements (the triples / tuples that may appear in TRAK architecture views) that describe safety, security and risk.]]\n[[File:TRAK metamodel part 3 management.jpg|thumb|Part of the TRAK metamodel (used in the TRAK enterprise architecture framework). Describes the management perspective elements and their relationships (tuples).]]\n\nThe TRAK Metamodel<ref name=\"metamodel\"/> both simplifies and extends the basic concepts within the MODAF 1.2 metamodel. It has removed and redefined stereotypes and any defence-specific constructs have been removed. The TRAK Metamodel specification contains a comparison of the TRAK metamodel at initial release against MODAF 1.2.003. This is also outlined separately.<ref>http://trak-community.org/index.php/wiki/TRAK:Initial_TRAK_Baseline_vs_MODAF_-_Stereotypes</ref>\n\nThe TRAK metamodel is shown below. ''Note that this is not a controlled copy''.\n\nSignificant changes vs MODAF include:\n* the TRAK metamodel is aimed at users (the MODAF M3 is an abstract UML profile intended as a specification for tool vendors to implement MODAF - there is no metamodel for users only fragments of 'simplified metamodel' which aim to represent the more complicated M3). In TRAK the metamodel shown is the master one.\n* System is central to TRAK and can represent [[hard systems]] and [[soft systems]] (in MODAF 1.2.003 System is an artefact<ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/38715/20100426MODAFSVViewpointV1_2_004U.pdf MODAF Metamodel 1.2.004 MODAF version 1.2.004]</ref> and part of the Physical Architecture and cannot include non physical parts<ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/38715/20100426MODAFSVViewpointV1_2_004U.pdf The MODAF System Viewpoint(SV) 26 April 2010]</ref> )\n* TRAK can represent any type of interface exchange / flow - information, energy or resource\n* TRAK can represent exchange characteristics associated with human resources - Organisations, Jobs and Roles\n* TRAK includes means to represent requirements through the Standard (document/collection) and Requirement (atomic) metamodel elements and enforced by Contract\n* TRAK includes the means to plan and describe the architecture task and architecture description and its organisation as a view (MV-02 Architecture Description Design Record)\n* other types of dependency and associations can be represented - physical, membership, responsibility extent\n* TRAK includes the means to describe assurance cases (including design verification) using the Claim - Argument - Evidence construct\n* TRAK includes the means to describe safety / security - threats/hazards, vulnerabilities, mitigations and risk and causes / impacts\n* addition of ISO/IEC 42010 concepts to represent the architectural task, architecture description and architecture views - to allow a description of the task scope, purpose, findings\n* addition of consistency rules for content that apply to the entire collection of views and context to improve navigation and visibility of content\n* rules that constrain how and in what order relationships can be made to improve the consistency of the set of views that forms the architecture description\n\nStructurally there are other changes:\n* TRAK has 24 viewpoints (vs c 47 views in MODAF)\n* the each viewpoint content is defined in terms of tuples (a node - relationship - node element construct i.e. a triple or 1,[[Tuple|tuple]] ) and has allowed and minimum acceptable content and correspondence rules with respect to other views within the architecture description because this is needed to specify a uniquely addressable path in a metamodel (specifying a block metamodel element is not sufficient on its own where there are several relationships involving the element). \n* Since ISO/IEC/IEEE 42010:2011 defines architecture in terms of the relationship of a system to its environment the smallest unit of architecture description that may appear in a TRAK architecture view is therefore the Architecture Description Tuple i.e. node - relationship - node.\n\nThe way in which TRAK is managed and released via a set of open source projects is also quite different from other enterprise architecture frameworks. All change requests and feature requests and the sentencing of them are fully visible to anyone, not restricted to those who specify or develop the framework.<ref>Sourceforge. TRAK Project Bug/Change Trackers. http://sourceforge.net/tracker/?group_id=393432</ref><ref>Sourceforge. TRAK Metamodel Project Bug/Change Trackers. http://sourceforge.net/tracker/?group_id=304403</ref><ref>Sourceforge. TRAK Viewpoints Project Bug/Change Trackers. http://sourceforge.net/tracker/?group_id=304405</ref> Releases are under change control and all history is maintained by versioning software ([[Subversion (software)|Subversion (SVN)]]).\n\n==Presentation of TRAK Views==\nTRAK does not specify a notation or presentation language ([[ISO/IEC 42010#Architecture Description Language|architecture description language]] in ISO/IEC 42010 terminology) in which to present the architecture views. TRAK architecture descriptions are not therefore [[Unified Modeling Language|UML]], [[SysML]] or [[BPMN]] models although any of these notations  can be used to prepare at least some of the views (an ADL might not contain the necessary concepts/stereotypes or might not allow them to be connected in the way needed to represent a TRAK architecture view).\n\nTRAK requires the metamodel element name of every architecture description element in a TRAK architecture view to be explicitly shown so that each TRAK view can be read as a set of declarative statements e.g. \n* ''''System'''. A ''  -is configured with->  '' '''Software'''. B'\n* ''''Claim'''. System A meets the requirement to ... ''  -about->  '' '''Standard'''. Climatic Environmental Specification.'\n* ''''Physical'''. Shield Building ''  -has->   '' '''Vulnerability'''. Structural Weakness ''  <-exploits-  '' '''Threat'''. Deliberate Aircraft Impact'\n\nTuples can be presented using nodes and relationships (a graph).\n[[File:Example TRAK SV 13.jpg|frame|center|Example TRAK SV-13 Solution Risk View Presented as a Graph Showing Tuples from the TRAK Metamodel]]\n\nTRAK also allows a view to be constructed from textual statements. Since a TRAK view is a set of [[Tuple#Etymology|tuples / triples]] it is possible to use a graph or a set of [[Resource Description Framework|RDF]] triples to present a TRAK view. TRAK also requires every block to have a name. The intent of this is to ensure that a TRAK architecture view is read as the author of the view meant it and improve semantic consistency. Presentation rules that apply to all TRAK architecture views are specified in the overall TRAK specification <ref name=\"trak\"/><ref>[http://sourceforge.net/p/trak TRAK Enterprise Architecture]</ref> (as 'Bye Laws').\n\nTRAK is a logical definition - it specifies what needs to be shown and minimum acceptable content but does not mandate how you achieve it. TRAK simply defines the node and connector elements and the allowed combinations (triples) that must / may appear in each view. It does not specify or mandaye any particular notation or language. For example a simple block and connector diagram (as above) is acceptable as is a set of plain text staments or a diagram using the [[Unified_Modeling_Language|UML]].\n\n==ISO 42010 Considerations==\nTRAK applies [[ISO/IEC 42010]] in the following ways:-\n* an architecture description is a response to a task which addresses a stakeholder's concerns (this is addressed using the TRAK::MVp-02 Architecture Description Design Record Viewpoint)\n* each TRAK architecture view is specified by a viewpoint within the TRAK architecture framework\n* each TRAK viewpoint identifies the stakeholders, concerns addressed, anti-concerns (things the viewpoint is not to be used for), the metamodel tuples needed, the metamodel tuples allowed, well-formedness (minimum acceptable content) and consistency rules with other views within the architecture description\n* correspondence rules are defined by viewpoints and for an architecture description using the TRAK metamodel.\n\nAn overall comparison between TRAK and [[ISO/IEC 42010]] is made in the TRAK Enterprise Architecture Framework document. A more detailed comparison against the 2011 version of the standard is made separately <ref name=\"TRAK00015\">TRAK00015 TRAK. \nArchitecture Description. Summary. Conformance Assessment \u2013 ISO/IEC/IEEE 42010:2011. http://sourceforge.net/projects/trak/files/ISO%2042010/TRAK00015_TRAK_AD_Summary_Conformance_with_42010_2011.pdf/download</ref> and is viewable as a set of web pages.<ref name=\"TRAK00013\">TRAK00013 TRAK. Architecture Description. Conformance Assessment \u2013 ISO/IEC/IEEE 42010:2011 http://trak.sourceforge.net/TRAK%20vs%20ISO_42010_AD/index.htm</ref> These, together with a compliance matrix,<ref name=\"TRAK00014\">TRAK00014 TRAK. Compliance Matrix. Conformance Assessment \u2013 ISO/IEC/IEEE 42010:2011 http://sourceforge.net/projects/trak/files/ISO%2042010/TRAK00014_TRAK_vs_ISO42010_compliance.ods/download</ref> compare:-\n# TRAK as an architecture framework against the requirements of section 6.1 (Architecture Frameworks) of ISO/IEC/IEEE 42010:2011 and; \n# a TRAK-conforming architecture description against section 5 (Architecture Descriptions) of ISO/IEC/IEEE 42010:2011.\n\n==Creating an Architecture Description Using TRAK==\nTRAK itself does not mandate process. There is an element of process introduced, however, because TRAK adheres to ISO/IEC 42010 which states that an architecture description is produced in response to a task and the task stakeholder concerns and also because TRAK has master architecture views which creates dependencies between views and results in minimum allowed architecture view sets.\n\nThis gives rise to a minimal process which is:\n* identify the task stakeholder and their [[#Conceptual Model - Concern|concerns]]\n* using the TRAK Viewpoints select the Viewpoints needed to address the stakeholder concerns\n* develop [[#Conceptual Model - Architecture View|views]] that conform to these viewpoints that address these concerns\n* these in turn may require additional views to be prepared to form a legitimate allowed view set\n* document the purpose, concerns, findings and the [[#Conceptual Model - Architecture Description|architecture description]] using a MV-02 Architecture Design Record View supplemented by a MV-01 Architecture Dictionary View\n\n==Licensing==\nTRAK is released under 2 forms of open source license:\n* GNU Free Documentation License ([[Gfdl|GFDL]]) for the logical definition - TRAK Overall, TRAK Metamodel and TRAK Viewpoints documents\n* GNU Public License ([[Gpl|GPL]]) for implementations of TRAK - UML profile for TRAK for general UML modelling tools and TRAK MDG Technology for [[Sparx Systems]] [[Enterprise Architect (software)|Enterprise Architect]] modelling tool.\n\n==Tool Support==\nTRAK supports modelling tools through the following mechanisms:\n* a [[Profile (UML)|UML profile]] for TRAK - for use with any [[UML tool|UML modelling tool]] that can import a UML profile\n* a plugin for [[Sparx Systems]] [[Enterprise Architect (software)|Enterprise Architect]] based on the UML profile for TRAK. Released as open source on Sourceforge <ref>[http://mdgfortrak.sourceforge.net MDG Technology for TRAK]</ref>\n* a template for [http://www.moodinternational.com/ MooD International's] [http://www.moodinternational.com/moodplatform.html MooD 2010 software platform] (developed by [http://vega.co.uk/ Vega Consulting Services Ltd] - part of [[Leonardo S.p.A.|Leonardo]]). Released as open source on Sourceforge.<ref>[http://sourceforge.net/projects/trakmoodtemp/ trakmoodtemp Project on Sourceforge]</ref>\n* a stencil for [[OmniGraffle]] ([[Mac OS X]], [[iPad]]). Released as open source on Sourceforge.<ref>[http://sourceforge.net/projects/trakomnigraffle/ trakomnigraffle Project on Sourceforge]</ref>\n* a template for [[Microsoft Visio]]. Released as open source on Sourceforge.<ref>[http://sourceforge.net/projects/trakforvisio/ trakforvisio Project on Sourceforge]</ref>\n\nA comparison of the stereotype (concepts) in the UML against those in the TRAK Metamodel <ref>[http://sourceforge.net/projects/trak/files/Suitability_of_Architecture_Description_Languages/UML/ trak project on Sourceforge]</ref> provides an analysis, for the UML Profile for TRAK, what TRAK Viewpoints and therefore TRAK Views UML is able to represent fully, partially and not at all. This is a consequence of the constructs available in UML and the particular implementation in the UML Profile for TRAK and arises because different architecture description languages ([[Architecture description language|ADLs]]) are often design for different purposes and sometimes different domains i.e. in ISO/IEC 42010 the concerns they address are different from those that the architecture framework, in this case TRAK, does.\n\nAs tools represent an implementation of the logical definition of TRAK they may contain limitations or errors owing to the notation language (architecture description language) used and tool-specific capabilities.\n\n==Examples of Architecture Description Using TRAK==\n* Sub Surface Upgrade Programme (SSUP). Upgrade of signalling and rolling stock for Circle, Hammersmith, Metropolitan and District lines on London Underground. Cited in Rail Value for Money Study. Whole System Programme Management Report. 25 May 2011.<ref name=\"rvfm_whole_system\"/>\n* Technical Strategy Leadership Group (TSLG). Railway Functional Architecture<ref>Technical Strategy Leadership Group (TSLG). Railway Functional Architecture. http://www.futurerailway.org/Research/Pages/Railway-Function-Architecture.aspx</ref>\n* Rail Safety & Standards Board (RSSB). UK Railway Functional Architecture. Ongoing research - RSSB Research & Development E-newsletter. Issue 66. Oct. 2010.<ref>RSSB Research & Development E-newsletter. Issue 66. Oct. 2010. Topic T912 The Railway Functional Architecture http://www.rssb.co.uk/SiteCollectionDocuments/research/enews/rd_enewsletter66.htm</ref> Justification for the selection/use of TRAK is provided in the summary report for the task.<ref>The Railway Functional Architecture Summary Report http://www.rssb.co.uk/sitecollectiondocuments/pdf/reports/research/T912_rpt_final.pdf</ref> The T912 railway functional architecture project is described separately.<ref>RSSB. Project T912 The Railway Functional Architecture. http://www.rssb.co.uk/RESEARCH/Lists/DispForm_Custom.aspx?ID=955</ref> The Railway Functional Architecture is made available as a set of HTML pages.<ref>The Railway Functional Architecture (HTML) http://www.futurerailway.org/research/Pages/EA%20HTML/index.htm</ref> \n* University of Birmingham. InfraGuidER (Infrastructure Guidelines for Environmental Railway Performance) deliverables 9 and 18.,<ref>InfraGuidER Deliverables http://www.infraguider.eu/prodotti_7.html</ref> minutes: D22: 2nd Workshop for EURNEX (European Rail Research Network of Excellence) poles of excellences <ref>Minutes: D22: 2nd Workshop for EURNEX poles of excellences  http://infraguider.eu/doc/INFRAG_WP5_NIT_DV_022_B.pdf</ref>\n* Integrated EA 2011. Managing Risk and Cost with an EA Approach. Mike Brownsword (Atego) & Joe Silmon (Centre for Railway Research and Education).,<ref>Integrated EA 2011: Managing Risk and Cost with an EA Approach http://www.integrated-ea.com/file_download/101/</ref>\n* An architecture description<ref name=\"TRAK00013\"/> describing the claims of compliance of TRAK as an architecture framework and a TRAK-conforming architecture description against the requirements of ISO/IEC/IEEE 42010:2011. Includes examples of the following views: MV-02 Architecture Description Design Record, MV-03 Requirements and Standards and MV-04 Assurance. The underlying model was then used to produce the compliance matrix<ref name=\"TRAK00014\"/> as an example of [[Model-based systems engineering|Model-Based Systems Engineering]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://sourceforge.net/p/trak TRAK Enterprise Architecture]\n* [http://trakumlprofile.sourceforge.net UML Profile for TRAK]\n* [http://trak-community.org TRAK Community support site]\n\n[[Category:Enterprise architecture frameworks]]\n", "name_user": "Wikitect", "label": "safe", "comment": 