  = \n|estate        = \n|meaning       = \n|footnotes     = \n}}\nThe old colonial American and [[Puritan]] '''Putnam''' family was founded by John and Margaret Gillam  Putnam in the [[17th century]], in [[Salem, Massachusetts]]. Many notable individuals are descendants of this family, including those listed below.\n\nJohn Putnam was born about 1580 and came from Aston Abbotts, Buckinghamshire, England. He was married to Priscilla Gould and they settled in Salem, Massachusetts. They were the parents of seven children: Elizabeth, Thomas, John, Nathaniel, Sara, Phoebe, and John. Their eldest son, Thomas, was the father of [[Thomas Putnam]] and Deacon Edward Putnam, who were involved in the Salem witch trials and were partially responsible for the executions of those convicted of witchcraft. <ref name=\"EbenPutnam\">{{Citation|last=Putnam|first=Eben|title=A History of the Putnam Family in England and America. Recording the Ancestry and Descendants of John Putnam of Danvers, Mass., Jan Poutman of Albany, N. Y., Thomas Putnam of Hartford, Conn, Volume 1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YN4UAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=October 4, 2007|year=1891|publisher=Salem Press Publishing and Printing Company}}</ref> \n\n==Notable members==\n*[[Albigence Waldo Putnam]] (1799\u20131869), historian\n*[[Ann Putnam, Jr.]] (1679\u20131716), accuser at [[Salem witch trials|Salem Witchcraft trials]]\n*[[Brenda Putnam]] (1890\u20131975), sculptor\n*[[Carleton Putnam]] (c. 1902\u20131998), aviator, activist & author <!--Not in tree-->\n*[[David Putnam]] (1898\u20131918), World War I air ace\n*[[Frederic Ward Putnam]] (1839\u20131915), American anthropologist, Harvard University\n*[[George Putnam (businessman)|George Putnam]] (1889\u20131960), great-great-grandson of Judge Samuel Putnam, founder of [[Putnam Investments]]; his son George Putnam, retired Chairman Putnam Investments; and grandson [[George Putnam III]], Chairman, [[Putnam Investments]]\n*[[George D. Putnam]] (born 1948), screenwriter <!--Not in tree-->\n*[[George Haven Putnam]] (1844\u20131930), book entrepreneur & publishing-family member\n*[[George Palmer Putnam]] (1814\u20131872), book entrepreneur\n*[[George P. Putnam]] (1887\u20131950), publisher, author, explorer, & publishing-family & aviation-family member\n*[[Gideon Putnam]] (1763\u20131812), entrepreneur\n*[[Herbert Putnam]] (1861\u20131955), American library administrator & publishing-family member\n*[[Israel Putnam]] (1718\u20131790), American General\n*[[James Jackson Putnam]] (1846\u20131918), neurologist\n*[[Mary Corinna Putnam Jacobi]] (1842\u20131906), American physician\n*[[Palmer Cosslett Putnam]] (1900\u20131984), [[Wind power]] pioneer and author, builder of the [[Smith\u2013Putnam wind turbine]]\n*Justice Samuel Putnam (1768\u20131853), Massachusetts Supreme Court justice, who wrote the opinion in [[Harvard College v. Amory]], which established the [[Prudent man rule]] in US Law\n*[[Robert Putnam]] (born 1941), American political scientist, Harvard University\n*[[Rufus Putnam]] (1738\u20131824), American soldier\n*[[Thomas Putnam]] (1651\u20131699), landowner in Salem during the [[Salem witch trials]]\n*[[William Lowell Putnam]] (1861\u20131923), American jurist & banker\n*[[Quinn Bradlee]] (born 1982), [[United States|American]] [[Filmmaking|filmmaker]], [[author]] and [[Advocacy|advocate]] for improving the lives of [[Disability|disabled]] individuals\n*[[Alan Copeland]] (born 1926), Grammy award-winning musician, vocal arranger, conductor and author\n\n==Family tree==\n{{hidden begin|expanded=yes|ta1=center|border=1px #aaa solid|title=Putnam family members}}\n{{Tree list}}\n*John Putnam (c 1580\u20131666) m. Priscilla Gould\n**Thomas Putnam (1614\u20131686)\n***[[Thomas Putnam]] (1652\u20131699), Salem witch trials accuser\n****{{Tree list/final branch}}[[Ann Putnam, Jr.]] (1679\u20131716), Salem witch trials accuser\n***Deacon Edward Putnam (1654\u20131747), Salem witch trials accuser\n****{{Tree list/final branch}}Elisha Putnam (1685\u20131745)\n*****{{Tree list/final branch}}[[Rufus Putnam]] (1738\u20131824), General\n***Joseph Putnam (1669\u20131722) m. Elizabeth Porter (1673\u20131746) <3\n****David Putnam (1707\u20131768)\n*****Israel Putnam (b. 1742)\n******{{Tree list/final branch}}Daniel Putnam\n*******{{Tree list/final branch}}Benjamin Putnam\n********{{Tree list/final branch}}Frederick Putnam\n*********{{Tree list/final branch}}David Putnam\n**********{{Tree list/final branch}}[[David Putnam]] (1898\u20131918), World War I ace\n*****{{Tree list/final branch}}William Putnam (b. 1749)\n******{{Tree list/final branch}}Andrew Putnam\n*******{{Tree list/final branch}}George Putnam\n********{{Tree list/final branch}}George Putnam\n*********{{Tree list/final branch}}[[William Lowell Putnam]] (1861\u20131923), lawyer and banker\n****{{Tree list/final branch}}[[Israel Putnam]] (1718\u20131790), General\n**Nathaniel Putnam (1619\u20131700)\n***{{Tree list/final branch}}Benjamin Putnam (1664\u20131715) m. Sarah Tarrant\n****Nathaniel Putnam (1686\u20131754)\n*****{{Tree list/final branch}}Archelaus Putnam Sr. (b. 1718)\n******Nathaniel Putnam (1746-1800)\n*******Nathaniel Putnam (1774-1849)\n********Nathaniel Putnam (1802-1886)\n*********Abby Putnam Morrison (1848-)\n**********Lillian Morrison Tingue (1885-)\n***********Grace Tingue Curran (1907-1988)\n******{{Tree list/final branch}}Archelaus Putnam Jr. (1740\u20131800)\n*******{{Tree list/final branch}}Caleb Putnam (1763\u20131826)\n********{{Tree list/final branch}}James Russell Putnam (1781\u20131841)\n*********{{Tree list/final branch}}James Mercier Putnam (1823\u20131887), instrumental in colonizing British Honduras\n**********{{Tree list/final branch}}James Henry Putnam (b. 1848), sugar plantation and railroad owner\n***********{{Tree list/final branch}}Robert Emmet Putnam (1883\u20131959)\n************[[Richard Johnson Putnam]] (1913\u20132002), federal judge\n************{{Tree list/final branch}}\"Bobby\" Emmet Putnam (1919\u20132009)\n*************{{Tree list/final branch}}Dr. Kimball Putnam Marshall (b. 1947), nationally recognized professor of business\n****Tarrant Putnam (1688\u20131732)\n*****Gideon Putnam (1726\u20131811)\n******Samuel Putnam (1768\u20131853), Massachusetts Supreme Court justice\n****{{Tree list/final branch}}Daniel Putnam (b. 1696)\n*****{{Tree list/final branch}}Daniel Putnam\n******{{Tree list/final branch}}Henry Putnam\n*******{{Tree list/final branch}}Henry Putnam\n********{{Tree list/final branch}}[[George Palmer Putnam]] (1814\u20141872), book publisher m. Victorine Haven\n*********[[Mary Corinna Putnam Jacobi]] (1842\u20131906), physician m. [[Abraham Jacobi]] (1830\u20131919), physician\n*********[[George Haven Putnam]] (1844\u20131930), book publisher\n**********[[Bertha Putnam]] (1872\u20131960), historian\n**********[[George P. Putnam]] (1887\u20131950), writer, explorer m. [[Amelia Earhart]] (1897\u20131937), aviator\n**********{{Tree list/final branch}}[[Palmer Cosslett Putnam]] (1900\u20131984), engineer\n*********[[John Bishop Putnam]] (1849\u20131915), book publisher\n*********Irving Putnam, book publisher\n**********{{Tree list/final branch}}Edmund Whitman Putnam (1882\u20131941), book publisher, physician m. Ethel Wilson\n*********{{Tree list/final branch}}[[Herbert Putnam]] (1861\u20131955), 8th [[Librarian of Congress]]\n**********{{Tree list/final branch}}[[Brenda Putnam]] (1890\u20131975), sculptor\n**{{Tree list/final branch}}John Putnam (1627\u20131710)\n***{{Tree list/final branch}}James Putnam Sr. (1661\u20141727), bricklayer\n****{{Tree list/final branch}}James Putnam Jr. (b. 1689), bricklayer\n*****{{Tree list/final branch}}Ebenezer Putnam\n******{{Tree list/final branch}}Ebenezer Putnam II\n*******{{Tree list/final branch}}Ebenezer Putnam III\n********{{Tree list/final branch}}[[Frederic Ward Putnam]] (1839\u20131915), naturalist\n*********{{Tree list/final branch}}[[Eben Putnam]] (1868\u20131933), historian and genealogist\n\n\n<!-- Unknown\n===George Palmer Putnam branch===\n\n*[[Adam Putnam]] (b. 1974), American politician\n*[[Ashley Putnam]] (b. 1952), opera singer\n* [[Benjamin A. Putnam]] ([[floruit|fl.]] 1810s), American soldier & politician   an officer in the First Seminole War and local Florida politician\n*[[Charles Putnam|Charles Flint Putnam]] (1854\u20131882), US naval officer, polar explorer\n*[[Howard Putnam]], travel business manager\n*[[George Putnam (newsman)]] (1914\u20132008), journalist\n*[[Hilary Putnam]],  philosopher\n*[[Samuel Putnam]]\n*[[Johnathan Putnam]], Labor Activist, Writer, Film Maker\n*[[Michael Putnam]] (b. 1933), American Professional Golfer\n*[[Robert D. Putnam]],  political scientist\n*[[Roger Putnam]] (1892\u20131972), American politician and industrialist\n*[[Seth Putnam]], musician\n*[[William LeBaron Putnam]] (1835\u20131918), American jurist & politician\n-->\n\n==References==\n*Eben Putnam, A history of the Putnam family in England and America, 1908\n*G. Andrews Moriarty Jr., A.M., LL.B., F.S.A., [http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~kugerrand/agv15.htm The English Ancestry of John Putnam Of Salem, Massachusetts]\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Putnam Family}}\n[[Category:American families]]\n\n\n{{name-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Kelvin", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling/grammar/punctuation/typographical correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Putnam_family"}
{"title_page": "Stef Nijland", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Stef N\u0133land\n| image = Nijland Toivonen PSV 2011.jpg\n| caption = Nijland (left) and then-teammate [[Ola Toivonen]] at [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]] in 2011\n| fullname = Stefan N\u0133land\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1988|8|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Hoogezand]], Netherlands\n| height = 1.87 m\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Centre forward]]\n| currentclub = [[De Graafschap]]\n| clubnumber = 10\n| youthyears1 = 1997\u20132007\n| youthclubs1 = [[FC Groningen|Groningen]]\n| years1 = 2007\u20132008\n| clubs1 = [[FC Groningen|Groningen]]\n| caps1 = 23\n| goals1 = 4\n| years2 = 2008\u20132013\n| clubs2 = [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]]\n| caps2 = 18\n| goals2 = 1\n| years3 = 2009\u20132010\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[Willem II (football club)|Willem II]] (loan)\n| caps3 = 16\n| goals3 = 4\n| years4 = 2011\u20132012\n| clubs4 = \u2192 [[N.E.C. (football club)|NEC]] (loan)\n| caps4 = 15\n| goals4 = 1\n| years5 = 2013\n| clubs5 = \u2192 [[Brisbane Roar]] (loan)\n| caps5 = 10\n| goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2013\u20132018\n| clubs6 = [[PEC Zwolle]]\n| caps6 = 108\n| goals6 = 20\n| years7 = 2018\u2013\n| clubs7 = [[De Graafschap]]\n| caps7 = 14\n| goals7 = 2\n| club-update = 10 June 2019\n}}\n\n'''Stefan N\u0133land''' ({{IPA-nl|\u02c8ste\u02d0.f\u0251n \u02c8n\u025bi\u032f.\u02ccl\u0251nt}}; born 10 August 1988) is a Dutch professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]]<ref>{{in lang|nl}} [http://www.vi.nl/Spelers/Speler.htm?dbid=56070&typeofpage=84137 Profile at Voetbal International]</ref> for [[De Graafschap]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===Groningen===\nBorn in [[Hoogezand]], N\u0133land began his professional career during the 2007\u201308 season with [[FC Groningen|Groningen]] and signed a contract with the club until 2009.<ref name=\"Nijland1\">{{cite news|title=Groningen verlengt contracten jeugdinternationals|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/groningen-verlengt-contracten-jeugdinternationals.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|date=14 January 2008|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nNijland made his Groningen debut, where he set up one of the goals, in a 3\u20130 win against [[NAC Breda]] in the opening game of the season on 18 August 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=FC Groningen pakt de punten in Breda|url=http://www.gelderlander.nl/sport/fc-groningen-pakt-de-punten-in-breda-1.2456769|publisher=De Gelderlander|language=Dutch|date=18 August 2007|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> He also made his European debut, where he played the whole game, in a 1\u20131 draw against [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]] on 20 September 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=FC Groningen en Fiorentina in evenwicht|url=http://www.gelderlander.nl/sport/fc-groningen-en-fiorentina-in-evenwicht-1.2507224|publisher=De Gelderlander|language=Dutch|date=20 September 2007|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> He continued to make a handful of first team appearances and then scored his first goals for the club, in an 8\u20131 win over [[IJsselmeervogels]] in the [[2007\u201308 KNVB Cup#Second round|second round of KNVB Cup]] on 26 September 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=PSV weerstaat Alves, knal Pardo velt VVV|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/psv-weerstaat-alves-knal-pardo-velt-vvv.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=26 September 2007|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> However, he suffered an injury, which he sustained in training and was sidelined for months.<ref>{{cite news|title=FC Groningen zonder Nijland|url=http://www.telegraaf.nl/telesport/voetbal/20558425/__FC_Groningen_zonder_Nijland__.html|publisher=De Telegraaf|language=Dutch|date=4 October 2007|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> After two months on the sidelined, he made his first team return on 9 December 2007, coming on as a substitute in the second half, in a 4\u20132 loss against [[SC Heerenveen|Heerenveen]].<ref>{{cite news|title=SC Heerenveen sterkste in doelpuntrijke derby|url=http://www.gelderlander.nl/sport/sc-heerenveen-sterkste-in-doelpuntrijke-derby-1.2482020|publisher=De Gelderlander|language=Dutch|date=9 December 2007|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Two weeks later on 22 December 2007, he scored his first Groningen league goal and set up one of the goals, in a 2\u20131 win over [[Heracles Almelo]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Heracles helpt Groningen weer eens aan uitzege|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/heracles-helpt-groningen-weer-eens-aan-uitzege.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=22 December 2007|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Seven days later on 29 December 2007, Nijland scored a brace, in a 3\u20131 win over [[Sparta Rotterdam]],<ref>{{cite news|title=FC Groningen zet goede reeks voort|url=http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/4324/Nieuws/article/detail/1401114/2007/12/29/FC-Groningen-zet-goede-reeks-voort.dhtml|publisher=Trouw|language=Dutch|date=29 December 2007|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> followed up by setting up two goals, in a 3\u20132 win over [[S.B.V. Excelsior|Excelsior]] in the next game.<ref>{{cite news|title=Groningen is derde na worsteling met Excelsior|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/groningen-is-derde-na-worsteling-met-excelsior.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=12 January 2008|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> For his performance, Nijland signed a contract extension with the club, keeping him until 2012<ref name=\"Nijland1\"/> and revealed that he turned down a move to join Ajax in the January transfer window, where he could have joined alongside [[Bruno Silva]] and [[Rasmus Lindgren]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Gronings talent Nijland zei nee tegen Ajax|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/gronings-talent-nijland-zei-nee-tegen-ajax.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=23 February 2008|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Nijland then scored again on 24 February 2008, in a 3\u20131 win over [[VVV-Venlo]].<ref>{{cite news|title=FC Groningen geeft VVV-Venlo valse hoop|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/fc-groningen-geeft-vvvvenlo-valse-hoop.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=24 February 2008|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Despite suffering from ankle injury,<ref>{{cite news|title=Enkelblessure Nijland|url=http://www.telegraaf.nl/telesport/voetbal/20549329/__Enkelblessure_Nijland__.html|publisher=De Telegraaf|language=Dutch|date=13 March 2008|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Nijland finished his first season at Groningen, making twenty\u2013three appearance and scoring six times in all competition.\n\n===PSV Eindhoven===\nOn 24 August 2008, Nijland left Groningen when he was transferred to [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]] for a fee of \u20ac4 million, signing a five\u2013year contract, keeping him until 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=PSV betaalt vier miljoen voor Nijland|url=https://www.telesport.nl/overzicht/voetbal/eredivisie/20654678/__PSV_betaalt_vier_mln_voor_Nijland__.html|publisher=De Telegraaf|language=Dutch|date=25 August 2008|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nNijland then made his PSV debut, where he made his first start for the club and played for 55 minutes before being substituted, in a 1\u20130 win over Sparta Rotterdam.<ref>{{cite news|title=PSV met minimale inspanningen langs Sparta|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/psv-met-minimale-inspanningen-langs-sparta.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=13 September 2008|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> After missing out one match, he returned and set up one of the goals, in a 3\u20132 loss against [[Roda JC Kerkrade|Roda JC]] on 25 October 2008.<ref>{{cite news|title=Roda JC is PSV opnieuw de baas|url=http://www.gelderlander.nl/sport/voetbal/2.2520/roda-jc-is-psv-opnieuw-de-baas-1.2726243|publisher=De Gelderlander|language=Dutch|date=25 October 2008|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> It wasn't until on 29 November 2008 when he scored his first goal for the club, in a 2\u20132 draw against Heerenveen.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gebrek aan hi\u00ebrarchie bij PSV|url=http://www.parool.nl/sport/gebrek-aan-hierarchie-bij-psv~a59917/|publisher=Het Parool|language=Dutch|date=1 December 2008|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> In his second meeting against his former club Groningen on 21 February 2009, Nijland came on as a late substitute in the second half and scored a winning goal, in a 1\u20130 win.<ref>{{cite news|title=PSV pakt in extremis de punten in Groningen|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/psv-pakt-in-extremis-de-punten-in-groningen.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=21 February 2009|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> However, as the 2008\u201309 season progressed, his first team opportunities was limited, as he appeared most of the time on the substitute bench before an injury forced him out for the rest of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.psv.nl/psv/nieuws/artikel/stef-nijland-voor-de-rest-van-het-seizoen-uitgeschakeld.htm|title=Stef Nijland voor de rest van het seizoen uitgeschakeld|publisher=PSV Eindhoven|language=Dutch|date=8 April 2009|access-date=28 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161031150406/http://www.psv.nl/psv/nieuws/artikel/stef-nijland-voor-de-rest-van-het-seizoen-uitgeschakeld.htm|archive-date=31 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In his first season at PSV, he went on to make nineteen appearance and scoring once in all competitions.\n\nIn the 2009\u201310 season, Nijland made one appearance for PSV, where he came on as a substitute in the second half, in a 2\u20130 win over Roda JC in [[2009\u201310 KNVB Cup#Third round|the third round of KNVB Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|title=PSV bekert verder na winst op Roda JC|url=http://www.gelderlander.nl/sport/psv-bekert-verder-na-winst-op-roda-jc-1.2771640|publisher=De Gelderlander|language=Dutch|date=28 October 2009|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Following his loan spell at Willem II came to an end, he scored on his first appearance for the club in the 2010\u201311 season, in a 3\u20130 win over Sparta Rotterdam in [[2010\u201311 KNVB Cup#Second round|second round of KNVB Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|title=PSV loopt in slotfase weg bij Sparta|url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/sport/psv-loopt-in-slotfase-weg-bij-sparta~a1024427/|publisher=De Volkskrant|language=Dutch|date=22 September 2010|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Nijland went on to make seven appearance in the 2010\u201311 season in all competition.\n\nAfter being told by the club's technical manager Marcel Brands that he would not be at the club next season,<ref>{{cite news|title=Stef Nijland zal niet terugkeren bij PSV Eindhoven|url=http://www.goal.com/nl/news/761/psv/2012/02/27/2933483/stef-nijland-zal-niet-terugkeren-bij-psv|publisher=Goal.com|language=Dutch|date=27 February 2012|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Nijland returned to the club at the end of the 2011\u201312 season and was linked with a move to German side [[TSV 1860 Munich|1860 Munich]] and even started a negotiation between the two parties,<ref>{{cite news|title=PSV-aanvaller Nijland in onderhandeling met Union Berlin|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/psvaanvaller-nijland-in-onderhandeling-met-union-berlin.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=3 December 2012|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> but remained at PSV Eindhoven after he rejected a move to the club.<ref>{{cite news|title=PSV Eindhoven kan overbodige Nijland niet aan Union Berlin slijten|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/psv-kan-overbodige-nijland-niet-aan-union-berlin-slijten.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=4 January 2013|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the 2012\u201313 season, Nijland was released by the club after being told that his contract would not be renewed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Engelaar, Nijland en Vukovic naderen afscheid bij PSV Eindhoven|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/Engelaar-Nijland-en-Vukovic-naderen-afscheid-bij-PSV.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=28 March 2013|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Loan spells===\nOn 24 December 2009, PSV loaned Nijland to [[Willem II (football club)|Willem II]] for the remainder of the 2009\u201310 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.psv.nl/Nieuws/Nieuwspagina/Stef-Nijland-op-huurbasis-naar-Willem-II.htm|title=Stef N\u0133land op huurbasis naar Willem II|publisher=PSV Eindhoven|language=Dutch|date=25 December 2009|access-date=28 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100126083951/http://www.psv.nl/Nieuws/Nieuwspagina/Stef-Nijland-op-huurbasis-naar-Willem-II.htm|archive-date=26 January 2010|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> Nijland made his Willem II debut on 13 January 2010 in a friendly match against UD Ojen, where he scored five goals, in a 9\u20131 victory for the club.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nijland scoort vijf keer voor Willem II|url=http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/4324/Nieuws/article/detail/1083395/2010/01/13/Nijland-scoort-vijf-keer-voor-Willem-II.dhtml|publisher=Trouw|language=Dutch|date=13 January 2010|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Ten days later on 23 January 2010, he scored on his league debut for Willem II, in a 4\u20132 loss against Heerenveen,<ref>{{cite news|title=Eindelijk weer een zege voor SC Heerenveen|url=http://www.parool.nl/sport/nijland-scoort-vijf-keer-voor-willem-ii~a275416/|publisher=Het Parool|language=Dutch|date=23 January 2010|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> followed up by scoring his second on 29 January 2010, in a 2\u20131 win against [[RKC Waalwijk]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Willem II wint degradatiegevecht met RKC Waalwijk|url=http://www.parool.nl/sport/willem-ii-wint-degradatiegevecht-met-rkc~a277464/|publisher=Het Parool|language=Dutch|date=29 January 2010|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> He went on to score two more goals later in the season against [[N.E.C. (football club)|NEC]],<ref>{{cite news|title=NEC wint inhaalduel met Willem II|url=http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/4324/Nieuws/article/detail/1090913/2010/02/17/NEC-wint-inhaalduel-met-Willem-II.dhtml|publisher=Trouw|language=Dutch|date=17 February 2010|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Sparta Rotterdam<ref>{{cite news|title=Nijland helpt Willem II aan drie punten, zorgen voor Vitesse nemen toe|url=http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/4324/Nieuws/article/detail/1584054/2010/03/15/Nijland-helpt-Willem-II-aan-drie-punten-zorgen-voor-Vitesse-nemen-toe.dhtml|publisher=Trouw|language=Dutch|date=15 March 2010|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> and [[FC Eindhoven|Eindhoven]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Willem II in slotfase langs Eindhoven|url=http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/4324/Nieuws/article/detail/1109860/2010/05/06/Willem-II-in-slotfase-langs-Eindhoven.dhtml|publisher=Trouw|language=Dutch|date=6 May 2010|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> At the end of the 2009\u201310 season, Nijland helped the club survive relegation to ensure that Willem II stayed in the top\u2013flight football for another season and scored five times in twenty appearance.<ref>{{cite news|title=Willem II redt 25e eredivisieschap op rij|url=http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/4324/Nieuws/article/detail/1111244/2010/05/16/Willem-II-redt-25e-eredivisieschap-op-rij.dhtml|publisher=Trouw|language=Dutch|date=16 May 2010|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 May 2011, PSV loaned Nijland to [[N.E.C. (football club)|NEC Nijmegen]] for the 2011/12 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nec-nijmegen.nl/tickets/nieuws/04800_psv-er-stef-nijland-volgt-koolwijk-en-platje-op-weg-naar-het-goffertstadion-u-ook|title=Stef N\u0133land op huurbasis naar NEC Nijmegen|publisher=N.E.C. Nijmegen|language=Dutch|date=25 May 2011|access-date=28 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110528062957/http://www.nec-nijmegen.nl/tickets/nieuws/04800_psv-er-stef-nijland-volgt-koolwijk-en-platje-op-weg-naar-het-goffertstadion-u-ook|archive-date=28 May 2011|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> Nijland scored on his debut in the opening game of the season, in a 2\u20132 draw against Heerenveen.<ref>{{cite news|title=SC Heerenveen geeft zege in vijf minuten uit handen|url=http://www.parool.nl/sport/heerenveen-geeft-zege-in-vijf-minuten-uit-handen~a2840011/|publisher=Het Parool|language=Dutch|date=6 August 2011|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> He scored his second goal of the season, in the [[2011\u201312 KNVB Cup#Second round|second round of KNVB Cup]], in a 4\u20131 win over [[Fortuna Sittard]] on 20 September 2011.<ref>{{cite news|title=NEC ontsnapt in verlenging bij Fortuna Sittard|url=http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/4324/Nieuws/article/detail/2920521/2011/09/20/NEC-ontsnapt-in-verlenging-bij-Fortuna-Sittard.dhtml|publisher=Trouw|language=Dutch|date=20 September 2011|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> However, Nijland suffered injuries as the 2011\u201312 season<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nec-nijmegen.nl/2011/11/n-e-c-onderuit-tegen-roda-jc-1-2/|title=N.E.C. onderuit tegen Roda JC: 1 \u2013 2|publisher=N.E.C. Nijmegen|language=Dutch|date=19 November 2011|access-date=28 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161031171604/http://www.nec-nijmegen.nl/2011/11/n-e-c-onderuit-tegen-roda-jc-1-2/|archive-date=31 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nec-nijmegen.nl/2011/11/update-blessures-selectie-21/|title=Update blessures selectie|publisher=N.E.C. Nijmegen|language=Dutch|date=29 November 2011|access-date=28 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161031171729/http://www.nec-nijmegen.nl/2011/11/update-blessures-selectie-21/|archive-date=31 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nec-nijmegen.nl/2012/04/voorbeschouwing-excelsior-n-e-c/|title=Voorbeschouwing Excelsior \u2013 N.E.C.|publisher=N.E.C. Nijmegen|language=Dutch|date=9 April 2012|access-date=28 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161031172232/http://www.nec-nijmegen.nl/2012/04/voorbeschouwing-excelsior-n-e-c/|archive-date=31 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> and went on to make nineteen appearance and scoring two times in the 2011\u201312 season in all competition.\n\nOn 28 January 2013, N\u0133land went to Australian club [[Brisbane Roar FC|Brisbane Roar]] on a four-month loan deal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Brisbane Roar Have Reportedly Signed Dutch Striker Stef Nijland|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/football/the-brisbane-roar-have-reportedly-signed-dutch-striker-stef-nijland/story-fnddgn65-1226563192354|publisher=The Courier Mail|date=28 January 2013}}</ref> Nijland made his debut for Brisbane in round 19 against [[Central Coast Mariners FC|Central Coast Mariners]] in a 2\u20132 draw.<ref>{{cite news|title=Besart Berisha heroics not enough to top Central Coasr Mariners|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-02-01/berisha-heroics-not-enough-to-top-mariners/4497070?|publisher=ABC (stands for Australian Broadcasting Corporation(|date=1 February 2013}}</ref> Despite keen on signing for the club on a permanent basis,<ref>{{cite news|title=Brisbane Roar keen to secure loan pair Stef Nijland and Steven Lustica|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/loan-pair-hear-roar-for-longer/story-fnddgn65-1226591105466|publisher=The Courier Mail|date=1 February 2013|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Nijland failed to score a single goal in his ten appearances at the club and at the end of the 2012\u201313 season, he returned to his parent club.<ref>{{cite news|title=Brisbane Roar coach Mike Mulvey has eye on overseas talent|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/brisbane-roar-coach-mike-mulvey-has-eye-on-overseas-talent/story-fndcvet9-1226626182283|publisher=The Daily Telegraph|date=23 April 2013|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===PEC Zwolle===\nAfter leaving PSV Eindhoven, Nijland signed for newly promoted side [[PEC Zwolle]], signing a three\u2013year contract, keeping him until 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nijland tekent voor 3 jaar bij PEC Zwolle|url=http://www.ad.nl/eredivisie/nijland-tekent-voor-3-jaar-bij-pec-zwolle~ad2f76cd/|publisher=Algemeen Dagblad|language=Dutch|date=13 May 2013|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Upon joining the club, Nijland re\u2013joined Manager [[Ron Jans]] from his time at Groningen.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nijland en Jans hebben 'positief gesprek' achter de rug|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/nijland-en-jans-hebben-positief-gesprek-achter-de-rug.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=8 May 2013|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nNijland made his PEC Zwolle debut, where he came on as a late substitute, in a 3-0 win over [[Heracles Almelo|Hercales]],<ref>{{cite news|title=PEC trotse koploper na knappe zege bij zwak Heracles|url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/sport/pec-trotse-koploper-na-knappe-zege-bij-zwak-heracles~a3490414/|publisher=De Volkskrant|language=Dutch|date=10 August 2013|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> It wasn't until on 1 September 2013 when he scored his first PEC Zwolle goal, in a 1\u20131 draw against [[FC Utrecht|Utrecht]].<ref>{{cite news|title=PEC Zwolle moet genoegen nemen met gelijkspel|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/pec-zwolle-moet-genoegen-nemen-met-gelijkspel-.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=1 September 2013|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> His second goal then came on 8 December 2013, in a 4\u20131 loss against [[Go Ahead Eagles]].<ref>{{cite news|title=PEC buigt in IJsselderby voor strijd en passie Eagles|url=http://www.ad.nl/eredivisie/pec-buigt-in-ijsselderby-voor-strijd-en-passie-eagles~ae5f060f/|publisher=Algemeen Dagblad|language=Dutch|date=8 December 2013|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> However, his first season at PEC Zwolle was a disappointment for him, as his first team opportunities was limited and restricted into making twenty\u2013five appearance and scoring two times in all competition.<ref>{{cite news|title=De Tien: grootste miskopen van dit Eredivisie-seizoen|url=http://www.voetbalprimeur.nl/nieuws/381467/de-tien-grootste-miskopen-van-dit-eredivisie-seizoen.html|publisher=Voetbal Primeur|language=Dutch|date=25 April 2014|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nFrustrated with a lack of first team opportunities last season, Nijland considered leaving the club ahead of the 2014\u201315 season<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pec.nu/pec-zwolle/stef-nijland-mag-vertrekken/|title=Stef Nijland mag vertrekken|publisher=PEC Zwolle|language=Dutch|date=17 July 2014|access-date=28 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161031202228/http://pec.nu/pec-zwolle/stef-nijland-mag-vertrekken/|archive-date=31 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite this, Nijland was named in the starting eleven in the 2014 Dutch [[2014 Johan Cruijff Schaal|Supercup]]-game between PEC and [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]], where he scored the winning goal in a 1-0 win, giving PEC its first ever Supercup win and himself his second major trophy at the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peczwolle.nl/nl/nieuwsarchief/pec-zwolle-wint-tweede-hoofdprijs-in-paar-maanden-tijd2014-08-03|title=PEC Zwolle wint tweede hoofdprijs in paar maanden tijd!|publisher=PEC Zwolle|language=Dutch|date=3 August 2014|access-date=31 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012214917/http://www.peczwolle.nl/nl/nieuwsarchief/pec-zwolle-wint-tweede-hoofdprijs-in-paar-maanden-tijd2014-08-03|archive-date=12 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Following the match, his performance was praised by the club's director Gerard Nijkamp.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ajax-beul Nijland maakt indruk bij PEC Zwolle|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/ajaxbeul-nijland-maakt-indruk-bij-pec.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=5 August 2013|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Niljand's season proved was an improvement for him, as he was given more first team opportunities and by the first half of the season, he scored five times in seventeen appearance against [[SBV Vitesse|Vitesse]] (in addition to being named Man of the Match by [[Voetbal International]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Matchwinner Nijland vergroot zorgen bij Vitesse|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/matchwinner-nijland-vergroot-zorgen-bij-vitesse.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=24 August 2014|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Heracles Almelo,<ref>{{cite news|title=PEC Zwolle te sterk voor tien Heraclieden|url=http://www.ad.nl/eredivisie/pec-zwolle-te-sterk-voor-tien-heraclieden~a5b014d1/|publisher=Algemeen Dagblad|language=Dutch|date=27 September 2014|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Go Ahead Eagles<ref>{{cite news|title=Go Ahead Eagles weer de sterkste in IJsselderby|url=http://www.ad.nl/eredivisie/go-ahead-eagles-weer-de-sterkste-in-ijsselderby~a2a9e9c9/|publisher=Algemeen Dagblad|language=Dutch|date=19 October 2014|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> and Excelsior (twice).<ref>{{cite news|title=Swingend PEC be\u00ebindigt fraaie thuisreeks van Excelsior|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/swingend-pec-beeindigt-fraaie-thuisreeks-van-excelsior-.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=30 November 2014|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> At the start of 2015, he scored three more goals against Utrecht<ref>{{cite news|title=FC Utrecht na hectische week met Kali ten onder tegen PEC Zwolle|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/fc-utrecht-na-hectische-week-met-kali-ten-onder-tegen-pec-.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=1 February 2015|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> and [[FC Dordrecht|Dordrecht]]<ref>{{cite news|title=PEC Zwolle naar derde plek na ruime zege op FC Dordrecht|url=http://www.ad.nl/eredivisie/pec-zwolle-naar-derde-plek-na-ruime-zege-op-fc-dordrecht~a94083ec/|publisher=Algemeen Dagblad|language=Dutch|date=4 February 2015|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> before receiving a straight red card, in a 1\u20130 loss against Go Ahead Eagles on 15 February 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Go Ahead bedwingt in IJsselderby 10 man PEC|url=http://www.parool.nl/sport/go-ahead-bedwingt-in-ijsselderby-10-man-pec~a3851924/|publisher=Het Parool|language=Dutch|date=15 February 2015|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> After serving a two match suspension,<ref>{{cite news|title=Jans en Nijland accepteren schikkingsvoorstel|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/jans-en-nijland-accepteren-schikkingsvoorstel.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=16 February 2015|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Nijland returned to the first team on 7 March 2015 and scored a hat\u2013trick of his career, in a 6\u20131 win over [[SC Cambuur|Cambuur]] despite playing for twenty\u2013one minutes during the match.<ref>{{cite news|title=PEC Zwolle spoelt reeks nederlagen weg met clubrecord|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/pec-spoelt-reeks-nederlagen-weg-met-clubrecord.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=7 March 2015|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Nijland scoort drie keer in negentien minuten: 'Geweldig'|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/nijland-scoort-drie-keer-in-negentien-minuten-geweldig.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=7 March 2015|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Despite suffering an injury towards the end of the 2014\u201315 season,<ref>{{cite news|title=PEC Zwolle zonder Nijland tegen Vitesse|url=http://www.ad.nl/eredivisie/pec-zwolle-zonder-nijland-tegen-vitesse~af7f4540/|publisher=Algemeen Dagblad|language=Dutch|date=20 May 2015|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Nijland finished the 2014\u201315 season, making thirty\u2013eight appearance and scoring thirteen times in all competitions, making him the club's topscorer.\n\nIn the 2015\u201316 season, Niljand continued to be in the first team regular despite facing new competitions<ref>{{cite news|title=Spits Nijland: verguisd en bejubeld bij PEC Zwolle|url=http://www.ad.nl/eredivisie/spits-nijland-verguisd-en-bejubeld-bij-pec-zwolle~a3050a1f/|publisher=Algemeen Dagblad|language=Dutch|date=9 November 2015|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> and it wasn't until on 7 November 2015 when he scored his first goal of the season, in a 1\u20131 draw against Heracules Almelo,<ref>{{cite news|title=Nijland helpt PEC in extremis aan punt tegen Heracles|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/nijland-helpt-pec-in-extremis-aan-punt-tegen-heracles.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=7 November 2015|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> followed up by scoring in a 5\u20130 win over Roda JC.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vincent Janssen helpt AZ aan overwinning, PEC Zwolle overklast Roda JC|url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/sport/janssen-helpt-az-aan-overwinning-pec-overklast-roda~a4192166/|publisher=De Volkskrant|language=Dutch|date=20 November 2015|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> As the 2015\u201316 season progressed, Niljand went on to score four more goals against Heerenveen,<ref>{{cite news|title=PEC Zwolle zet zwak SC Heerenveen te kijk|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/pec-zwolle-zet-zwak-sc-heerenveen-te-kijk.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=16 January 2016|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> De Graafschap (twice)<ref>{{cite news|title=Tandem Veldwijk-Nijland helpt PEC langs De Graafschap|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/ajax-won-slechts-een-van-de-laatste-zes-duels-met-pec-.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=5 March 2016|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> and Willem II.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cambuur met lege handen na duel met Roda JC, PEC Zwolle houdt zicht op play-offs|url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/sport/cambuur-met-lege-handen-na-duel-met-roda-jc-pec-zwolle-houdt-zicht-op-play-offs~a4266584/|publisher=De Volkskrant|language=Dutch|date=19 March 2016|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> As a result, Niljand signed a contract extension with the club, keeping him until 2018.<ref>{{cite news|title=PEC legt 'Mister Groningen' Nijland langer vast|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/pec-legt-mister-groningen-nijland-langer-vast.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=29 January 2016|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Despite suffering from injuries as the 2015\u201316 season progressed,<ref>{{cite news|title=PEC zonder Nijland tegen FC Twente|url=http://www.ad.nl/eredivisie/pec-zonder-nijland-tegen-fc-twente~a38320f8/|publisher=Algemeen Dagblad|language=Dutch|date=11 March 2016|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=PEC Zwolle op zoek naar twee zeges|url=http://www.gelderlander.nl/algemeen/sport/voetbal/pec-op-zoek-naar-twee-zeges-1.5927854|publisher=De Gelderlander|language=Dutch|date=15 April 2016|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Nijland finished the 2015\u201316 season, making twenty\u2013seven appearance and scoring six times in all competitions.\n\nIn the 2016\u201317 season, Nijland appeared in the first three matches to the season before a thigh injury, which he sustained during a 4\u20130 defeat to PSV Eindhoven.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kortom \u2013Praet naar Sampdoria, miljoenentransfer Dragovic|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/kortom-praet-naar-sampdoria-miljoenentransfer-dragovic.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=23 August 2016|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nIn May 2008, Nijland was called up by [[Netherlands national football team|the B Team]].<ref>{{cite news|title=De Haan haalt EK-afvaller Maduro bij selectie|url=http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/4324/Nieuws/article/detail/1224091/2008/05/16/De-Haan-haalt-EK-afvaller-Maduro-bij-selectie.dhtml|publisher=Trouw|language=Dutch|date=16 May 2008|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe is the son of Hans N\u0133land, the former Managing Director of [[FC Groningen]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Groningen boos \u00e9n trots op jonge Nijland|url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/sport/groningen-boos-en-trots-op-jonge-nijland~a314185/|publisher=De Volkskrant|language=Dutch|date=21 February 2009|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to playing football, Nijland said he has been taking Spanish classes in an interview with [[Goal.com]]. Stef also revealed that he's often being called Stefan than Stef.<ref>{{cite news|title=INTERVIEW met Stef Nijland: \"Mijn eerste jaar is een leerjaar\"|url=http://www.goal.com/nl/news/213/eredivisie/2009/01/29/1083377/interview-met-stef-nijland-mijn-eerste-jaar-is-een-leerjaar|publisher=Goal.com|language=Dutch|date=29 January 2011|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{Updated|match played on 1 July 2019}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Stef Nijland \u00bb Club matches |url=https://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/stef-nijland/2/ |website=worldfootball.net |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club!!rowspan=\"2\"|Season!!colspan=\"3\"|League!!colspan=\"2\"|Cup!!colspan=\"2\"|Other!!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[FC Groningen|Groningen]]||[[2007\u201308 Eredivisie|2007\u201308]]||[[Eredivisie]]\n|23||4||0||0||0||0||23||4\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]]||[[2008\u201309 Eredivisie|2008\u201309]]||rowspan=\"3\"|Eredivisie\n|14||1||0||0||3{{efn|Appearances in [[UEFA Champions League]]}}||0||17||1\n|-\n|[[2009\u201310 PSV Eindhoven season|2009\u201310]]\n|0||0||1||0||0||0||1||0\n|-\n|[[2010\u201311 PSV Eindhoven season|2010\u201311]]\n|4||0||2||1||1{{efn|Appearance in [[UEFA Europa League]]}}||0||7||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!18!!1!!3!!1!!4!!0!!25!!2\n|-\n|[[Willem II (football club)|Willem II]] (loan)||[[2009\u201310 Eredivisie|2009\u201310]]||Eredivisie\n|16||4||0||0||4{{efn|Appearances in Promotion/relegation play-offs}}||1||20||5\n|-\n|[[N.E.C. (football club)|NEC]] (loan)||[[2011\u201312 Eredivisie|2011\u201312]]||Eredivisie\n|15||1||2||1||0||0||17||2\n|-\n|[[Brisbane Roar FC|Brisbane Roar]] (loan)||[[2012\u201313 Brisbane Roar FC season|2012\u201313]]||[[A-League]]\n|10||0||0||0||1{{efn|Appearance in [[AFC Champions League]]}}||0||11||0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\"|[[PEC Zwolle]]||[[2013\u201314 Eredivisie|2013\u201314]]||rowspan=\"5\"|Eredivisie\n|23||2||1||0||0||0||24||2\n|-\n|[[2014\u201315 Eredivisie|2014\u201315]]\n|30||11||5||0||3{{efn|Two Appearances in [[UEFA Europa League]], One Appearance in [[Johan Cruyff Shield]]}}||2||38||13\n|-\n|[[2015\u201316 PEC Zwolle season|2015\u201316]]\n|26||6||1||0||0||0||27||6\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 PEC Zwolle season|2016\u201317]]\n|13||0||0||0||0||0||13||0\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 PEC Zwolle season|2017\u201318]]\n|16||1||2||1||0||0||18||2\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!108!!20!!9!!1!!3!!2!!120!!23\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[De Graafschap]]||[[2018\u201319 Eredivisie|2018\u201319]]||rowspan=\"1\"|Eredivisie\n|14||2||2||0||0||0||16||2\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career totals\n!204!!32!!16!!3!!12!!3!!232!!38\n|}\n{{Reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n<div>{{col-begin}}\n{{col-end}}\n</div>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{WorldFootball.net|stef-nijland}}\n* [https://www.vi.nl/spelers/stef-nijland/profiel Stef Nijland] at ''[[Voetbal International]]'' {{in lang|nl}} \u2013 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160123095050/http://www.vi.nl/spelers/carriere/stef-nijland.htm}}\n\n{{De Graafschap squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nijland, Stefan}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dutch footballers]]\n[[Category:FC Groningen players]]\n[[Category:PSV Eindhoven players]]\n[[Category:Willem II (football club) players]]\n[[Category:NEC Nijmegen players]]\n[[Category:PEC Zwolle players]]\n[[Category:De Graafschap players]]\n[[Category:Eredivisie players]]\n[[Category:Brisbane Roar FC players]]\n[[Category:A-League players]]\n[[Category:People from Hoogezand-Sappemeer]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Dutch expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in Australia]]\n[[Category:Dutch expatriate sportspeople in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Stef N\u0133land\n| image = Nijland Toivonen PSV 2011.jpg\n| caption = Nijland (left) and then-teammate [[Ola Toivonen]] at [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]] in 2011\n| fullname = Stefan N\u0133land\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1988|8|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Hoogezand]], Netherlands\n| height = 1.87 m\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Centre forward]]\n| currentclub = [[De Graafschap]]\n| clubnumber = 10\n| youthyears1 = 1997\u20132007\n| youthclubs1 = [[FC Groningen|Groningen]]\n| years1 = 2007\u20132008\n| clubs1 = [[FC Groningen|Groningen]]\n| caps1 = 23\n| goals1 = 4\n| years2 = 2008\u20132013\n| clubs2 = [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]]\n| caps2 = 18\n| goals2 = 1\n| years3 = 2009\u20132010\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[Willem II (football club)|Willem II]] (loan)\n| caps3 = 16\n| goals3 = 4\n| years4 = 2011\u20132012\n| clubs4 = \u2192 [[N.E.C. (football club)|NEC]] (loan)\n| caps4 = 15\n| goals4 = 1\n| years5 = 2013\n| clubs5 = \u2192 [[Brisbane Roar]] (loan)\n| caps5 = 10\n| goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2013\u20132018\n| clubs6 = [[PEC Zwolle]]\n| caps6 = 108\n| goals6 = 20\n| years7 = 2018\u2013\n| clubs7 = [[De Graafschap]]\n| caps7 = 14\n| goals7 = 2\n| club-update = 10 June 2019\n}}\n\n'''Stefan N\u0133land''' ({{IPA-nl|\u02c8ste\u02d0.f\u0251n \u02c8n\u025bi\u032f.\u02ccl\u0251nt}}; born 10 August 1988) is a Dutch professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]]<ref>{{in lang|nl}} [http://www.vi.nl/Spelers/Speler.htm?dbid=56070&typeofpage=84137 Profile at Voetbal International]</ref> for [[De Graafschap]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===Groningen===\nBorn in [[Hoogezand]], N\u0133land began his professional career during the 2007\u201308 season with [[FC Groningen|Groningen]] and signed a contract with the club until 2009.<ref name=\"Nijland1\">{{cite news|title=Groningen verlengt contracten jeugdinternationals|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/groningen-verlengt-contracten-jeugdinternationals.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|date=14 January 2008|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nNijland made his Groningen debut, where he set up one of the goals, in a 3\u20130 win against [[NAC Breda]] in the opening game of the season on 18 August 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=FC Groningen pakt de punten in Breda|url=http://www.gelderlander.nl/sport/fc-groningen-pakt-de-punten-in-breda-1.2456769|publisher=De Gelderlander|language=Dutch|date=18 August 2007|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> He also made his European debut, where he played the whole game, in a 1\u20131 draw against [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]] on 20 September 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=FC Groningen en Fiorentina in evenwicht|url=http://www.gelderlander.nl/sport/fc-groningen-en-fiorentina-in-evenwicht-1.2507224|publisher=De Gelderlander|language=Dutch|date=20 September 2007|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> He continued to make a handful of first team appearances and then scored his first goals for the club, in an 8\u20131 win over [[IJsselmeervogels]] in the [[2007\u201308 KNVB Cup#Second round|second round of KNVB Cup]] on 26 September 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=PSV weerstaat Alves, knal Pardo velt VVV|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/psv-weerstaat-alves-knal-pardo-velt-vvv.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=26 September 2007|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> However, he suffered an injury, which he sustained in training and was sidelined for months.<ref>{{cite news|title=FC Groningen zonder Nijland|url=http://www.telegraaf.nl/telesport/voetbal/20558425/__FC_Groningen_zonder_Nijland__.html|publisher=De Telegraaf|language=Dutch|date=4 October 2007|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> After two months on the sidelined, he made his first team return on 9 December 2007, coming on as a substitute in the second half, in a 4\u20132 loss against [[SC Heerenveen|Heerenveen]].<ref>{{cite news|title=SC Heerenveen sterkste in doelpuntrijke derby|url=http://www.gelderlander.nl/sport/sc-heerenveen-sterkste-in-doelpuntrijke-derby-1.2482020|publisher=De Gelderlander|language=Dutch|date=9 December 2007|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Two weeks later on 22 December 2007, he scored his first Groningen league goal and set up one of the goals, in a 2\u20131 win over [[Heracles Almelo]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Heracles helpt Groningen weer eens aan uitzege|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/heracles-helpt-groningen-weer-eens-aan-uitzege.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=22 December 2007|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Seven days later on 29 December 2007, Nijland scored a brace, in a 3\u20131 win over [[Sparta Rotterdam]],<ref>{{cite news|title=FC Groningen zet goede reeks voort|url=http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/4324/Nieuws/article/detail/1401114/2007/12/29/FC-Groningen-zet-goede-reeks-voort.dhtml|publisher=Trouw|language=Dutch|date=29 December 2007|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> followed up by setting up two goals, in a 3\u20132 win over [[S.B.V. Excelsior|Excelsior]] in the next game.<ref>{{cite news|title=Groningen is derde na worsteling met Excelsior|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/groningen-is-derde-na-worsteling-met-excelsior.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=12 January 2008|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> For his performance, Nijland signed a contract extension with the club, keeping him until 2012<ref name=\"Nijland1\"/> and revealed that he turned down a move to join Ajax in the January transfer window, where he could have joined alongside [[Bruno Silva]] and [[Rasmus Lindgren]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Gronings talent Nijland zei nee tegen Ajax|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/gronings-talent-nijland-zei-nee-tegen-ajax.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=23 February 2008|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Nijland then scored again on 24 February 2008, in a 3\u20131 win over [[VVV-Venlo]].<ref>{{cite news|title=FC Groningen geeft VVV-Venlo valse hoop|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/fc-groningen-geeft-vvvvenlo-valse-hoop.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=24 February 2008|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Despite suffering from ankle injury,<ref>{{cite news|title=Enkelblessure Nijland|url=http://www.telegraaf.nl/telesport/voetbal/20549329/__Enkelblessure_Nijland__.html|publisher=De Telegraaf|language=Dutch|date=13 March 2008|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Nijland finished his first season at Groningen, making twenty\u2013three appearance and scoring six times in all competition.\n\n===PSV Eindhoven===\nOn 24 August 2008, Nijland left Groningen when he was transferred to [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]] for a fee of \u20ac4 million, signing a five\u2013year contract, keeping him until 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=PSV betaalt vier miljoen voor Nijland|url=https://www.telesport.nl/overzicht/voetbal/eredivisie/20654678/__PSV_betaalt_vier_mln_voor_Nijland__.html|publisher=De Telegraaf|language=Dutch|date=25 August 2008|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nNijland then made his PSV debut, where he made his first start for the club and played for 55 minutes before being substituted, in a 1\u20130 win over Sparta Rotterdam.<ref>{{cite news|title=PSV met minimale inspanningen langs Sparta|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/psv-met-minimale-inspanningen-langs-sparta.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=13 September 2008|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> After missing out one match, he returned and set up one of the goals, in a 3\u20132 loss against [[Roda JC Kerkrade|Roda JC]] on 25 October 2008.<ref>{{cite news|title=Roda JC is PSV opnieuw de baas|url=http://www.gelderlander.nl/sport/voetbal/2.2520/roda-jc-is-psv-opnieuw-de-baas-1.2726243|publisher=De Gelderlander|language=Dutch|date=25 October 2008|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> It wasn't until on 29 November 2008 when he scored his first goal for the club, in a 2\u20132 draw against Heerenveen.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gebrek aan hi\u00ebrarchie bij PSV|url=http://www.parool.nl/sport/gebrek-aan-hierarchie-bij-psv~a59917/|publisher=Het Parool|language=Dutch|date=1 December 2008|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> In his second meeting against his former club Groningen on 21 February 2009, Nijland came on as a late substitute in the second half and scored a winning goal, in a 1\u20130 win.<ref>{{cite news|title=PSV pakt in extremis de punten in Groningen|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/psv-pakt-in-extremis-de-punten-in-groningen.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=21 February 2009|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> However, as the 2008\u201309 season progressed, his first team opportunities was limited, as he appeared most of the time on the substitute bench before an injury forced him out for the rest of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.psv.nl/psv/nieuws/artikel/stef-nijland-voor-de-rest-van-het-seizoen-uitgeschakeld.htm|title=Stef Nijland voor de rest van het seizoen uitgeschakeld|publisher=PSV Eindhoven|language=Dutch|date=8 April 2009|access-date=28 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161031150406/http://www.psv.nl/psv/nieuws/artikel/stef-nijland-voor-de-rest-van-het-seizoen-uitgeschakeld.htm|archive-date=31 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In his first season at PSV, he went on to make nineteen appearance and scoring once in all competitions.\n\nIn the 2009\u201310 season, Nijland made one appearance for PSV, where he came on as a substitute in the second half, in a 2\u20130 win over Roda JC in [[2009\u201310 KNVB Cup#Third round|the third round of KNVB Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|title=PSV bekert verder na winst op Roda JC|url=http://www.gelderlander.nl/sport/psv-bekert-verder-na-winst-op-roda-jc-1.2771640|publisher=De Gelderlander|language=Dutch|date=28 October 2009|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Following his loan spell at Willem II came to an end, he scored on his first appearance for the club in the 2010\u201311 season, in a 3\u20130 win over Sparta Rotterdam in [[2010\u201311 KNVB Cup#Second round|second round of KNVB Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|title=PSV loopt in slotfase weg bij Sparta|url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/sport/psv-loopt-in-slotfase-weg-bij-sparta~a1024427/|publisher=De Volkskrant|language=Dutch|date=22 September 2010|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Nijland went on to make seven appearance in the 2010\u201311 season in all competition.\n\nAfter being told by the club's technical manager Marcel Brands that he would not be at the club next season,<ref>{{cite news|title=Stef Nijland zal niet terugkeren bij PSV Eindhoven|url=http://www.goal.com/nl/news/761/psv/2012/02/27/2933483/stef-nijland-zal-niet-terugkeren-bij-psv|publisher=Goal.com|language=Dutch|date=27 February 2012|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Nijland returned to the club at the end of the 2011\u201312 season and was linked with a move to German side [[TSV 1860 Munich|1860 Munich]] and even started a negotiation between the two parties,<ref>{{cite news|title=PSV-aanvaller Nijland in onderhandeling met Union Berlin|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/psvaanvaller-nijland-in-onderhandeling-met-union-berlin.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=3 December 2012|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> but remained at PSV Eindhoven after he rejected a move to the club.<ref>{{cite news|title=PSV Eindhoven kan overbodige Nijland niet aan Union Berlin slijten|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/psv-kan-overbodige-nijland-niet-aan-union-berlin-slijten.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=4 January 2013|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the 2012\u201313 season, Nijland was released by the club after being told that his contract would not be renewed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Engelaar, Nijland en Vukovic naderen afscheid bij PSV Eindhoven|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/Engelaar-Nijland-en-Vukovic-naderen-afscheid-bij-PSV.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=28 March 2013|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Loan Spells===\nOn 24 December 2009, PSV loaned Nijland to [[Willem II (football club)|Willem II]] for the remainder of the 2009\u201310 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.psv.nl/Nieuws/Nieuwspagina/Stef-Nijland-op-huurbasis-naar-Willem-II.htm|title=Stef N\u0133land op huurbasis naar Willem II|publisher=PSV Eindhoven|language=Dutch|date=25 December 2009|access-date=28 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100126083951/http://www.psv.nl/Nieuws/Nieuwspagina/Stef-Nijland-op-huurbasis-naar-Willem-II.htm|archive-date=26 January 2010|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> Nijland made his Willem II debut on 13 January 2010 in a friendly match against UD Ojen, where he scored five goals, in a 9\u20131 victory for the club.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nijland scoort vijf keer voor Willem II|url=http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/4324/Nieuws/article/detail/1083395/2010/01/13/Nijland-scoort-vijf-keer-voor-Willem-II.dhtml|publisher=Trouw|language=Dutch|date=13 January 2010|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Ten days later on 23 January 2010, he scored on his league debut for Willem II, in a 4\u20132 loss against Heerenveen,<ref>{{cite news|title=Eindelijk weer een zege voor SC Heerenveen|url=http://www.parool.nl/sport/nijland-scoort-vijf-keer-voor-willem-ii~a275416/|publisher=Het Parool|language=Dutch|date=23 January 2010|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> followed up by scoring his second on 29 January 2010, in a 2\u20131 win against [[RKC Waalwijk]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Willem II wint degradatiegevecht met RKC Waalwijk|url=http://www.parool.nl/sport/willem-ii-wint-degradatiegevecht-met-rkc~a277464/|publisher=Het Parool|language=Dutch|date=29 January 2010|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> He went on to score two more goals later in the season against [[N.E.C. (football club)|NEC]],<ref>{{cite news|title=NEC wint inhaalduel met Willem II|url=http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/4324/Nieuws/article/detail/1090913/2010/02/17/NEC-wint-inhaalduel-met-Willem-II.dhtml|publisher=Trouw|language=Dutch|date=17 February 2010|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Sparta Rotterdam<ref>{{cite news|title=Nijland helpt Willem II aan drie punten, zorgen voor Vitesse nemen toe|url=http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/4324/Nieuws/article/detail/1584054/2010/03/15/Nijland-helpt-Willem-II-aan-drie-punten-zorgen-voor-Vitesse-nemen-toe.dhtml|publisher=Trouw|language=Dutch|date=15 March 2010|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> and [[FC Eindhoven|Eindhoven]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Willem II in slotfase langs Eindhoven|url=http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/4324/Nieuws/article/detail/1109860/2010/05/06/Willem-II-in-slotfase-langs-Eindhoven.dhtml|publisher=Trouw|language=Dutch|date=6 May 2010|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> At the end of the 2009\u201310 season, Nijland helped the club survive relegation to ensure that Willem II stayed in the top\u2013flight football for another season and scored five times in twenty appearance.<ref>{{cite news|title=Willem II redt 25e eredivisieschap op rij|url=http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/4324/Nieuws/article/detail/1111244/2010/05/16/Willem-II-redt-25e-eredivisieschap-op-rij.dhtml|publisher=Trouw|language=Dutch|date=16 May 2010|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 May 2011, PSV loaned Nijland to [[N.E.C. (football club)|NEC Nijmegen]] for the 2011/12 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nec-nijmegen.nl/tickets/nieuws/04800_psv-er-stef-nijland-volgt-koolwijk-en-platje-op-weg-naar-het-goffertstadion-u-ook|title=Stef N\u0133land op huurbasis naar NEC Nijmegen|publisher=N.E.C. Nijmegen|language=Dutch|date=25 May 2011|access-date=28 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110528062957/http://www.nec-nijmegen.nl/tickets/nieuws/04800_psv-er-stef-nijland-volgt-koolwijk-en-platje-op-weg-naar-het-goffertstadion-u-ook|archive-date=28 May 2011|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> Nijland scored on his debut in the opening game of the season, in a 2\u20132 draw against Heerenveen.<ref>{{cite news|title=SC Heerenveen geeft zege in vijf minuten uit handen|url=http://www.parool.nl/sport/heerenveen-geeft-zege-in-vijf-minuten-uit-handen~a2840011/|publisher=Het Parool|language=Dutch|date=6 August 2011|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> He scored his second goal of the season, in the [[2011\u201312 KNVB Cup#Second round|second round of KNVB Cup]], in a 4\u20131 win over [[Fortuna Sittard]] on 20 September 2011.<ref>{{cite news|title=NEC ontsnapt in verlenging bij Fortuna Sittard|url=http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/4324/Nieuws/article/detail/2920521/2011/09/20/NEC-ontsnapt-in-verlenging-bij-Fortuna-Sittard.dhtml|publisher=Trouw|language=Dutch|date=20 September 2011|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> However, Nijland suffered injuries as the 2011\u201312 season<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nec-nijmegen.nl/2011/11/n-e-c-onderuit-tegen-roda-jc-1-2/|title=N.E.C. onderuit tegen Roda JC: 1 \u2013 2|publisher=N.E.C. Nijmegen|language=Dutch|date=19 November 2011|access-date=28 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161031171604/http://www.nec-nijmegen.nl/2011/11/n-e-c-onderuit-tegen-roda-jc-1-2/|archive-date=31 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nec-nijmegen.nl/2011/11/update-blessures-selectie-21/|title=Update blessures selectie|publisher=N.E.C. Nijmegen|language=Dutch|date=29 November 2011|access-date=28 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161031171729/http://www.nec-nijmegen.nl/2011/11/update-blessures-selectie-21/|archive-date=31 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nec-nijmegen.nl/2012/04/voorbeschouwing-excelsior-n-e-c/|title=Voorbeschouwing Excelsior \u2013 N.E.C.|publisher=N.E.C. Nijmegen|language=Dutch|date=9 April 2012|access-date=28 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161031172232/http://www.nec-nijmegen.nl/2012/04/voorbeschouwing-excelsior-n-e-c/|archive-date=31 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> and went on to make nineteen appearance and scoring two times in the 2011\u201312 season in all competition.\n\nOn 28 January 2013, N\u0133land went to Australian club [[Brisbane Roar FC|Brisbane Roar]] on a four-month loan deal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Brisbane Roar Have Reportedly Signed Dutch Striker Stef Nijland|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/football/the-brisbane-roar-have-reportedly-signed-dutch-striker-stef-nijland/story-fnddgn65-1226563192354|publisher=The Courier Mail|date=28 January 2013}}</ref> Nijland made his debut for Brisbane in round 19 against [[Central Coast Mariners FC|Central Coast Mariners]] in a 2\u20132 draw.<ref>{{cite news|title=Besart Berisha heroics not enough to top Central Coasr Mariners|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-02-01/berisha-heroics-not-enough-to-top-mariners/4497070?|publisher=ABC (stands for Australian Broadcasting Corporation(|date=1 February 2013}}</ref> Despite keen on signing for the club on a permanent basis,<ref>{{cite news|title=Brisbane Roar keen to secure loan pair Stef Nijland and Steven Lustica|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/loan-pair-hear-roar-for-longer/story-fnddgn65-1226591105466|publisher=The Courier Mail|date=1 February 2013|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Nijland failed to score a single goal in his ten appearances at the club and at the end of the 2012\u201313 season, he returned to his parent club.<ref>{{cite news|title=Brisbane Roar coach Mike Mulvey has eye on overseas talent|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/brisbane-roar-coach-mike-mulvey-has-eye-on-overseas-talent/story-fndcvet9-1226626182283|publisher=The Daily Telegraph|date=23 April 2013|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===PEC Zwolle===\nAfter leaving PSV Eindhoven, Nijland signed for newly promoted side [[PEC Zwolle]], signing a three\u2013year contract, keeping him until 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nijland tekent voor 3 jaar bij PEC Zwolle|url=http://www.ad.nl/eredivisie/nijland-tekent-voor-3-jaar-bij-pec-zwolle~ad2f76cd/|publisher=Algemeen Dagblad|language=Dutch|date=13 May 2013|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Upon joining the club, Nijland re\u2013joined Manager [[Ron Jans]] from his time at Groningen.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nijland en Jans hebben 'positief gesprek' achter de rug|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/nijland-en-jans-hebben-positief-gesprek-achter-de-rug.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=8 May 2013|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nNijland made his PEC Zwolle debut, where he came on as a late substitute, in a 3-0 win over [[Heracles Almelo|Hercales]],<ref>{{cite news|title=PEC trotse koploper na knappe zege bij zwak Heracles|url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/sport/pec-trotse-koploper-na-knappe-zege-bij-zwak-heracles~a3490414/|publisher=De Volkskrant|language=Dutch|date=10 August 2013|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> It wasn't until on 1 September 2013 when he scored his first PEC Zwolle goal, in a 1\u20131 draw against [[FC Utrecht|Utrecht]].<ref>{{cite news|title=PEC Zwolle moet genoegen nemen met gelijkspel|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/pec-zwolle-moet-genoegen-nemen-met-gelijkspel-.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=1 September 2013|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> His second goal then came on 8 December 2013, in a 4\u20131 loss against [[Go Ahead Eagles]].<ref>{{cite news|title=PEC buigt in IJsselderby voor strijd en passie Eagles|url=http://www.ad.nl/eredivisie/pec-buigt-in-ijsselderby-voor-strijd-en-passie-eagles~ae5f060f/|publisher=Algemeen Dagblad|language=Dutch|date=8 December 2013|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> However, his first season at PEC Zwolle was a disappointment for him, as his first team opportunities was limited and restricted into making twenty\u2013five appearance and scoring two times in all competition.<ref>{{cite news|title=De Tien: grootste miskopen van dit Eredivisie-seizoen|url=http://www.voetbalprimeur.nl/nieuws/381467/de-tien-grootste-miskopen-van-dit-eredivisie-seizoen.html|publisher=Voetbal Primeur|language=Dutch|date=25 April 2014|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nFrustrated with a lack of first team opportunities last season, Nijland considered leaving the club ahead of the 2014\u201315 season<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pec.nu/pec-zwolle/stef-nijland-mag-vertrekken/|title=Stef Nijland mag vertrekken|publisher=PEC Zwolle|language=Dutch|date=17 July 2014|access-date=28 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161031202228/http://pec.nu/pec-zwolle/stef-nijland-mag-vertrekken/|archive-date=31 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite this, Nijland was named in the starting eleven in the 2014 Dutch [[2014 Johan Cruijff Schaal|Supercup]]-game between PEC and [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]], where he scored the winning goal in a 1-0 win, giving PEC its first ever Supercup win and himself his second major trophy at the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peczwolle.nl/nl/nieuwsarchief/pec-zwolle-wint-tweede-hoofdprijs-in-paar-maanden-tijd2014-08-03|title=PEC Zwolle wint tweede hoofdprijs in paar maanden tijd!|publisher=PEC Zwolle|language=Dutch|date=3 August 2014|access-date=31 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012214917/http://www.peczwolle.nl/nl/nieuwsarchief/pec-zwolle-wint-tweede-hoofdprijs-in-paar-maanden-tijd2014-08-03|archive-date=12 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Following the match, his performance was praised by the club's director Gerard Nijkamp.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ajax-beul Nijland maakt indruk bij PEC Zwolle|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/ajaxbeul-nijland-maakt-indruk-bij-pec.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=5 August 2013|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Niljand's season proved was an improvement for him, as he was given more first team opportunities and by the first half of the season, he scored five times in seventeen appearance against [[SBV Vitesse|Vitesse]] (in addition to being named Man of the Match by [[Voetbal International]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Matchwinner Nijland vergroot zorgen bij Vitesse|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/matchwinner-nijland-vergroot-zorgen-bij-vitesse.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=24 August 2014|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Heracles Almelo,<ref>{{cite news|title=PEC Zwolle te sterk voor tien Heraclieden|url=http://www.ad.nl/eredivisie/pec-zwolle-te-sterk-voor-tien-heraclieden~a5b014d1/|publisher=Algemeen Dagblad|language=Dutch|date=27 September 2014|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Go Ahead Eagles<ref>{{cite news|title=Go Ahead Eagles weer de sterkste in IJsselderby|url=http://www.ad.nl/eredivisie/go-ahead-eagles-weer-de-sterkste-in-ijsselderby~a2a9e9c9/|publisher=Algemeen Dagblad|language=Dutch|date=19 October 2014|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> and Excelsior (twice).<ref>{{cite news|title=Swingend PEC be\u00ebindigt fraaie thuisreeks van Excelsior|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/swingend-pec-beeindigt-fraaie-thuisreeks-van-excelsior-.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=30 November 2014|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> At the start of 2015, he scored three more goals against Utrecht<ref>{{cite news|title=FC Utrecht na hectische week met Kali ten onder tegen PEC Zwolle|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/fc-utrecht-na-hectische-week-met-kali-ten-onder-tegen-pec-.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=1 February 2015|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> and [[FC Dordrecht|Dordrecht]]<ref>{{cite news|title=PEC Zwolle naar derde plek na ruime zege op FC Dordrecht|url=http://www.ad.nl/eredivisie/pec-zwolle-naar-derde-plek-na-ruime-zege-op-fc-dordrecht~a94083ec/|publisher=Algemeen Dagblad|language=Dutch|date=4 February 2015|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> before receiving a straight red card, in a 1\u20130 loss against Go Ahead Eagles on 15 February 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Go Ahead bedwingt in IJsselderby 10 man PEC|url=http://www.parool.nl/sport/go-ahead-bedwingt-in-ijsselderby-10-man-pec~a3851924/|publisher=Het Parool|language=Dutch|date=15 February 2015|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> After serving a two match suspension,<ref>{{cite news|title=Jans en Nijland accepteren schikkingsvoorstel|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/jans-en-nijland-accepteren-schikkingsvoorstel.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=16 February 2015|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Nijland returned to the first team on 7 March 2015 and scored a hat\u2013trick of his career, in a 6\u20131 win over [[SC Cambuur|Cambuur]] despite playing for twenty\u2013one minutes during the match.<ref>{{cite news|title=PEC Zwolle spoelt reeks nederlagen weg met clubrecord|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/pec-spoelt-reeks-nederlagen-weg-met-clubrecord.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=7 March 2015|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Nijland scoort drie keer in negentien minuten: 'Geweldig'|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/nijland-scoort-drie-keer-in-negentien-minuten-geweldig.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=7 March 2015|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Despite suffering an injury towards the end of the 2014\u201315 season,<ref>{{cite news|title=PEC Zwolle zonder Nijland tegen Vitesse|url=http://www.ad.nl/eredivisie/pec-zwolle-zonder-nijland-tegen-vitesse~af7f4540/|publisher=Algemeen Dagblad|language=Dutch|date=20 May 2015|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Nijland finished the 2014\u201315 season, making thirty\u2013eight appearance and scoring thirteen times in all competitions, making him the club's topscorer.\n\nIn the 2015\u201316 season, Niljand continued to be in the first team regular despite facing new competitions<ref>{{cite news|title=Spits Nijland: verguisd en bejubeld bij PEC Zwolle|url=http://www.ad.nl/eredivisie/spits-nijland-verguisd-en-bejubeld-bij-pec-zwolle~a3050a1f/|publisher=Algemeen Dagblad|language=Dutch|date=9 November 2015|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> and it wasn't until on 7 November 2015 when he scored his first goal of the season, in a 1\u20131 draw against Heracules Almelo,<ref>{{cite news|title=Nijland helpt PEC in extremis aan punt tegen Heracles|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/nijland-helpt-pec-in-extremis-aan-punt-tegen-heracles.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=7 November 2015|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> followed up by scoring in a 5\u20130 win over Roda JC.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vincent Janssen helpt AZ aan overwinning, PEC Zwolle overklast Roda JC|url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/sport/janssen-helpt-az-aan-overwinning-pec-overklast-roda~a4192166/|publisher=De Volkskrant|language=Dutch|date=20 November 2015|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> As the 2015\u201316 season progressed, Niljand went on to score four more goals against Heerenveen,<ref>{{cite news|title=PEC Zwolle zet zwak SC Heerenveen te kijk|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/pec-zwolle-zet-zwak-sc-heerenveen-te-kijk.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=16 January 2016|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> De Graafschap (twice)<ref>{{cite news|title=Tandem Veldwijk-Nijland helpt PEC langs De Graafschap|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/ajax-won-slechts-een-van-de-laatste-zes-duels-met-pec-.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=5 March 2016|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> and Willem II.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cambuur met lege handen na duel met Roda JC, PEC Zwolle houdt zicht op play-offs|url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/sport/cambuur-met-lege-handen-na-duel-met-roda-jc-pec-zwolle-houdt-zicht-op-play-offs~a4266584/|publisher=De Volkskrant|language=Dutch|date=19 March 2016|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> As a result, Niljand signed a contract extension with the club, keeping him until 2018.<ref>{{cite news|title=PEC legt 'Mister Groningen' Nijland langer vast|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/pec-legt-mister-groningen-nijland-langer-vast.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=29 January 2016|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Despite suffering from injuries as the 2015\u201316 season progressed,<ref>{{cite news|title=PEC zonder Nijland tegen FC Twente|url=http://www.ad.nl/eredivisie/pec-zonder-nijland-tegen-fc-twente~a38320f8/|publisher=Algemeen Dagblad|language=Dutch|date=11 March 2016|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=PEC Zwolle op zoek naar twee zeges|url=http://www.gelderlander.nl/algemeen/sport/voetbal/pec-op-zoek-naar-twee-zeges-1.5927854|publisher=De Gelderlander|language=Dutch|date=15 April 2016|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> Nijland finished the 2015\u201316 season, making twenty\u2013seven appearance and scoring six times in all competitions.\n\nIn the 2016\u201317 season, Nijland appeared in the first three matches to the season before a thigh injury, which he sustained during a 4\u20130 defeat to PSV Eindhoven.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kortom \u2013Praet naar Sampdoria, miljoenentransfer Dragovic|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/kortom-praet-naar-sampdoria-miljoenentransfer-dragovic.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=Dutch|date=23 August 2016|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nIn May 2008, Nijland was called up by [[Netherlands national football team|the B Team]].<ref>{{cite news|title=De Haan haalt EK-afvaller Maduro bij selectie|url=http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/4324/Nieuws/article/detail/1224091/2008/05/16/De-Haan-haalt-EK-afvaller-Maduro-bij-selectie.dhtml|publisher=Trouw|language=Dutch|date=16 May 2008|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe is the son of Hans N\u0133land, the former Managing Director of [[FC Groningen]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Groningen boos \u00e9n trots op jonge Nijland|url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/sport/groningen-boos-en-trots-op-jonge-nijland~a314185/|publisher=De Volkskrant|language=Dutch|date=21 February 2009|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to playing football, Nijland said he has been taking Spanish classes in an interview with [[Goal.com]]. Stef also revealed that he's often being called Stefan than Stef.<ref>{{cite news|title=INTERVIEW met Stef Nijland: \"Mijn eerste jaar is een leerjaar\"|url=http://www.goal.com/nl/news/213/eredivisie/2009/01/29/1083377/interview-met-stef-nijland-mijn-eerste-jaar-is-een-leerjaar|publisher=Goal.com|language=Dutch|date=29 January 2011|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{Updated|match played on 1 July 2019}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Stef Nijland \u00bb Club matches |url=https://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/stef-nijland/2/ |website=worldfootball.net |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club!!rowspan=\"2\"|Season!!colspan=\"3\"|League!!colspan=\"2\"|Cup!!colspan=\"2\"|Other!!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[FC Groningen|Groningen]]||[[2007\u201308 Eredivisie|2007\u201308]]||[[Eredivisie]]\n|23||4||0||0||0||0||23||4\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]]||[[2008\u201309 Eredivisie|2008\u201309]]||rowspan=\"3\"|Eredivisie\n|14||1||0||0||3{{efn|Appearances in [[UEFA Champions League]]}}||0||17||1\n|-\n|[[2009\u201310 PSV Eindhoven season|2009\u201310]]\n|0||0||1||0||0||0||1||0\n|-\n|[[2010\u201311 PSV Eindhoven season|2010\u201311]]\n|4||0||2||1||1{{efn|Appearance in [[UEFA Europa League]]}}||0||7||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!18!!1!!3!!1!!4!!0!!25!!2\n|-\n|[[Willem II (football club)|Willem II]] (loan)||[[2009\u201310 Eredivisie|2009\u201310]]||Eredivisie\n|16||4||0||0||4{{efn|Appearances in Promotion/relegation play-offs}}||1||20||5\n|-\n|[[N.E.C. (football club)|NEC]] (loan)||[[2011\u201312 Eredivisie|2011\u201312]]||Eredivisie\n|15||1||2||1||0||0||17||2\n|-\n|[[Brisbane Roar FC|Brisbane Roar]] (loan)||[[2012\u201313 Brisbane Roar FC season|2012\u201313]]||[[A-League]]\n|10||0||0||0||1{{efn|Appearance in [[AFC Champions League]]}}||0||11||0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\"|[[PEC Zwolle]]||[[2013\u201314 Eredivisie|2013\u201314]]||rowspan=\"5\"|Eredivisie\n|23||2||1||0||0||0||24||2\n|-\n|[[2014\u201315 Eredivisie|2014\u201315]]\n|30||11||5||0||3{{efn|Two Appearances in [[UEFA Europa League]], One Appearance in [[Johan Cruyff Shield]]}}||2||38||13\n|-\n|[[2015\u201316 PEC Zwolle season|2015\u201316]]\n|26||6||1||0||0||0||27||6\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 PEC Zwolle season|2016\u201317]]\n|13||0||0||0||0||0||13||0\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 PEC Zwolle season|2017\u201318]]\n|16||1||2||1||0||0||18||2\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!108!!20!!9!!1!!3!!2!!120!!23\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[De Graafschap]]||[[2018\u201319 Eredivisie|2018\u201319]]||rowspan=\"1\"|Eredivisie\n|14||2||2||0||0||0||16||2\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career totals\n!204!!32!!16!!3!!12!!3!!232!!38\n|}\n{{Reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n<div>{{col-begin}}\n{{col-end}}\n</div>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{WorldFootball.net|stef-nijland}}\n* [https://www.vi.nl/spelers/stef-nijland/profiel Stef Nijland] at ''[[Voetbal International]]'' {{in lang|nl}} \u2013 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160123095050/http://www.vi.nl/spelers/carriere/stef-nijland.htm}}\n\n{{De Graafschap squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nijland, Stefan}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dutch footballers]]\n[[Category:FC Groningen players]]\n[[Category:PSV Eindhoven players]]\n[[Category:Willem II (football club) players]]\n[[Category:NEC Nijmegen players]]\n[[Category:PEC Zwolle players]]\n[[Category:De Graafschap players]]\n[[Category:Eredivisie players]]\n[[Category:Brisbane Roar FC players]]\n[[Category:A-League players]]\n[[Category:People from Hoogezand-Sappemeer]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Dutch expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in Australia]]\n[[Category:Dutch expatriate sportspeople in Australia]]\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLoan spells:Fix heading.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stef_Nijland"}
{"title_page": "Paul Newman", "text_new": "{{About|the American actor}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{short description|American actor and film director}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Paul Newman\n| image              = Paul Newman - 1958.jpg\n| caption            = Newman in 1958\n| birth_name         = Paul Leonard Newman\n| birth_date         = {{birth date |1925|1|26}}\n| birth_place        = [[Shaker Heights, Ohio]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2008|9|26|1925|01|26}}\n| death_place        = [[Westport, Connecticut]], U.S.\n| occupation         = Actor, film director, producer, race car driver, indy car owner, entrepreneur\n| nationality        = American\n| years_active       = 1953\u20132008\n| organizations      = [[SeriousFun Children's Network]], [[Safe Water Network]]\n| party              = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| height             = \n| spouse             = {{marriage|Jackie Witte|1949|1958|end=divorced}}<br />{{marriage|[[Joanne Woodward]]|1958}}\n| children           = 6; including [[Scott Newman (actor)|Scott]], [[Nell Newman|Nell]], [[Melissa Newman]] and [[Clea Newman Soderlund]]\n| education          = [[Kenyon College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Yale University]]\n}}\n\n'''Paul Leonard Newman''' (January 26, 1925 \u2013 September 26, 2008) was an [[United States|American]] actor, film director, producer, race car driver, [[Champ Car|IndyCar]] owner, entrepreneur, and philanthropist. He [[List of awards and nominations received by Paul Newman|won and was nominated for numerous awards]], winning an [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] for his performance in the 1986 film ''[[The Color of Money]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url= http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/help/helpMain.jsp?helpContentURL=statistics/indexStats.html |title= Persons with 5 or More Acting Nominations |date=March 2008 |accessdate= December 30, 2008 |publisher=[[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090301005626/http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/help/helpMain.jsp?helpContentURL=statistics%2FindexStats.html |archivedate= March 1, 2009 }}</ref> a [[BAFTA Award]], a [[Screen Actors Guild Award]], a [[Cannes Film Festival|Cannes Film Festival Award]], an [[Emmy Award]], and many others. Newman's other roles include the title characters in ''[[The Hustler (film)|The Hustler]]'' (1961), ''[[Hud (1963 film)|Hud]]'' (1963), ''[[Harper (film)|Harper]]'' (1966), ''[[Cool Hand Luke]]'' (1967), ''[[Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid]]'' (1969), ''[[The Life and Times of Judge Roy Bean]]'' (1972), and leading roles in ''[[The Sting]]'' (1973), ''[[Slap Shot]]'' (1977), and ''[[The Verdict]]'' (1982). He voiced [[Doc Hudson]] in the [[Cars (film)|first installment]] of [[Pixar|Disney-Pixar's]] ''[[Cars (franchise)|Cars]]'' as his final acting performance, with voice recordings being used in ''[[Cars 3]]'' (2017).\n\nNewman won several national championships as a driver in [[Sports Car Club of America]] road racing, and his race teams won several championships in [[open wheel racing|open-wheel]] [[Champ Car|IndyCar]] racing. He was a co-founder of [[Newman's Own]], a food company from which he donated all post-tax profits and royalties to charity.<ref name=\"faq\">{{cite web|url=http://newmansownfoundation.org/about-us |title= Newman's Own Foundation - More than $350 Million Donated Around the World |work= newmansownfoundation.org |accessdate= October 21, 2015}}</ref> As of November 2018, these donations have totaled over US$535&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://newmansownfoundation.org/about-us/total-giving |title= Total Giving |website= newmansownfoundation.org |accessdate= June 27, 2016 }}</ref> He was a co-founder of [[Safe Water Network]], a nonprofit that develops sustainable drinking water solutions for those in need.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kaye |first1= Leon |title= How Safe Water Network's Partnership With Companies Benefits the World's Poor |url= http://www.triplepundit.com/2012/10/safe-water-networks-partnership-companies-benefits-worlds-poor |website= triplepundit.com |publisher= Triple Pundit |accessdate= September 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, Newman founded the [[SeriousFun Children's Network]], a global family of [[summer camps]] and programs for children with serious illness which has served 290,076 children since its inception.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.seriousfunnetwork.org/serious-impact |title= A Global Community of Camps and Programs |work= seriousfunnetwork.org |accessdate= October 21, 2015}}</ref> In 2006, Paul Newman also co-founded [[Safe Water Network]] with [[John C. Whitehead|John Whitehead]], former chairman of Goldman Sachs, and Josh Weston, former chairman of ADP, to improve access to safe water to underserved communities around the world. He was the husband of Oscar winning actress [[Joanne Woodward]].\n\n==Early life==\nNewman was born January 26, 1925, in [[Shaker Heights, Ohio]], the second son of Theresa Garth ([[married and maiden names|''n\u00e9e'']] Fetzer, Fetzko, or Fetsko; {{lang-sk|Ter\u00e9zia Feckov\u00e1}};<ref name=LaxE->[[Eric Lax|Lax, Eric]] (1996). ''Paul Newman: A Biography''. Atlanta: Turner Publishing; {{ISBN|1-57036-286-6}}.</ref><ref name=\"Morella\">Morella, Joe; Epstein, Edward Z. (1988). ''Paul and Joanne: A Biography of Paul Newman and Joanne Woodward''. Delacorte Press; {{ISBN|0-440-50004-4}}.</ref> 1894\u20131982) and Arthur Sigmund Newman, Sr. (1893\u20131950)<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/54622376/arthur-sigmund-newman Arthur Sigmund Newman, Sr]</ref>, who ran a sporting goods store.<ref>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/15/Paul-Newman.html Profile], FilmReference.com; accessed October 21, 2015.</ref><ref name=gen>{{cite web |date= 2010 |url= http://genealogy.com/famousfolks/paul-newman/index.html |title= Ancestry of Paul Newman |accessdate= December 14, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100927095315/http://genealogy.com/famousfolks/paul-newman/index.html |archivedate= September 27, 2010 |agency= Genealogy.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.scribd.com/doc/15233061/Paul-Newman-A-Life-by-Shawn-Levy-Excerpt |title= Paul Newman: A Life |first=Shawn |last=Levy |format= excerpt |publisher= Scribd.com |date= November 5, 2009 |accessdate= February 1, 2012}}</ref>\n\nPaul's father was [[Jews|Jewish]],<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/was-paul-newmans-acting-career-limited-by-his-charm-and-good-looks-1927486.html |title= Was Paul Newman's acting career limited by his charm and good looks? |website=The Independent |date= March 26, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Tom|last=Tugend|url=http://jewishjournal.com/uncategorized/66267/|title=Paul Newman \u2013 Hollywood's most famous half-Jew \u2013 dies at 83 [VIDEO]|work=[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles]]|date=September 28, 2008|accessdate=May 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/film-tv/news/paul-newman-actor-racing-driver-activist-and-philanthropist-28449059.html|title=Paul Newman: Actor, racing driver, activist and philanthropist|last=|first=|date=September 29, 2008|work=BelfastTelegraph.co.uk|access-date=May 27, 2018|language=|issn=}}</ref> the son of Simon Newman and Hannah Cohn, [[Hungarian-Jewish]] and [[Polish-Jewish]] emigrants from [[Kingdom of Hungary|Hungary]] and [[Vistula Land]].<ref name=gen/><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=AfgbEC0LrFMC&pg=PA1 |title= Paul Newman: A Biography |page=1 |isbn= 9780313383113 |last1= Borden |first1= Marian Edelman |date= November 2, 2010 }}</ref> Paul's mother was a practitioner of [[Christian Science]]. She was born to a [[Slovaks|Slovak]] [[Roman Catholic]] family in Peticse (near Homonna) in the [[Austro-Hungarian Empire]] (present-day [[Pti\u010die]] near [[Humenn\u00e9]], [[Slovakia]]).<ref name=\"Morella\"/><ref>\"Paul Newman, A Big Gun at 73\". ''[[Buffalo News]]''. March 7, 1998; retrieved March 8, 2008.</ref><ref>[http://www.pticie.host.sk/english.htm Pti\u010die] {{webarchive |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080317131910/http://www.pticie.host.sk/english.htm |date= March 17, 2008}}, Obecn\u00fd \u00farad Pti\u010die, pticie.host.sk; accessed October 21, 2015. {{in lang|sk}}</ref><ref>[http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2008/09/27/cultura/1222521210.html \"Fallece el actor Paul Newman\"], Elmundo.es, September 27, 2008. {{in lang|es}}</ref> Newman had no religion as an adult, but described himself as a Jew, saying \"it's more of a challenge\".<ref name=\"time\">Skow, John. [http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,923114-5,00.html \"Verdict on a Superstar\"]. [[Time (magazine)|''Time'']]. December 6, 1982.</ref> Newman's mother worked in his father's store, while raising Paul and his elder brother, Arthur,<ref>{{cite web |url= https://former.imdb.com/name/nm0627983/?ref_=fn_al_nm_1 |title= Arthur S. Newman Jr. |work=IMDb |accessdate= October 21, 2015}}</ref> who later became a producer and production manager.<ref name=\"tiscali\">[http://www.tiscali.co.uk/entertainment/film/biographies/paul_newman_biog.html Paul Newman biography] {{webarchive |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20071023063214/http://www.tiscali.co.uk/entertainment/film/biographies/paul_newman_biog.html |date= October 23, 2007}}, Tiscali.co.uk.com; accessed October 21, 2015.</ref>\n\nNewman showed an early interest in the theater; his first role was at the age of seven, playing the court jester in a school production of ''[[Robin Hood]]''. At age 10, Newman performed at the [[Cleveland Play House]] in a production of ''[[St. George and the Dragon|Saint George and the Dragon]]'', and was a notable actor and alumnus of their Curtain Pullers children's theatre program.<ref name=\"Cleveland Mem\">{{cite web |title= Paul Newman at The Cleveland Play House Children's Theatre|url= http://images.ulib.csuohio.edu/cdm/ref/collection/press/id/5556 |website= The Cleveland Memory Project |accessdate= May 28, 2015}}</ref> Graduating from [[Shaker Heights High School]] in 1943, he briefly attended [[Ohio University]] in [[Athens, Ohio]], where he was initiated into the [[Phi Kappa Tau]] fraternity.<ref name=\"tiscali\"/>\n\nNewman served in the [[United States Navy]] in [[World War II]] in the [[Asiatic-Pacific Theater|Pacific theater]].<ref name=\"tiscali\"/> Initially, he enrolled in the Navy [[V-12 Navy College Training Program|V-12]] pilot training program at [[Yale University]], but was dropped when his [[colorblindness]] was discovered.<ref name=\"tiscali\"/><ref name=\"navy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.history.navy.mil/bios/newman_p.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141125005231/http://www.history.navy.mil/bios/newman_p.htm|archivedate=November 25, 2014|title=Biographies in Naval History: Paul Newman|website=United States Navy, Naval History and Heritage Command}}</ref>\n\nBoot camp followed, with training as a radioman and rear gunner. Qualifying in [[torpedo bomber]]s in 1944, [[Radioman|Aviation Radioman Third Class]] Newman was sent to [[Barbers Point]], [[Hawaii]]. He was subsequently assigned to Pacific-based replacement torpedo squadrons VT-98, VT-99, and VT-100, responsible primarily for training replacement combat pilots and air crewmen, with special emphasis on carrier landings.<ref name=\"navy\"/> He later flew as a turret gunner in an [[Grumman TBF Avenger|Avenger]] torpedo bomber. As a radioman-gunner, his unit was assigned to the aircraft carrier {{USS|Bunker Hill|CV-17|2}} along with other replacements shortly before the [[Battle of Okinawa]] in the spring of 1945. The pilot of his aircraft had an ear infection, which kept their plane grounded. The rest of their squadron flew to the ''Bunker Hill''. Days later, a [[kamikaze]] attack on the vessel killed a number of service members, including the other members of his unit.<ref>{{cite book |authorlink=Max Hastings |last=Hastings |first=Max |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CJjkIWfuGCkC |title=Retribution: The Battle for Japan, 1944-45 |isbn=9780307275363 |year=2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Honoring Those Who Serve|url=http://newmansownfoundation.org/military|accessdate=October 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter the war, Newman completed his [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in [[drama]] and [[economics]] at [[Kenyon College]] in [[Gambier, Ohio]] in 1949.<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[USA Today]]|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/movies/2007-06-02-1290486787_x.htm|title=Newman gives $10M to Ohio alma mater|date=June 2, 2007|accessdate=September 19, 2013}}</ref> Shortly after earning his degree, he joined several summer stock companies, most notably the [[Belfry Players]] in [[Wisconsin]]<ref>Franzene, Jessica, \"Theologians & Thespians,\" in Welcome Home, a realtors' guide to property history in the Lake Geneva region, August 2012</ref> and the Woodstock Players in [[Illinois]]. He toured with them for three months and developed his talents as a part of Woodstock Players.<ref name=\"tiscali\"/><ref>{{Cite book |last1=Borden |first1=Marian Edelman |date=2010 |title=Paul Newman: A Biography |url=https://books.google.com/?id=AfgbEC0LrFMC&pg=PA11 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |page=11 |isbn=978-0-313-38310-6}}</ref> He later attended the [[Yale School of Drama]] for one year, before moving to [[New York City]] to study under [[Lee Strasberg]] at the [[Actors Studio]].<ref name=\"tiscali\"/> [[Oscar Levant]] wrote that Newman initially was hesitant to leave New York for Hollywood, and that Newman had said, \"Too close to the cake. Also, no place to study.\"<ref>[[Oscar Levant|Levant, Oscar]] (1969). ''[[The Unimportance of Being Oscar]]''. Pocket Books. p. 56; {{ISBN|0-671-77104-3}}.</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Paul Newman 1954.JPG|thumb|Newman in 1954]]\nNewman arrived in New York City in 1951 with his first wife, Jackie Witte, taking up residence in the [[St. George, Staten Island|St. George]] section of [[Staten Island]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.silive.com/news/index.ssf/2008/09/actor_paul_newmans_dramatic_ro.html|title=Actor Paul Newman's dramatic roots were sprouted on Staten Island|website=SILive.com|publisher=[[Staten Island Advance]]|accessdate=September 2, 2015|date=September 27, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://forgotten-ny.com/NEIGHBORHOODS/cynthiatour/st.george.html|title=Forgotten-NY Neighborhoods: St. George: Staten Island's Wonderland|accessdate=July 13, 2014 |url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090213101046/http://forgotten-ny.com/NEIGHBORHOODS/cynthiatour/st.george.html |archivedate=February 13, 2009}}</ref>\n\nHe made his [[Broadway theatre]] debut in the original production of [[William Inge]]'s ''[[Picnic (play)|Picnic]]'' with [[Kim Stanley]] in 1953 and appeared in the original Broadway production of ''[[The Desperate Hours (play)|The Desperate Hours]]'' in 1955. In 1959, he was in the original Broadway production of ''[[Sweet Bird of Youth]]'' with [[Geraldine Page]] and three years later starred with Page in the film version. During this time Newman started acting in television. His first credited role was in a 1952 episode of ''[[Tales of Tomorrow]]'' entitled \"Ice from Space\".<ref>{{cite episode|title=Ice From Space|series=Tales of Tomorrow|serieslink=Tales of Tomorrow|airdate=August 8, 1952|season=1|number=43}}</ref> In the mid-1950s, he appeared twice on [[CBS]]'s ''[[Appointment with Adventure]]'' [[anthology series]].<ref name=IMDb1/>\n\nIn February 1954, Newman appeared in a [[screen test]] with [[James Dean]], directed by [[Gjon Mili]], for ''[[East of Eden (film)|East of Eden]]'' (1955). Newman was tested for the role of Aron Trask, Dean for the role of Aron's twin brother Cal. Dean won his part, but Newman lost out to [[Richard Davalos]]. That same year, he co-starred with [[Eva Marie Saint]] and [[Frank Sinatra]] in a live\u2014and color\u2014television broadcast of ''[[Our Town (television)|Our Town]]'', a musical adaptation of [[Thornton Wilder]]'s stage play. Newman was a last-minute replacement for James Dean.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Weiner|first=Ed|last2=Editors of TV Guide|title=The TV Guide TV Book: 40 Years of the All-Time Greatest Television Facts, Fads, Hits, and History|place=New York|publisher=Harper Collins|year=1992|edition=First|page=118}}</ref> Newman also replaced Dean after Dean's death as a boxer in a television adaptation by A. E. Hotchner of a Hemingway story, \"The Battler,\" which was broadcast live on October 18, 1955, and directed by Arthur Penn. That performance led to his breakthrough role as Rocky Graziano in the film ''Somebody Up There Likes Me'' in 1956.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Weber|first=Bruce|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/15/books/a-e-hotchner-dead.html|title=A. E. Hotchner, Writer and Friend of the Famous, Dies at 102|date=2020-02-15|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-04|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>The Dean connection had resonance two other times, as Newman was cast in two leading roles originally earmarked for Dean, as Billy the Kid in ''[[The Left Handed Gun]]'' and as [[Rocky Graziano]] in ''[[Somebody Up There Likes Me (1956 film)|Somebody Up There Likes Me]]'', both filmed after Dean's death in an automobile collision.<ref name=IMDb1/> \n\nNewman's first film for Hollywood was ''[[The Silver Chalice (film)|The Silver Chalice]]'' (1954). The film was a box-office failure, and the actor would later acknowledge his disdain for it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OKRWD9ec_Eo|title=Inside The Actors Studio \u2013 Paul Newman|publisher=YouTube|date=June 8, 2011|accessdate=February 1, 2012}}</ref> In 1956, Newman garnered much attention and acclaim for the role of Rocky Graziano in ''[[Somebody Up There Likes Me (1956 film)|Somebody Up There Likes Me]]''. In 1958, he starred in ''[[Cat on a Hot Tin Roof (1958 film)|Cat on a Hot Tin Roof]]'' (1958), opposite [[Elizabeth Taylor]]. The film was a box-office smash, and Newman garnered his first Academy Award nomination. Also in 1958, Newman starred in ''[[The Long, Hot Summer]]'' with [[Joanne Woodward]], with whom he reconnected on the set in 1957 (they had first met in 1953). He won Best Actor at the [[1958 Cannes Film Festival]] for this film.<ref name=IMDb1/>\n\n===Major films===\nNewman starred in ''[[The Young Philadelphians]]'' (1959), a [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] which co-starred [[Barbara Rush]], [[Robert Vaughn]] and [[Alexis Smith]], and was directed by [[Vincent Sherman]].<ref name=\"The Young Philadelphians\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/26570/The-Young-Philadelphians/full-credits.html|title=The Young Philadelphians|work=[[Turner Classic Movies]]|publisher=[[Turner Broadcasting System]] ([[Time Warner]])|location=[[Atlanta]]|accessdate=November 14, 2016}}</ref> The film was based on the 1956 novel, ''The Philadelphian'', by [[Richard P. Powell]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://www.amazon.com/Philadelphian-novel-Richard-Powell/dp/B000WA4UPO|title=The Philadelphian, a novel|last=Powell|first=Richard P.|publisher=[[Charles Scribner's Sons]]|year=1956|location=[[New York City]]|asin=B000WA4UPO|authorlink=Richard P. Powell}}</ref>\n\n[[File:The Hustler 1961 screenshot 4.png|thumb|Newman in ''[[The Hustler (film)|The Hustler]]'' (1961)]]\n[[File:Paul Newman in front of St. Mark%27s Square, 1963.jpg|thumb|Paul Newman riding a water taxi in Venice, 1963]]\nHe followed up with leads in ''[[Exodus (1960 film)|Exodus]]'' (1960), ''[[From the Terrace]]'', (1960), ''[[The Hustler (film)|The Hustler]]'' (1961), ''[[Hud (1963 film)|Hud]]'' (1963), ''[[Torn Curtain]]'' (1966), ''[[Harper (film)|Harper]]'' (1966), ''[[Hombre (film)|Hombre]]'' (1967), ''[[Cool Hand Luke]]'' (1967), ''[[The Towering Inferno]]'' (1974), ''[[Slap Shot (film)|Slap Shot]]'' (1977), ''[[Absence of Malice]]'' (1981) and ''[[The Verdict]]'' (1982). He teamed up with fellow actor [[Robert Redford]] and director [[George Roy Hill]] for ''[[Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid]]'' (1969) and ''[[The Sting]]'' (1973). After his marriage to Woodward they appeared together in ''[[The Long, Hot Summer]]'' (1958), ''[[Rally 'Round the Flag, Boys!]]'', (1958), ''[[From the Terrace]]'' (1960), ''[[Paris Blues]]'' (1961), ''[[A New Kind of Love]]'' (1963), ''[[Winning (film)|Winning]]'' (1969), ''[[WUSA (film)|WUSA]]'' (1970), playing Harper for a 2nd time in ''[[The Drowning Pool (film)|The Drowning Pool]]'' (1975), ''[[Slap Shot (film)|Slap Shot]]'' (1977) ''[[Harry & Son]]'' (1984), and ''[[Mr. and Mrs. Bridge]]'' (1990). They starred in the [[HBO]] [[miniseries]] ''[[Empire Falls (miniseries)|Empire Falls]]'', but did not share any scenes.\n\n[[File:Paul Newman Cannes 1987.jpg|thumb|upright|Newman at the [[1987 Cannes Film Festival]]]]\nIn addition to starring in and directing ''Harry & Son'', Newman directed four feature films starring Woodward. They were ''[[Rachel, Rachel]]'' (1968), based on [[Margaret Laurence]]'s ''A Jest of God'', the screen version of the [[Pulitzer Prize]]\u2013winning play ''[[The Effect of Gamma Rays on Man-in-the-Moon Marigolds]]'' (1972), the television screen version of the Pulitzer Prize\u2013winning play ''[[The Shadow Box]]'' (1980), and a screen version of [[Tennessee Williams]]' ''[[The Glass Menagerie (1987 film)|The Glass Menagerie]]'' (1987). Twenty-five years after ''The Hustler'', Newman reprised his role of \"Fast Eddie\" Felson in the [[Martin Scorsese]]\u2013directed film ''[[The Color of Money]]'' (1986), for which he won the Academy Award for Best Actor.<ref>{{cite web|title=\"1986 Award Winners\". National Board of Review of Motion Pictures|url=http://www.nationalboardofreview.org/award-years/1986/|website=National Board of Review|accessdate=October 31, 2016|date=2016}}</ref> Some deemed this to be a weak rinse of the original Felson role and the Academy Award as an honorary tribute to a portfolio of Oscar-nominated roles that had not won at the time but were more deserving. In 1994 Newman played alongside [[Tim Robbins]] as the character \"Sidney J. Mussburger\" in the [[Coen Brothers]] comedy ''[[The Hudsucker Proxy]]''.\n\n===21st century roles===\nIn 2003, Newman appeared in a Broadway revival of Wilder's ''[[Our Town]]'', receiving his first Tony Award nomination for his performance. [[PBS]] and the cable network [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] aired a taping of the production, and Newman was nominated for an Emmy Award<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/celebrities/paul-newman|title=Paul Newman|work=Television Academy|accessdate=October 21, 2015}}</ref> for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Miniseries or TV Movie.\n\nNewman's last movie appearance was as a conflicted mob boss in the 2002 film ''[[Road to Perdition]]'' opposite [[Tom Hanks]], for which he was nominated for an Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor. His last appearance overall, although he continued to provide voice work for films, was in 2005 in the HBO mini-series ''[[Empire Falls (miniseries)|Empire Falls]]'' (based on the [[Empire Falls|Pulitzer Prize-winning novel]] by [[Richard Russo]]) in which he played the dissolute father of the protagonist, Miles Roby, and for which he won a Golden Globe and a Primetime Emmy. In 2006, in keeping with his strong interest in car racing, he provided the voice of [[Doc Hudson]], a retired anthropomorphic race car, in [[Walt Disney Pictures|Disney]]/[[Pixar]]'s ''[[Cars (film)|Cars]]'' \u2013 this was his final role for a major feature film. While not in the second film ''[[Cars 2]]'' (2011), his voice was later used in the third film, (which was done through the use of archive recordings) ''[[Cars 3]]'' (2017), for which he received billing, almost nine years after his death.\n\n[[File:Paul Newman in Carnation, Washington June 2007 cropped.jpg|thumb|upright|Newman in 2007]]\nNewman retired from acting in May 2007, saying \"You start to lose your memory, you start to lose your confidence, you start to lose your invention. So I think that's pretty much a closed book for me.\"<ref>[http://www.news.com.au/story/0,23599,21797406-2,00.html \"Paul Newman quits films after stellar career\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070528072858/http://www.news.com.au/story/0%2C23599%2C21797406-2%2C00.html |date=May 28, 2007 }}, News.com.au. May 27, 2007. [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6695939.stm ''Hollywood star Newman to retire''], bbc.co.uk, May 27, 2007.</ref> He came out of retirement to record narration for the 2007 documentary ''[[Dale (film)|Dale]]'', about the life of [[NASCAR]] driver [[Dale Earnhardt]], and for the 2008 documentary ''[[The Meerkats]]''.\n\n==Philanthropy==\nWith writer [[A. E. Hotchner]], Newman founded [[Newman's Own]], a line of food products, in 1982. The brand started with salad dressing and has expanded to include pasta sauce, lemonade, popcorn, salsa, and wine, among other things. Newman established a policy that all proceeds, after taxes, would be donated to charity. He co-wrote a [[memoir]] about the subject with Hotchner, ''Shameless Exploitation in Pursuit of the Common Good''. Among other awards, Newman's Own co-sponsors the [[PEN/Newman's Own First Amendment Award]], a $25,000 reward designed to recognize those who protect the [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] as it applies to the written word.<ref>{{cite web|title=PEN/Newman's Own First Amendment Award recipient announced|url=https://pen.org/press-release/pennewmans-own-first-amendment-award-recipient-announced/|website=PEN American Center|accessdate=January 2, 2013|date=April 5, 2004}}</ref>\n\nOne beneficiary of his philanthropy is the [[Hole in the Wall Gang Camp]], a residential summer camp for seriously ill children located in [[Ashford, Connecticut]], which Newman co-founded in 1988. It is named after the gang in his film ''Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid'' (1969), and the real-life, historic [[Hole-in-the-Wall]] outlaw hangout in the mountains of northern [[Wyoming]]. Newman's college fraternity, [[Phi Kappa Tau]], adopted his Connecticut Hole in the Wall camp as their \"national philanthropy\" in 1995. The original camp has expanded to become several Hole in the Wall Camps in the U.S., Ireland, France, and Israel.<ref name=\"faq\"/>\n\nIn 1983, Newman became a Major Donor for [[The Mirror Theater Ltd]], alongside [[Dustin Hoffman]] and [[Al Pacino]], matching a grant from [[Laurence Rockefeller]].<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/12/07/arts/broadway.html |title = Broadway|newspaper = The New York Times|date = December 7, 1984|last1 = Nemy|first1 = Enid}}</ref> Newman was inspired to invest by his connection with [[Lee Strasberg]], as Lee's then daughter-in-law Sabra Jones was the Founder and Producing Artistic Director of The Mirror. Paul Newman remained a friend of the company until his death and discussed at numerous times possible productions in which he could star with his wife, [[Joanne Woodward]].\n\nIn June 1999, Newman donated $250,000 to [[Catholic Relief Services]] to aid refugees in [[Kosovo]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Paul Newman Philanthropy|url=http://www.facesofphilanthropy.com/paul-newman/|date=November 14, 2011|accessdate=November 14, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn June 1, 2007, [[Kenyon College]] announced that Newman had donated $10&nbsp;million to the school to establish a scholarship fund as part of the college's $230&nbsp;million fund-raising campaign. Newman and Woodward were honorary co-chairs of a previous campaign.<ref name=\"Reuters-Kenyon\">{{cite news|title=Paul Newman donates $10 mln to Kenyon College|work=Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/entertainmentNews/idUSN0238991920070602|date=June 2, 2007|accessdate=June 4, 2007}}</ref>\n\nNewman was one of the founders of the Committee Encouraging Corporate Philanthropy (CECP).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.corporatephilanthropy.org|title=CECP \u2013 Committee Encouraging Corporate Philanthropy|publisher=Corporatephilanthropy.org|accessdate=March 10, 2010}}</ref>\nNewman was named the Most Generous Celebrity of 2008 by Givingback.org. He contributed $20,857,000 for the year of 2008 to the Newman's Own Foundation, which distributes funds to a variety of charities.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Giving Back 30 |url=http://www.givingback.org/Programs_Services/GivingBack30_2008.html |publisher=The Giving Back Fund |date=November 1, 2009 |accessdate=November 4, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091109044844/http://givingback.org/Programs_Services/GivingBack30_2008.html |archivedate=November 9, 2009 |df= }}</ref>\n\nUpon Newman's death, the Italian newspaper (a \"semi-official\" paper of the [[Holy See]]) ''[[L'Osservatore Romano]]'' published a notice lauding Newman's philanthropy. It also commented that \"Newman was a generous heart, an actor of a dignity and style rare in Hollywood quarters.\"<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[Catholic News Service]]|url=http://www.catholicnews.com/data/stories/cns/0804957.htm|archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20130307090949/http://www.catholicnews.com/data/stories/cns/0804957.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=March 7, 2013|title=Catholic film critics laud actor Paul Newman's career, generosity|first=Mark|last=Pattison|date=September 30, 2008|accessdate=April 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\nNewman was responsible for preserving lands around Westport, Connecticut. He lobbied the state's governor for funds for the 2011 Aspetuck Land Trust in Easton.<ref name=\"BrooksBrooks2011\">{{cite book|author1=Christopher Brooks|author2=Catherine Brooks|title=60 Hiles Within 60 Miles: New York City|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6O-VwJe-oEwC&pg=PA620|accessdate=February 19, 2013|date=April 22, 2011|publisher=ReadHowYouWant.com|isbn=978-1-4596-1793-3|pages=620\u2013621}}</ref> In 2011 Paul Newman's estate gifted land to Westport to be managed by the [[Aspetuck Land Trust]].<ref name=Hennessy2011>{{cite news|last=Hennessy|first=Christina|title=Sightseeing: Newman Poses Nature Preserve may have marquee name, but nature is the star|url=http://www.ctpost.com/news/article/Sightseeing-Newman-Poses-Nature-Preserve-may-2226539.php|accessdate=September 16, 2012|newspaper=The Stamford Advocate|date=October 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Political activism==\n[[File:Paul newman menomonee falls wisconsin mcarthy eugene rally.jpg|thumb|upright|Newman at a political rally for [[Eugene McCarthy]] in 1968]]\nNewman was a lifelong [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]. For his support of [[Eugene McCarthy]] in [[1968 United States presidential election|1968]] (and effective use of television commercials in California) and his opposition to the [[Vietnam War]], Newman was placed nineteenth on [[Nixon's Enemies List|Richard Nixon's enemies list]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artsci.wustl.edu/~polisci/calvert/PolSci3103/watergate/enemy.htm |title=List of White House 'Enemies' and Memo Submitted by Dean to the Ervin Committee |publisher=Facts on File |accessdate=March 10, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030621235432/http://www.artsci.wustl.edu/~polisci/calvert/PolSci3103/watergate/enemy.htm |archivedate=June 21, 2003 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> which Newman claimed was his greatest accomplishment. During the 1968 general election, Newman supported Democratic nominee Hubert Humphrey and appeared in a pre-election night telethon for him. Newman was also a vocal supporter of gay rights.<ref>Levy 2009, p. 241.</ref><ref>Borden 2010, p. 96.</ref>\n\nIn January 1995, Newman was the chief investor of a group, including the writer [[E.L. Doctorow]] and the editor [[Victor Navasky]], that bought the progressive-left wing periodical ''[[The Nation]]''.<ref name=\"st\">{{cite news|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19950114&slug=2099418|title=Liberal Weekly The Nation Sold To Paul Newman, Others|newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=January 14, 1995|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> Newman was an occasional writer for the publication.<ref name=\"nationbye\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.thenation.com/article/paul-newmanin-his-own-words|title=Paul Newman:In His Own Words|last=Newman|first=Paul|magazine=The Nation|date=August 21, 2000|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nConsistent with his work for [[Liberalism in the United States|liberal]] causes, Newman publicly supported [[Ned Lamont]]'s candidacy in the 2006 Connecticut Democratic Primary against Senator [[Joe Lieberman]], and was even rumored as a candidate himself, until Lamont emerged as a credible alternative. He donated to [[Christopher Dodd|Chris Dodd]]'s presidential campaign.<ref>[http://www.wfsb.com/politics/12281464/detail.html?rss=hart&psp=news ''Dodd Gets Financial Boost From Celebs''], WFSB.com, April 17, 2007. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110509071619/http://www.wfsb.com/politics/12281464/detail.html?rss=hart&psp=news |date=May 9, 2011 }}</ref> Newman earlier donated money to [[Bill Richardson]]'s campaign for president in 2008.\n\nNewman attended the [[March on Washington]] on August 28, 1963,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.realclearpolitics.com/articles/2013/08/29/hollywood_whos_who_marched_with_king_in_63__119762.html|title=Hollywood Who's Who Marched With King In '63|work=RealClearPolitics.com|date=August 29, 2013|accessdate=December 6, 2016|first=Carl|last=Cannon}}</ref> and was also present at the first [[Earth Day]] event in [[Manhattan]] on April 22, 1970.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2008/09/28/MN8R1194R6.DTL|title=Paul Newman an icon of cool masculinity|work=San Francisco Chronicle|date=September 28, 2008|accessdate=March 10, 2010|first=Steven|last=Winn}}</ref>\n\nNewman was concerned about [[global warming]] and supported [[Nuclear energy in the United States|nuclear energy development]] as [[Global warming mitigation#Nuclear power|a solution]].<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/people/2007-05-23-paul-newman_N.htm|title=Cool Hand Nuke: Paul Newman endorses power plant|date=May 23, 2007|accessdate=April 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Auto racing==\n{{Infobox Le Mans driver\n| Name=\n| Image=\n| Nationality=\n| Years=[[1979 24 Hours of Le Mans|1979]]\n| Team(s)=Dick Barbour Racing\n| Best Finish=2nd <small>([[1979 24 Hours of Le Mans|1979]])</small>\n| Class Wins=1 <small>([[1979 24 Hours of Le Mans|1979]])</small>}}\n[[File:Paul Newman Racing 1979 Spyder NF-11 Chevrolet V8 - CanAm single seater racer based on Lola T333CS.jpg|thumb|right|A ''Newman Freeman Racing'' [[Spyder NF]] [[Can-Am]] race car from 1979 (photograph taken 2011)]]\n\nNewman was an auto racing enthusiast, and first became interested in motorsports (\"the first thing that I ever found I had any grace in\") while training at the [[Watkins Glen International|Watkins Glen Racing School]] for the filming of ''[[Winning (film)|Winning]]'', a 1969 film. Because of his love and passion for racing, Newman agreed in 1971 to star in and to host his first television special, ''[[Once Upon a Wheel]],'' on the history of auto racing. It was produced and directed by [[David Winters (choreographer)|David Winters]], who co-owned a number of racing cars with Newman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.davidwinters.net/onceuponawheel.htm|title=Once Upon A Wheel|publisher=Davidwinters.net|accessdate=February 1, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005062236/http://www.davidwinters.net/onceuponawheel.htm|archivedate=October 5, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.davidwinters.net/archives.htm|title=David Winters Tribute Site|publisher=Davidwinters.net|date=April 1, 2003|accessdate=February 1, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120217010533/http://www.davidwinters.net/archives.htm|archivedate=February 17, 2012}}</ref> Newman's first professional event as a racer was in 1972 at [[Thompson International Speedway]], quietly entered as \"P. L. Newman\", by which he continued to be known in the racing community.<ref name=\"P.L. Newman\">{{cite magazine|url=http://autoweek.com/article/car-news/racing-community-saddened-death-paul-newman|title=Racing community saddened by death of Paul Newman|magazine=Autoweek|date=September 26, 2008|accessdate=September 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe was a frequent competitor in [[Sports Car Club of America]] (SCCA) events for the rest of the decade, eventually winning four national championships. He later drove in the [[1979 24 Hours of Le Mans]] in Dick Barbour's [[Porsche 935]] and finished in second place.<ref name=\"1979 Le Mans\">{{cite web|url=http://www.formula2.net/1979.htm|title=XLVII Grand Prix d'Endurance les 24 Heures du Mans 1979|publisher=Le Mans & F2 Register|date=May 2, 2008|accessdate=September 27, 2008}}</ref> Newman reunited with Barbour in 2000 to compete in the [[2000 Petit Le Mans|Petit Le Mans]].<ref name=\"Petit\">{{cite web|url=http://wsrp.ic.cz/alms2000.html#9 |title=American Le Mans Series 2000 |publisher=World Sports Racing Prototypes |date=October 2, 2005 |accessdate=September 27, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081005044003/http://wsrp.ic.cz/alms2000.html |archivedate=October 5, 2008 |df= }}</ref>\n\nFrom the mid-1970s to the early 1990s, he drove for the ''[[Bob Sharp (racing driver)|Bob Sharp]] Racing'' team, racing mainly [[Datsun]]s (later rebranded as [[Nissan Motors|Nissans]]) in the [[Trans-Am Series]]. He became closely associated with the brand during the 1980s, even appearing in commercials for them in Japan and having [[Nissan Skyline#Paul Newman Version|a special edition of the Nissan Skyline]] named after him. At the age of 70 years and eight days, Newman became the oldest driver to date to be part of a winning team in a major sanctioned race,<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Vaughn|first=Mark|title=Paul Newman 1925\u20132008|magazine=[[AutoWeek]]|volume=58|issue=40|page=43|date=October 6, 2008}}</ref> winning in his class at the 1995 [[24 Hours of Daytona]].<ref name=\"1995 Daytona\">{{cite web|url=http://wsrp.ic.cz/imsa1995.html#1 |title=International Motor Sports Association 1995 |publisher=World Sports Racing Prototypes |date=February 14, 2007 |accessdate=September 27, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090408195356/http://wsrp.ic.cz/imsa1995.html |archivedate=April 8, 2009 |df= }}</ref> Among his last major races were the [[Baja 1000]] in 2004 and the 24 Hours of Daytona once again in 2005.<ref name=\"2005 Daytona\">{{cite web|url=http://wsrp.ic.cz/grandam2005.html#1|title=Grand-American Road Racing Championship 2005|publisher=World Sports Racing Prototypes|date=December 17, 2005|accessdate=September 27, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012210032/http://wsrp.ic.cz/grandam2005.html#1|archivedate=October 12, 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Road America Paul Newman Nissan on display.jpg|thumb|Sharp/Newman Nissan (2013)]]\n\nDuring the 1976 auto racing season, Newman became interested in forming a professional auto racing team and contacted [[Bill Freeman (racing driver)|Bill Freeman]] who introduced Newman to professional auto racing management, and their company specialized in [[Can-Am]], [[IndyCar Series|Indy Cars]], and other high-performance racing automobiles. The team was based in [[Santa Barbara, California]] and commuted to [[Willow Springs International Motorsports Park]] for much of its testing sessions.\n\nTheir ''Newman Freeman Racing'' team was very competitive in the North American [[Can-Am]] series in their Budweiser sponsored Chevrolet-powered [[Spyder NF-10|Spyder NFs]]. Newman and Freeman began a long and successful partnership with the Newman Freeman Racing team in the Can-Am series which culminated in the Can-Am Team Championship trophy in 1979. Newman was associated with Freeman's established [[Porsche racing]] team which allowed both Newman and Freeman to compete in [[SCCA]] and [[International Motor Sports Association|IMSA]] racing events together, including the [[12 Hours of Sebring|Sebring 12-hour endurance sports car race]]. This car was sponsored by Beverly Porsche/Audi. Freeman was [[Sports Car Club of America]]'s Southern Pacific National Champion during the ''Newman Freeman Racing'' period. Later Newman co-founded [[Newman/Haas/Lanigan Racing|''Newman/Haas Racing'']] with [[Carl Haas]], a [[Champ Car]] team, in 1983, going on to win eight drivers' championships under his ownership. The 1996 racing season was chronicled in the [[IMAX]] film ''[[Super Speedway]]'' (1997), which Newman narrated. He was a partner in the [[Atlantic Championship]] team ''[[Newman Wachs Racing]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newmanwachsracing.com/index.php/2016/10/07/legendary-newman-name-returning-to-open-wheel-racing/|title=Legendary Newman Name Returning to Open-Wheel Racing \u2013 Newman Wachs Racing|website=newmanwachsracing.com|language=en-US|access-date=July 16, 2018}}</ref> Newman voiced ''[[Doc Hudson]]'' in ''[[Cars (2006)]]''.\n\nHaving said he would quit \"when I embarrass myself\", Newman competed into his 80s, winning at [[Lime Rock Park|Lime Rock]] in what former co-driver [[Sam Posey]] called a \"brutish Corvette\" displaying his age as its number: 81.<ref name=\"P.L. Newman\"/> He took the pole in his last professional race, in 2007 at Watkins Glen International, and in a 2008 run at Lime Rock, arranged by friends, he reportedly still did 9/10ths of his best time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.drivingline.com/2012/04/paul-newman-from-lime-rock-connecticut|title=PL Newman from Lime Rock Connecticut|publisher=DRIVINGLine|date=April 17, 2012|accessdate=September 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nNewman was posthumously inducted into the [[SCCA Hall of Fame]] at the national convention in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas, Nevada]] on February 21, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scca.org/newsarticle.aspx?hub=6&news=3533|title=Newman Leads List of New SCCA Hall of Fame Inductees|publisher=Sports Car Club of America|date=December 3, 2008|accessdate=March 13, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610053825/http://www.scca.org/newsarticle.aspx?hub=6&news=3533|archivedate=June 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nNewman's racing life was chronicled in the documentary ''[[Winning: The Racing Life of Paul Newman]]'' (2015).\n\n===Motorsports career results===\n\n====SCCA National Championship Runoffs====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:90%\"\n|-\n! Year !! Track !! Car !! Class !! Finish !! Start !! Status\n|-\n| 1973 || [[Road Atlanta]] || [[Datsun 510|Nissan 510]] || B Sedan || 9 || 15 || Running\n|-\n| 1975 || [[Road Atlanta]] || [[Datsun 510|Nissan 510]] || B Sedan || 6 || 11 || Running\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1976 ||rowspan=2| [[Road Atlanta]] || [[Datsun 510|Nissan 510]] || B Sedan ||style=\"background:#FFDF9F;\"| 3 || 6 || Running\n|-\n| [[Triumph TR6]] || D Production ||style=\"background:#FFFFBF;\"| 1 || 1 || Running\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1978 ||rowspan=2| [[Road Atlanta]] || [[Nissan S30|Nissan 280Z]] || C Production ||style=\"background:#DFDFDF;\"| 2 || 3 || Running\n|-\n| [[Nissan 200SX]] || B Sedan ||style=\"background:#FFFFBF;\"| 3 || 4 || Running\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1979 ||rowspan=2| [[Road Atlanta]] || [[Nissan S130|Nissan 280ZX]] || C Production ||style=\"background:#FFFFBF;\"| 1 || 2 || Running\n|-\n| [[Nissan 200SX]] || B Sedan ||style=\"background:#FFFFBF;\"| 3 || 3 || Running\n|-\n| 1980 || [[Road Atlanta]] || [[Nissan S130|Nissan 280ZX]] || C Production ||style=\"background:#DFDFDF;\"| 2 || 6 || Running\n|-\n| 1982 || [[Road Atlanta]] || [[Nissan S130|Nissan 280ZX]] Turbo || GT1 ||style=\"background:#DFDFDF;\"| 2 || 23 || Running\n|-\n| 1983 || [[Road Atlanta]] || [[Nissan S130|Nissan 280ZX]] || GT1 || 21 || 1 || Running\n|-\n| 1985 || [[Road Atlanta]] || [[Nissan 